<a href="#Estab"><IMG SRC="images/estabctr.gif" ALT="Establishment" BORDER=0></a>

<a href="#Scholars"><IMG SRC="images/scholars.gif" ALT="Associated Scholars" BORDER=0></a>

<a href="#Clinic"><IMG SRC="images/warcrime.gif" ALT="War Crimes Clinic" BORDER=0></a>

<a href="#Group"><IMG SRC="images/group.gif" ALT="Law & Policy Group" BORDER=0></a>

</CENTER>



<HR NOSHADE>



<A NAME="Estab">
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Establishment of the Center for International Law and Policy</H1></A>



<BR>

<pre>

                            MEMORANDUM



TO:    Full-time Faculty and Deans

FROM:  Professors Fischer and Scharf

DATE:  May 15, 1996

RE:    Proposal for a "New England Center for International Law

and    Policy"



     Based on the guidance of the faculty at its May 7, 1996

meeting, we offer the following proposal for the establishment of

a New England Center for International Law and Policy to be voted

on at the May 21st faculty meeting:



     It is proposed that the New England School of Law establish

the "New England Center for International Law and Policy" to

serve as the temporary home for the Public International Law and

Policy Group (described in previous memo from the Faculty

Development Committee) and as the hub for other activities

related to international and comparative law at NESL.  To this

end, NESL will provide the Group certain accommodations as host

and work out a mutually-advantageous affiliation.  In addition,

NESL will identify some type of office space for the Center,

dedicate a phone extension with voice mail, create an e-mail

address, print stationery and a brochure, and appoint one or more

full-time faculty members to oversee and develop a plan for the

activities of the Center.  A report will be made to the faculty

in the fall concerning the program goals of the Center for the

next academic year.  Further major steps will be taken only after

consultation with the Faculty and/or Dean as appropriate.



     The kinds of things we would like to explore as future

activities of the Center would include:  the appointment of a

group of "associated Scholars," both from NESL and outside, to be

affiliated with the Center; hosting or co-hosting periodic

symposia to be held at NESL, and publishing the papers or

proceedings of such conferences; development of a newsletter

and/or occasional papers series, identified with the Center and

NESL; creation of an international and comparative law clinical

program for our students; establishment of a visiting scholar or

scholarly-exchange program; liaising with foreign lawyers and

businessmen, with an eye to obtaining foreign placements for our

students and graduates; and seeking outside funding to support

the activities of the Center.  There will be many other ideas, as

well.  The Center will give us an identity and an organizational

basis that will enable us to seek out and to take advantage of

opportunities, including foundation grants, as they may arise.

</pre>



<hr noshade>



