<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Financial Information</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">
<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<IMG SRC="images/regis4.gif" ALT="Financial Information" width=475 height=63>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>

<A NAME="payment">
<H3>Payment of Tuition:</H3>
<i>(Send payments "Attention: Student Accounts")</I><P>

In order for a student to complete registration, the required payment is due no later than Friday, August 9, l996.  Mailed payments must be postmarked (U.S. Post Office) no later than August 9, l996, to be considered timely.  Payments received beyond that date will be subject to a late registration fee of $100.00.  <B>See section below on late registration fees and penalties.</B>  Students will be notified of the rate of tuition and fees when the rates are set.  Complete information on the mandatory Student Health Plan will also be enclosed with the tuition notice. <B>See section below on Massachusetts mandatory health insurance.</B><P> 

Special Part-time students should contact Student Accounts regarding their tuition charges.<P>

Students receiving money from outside sources including Veterans' Administration, Social Security, company, or other personal funds are subject to the August 9 deadline whether or not they have received said funds. Federal loan recipients who are unduly tardy in applying for loans, i.e., after June 1 for Semester I, and after November 1, Semester II, will also be subject to the August 9 deadline and may not be allowed to wait for the loan proceeds to be disbursed.  We are required to deduct from all Federal loan checks the <B>full amount</B> for the semester then due and payable. <B>Questions regarding tuition may be directed to Student Accounts</B>.<P>

<A NAME="option_1">
<H4>Option 1</H4>

Full amount (tuition and fees) due by August 9, l996.  Please put your Student I.D. Number on the face of the check.<P>

<A NAME="option_2">
<H4>Option 2</H4>

Installment payment plan with AMS.  This is the only installment plan available at the school.  The AMS Plan is not suitable for a student whose aid and educational loans will  cover the entire balance due the school, because we are required to deduct from all Federal loan checks any outstanding balance.  Furthermore, students who do not budget the required amount will be subject to interest charges on the underbudgeted amount.  The toll-free number for new subscribers to the AMS Plan is 1-800-635-0120.  For previously established accounts you may call AMS at this number: 1-800-556-6684.  AMS applications will be available at the Student Accounts window during the month of April.<P>

<A NAME="refunds">
<H3>Refunds Due to Overpayment of Tuition:</H3>

Refund checks from requests for refunds due to overpayment of tuition via Federal loan checks will be ready as follows.<P>

<TABLE BORDER>
<TR>
<TH>Loan checks endorsed on</TH>
<TH>Refund will be ready on</TH>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>Friday, Monday, and Tuesday</TD>
<TD>Wednesday at 12 noon.</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>Wednesday and Thursday</TD>
<TD>Friday at 12 noon.</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>

<A NAME="penalties">
<H3>Late Registration/Payment Fees and Penalties:</H3>
A student who does not register at the time designated will be assessed a $50.00 late registration fee.  In addition, any student who fails to make the fall tuition payment by the deadline, August 9, l996, will not be considered a registered student and will be subject to both a late registration fee of $50.00 <B>and</B> a late payment fee of $50.00.  A maximum of $100.00 in late registration/late payment fees may be incurred during the semester.  A loan applicant who has not met the filing deadlines stated in paragraph 1, and who has not paid by August 9, l996, will be liable for the $100 late registration/payment fees.  In addition, a loan applicant who has met the filing deadlines must also submit remaining financial documents in a timely manner in order to avoid the above mentioned fees.<P>

<A NAME="delinquent">
<H3>Delinquent Accounts:</H3>
Students who are delinquent in their financial obligations to the school are subject to exclusion from classes or dismissal from school until payment has been made. Matriculation is conditioned upon full payment of law school obligations and is subject to cancellation at any time for nonpayment thereof. A student will not be permitted to take a final examination if he or she is financially delinquent on the day the examination is scheduled.<P>

<A NAME="interest">
<H3>Interest Charges:</H3>
Interest will be assessed from August 9, l996, on all open balances not paid in full after applying Federal loans and AMS Contract amounts as well as school grants, if applicable.  Should you not be receiving Federal loans or school grants and have not enrolled with AMS, your tuition and fees must be paid in full not later than August 9, l996.  Any such accounts not paid will also be subject to interest charges from that date.  The rate of interest is 1% per month times the unpaid balance.  This is an annual rate which equals 12% and will be in addition to any late charges incurred as set forth in item 3.<P>

<A NAME="insurance">
<H3>Massachisetts Mandatory Student Health Insurance:</H3>
Under the Massachusetts Universal Health Care Act of 1989 each institution of higher education <B>must require</B> all full-time and part-time students to participate in the student health insurance program or in a health insurance program with comparable coverage.  For this purpose, part-time students are defined as those participating in at least 75% of the academic requirements for full-time students.  If a student has comparable alternative coverage and does not require the health insurance offered by New England School of Law the student <B>must</B> complete, sign and return a waiver form by September 20, l996; otherwise, a late charge of $40 will be incurred and the late waiver must then be approved by the underwriters.  The underwriters will not approve waivers received after November 1, 1996, nor will they approve petitions to add coverage after November 1, 1996.<P>

<A NAME="withdrawal">
<H3>Withdrawl Policy and Refund Schedule:</H3>
Under the student rules, any student in good standing who has not previously withdrawn may, <B>Upon Written Notice to the Associate Dean</B>, voluntarily withdraw from the law school.  Such a student may return in the academic year immediately following the withdrawal by notifying the Associate Dean by April 1 of his or her intention to return. See the Assistant Dean for further information about this. It is important that if a student should decide to withdraw he or she notify the Associate Dean in writing immediately.  The student will be held liable for tuition until this written notification is received.  The effective date of withdrawal is the date of receipt of said notification.<P>

If a withdrawing student's account is paid in full, he or she will receive a refund as scheduled below.  If a withdrawing student has an unpaid balance due on his or her account, the amount due must be paid before withdrawal without prejudice will be granted.  Fees are not refundable.<P>

<TABLE BORDER>

<TR>
<TH>Withdrawal Within</TH>
<TH>Refund</TH>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>1st week of the semester</TD>
<TD>80%</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>2nd week of the semester</TD>
<TD>60%</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>3rd week of the semester</TD>
<TD>40%</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>4th week of the semester</TD>
<TD>20%</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>After 4th week</TD>
<TD>0%</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
<P>

Students who are receiving Federal Title IV funds (Federal Stafford and Perkins Loans) are subject to a federally mandated refund policy.  Title IV aid recipients wishing to withdraw should consult with the Director of Financial Aid to determine the impact this will have on his or her financial aid package.  Refunds will be made in the following order:<P>

<UL>
<LI>To outstanding balances on Federal Unsubsidized Stafford Loans
<LI>To outstanding balances on Federal Subsidized Stafford Loans
<LI>To outstanding balances on Federal Perkins Loans
<LI>To other Federal, State, private, or institutional sources of aid
<LI>To the students contact Student Accounts regarding their tuition charges
</UL>
<P>

<A NAME="financial_aid">
<H3>Financial Aid and Tuition Payment Procedures:</H3>

<B>Important Dates:</B><P>

<TABLE BORDER>

<TR>
<TH>Date</TH>
<TH>Event</TH>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>June 1, 1996</TD>	
<TD>Deadline to submit Federal Stafford loan applications for Fall semester to avoid late registration fee.</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>August 19-23, & 26-30, 1996</TD>
<TD>Fall semester Perkins Loan recipients sign promissory note. Time/Location TBA.</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
<P>


Tuition payment procedures for students receiving financial aid are as follows:<P>

<A NAME="campus_based">
<H3>Campus-Based Funds:</H3>

<A NAME="nesl_grants">
<B>New England School of Law Grants, MacLean Grants, Getchell Grants, Jacqueline Lloyd Grants, and other Law School scholarships</B><P>

The amount of the fall semester award will be deducted from the student's account by the Controller's Office.  To figure the remaining balance due, the student should deduct the amount of the award from the current semester charges.  The student is then responsible for payment of the remainder of the balance.<P>

<A NAME="perkins">
<B>Federal Perkins Loan:</B><P>

To figure the balance, deduct the appropriate amount awarded for the fall semester from the amount due to the School.  Please note that the Student Accounts Office will not officially credit your account until you have signed your promissory note and other required loan documents.  These documents must be signed at the beginning of the school year.  Failure to sign your note each semester will result in the cancellation of your loan.  Should your account be fully paid before your note is signed, the Controller's Office will issue the student a refund check.  These funds must be used for educationally related expenses.<P>

<A NAME="work_study">
<B>Federal Work Study:</B><P> 

The Federal Work-Study Program requires that the student earn his or her award, therefore, no money is automatically deducted from the student's account.  First time students on the Federal-Work Study Program are paid at $6.00 per hour, for on-campus jobs and $7.00 per hour for off-campus jobs, semi-monthly, for the hours actually worked.  Positions and eligible agencies are listed in the Financial Aid Office.  Recipients are required to meet with the Assistant Director of Financial Aid before beginning work to insure all proper paperwork has been completed.  Students who begin employment without authorization will not be paid for those hours.  Additional information is available from the Financial Aid Office.<P>

<A NAME="loan_programs">
<H3>Educational Loan Programs:</H3>

<A NAME="stafford_loan">
<B>Federal Stafford Loan (Subsidized and Unsubsidized):</B><P>

Students intending to pay their tuition with proceeds from the Federal Stafford Loan Program generally do not benefit by using the deferred payment option (AMS).  The student does, however, have the option to fully pay his or her account and use the bank loan proceeds for educationally related living expenses.  Student loan applicants must file their loan application with the Financial Aid Office on or before June 1, 1996, along with all other required documents, in order to avoid being assessed late registration fees.  Students  who submit applications after this date will be subject to late fee charges by the Student Accounts Office unless they make the required payment when due in anticipation of receiving loan funds at a later date.<P>

Checks are jointly payable to the school and student and must be endorsed promptly at the Controller's Office upon notification that the check has been received.  Stafford Loan proceeds may also be sent to the school by a process known as Electronic Funds Transfer, or EFT. Federal regulations require that all first-time Federal Stafford Loan borrowers at New England School of Law attend an Entrance Interview prior to endorsing his or her loan check or receiving proceeds through EFT.  The purpose of the Entrance Interview is to discuss the student's rights and responsibilities as a student loan recipient.  Student's will be notified during the summer of the schedule for Entrance Interviews.<P>

Students should remember that Federal Stafford Loans are disbursed in two installments (one in the Fall for first semester and generally one in January for second semester) and should plan accordingly.  Federal Stafford loan proceeds are remitted under Title IV regulations and must be used for educationally related expenses.  As such, the Controller's Office is required to deduct from all student loan proceeds the full amount for the semester then due and payable.  Requests for refunds due to overpayment of tuition via a loan check are handled as follows:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Students whose checks are endorsed on Friday, Monday and Tuesday will receive their refund check after 12 noon on Wednesday.
<LI>Students whose checks are endorsed on Wednesday and Thursday will receive their refund check after 12 noon on Friday.
</UL>
<P>

<A NAME="teri">
<B>TERI/Law Access Loan (LOL):</B><P>

These supplemental loans are at market interest rates and should be pursued after seeking the full Federal Stafford loan amounts.  Institutional guidelines and its interaction with Students Accounts will be similar to the other bank loan programs.  Further information about these programs is available in the Financial Aid Office.<P>

