<A NAME="drop_add">
<H3>Drop/Add Policy and Procedure:</H3>

The Drop/Add Period begins immediately after registration (for seniors Drop/Add begins April 12, and for non-seniors Drop/Add begins April 22, 1996) and continues through the first five days of the semester (August 26-30, 1996).  Courses may be added or dropped without record through August 30, 1996.  In order to drop or add a course during this period, a student must complete a Drop/Add Form at the Registrar's Office.  A student wishing to withdraw from a course after the first five days of classes must submit a <I>Student Request Form </I>to the Associate or Assistant Dean for approval.  A course dropped under these circumstances will result in the recording of a "withdrawal" for that course on the student's transcript.  If approval is not obtained, the student must complete the course or receive an "incomplete".  Academic standing alone will not always be considered good cause for granting permission to withdraw from a course after having taken an examination which will receive weight in the final course grade.<P>

<A NAME="audit">
<H3>Audit Policy and Procedure:</H3>

With the permission of the course instructor, an elective course (other than a clinical or simulation course) may be audited rather than taken for grade credit.  Such course will be included on the student's transcript as an "audit".  Audited courses are not counted towards fulfillment of either residency or graduation requirements.  No examination may be taken in an audited course.  Students should note that audit permission is generally not granted for seminar courses.  If there is a question of audit eligibility, students should ascertain the audit policy of their courses prior to the conclusion of the Drop/Add Period.<P>

To audit a course, a student must obtain the course instructor's signature on an audit certification form, indicating permission to audit the course.  Upon completion of the course, the student must obtain the course instructor's signature on the audit certification form, certifying satisfactory completion of the course to justify the audit status.  A "withdrawal" will be recorded for any audited course for which no audit certification is received prior to the date of the final examination in that course.  Students are advised that audit credits over the maximum allowable credits per semester are subject to two-thirds the tuition credit charge of regular credits taken for a grade.  In order to change from credit to audit status in a course, a student must submit an audit certification form to the course instructor for approval.  If approval is obtained, this form should be submitted to the Registrar's Office.  A change from audit to credit status in a course may be made only during the Drop/Add Period by submitting a Drop/Add Form to the Registrar's Office.<P>

<A NAME="reg_clinic">
<H3>Registration for Clinical Courses:</H3>

<I>To obtain the 16-page booklet describing the clinical courses in detail, attend the clinic information on Monday, April First 1996, at 4:20-5:55 in Room 301, or contact the Clinic Office at 46 Church Street. (422-7300)</I><P>

Registration for Clinical Courses occurs during the first two days of Senior Pre-Registration and the first two days of General Registration.  For seniors, clinic registration will occur April 8 and 9, 1996.  For non-seniors, clinic registration will occur April 16 and 17, 1996.  To the extent that there are openings in the clinical courses, late registration will be allowed during the remainder of the senior and general registration period and during the Drop/Add Period.<P>

Clinical Courses being offered each semester are listed in the Schedule of Courses for the Fall semester.  To obtain a more detailed description of each course, students may contact the Clinic Office at 46 Church Street. (422-7380)<P>

Day students who have completed their first year and evening students who have completed their first two years are eligible for all but two of NESL's clinical offerings. For those two clinics students must be in their last year of law school.  Students must also have maintained at least 2.0 grade point average.  Finally, for most clinic courses, students must have taken or be taking a related substantive course.  The specific requirements for each Clinic Course are included in the materials available from the Clinic Office.<P>

Initial Clinic Registration will take place at the Registrar's Office during the above listed days.  During the Drop/Add Period, students must make changes in their clinical schedule by submitting the appropriate form to the Registrar's Office and by notifying the Clinic Office.<P>

<A NAME="reg_ind">
<H3>Registration for Independent Legal Research:</H3>

Ordinarily, no student may receive credit for more than one Independent Legal Research project.  There is a limit of two (2) credit hours for such projects.  This course is open only to students in their final year of law school.<P>

The objective of an Independent Legal Research project is for the student to demonstrate a mastery of a legal subject area, substantial legal analysis, logical organization and writing competence.<P>

Before registering for Independent Legal Research, the student must complete an Independent Legal Research (UCWR/ILR) Form and a Student Request Form containing:  (i) a narrative description of the area of proposed study, together with an outline to be attached setting forth in reasonable detail the proposed course of study;  (ii) a break-down of the approximate minimum hours to be spent: (a) in research and writing; (b) in the tutorial with a faculty member who has agreed to act as the Independent Legal Research advisor to the student; and (iii) proposed schedule outlining times by which a first draft, second draft, third draft and final draft will be completed.  The form should also contain the signature of a full-time faculty member, indicating both approval of the student's proposal and consent to act as the supervisor of the student's Independent Legal Research project.  After obtaining the approval of a faculty member, the student must obtain the signature of the Co-ordinator of Upperclass Writing Programs, approving the project.   The student registers for Independent Legal Research by submitting the completed Student Request Form and the UCWR/ILR Form, along with the normal registration form, to the Registrar's office.<P>

A student may register for Independent Legal Research only during the normal registration period of each semester, so students who wish to register should ordinarily begin their planning the semester before.<P>

A student who wishes to fulfill the Upperclass Writing Requirement through the Independent Legal Research project must register for both Independent Legal Research and for the UCWR.<P>

Each student who registers for Independent Legal Research must attend a seminar given by the Co-ordinator of Upperclass Writing Programs at the beginning of the semester in which he or she has enrolled in the Independent Legal Research Program.  The Co-ordinator must sign a form verifying the student's attendance at this seminar.  In addition to consulting with his or her faculty advisor, any student who would like help with his or her writing skills is encouraged to contact the writing instructors who are available to NESL students through an appointment with the faculty receptionist.<P>

As a general rule, each student should be prepared to spend a minimum of 4 hours per credit-hour times the number of weeks in the semester (i.e., for 1 credit hour:  4 x 14 = 56 hours for two credit hours 112 hours) in research, writing and in a tutorial with the student's Independent Legal Research faculty advisor.  No clinical experience or work done for any course or employer, or done anytime prior to registering for Independent Legal Research may be used as an Independent Legal Research project.<P>

No faculty member may have more than 15 students during any academic year for whom he or she acts as UCWR Advisor and/or Independent Legal Research Advisor.<P>

<A NAME="reg_div">
<H3>Registration for Courses in a Different Division:</H3>

Without obtaining approval, day division students may register for one course in the evening division and evening division students may register for one course in the day division.  This option is available for elective courses only and does not apply to required courses.  The Associate Dean shall have the right to suspend this option prior to the expiration date of the Drop/Add Period where there is or will be a significant numerical imbalance between the same course when offered separately in both divisions.  A student wishing to register for more than one course out of division should submit a student request form to the Associate Dean or Assistant Dean for approval.  If approved, this form should accompany the registration form.  When a student elects to register for a course or courses out of division, that student is not eligible to have any re-scheduling of exam conflicts which may occur as a result, unless it results in two exams at the exact same date and time.  All courses scheduled to begin between 4-5:55 p.m. are available to both day and evening division students.<P>

<A NAME="resched">
<H3>Re-Scheduling Final Examinations-Policy and Procedure:</H3>

The final examination schedule is formulated so that examinations for courses strongly recommended will be evenly spaced.  The final examination schedule for this semester is contained in this booklet (Section VIII) in order to provide students with an opportunity to avoid conflicts.  The rules governing deviations from the examination schedule are as follows:  <B>Prior to Registration</B>, a student wishing to register for courses having conflicting examination times (as delineated below) may seek permission to take the courses by submitting a student request form to the Assistant Dean for approval.  If approval is obtained, this form should accompany the registration form.  A request for a rescheduled exam must be submitted to the Asssistant Dean prior to the conclusion of the Drop/Add Period.  The Dean's Office will then adjust that student's final examination schedule accordingly.  The <B>only</B> situations which constitute an examination conflict are as follows:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Two courses with examinations on the same day and time;
<LI>A minimum of three courses with exams in a two day period. (This situation will not be eligible for re-scheduling if it occurs because the student took a course out of division). 
</OL>
<P>

The following are examples of situations which <B>will not</B> constitute an exam conflict and therefore will not be eligible for re-scheduling:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Two exams on the same day, but not the same time;
<LI>Two exams in a two-day period, three exams in a three-day  period;
<LI>An exam for a course taken out of division which results in three exams in a two-day period where at least one exam is for a course taken out of division.
</OL>
<P>

Exam conflicts created by student action during the Drop/Add Period will not create a right to have that conflict resolved unless the exams are given at the exact same time.  Any student who, because of a learning disability or other impairment, requires extra time on examinations, should see the Associate Dean or Assistant Dean as early in the semester as possible.<P>

Note: Due to the addition of more sections of recommended courses, exams on consecutive days are possible.  Students are advised to refer to the exam schedule when choosing courses.  Taking WET "A" and Professional Responsibility "J" together will not qualify for a rescheduled exam.<P>

<A NAME="prereq">
<H3>Course Pre-Requisites or Co-Requisites:</H3>

Each student is responsible for ascertaining that he or she has met all pre-requisites before registering for any course for which there is a pre-requisite, or is co-registered for any course that is a co-requisite.  Students shut out of a co-requisite by over-enrollment must contact the Associate Dean.  A student wishing a waiver of any pre-requisite or co-requisite should submit a student request form to the course instructor for approval, and if approval is obtained, then to the Associate Dean or Assistant Dean for approval.  Approval by the course instructor does not ensure approval by the Associate Dean or Assistant Dean.  If approval by the Associate Dean or Assistant Dean is obtained, this form should accompany the registration form.  The failure of a student to have the proper pre-requisites or co-requisites or an authorized waiver prior to registration may result in his or her involuntary withdrawal from the course with consequent loss of credit and residency.  The pre-requisites for courses offered in both semesters are listed below:<P>

