<A NAME="upperclass">
<H3>Upper-Class Writing Requirement Information:</H3>


Fulfilling the Upperclass Writing Requirement (UCWR) is a pre-requisite to graduation.  It is advisable, if possible, to complete it prior to your final semester in law school. The UCWR can only be fulfilled by a qualified paper, written under the supervision of a <B>full-time</B> faculty member.   Adjunct faculty cannot certify a paper for UCWR purposes.  In addition, no work done outside the law school (e.g. for an employer) or done prior to the time of registering for the Upperclass Writing Requirement (e.g. for a prior class) will satisfy this requirement.<P>

To satisfy the UCWR, a paper must demonstrate <B>substantial</B> legal analysis as well as logical organization and competent writing skills.  The actual form and length of the paper should be developed with the full-time faculty member supervising your project.  Normally at least two rewrites of the paper will be required.  Students should register for the UCWR in the semester they intend to complete it.<P>

Before registering for the UCWR, the student must complete an UCWR Registration Form, obtained from the Registrar's office.  The form asks for a narrative description of the topic to be covered, an outline of the proposed paper and a proposed schedule stating times by which a first draft, second draft and final draft will be completed.  After completing the form, the student must obtain the signature of a full-time faculty member, indicating both approval of the student's proposal and consent to act as that student's UCWR supervisor.  No faculty member may supervise more than 15 student writing projects per academic year unless this requirement is simultaneously fulfilled with a course paper.<P>

After obtaining the approval and signature of a full-time faculty member, the student should enter on the UCWR form the code number that corresponds to the faculty member supervising the paper.  For example, if a student plans to fulfill the writing requirement with Professor Finneran, the student would enter her code (i.e., 733 see page 20 for codes) on the form. A student who plans to fulfill the UCWR through a qualified paper to be submitted in a course must enter the code of the course instructor on the UCWR form and register for the course on the normal registration form.<P>  

A student registers for the UCWR by submitting a completed UCWR form to the Registrar's office during the usual Drop/Add Period for the semester and completing a mandatory seminar described below.  If a student fails to complete the writing requirement during the semester he or she registered for it, an incomplete (IP stands for "In Progress") will be entered. Upon completion of the paper the incomplete (IP) shall be changed to a Pass.  This applies to the UCWR <B>only</B>.<P>

<B>Prior to beginning the UCWR paper, each student must attend a seminar given by the Director of Writing Programs.  The seminar will be given at the beginning of the semester in which the student has enrolled to complete the UCWR</B>.<P>

Attendance in one of the seminars is <B>mandatory</B> for completion of enrollment in the UCWR.  Verification will be made through a sign-up sheet at each seminar.  <B>The faculty-signed registration form must be delivered to the Registrar's Office no later than September 9, 1996 for the Fall semester and January 17, 1997 for the Spring semester.</B><P>

<B>In addition to attending the mandatory writing seminar, each student must attend a 90 minute UCWR Advanced Computer Assisted Legal Research (CALR) seminar in the library</B>.  Students can elect to take either WESTLAW or LEXIS and must register for a seminar at the library desk.  The training classes will begin on the same day as the UCWR writing seminar and will continue during the semester.  Students are encouraged to take the CALR training early in the semester.  The deadline for registering for the CALR seminar is <B>October 4, 1996</B>.<P>

Students should consult the Student Handbook of Rules and Regulations for additional methods of fulfilling the UCWR as well as other pertinent information regarding this requirement.<P>

In order to receive a "Pass" in the UCWR, a student must demonstrate competence in legal analysis and communication in a written form (e.g., memorandum, law review article style).<P>

