<A NAME="ucwr_q">
<H3>Questions and Answers About UCWR:</H3>

<I>Q: Can I use a memo written as part of my employment in a law office?</I><P>

A: No.  You can use the knowledge and research you developed in writing the memo to form the basis of a topic which is developed in more depth under the supervision of a full-time faculty member.<P>

<I>Q: Can I use a Moot Court Competition Brief?</I><P>

A: Yes, but it must be expanded and rewritten under the supervision of a full-time faculty member after the competition ends.<P>

<I>Q: The topic I want to write about is covered only in a course 	taught by an adjunct (part-time) professor.  Can I fulfill the UCWR by doing a paper in that course?</I><P>

A: No, but you can use the knowledge and research developed in the course and write a paper on the same or a similar topic under the supervision of a full-time faculty member to fulfill the UCWR.<P>

<I>Q: The professor I want to work with has no more spaces available for UCWR projects.  Help?</I><P>

A: Ask the professor to recommend another faculty member familiar with that area of law.  If it is very important to you to work on a specific topic with a particular faculty member you should ask well in advance to make sure he or she will have room for you.<P>

<I>Q: I want to do the paper over the summer. Can I?</I><P>

A: Ask the faculty member of your choice to meet with you late in the Spring semester to develop your topic.  Then you are ready to research and write a draft over the summer.<P>

