<P>

<A NAME="desc">
<H3>Course Descriptions Not Included in the Catalog:</H3>

The following  course classifications have been added to the list of courses:<P>

<A NAME="c1">
<B>Advanced Environmental Law:</B><P>

A variety of seminar courses are offered under the heading Advanced Environmental Law.  Examples of such courses include Environmental Theory and Politics, Environmental Litigation, and International Environmental Law.  Advanced Environmental Law may or may not require students to have completed the survey course in Environmental Law as a prerequisite; in most cases, however, students who have completed Environmental Law will be given preferred enrollment.<P>

<I>2 or 3 credits</I><P>

<A NAME="c2">
<B>Advanced International and Comparative Law:</B><P>

A variety of seminar courses are offered on topics in comparative law and advanced international law, in addition to Immigration Law and the basic courses on (Public) International Law and International Business Transactions.  These have included European Union Law, International Criminal Law, and International Human Rights Law.<P>

<I>2 or 3 credits</I><P>

<A NAME="c3">
<B>Advanced Constitutional Law:  Mass Media Law:</B><P>

This course deals with media law, not just necessarily the first amendment, because media law has many sources other than the first amendment.  For example, the law of defamation is largely state common law.  A reporter's privilege to refuse disclose confidences is controlled in many states by statute.  Open meetings and open record statutes determine the outcome of most controversies over press access to governmental information.  Conversely, many areas of first amendment have little to do with mass media.  The religion, association, and petition clauses of that amendment rarely are invoked by mass media.  Nevertheless, the first amendment does play a large role in nearly every area of media law.<P>

<I>2  credits; Professor O'Toole</I><P>


<A NAME="c4">
<B>Advanced International Law:  Internation Law Women's Issues:</B><P>

Traditional international law courses fall into either "public" (human rights) or "private" (economic) categories.  Neither category has integrated a gender perspective into the core of analysis.  In this course, we will explore both international human rights and economic law as they affect women.<P>

Human rights issues affecting women are often treated as purely "private" action, therefore beyond the purview of human mutilation, forced child marriage, sex slave trade, systematic use of rape, forced veiling, as well as domestic violence, and denial of access to reproductive technology, are often not viewed as violating international human rights norms.<P>

Private (economic) international law courses often exclude gender concerns on the theory of deferring to local cultures and customs.  Thus critical issues such as the legal capacity of women to enter into contracts, and to hold, transfer and inherit property which are pre-requisites to participating in a market economy, are widely denied to women under current international legal practices.  Employment policies and practices of multinational corporations can be analyzed under various domestic and international laws.<P>

In addition, quasi-public multinational lenders such as the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, have recently announced initiatives to assess the gender impact in their lending policies, affecting issues of land reform and agricultural policies as well as assessing the gender participation rates in various programs.  Since the accountability mechanisms for these institutions are relatively undeveloped, they present a particularly exciting challenge in the context of pursuing gender analysis and legal accountability.<P>

Course participants will research and write a paper, which may be used to fulfill the Upper Class Writing Requirement, on one of these topics.  No examination.<P>

<I>2 credits; Professor Spahn</I><P>

<A NAME="c5">
<B>Advanced Lawyering Process Clinic (Spring Semester only):</B><P>

This advanced clinical course affords students a further opportunity to enhance lawyering skills and to explore some of the more difficult problems to which they were exposed in the Lawyering Process course.  Students will spend eight hours per week handling cases in the Clinical Law Office under the supervision of a clinical faculty member.  This fieldwork will be concentrated in the more advanced stages of litigation, including discovery, negotiation, and trial.  A bi-weekly seminar will use readings, case discussions and simulations to address areas of poverty law, skills development, ethical considerations, and policy issues involved in the legal process.  Students will also be exposed to the management of legal work by means of limited involvement in the supervision of less experienced students and in the administration of the Clinical Law Office.<P>

Each student will be required to pay a $20.00 fee toward costs for running the clinic, including malpractice insurance.<P>

<I>Prerequisite:  Lawyering Process</I><P>

<I>Enrollment:  Limited to 4</I><P>

<I>2 credits; Professor Engler</I><P>

<A NAME="c6">
<B>Advanced Legal Writing:</B><P>

This advanced course examines the principles of good legal writing and drafting.  In the first half of the course, students will research and write appellate briefs.  In the second half of the course, students will draft several documents, including wills, contracts, statutes, and pleadings.<P>

Classroom instruction will be supplemented by individual conferences.  Successful completion of this course satisfies the Upper Class Wiring Requirement.  Enrollment is limited to 20 students.<P>

<I>3 credits;  Professor Cooper</I><P>

<A NAME="c7">
<B>American Indian Law:</B><P>

This course studies the law that regulates the legal relationships between Indian tribes and the United States.  Topics covered include the historical development of the status of Indian tribes as "domestic dependent nations"; Indian property rights and land claims; Indian religious and cultural rights; the federal trust responsibility to Indian tribes, tribal sovereignty; overlapping federal, state, and tribal governmental authority; Indian gaming; and indigenous peoples' rights under international law.  In additional to conventional legal materials, the course reading includes historical and anthropological materials.  In addition to developing knowledge of Indian law, the course is designed to examine what Indian law reveals about the ability of the law and society to tolerate diversity.<P>

<I>3 credits; Professor Dussias</I><P>

<A NAME="c8">
<B>The Appellate Process:</B><P>

The focus of this course is on principles that apply in all appellate court systems, such as the raising and preserving of issues at the adjudicative level; the doctrine of finality; mandatory and discretionary interlocutory review; jurisdiction of the appellate courts; perfecting the appeal; mandatory and discretionary review by the highest appellate court before or after decision by an intermediate appellate court; and standards of appellate review.<P>

<I>3 credits; Attorney Johnedis</I><P>

<A NAME="c9">
<B>Business Transactions for Lawyers:</B><P>

Business transactions and records will be studied to provide students unfamiliar with the business world enough information and insight to understand the business decision-making process.  The role of legal and accounting professionals in that process will be examined, with particular emphasis on professional responsibilities.<P>

Students will be introduced to the design and functions of basic financial records. For the business person, they supply information for decisions such as continuation, expansion or dropping of business activity, or for retaining or promoting an employee.  The cases and documents will show the tensions between financial records that accurately predict profit potential on the one hand, and records that either conservatively understate it (the tax auditor's bias, or perhaps the bias of a promoter/speculator).<P>

Students without any business training or experience should consider taking this course before or while taking Business Organizations or Personal Income Taxation, although it is not a prerequisite for these courses.  Students who contemplate the general practice of law should also consider taking this course.<P>

<I>2 credits; Professor Hyman</I><P>

<A NAME="c10">
<B>Clinical Courses:</B><P>

To obtain the 16-page booklet describing the clinical courses in detail, attend the clinic information meeting (Monday, April 1, 1996, 4:20-5:55, Room 301) or contact the Clinic Office at 46 Church Street. (422-7380)<P>

<A NAME="c11">
<B>Domestic Violence:</B><P>

This seminar will focus on violence against women in family or dating types of situations.  Among the subjects that may be covered in any particular semester are:  restraining orders, shelters, mandatory arrests, criminal prosecutions, diversion programs, divorce and custody proceedings and other current remedial efforts.  My goal in teaching this course is to identify concrete ways in which the law can be used to improve the situation for victims of domestic violence, while protecting the rights of accused batterers.  The course will examine domestic violence with in its social context, drawing on both traditional legal materials and less traditional non-legal materials.  In our study we will try to identify when and how issues of race, class, ethnicity, and sexual preference are affecting the analyses that we are considering.<P>

Each student will be required to write a paper that contributes in some way to advancing through about how to decrease domestic violence.  There will be no final examination and the paper may be expanded in order to fulfill the Upperclass Writing Requirement.<P>

<I>2 credits; Professor Greenberg</I><P>

<A NAME="c12">
<B>Employment Law Clinic (Spring semester only):</B><P>

Students in this clinical component will spend ten hours per week in settings that offer exposure to matters involving employment law.  The primary placement for the clinic will be at the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination, in either the prosecution hearings division.  Additional placements are possible in other governmental agencies, private firms or public interest organizations.<P>

Students are required to submit weekly diaries, describing and evaluating their experience during the week in light of the doctrines taught in the classroom course.  The students will meet with the professor teaching Employment Law and/or the Clinical Director in a series of five seminars to explore the relationship between the principles of Employment Law covered in the course and the practice of employment law from the students' fieldwork.<P>

<I>Corequisite or prerequisite:  Employment Law</I><P>

<I>Limited enrollment</I><P>

<I>2 credits; Professor Spahn</I><P>

<A NAME="c13">
<B>Honors Judicial Internship:</B><P>

This course provides an opportunity to hone research and writing skills in the context of part time internships with state or federal judges.  It will also offer unique opportunities to observe and work on the judicial side of the profession, an experience which greatly enhances a lawyer's effectiveness in the practice of law.<P>

Each student intern will work for the semester as a law intern for a judge in the Boston area.  Credit of 2 to 4 hours will be available, depending on the particular placement and the amount of time spent weekly actually working as a judicial intern.  The expectation is that students will work between 10 and 20 hours a week.  In addition, regular meetings between student and the faculty supervisor will be held.<P>

The actual duties of each student will be determined primarily by the judge for whom the student interns, and will vary somewhat in light of the nature of the court, cases, and judge involved.  The core requirements of the course will be legal research and writing of some type and the maintenance of a journal detailing the clerking experience.  The writing requirement may include preparation of memoranda for the court, writing proposed judicial opinions, or writing a paper for the faculty supervisor on a particular issue arising during the clerking experience.  Generally, student interns will have an opportunity to observe court proceedings, such as motion sessions, trials, or appellate arguments, and interact with the judges for whom they are interning.<P>
  
Selection for the course is highly competitive.  To be eligible to enroll in the course, a student, whether in the evening or day division, must have completed all courses required in the first year day curriculum, and must have a grade point average that places the student in the upper 30% of the class.  Actual final selection for the course will be contingent upon acceptance of a student intern by the court for whom the intern is to work, which may not occur until early August.  Enrollment in the course for the semester generally will be limited to no more than twelve (12) students (depending on the availability of placements).  Final course grades will be based on evaluation of student interns by the judges with whom the interns have worked and the faculty supervisor.<P>

Students interested in the course should not register for the course at this time, but should complete their fall registration as if they were not taking the course.  When students are finally accepted for the course, registration can be completed through Drop/Add.  <B>To be considered for the course submit a student request form, a resume, two references and a short writing sample to Professor Sorenson by April 22, 1996.  Applications will be reviewed and applicants will be contacted to confirm their interest in the course before materials are sent to judges</B>.<P>

<I>2-4 credits; Professor Sorenson</I><P>

<A NAME="c14">
<B>Perspectives: Housing Discrimination:</B><P>

This course is designed to familiarize students with the statutory prohibitions of housing discrimination, procedures for enforcement, standards of proof, and remedies for violations.  Emphasis is place on the key provisions of the Fair Housing Act (Title VIII) and on important cases interpreting their applicability.  Other topics covered include the basic features of 42 U. S. C. 1982 and other fair housing sources, theories liability, and litigation and proof issues.<P>

<I>2 credits; Attorney Mondshein</I><P>

<A NAME="c15">
<B>The Law and the Elderly:</B><P>

This course presents a broad overview of the legal and policy questions relating to aging individuals and an older society.  As our elderly population continues to grow faster than the population as a whole, the legal profession must be prepared to address the wide range of legal issues that particularly affect the elderly.<P>

Topics which are explored include how the elderly live when they retire and their income drops, health care options and access to care, housing alternatives when a person ages and becomes frail, and long term care policies.  Students also study health care decision making, planning for incapacity, the legal consideration when individuals can no longer make decisions for themselves, and elder abuse, neglect and financial exploitation.<P>

This course involves frequent use of simulations, role plays, and problem solving extrapolated from actual situations encountered by elderly clients.<P>

<I>2 or 3 credits;  Professor I. Klein</I><P>

<A NAME="c16">
<B>Mediation:</B><P>

This course will focus on legal, ethical, sociological and procedural aspects of mediation.  It will involve a series of student simulation exercises based on fact patterns drawn from several of the following fields:  divorce, child custody, land use, education, health care, construction, employment, and small business.  Special attention will be given to issues of whether mediation - as opposed to judicial proceedings - tends to disempower the already weak.<P>

<I>3 credits; Attorney Dorsey</I><P>

<A NAME="c17">
<B>Perspectives: Race and the Law:</B><P>

This course will focus on selected topics illustrating ways in which the law succeeds or fails to reflect both actual racial and cultural diversity and popular misconceptions of racial and cultural difference.  In addition to legal texts (including trial transcripts), some on-legal texts may be studied to illuminate race-biased thinking.<P>

<I>2 credits; Professor Ward</I><P>

<A NAME="c18">
<B>Perspectives: Real Estate Development:</B><P>

This course will examine selected legal issues involved in real estate development and finance, with a focus on the role of the real estate lawyer and on significant transactional documents.  The course is intended to supplement other real estate-related courses.  Assignments will include reading as well as some drafting.  Classes wil include discussion of the week's assignment, with some participatory negotiations.  Completion of Property is a pre-requisite.<P>

<I>2 credits; Attorney Canter</I><P>

<A NAME="c19">
<B>Regulated Industries:  Communications Law:</B><P>

This course will examine the laws concerning the communication of multimedia through a variety of high-capacity transmission systems, such as telephone, cable, fiber optic and satellite.  We will begin by examining federal communications law and its impact on the transformation of the Bell system, and then study the similarities and differences in the legal mechanisms which govern data, voice and multimedia transmissions.  Finally, we will anticipate and evaluate the major changes in the telecommunications industry which will result from the FCC's implementation of the Telecommunications Act of 1996.<P>

<I>2 credits; Attorney Gladstone</I><P>

<A NAME="c20">
<B>Perspectives:  AIDS and the Law:</B><P>

AIDS has become the most litigated disease in history, affecting nearly every area of the law.  Students participating in the Perspectives:AIDS And The Law seminar will examine the impact of the HIV/AIDS epidemic in a number of substantive areas, such as employment, health care, tort law, criminal and prisons law.  Issues involving the intersection of law an public policy, including testing, confidentiality and privacy , will also be explored.  Students will be required to submit a research paper in lieu of an examination.  Limited to 20 students.<P>

<I>2 credits;  Attorney Davidson</I><P>

<A NAME="c21">
<B>Perspectives: American Legal Thought:</B><P>

During the first seven weeks of the seminar, the instructor will assign to and discuss with his students, photocopied materials on American legal thought.  Topics such as History of Legal Education Formalism, Economic Instrumentalism, Realism Reasoned Elaboration, and Critical Legal Studies are included.  During the final seven weeks of the semester, students give presentations on the papers they are preparing for the course.  The final paper can be submitted to satisfy the Upperclass Writing Requirement.<P>

If the requisite number of students do not sign up, the instructor may offer a modified version of the course for several students under the course title Independent Legal Research. (2 credits)<P>

<I>3 credits;  Professor Chester</I><P>

<A NAME="c22">
<B>Perspectives:  Estate and Trust Administration:</B><P>

This course deals with the process of probate and trust administration.  The probate system was developed in order to pay creditors of the decedent and make distributions of the decedent's property in an orderly way.  Formal probate has become time-consuming and costly.  Various alternatives to formal probate are discussed including summary probate and independent administration.  Also discussed are ways to avoid probate altogether through will substitutes such as revocable living trusts.  Finally, revocable living trusts are compared with testamentary trusts with regard to their characteristics and administration.<P>

<I>2 credits; Professor Chester</I><P>

<A NAME="c23">
<B>Perspectives:  Property Theory and Concepts:</B><P>

This course will undertake an intellectual in-depth study of property issues.   The readings will include political and historical analyses of U. S. property law, and a study of modern trends in American property concepts.  Students will also examine property concepts as they exist in other cultures.<P>

<I>2 credits; Professors Dussias and Manus</I><P>

<A NAME="c24"> 
<B>Perspectives: Contemporay Popular Criticism of American Lawyers and the Legal System:</B><P>

In recent years, many Americans have accepted the view that the legal system constitutes a burden to business, negatively influences harmonious social relations, and fails to provide justice.  The course will examine the accuracy of selected and influential ideas driving contemporary criticism.  Students will analyze data and commentary on such issues as the existence of a lawyer "glut," the relationship between lawyers per capita and GNP, the impact of lawyers and tort law on health-related industries, the link between due process rights and crime rates, the relationship between law and a perceived cultural misemphasis on blame in lieu of personal responsibility, and the law's influence as a normative force in society.  An elementary knowledge of statistics will be helpful but not required.<P>

<I>2 credits;  Professor Teich</I><P>

<A NAME="c25">
<B>Taxation of Business Entities (New Course 1997):</B><P>

This course compares and contrasts the tax treatment of the various legal forms of business organization.  The main contrast is between the double-level tax treatment of regular C Corporations and the single-level treatment of S Corporations, partnerships and the relatively new limited liability company.  The course takes a transactional approach and voers the formation operation and liquidation of the various business entities.<P>

This course is intended for students who are interested in specializing in tax as well as students who have an interest in a general business practice.<P>

<I>Prerequisites:  Personal Income tax and Business Organizations</I><P>

<I>4 credits</I><P>

