<UL>
<LI>Credit Requirements per semester:  9 minimum - 12 maximum
<LI>No required courses, all electives
</UL>
<P>

<A NAME="rec">
<H3>Strongly Recommended Courses:</H3>

The following upper-level courses are strongly recommended by the faculty to be taken by all students prior to graduation:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Administrative Law
<LI>Business Organizations
<LI>Personal Income Taxation 
<LI>Wills, Estates & Trusts
</UL>
<P>

In the Evening, Personal Income Tax and Business Organizations are offered in the Fall semester and Administrative Law and Wills, Estates & Trusts are offered in the Spring semester.<P>

The Evening Division schedule is arranged so that students in their third year can take 
Business Organizations, Personal Income Taxation and Commercial Paper during the Fall semester and Administrative Law, Wills, Estates & Trusts, and Secured Transactions during the Spring semester.<P>

Evening students who intend to take Estate Planning in their fourth year must take WET in the spring semester of their third year as this is a prerequisite for Estate Planning.<P>

<B>Students interested in specializing in Taxation are advised to schedule accordingly:</B><P>


<TABLE BORDER>
<TR>
<TH> </TH>
<TH>Fall</TH>
<TH>Spring</TH>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>Second Year Day</TD>
<TD>Personal Income Taxation Business Organizations</TD>
<TD>Corporate Taxation & Partnership & Subchapter S Taxation (these courses have been replaced with: Taxation of Business Entities)</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>Third Year Evening</TD>
<TD>Personal Income Taxation Business Organizations</TD>
<TD>Corporate Taxation,Partnership & Subchapter S Taxation (These courses have been replaced with: Taxation of Business Entities)</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>Third Year Day</TD>
<TD> </TD>
<TD>Advanced Corporate Taxation Business Planning</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>Fourth Year Evening</TD>
<TD> </TD>
<TD>Advanced Corporate Taxation Business Planning</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
<P>

Corporate Income Taxation (replaced in 1997 by Taxation of Business Entities) is strongly recommended for all students considering a business-oriented or tax-oriented practice.  The Tax Clinic is also recommended for students interested in specializing in Taxation.  Personal Income Taxation is a Pre/Co-Requisite for the Tax Clinic.<P>

Students who have taken either Corporate Taxation or Partnership and Sub-Chapter S Taxation cannot take the new course, Taxation of Business Entities.  Enrollment in either of the courses being replaced by Taxation of Business Entities precludes subsequent enrollment in the new course.  Students may still elect to take only Corporate Tax or Partnership (but not both) during the semester these courses will be offered for the last time. (Spring, 1997)<P>

<A NAME="altern">
<H3>Courses offered in Alternate Years:</H3>

The following courses will be offered in alternate years as indicated:

<UL>
<LI>Admiralty (offered 1996/97)
<LI>Antitrust (offered 1996/97)
<LI>Computer Law (offered 1997/98)
<LI>Education and the Law (offered 1997/98)
<LI>Legislation (offered 1997/98)
<LI>Military Justice (offered 1996/97)
</UL>
<P>

<A NAME="transfer">
<H3>Transfer Between Divisions:</H3>

A student may request a transfer from the day to the evening division or evening to the day division provided such student submits a student request form to the Associate/Assistant Dean by April First prior to the academic year for which transfer is sought.  Approval for such transfers will only be granted in extraordinary circumstances.  If approval of the Associate/ Assistant Dean is obtained, the fact of the transfer should be noted on subsequent registration forms submitted by the student.  There is a division transfer fee of $100.00.<P>

<A NAME="student">
<H3>Student Employment:</H3>

A full-time student is defined as "a student who devotes substantially all of his/her working hours to the study law" (ABA Standards for Approval of Law Schools, Standard 305(a)(iii)).  Standard 305(a)(iii) has been interpreted to mean that a student may not work in excess of 20 hours a week while attending law school on a full-time basis.  Requests by full-time students for special scheduling consideration because of employment will not be granted.<P>

<A NAME="bar">
<H3>Bar Course Requirements:</H3>

On the following pages is a listing of bar course requirements for following states.  Use this information as you deem appropriate when scheduling your courses<P>

Listed in parentheses are the New England School of Law courses in which a student is most likely to encounter the corresponding subject matter.  Students should note, however, that this listing is not a representation that the courses listed cover all topics in the corresponding bar categories.  Preparation for a particular jurisdiction's bar examination is best accomplished through a reputable bar review course which covers the law of that jurisdiction.<P>

