<p>

<p>

<h4><a name="General Information">General Information</a></h4>
<P>The <I>New England International and Comparative Law Annual </I>is proud to publish  its third volume at the New England School of Law.   The Journal was established in 1994 as an in-house publication.   After the publication of its second volume, in 1996, the law school faculty voted to make the <I>Annual </I>available on the Internet.  As a young, experimental enterprise, the Annual has a small staff and limited resources.  The articles tend to be short pieces, written by students, which focus on provocative and current issues in the fields of international and comparative law.  While the <I>Annual </I>is intended to be less formal than a conventional law journal, we think that you will find the information, thoughts, and analysis contained in its articles to be interesting and useful.  Furthermore,  the <I>Annual </I>plays a significant role in NESL's new Center for International Law and Policy.  Volume 4 of the <I>Annual,</I> which will be available on the Internet in May 1997, will feature  the text of a speech about the controversial Helms-Burton (Cuban Sanctions) Act, which was delivered at the Center's first function by Nicholas Rostow, formerly Chief Counsel of the National Security Council and  currently Executive Director of the Massachusetts Office of International Trade and Investment.</P>

<p>

<p>

<h4><a name="Forthcoming Issues">Forthcoming Issues</a></h4>
Volume 3 of the <i>New England International and Comparative Law Annual</i> will be published
April 15, 1997.  It will be available on the World Wide Web shortly thereafter.<p>

<a href="#top">Return to top</a><p>

<p>

<h4><a name="Submission of Articles">Submission of Student Written Articles</a></h4>
Students wishing to submit an article which concerns International or Comparative Law should mail both a
hard copy (double spaced, 20-50 pages) and a copy on diskette (Word Perfect 5.1/5.2) to the
<i>Annual</i> at the address below.  Text and footnotes in the <i>Annual</i> conform to the latest editions of
<i>The Bluebook: A Uniform System of Citation</i>, except where common sense dictates otherwise. 
The editors of the Annual verify the accuracy of all footnotes that cite to sources accessible
through the National Inter-Library Loan System, as well as those sources unavailable in the
United States which can be obtained within a reasonable time.<p>

