<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Business Transactions for Lawyers -  Professor Salter</H2>
<H3>Meeting Times:  Tuesday - Friday  9:00 - 9:55</H3><H4>Fall, 1996</H4>

</CENTER>
<A NAME = "TOP">
<HR noshade>

<H5>Information:</H5>
     <PRE>
     Office Hours: Tuesdays & Thursdays 10 - 2, and by appointment

     Office Phone: 422-7275   (evenings OK)

     Email:   Salter@world.std.com    Or ssalter@fac.nesl.edu

     Home Phone (weekends): 416/422-5685

</PRE>



<H5>Required Text:   </H5>

    <PRE> Hamilton, Money Management for Lawyers and Clients (1993)

                      ISBN   0-316-34131-2

First Assignment:   Hamilton 3 - 19

          Be prepared to discuss in class a comparison of
               
               - a $10,000 student loan for tuition 
               - a commercial loan for $10,000 (Form 1-1)
               - bank loan of $10,000 to purchase a car     
                         (Forms 1-2, 1-3)
               
                 Compare on the following points:
                    qualification of borrower for loan
                    lending institutions
                    terms - rate of interest
                            period for repayment
                            prepayment penalties
                    guarantee 
                    collateral
                              possession of collateral
                              right to income/use of collateral
                    assignability
                    events that trigger acceleration of
                              collection of debt

     Key Terms and Concepts:
          
      principal
      simple interest                         compound interest
      variable interest rates        "locked in" interest rates
      down payment on a purchase                 term of a loan
      present value                                future value
      APR                          Federal Truth in Lending Act
      note, security interest, lien, collateral
      security agreement, financing statement 
      perfection of security interest by filing; by possession
      default, insolvency, bankruptcy
      assignability, negotiability, indorser
      holder in due course rights
      foreclosure, deficiency judgment
      small claims courts
      repossession
</PRE>
<CENTER>

