<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Business Transactions for Lawyers -  Professor Salter</H2>
<H2>Handout  4 - Assignment 3</H2>
<H3>Meeting Times:  Tuesday - Friday  9:00 - 9:55</H3><H4>Fall, 1996</H4>

</CENTER>
<A NAME = "TOP">
<HR noshade>
<PRE>
Handouts to date
     
     Handout No.  1    First Assignment

     Handout No.  2. 
               A.  Schedule of Assignments
               B.  Proposal for Evaluation
     
     Handout No.  3.  Second Assignment


Handout No.  4.  Third Assignment: Hamilton 59 - 77

   Be prepared to discuss in class

     What kind of information is in a credit report?

     Are you likely to have a national credit file?

     Can it be retrieved by 

          A landlord from whom you seek to rent?  After you are a tenant?
          A bank or store when you ask for a loan?  While you owe a loan?
          An auto dealer when you seek to lease a car?  During the lease?
          A prospective employer?   A current employer?  A past employer?
                         A person who is considering hiring you for legal services?
          A lawyer whom you have asked to represent you in a tort claim?
          Your spouse?   Your ex - spouse?   The IRS?
          A person who has ansered your kinky "personals" ad?
          Your mother's new boyfriend?
          You?

     Can you find out who has asked for your file? 

     What did the Fair Credit Reporting Act of 1971 (federal) give to consumers
          that they did not have before?

     Is it a good idea to avoid credit transactions, dealing only with cash, as a rule?
          Explain why, or why not.

     What is a "secured" credit card?

     When do you have an opportunity to examine your files for errors?

     Explain briefly the procedures to follow if you discover errors.

     What are the liabilities of the credit reporting agency for failure to take
          reasonable steps tocorrect errors that are proved by documentation?
          Is there another standard if the consumer disputes the point in the
               report, but documentation is not available to prove or 
               disprove the accuracy of the alleged error?

     What identifying information is used to collect information on an individual?

     What credit-relevant information is usually requested on a loan application?

     What outcomes may result from lying on a loan application?

     Why do most lenders use the "cash flow" approach in deciding whether to
          extend credit rather than the "pounce" approach?  

     List likely goals of a savings plan (p.  69) for persons in the following positions

          A law student with living employed parents,
               no children, no car, no house.

          A bookkeeper with one living employed parent, two children, and
               no child support payments, no house.

          A thirty-something business person with an unemployed spouse,
               two children, and one living retired parent in good health.

          A fifty-something lawyer with an unemployed spouse, two grown
               employed children, and two living retired parents in poor health.

          Bambi; Rocky the squirrel

Keeping track of expenditures vs.  Saving windfalls.

Why does the author counsel against making important investment decisions in times of stress?
          Why does he not list divorce/separation as a stressful event?
          Why does he not list marriage as such an event?
          What other stressful events can you suggest that might impair judgment?


  </PRE>

