<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Civil Procedure "E" -- Professor Cox Intro. to Course</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A NAME = "top">
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2> CIVIL PROCEDURE "E" --  PROFESSOR COX</H2>
<H3>  INTRODUCTION TO COURSE</H3>
<H4>  M 6-7:10 & Th 6:55-8:15<BR>
                       ROOM 304; FALL '96</H4>
</CENTER>

<HR noshade>

<BR>
                              	
<H4>Introduction </H4>                  
Casebook is Marcus, Redish & Sherman, Civil Procedure: A Modern
Approach (West 2d Ed. 1995).  I am recommending the print and
electronic version for all who have regular access to a computer
which can support the software (see ASystem Requirements@ on the
package before purchasing).<BR>
Statutory Supplement is O'Connor's Federal Rules (Jones McClure
1996).<BR>
Also required is Stern, The Buffalo Creek Disaster (Vintage
1976).<BR>
Highly recommended are one or more of the following:<BR>
     Freer & Perdue, Civil Procedure: Cases, Materials and
     Questions (Anderson 1996);<BR>
     Friedenthal, Kane & Miller, Civil Procedure (Hornbook
     Series) (West, 2d Ed. 1993);<BR>
     Glannon, Civil Procedure: Examples & Explanations (Little
     Brown, 2d Ed. 1992);<BR>
     Shreve & Raven-Hansen, Understanding Civil Procedure
     (Matthew Bender, 2d Ed. 1994);<BR>
     Tepley & Whitten, Civil Procedure (University Textbook
     Series) (Foundation Press 1994).<P>


<H4>What this course is about</H4>
     In your other courses you will be learning the content of
substantive law (e.g., what kind of conduct could lead to a tort
suit; when is a contract enforceable and what remedies can be had
for breach). CivPro does not have similar substantive content.
Instead, this course deals with issues such as where suits can be
brought and how they can be conducted (e.g., what kinds of
motions can be filed, whether and how to get information from
other parties; whether and how additional issues and parties can
be brought into a suit).<P>
     Procedure, however, can determine outcomes, and jurisdiction
(whether the court can hear the case) is power. One of the goals
of this course is to help you understand that regardless of the
content of the underlying law about which you and your client so
deeply care, if you sue in the wrong court or fail to properly
use the processes which the court provides, you will not even get
to have any substantive law applied to your case.  From a
defendant's perspective, this avoidance of getting to trial or to
the merits might become the goal of the litigation, if the
substantive law would eventually be unfavorable.  From a
plaintiff's perspective, getting to the right court, keeping
defendants in suits who don't want to be there, or forcing
defendants to hand over information they would prefer to keep to
themselves may trigger settlement of suits apart from the other
underlying merits of the action.<P>
     I want you not only to come to understand how the rules of
procedure work (and how you therefore as a potential litigator
might be able to work the rules); I also want you to develop an
opinion about whether these seem like "good" rules of how a court
system should operate. This means asking at least two types of
related questions about particular rules or doctrines of
procedure:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>
 1) do they make logical and good policy sense in their
own terms by adequately addressing the concerns which they claim
to address; 
<LI>2) do they leave out important issues which should be
addressed but won't be once the rules become the way of doing
things.
</UL>
     CivPro thus gets you very soon into some pretty "heady"
considerations of how judicial power should be shared or parceled
out in a federal system, and what goals can and should be
accomplished through the court system. I will test on these
"should" aspects of the course in addition to whether you know
what the "rules" are.<P>

<H4>Readings</H4>
     A list of <A HREF="civrdgse.htm">"Expected Reading Assignments"</A> is available with
this syllabus. The list is subject to modification, but gives an
idea of what I hope to cover this semester.<P>
     Your Marcus Redish & Sherman casebook comes in either print
plus electronic or print only format.  The electronic version is
optional, but I strongly encourage many of you to buy and use it
so we can experiment and find out if the electronic links really
do help us more quickly absorb note material and other info to
which the casebook might lead us. In addition to the casebook....<P>
     The O'Connor's Federal Rules includes both the text of the
rules and a lengthy practitioner's guide at the front which you
may find helpful as an additional study aid. I include page
assignments from the guide with other optional readings in the
supplemental readings section of assignments.<P>
     The Buffalo Creek book is designed to give you at least one
real life litigation example against which to bounce and apply
the concepts, doctrines and rules encountered in the course. The
book will be used both semesters. You should feel free to read it
all now even though only the first portions are required in the
first semester. (The remainder will become Christmas break
reading if you haven't read it by then ). As with almost all
other materials assigned in this course, especially cases, you
should not accept the perspective of the writer as being the only
way to approach the problems raised by the writer, nor should you
unskeptically accept the writer's view of what he thought was the
best thing to do as necessarily correct. Read all materials in
this course critically.<P>
     The highly recommended materials are not required to be
purchased, but you should strongly consider investing in one of
them (and having others available in your study group).  Reading
assignments from any of these highly recommended books are not
required. Nevertheless, I provide these in some detail on the
syllabus because students find CivPro to be a particularly
difficult course (see, e.g., Marcus, Redish & Sherman at iii;
Glannon at ix). Regular recourse to some form of supplemental
material can help.  Hearing the same thing said in several
different ways (i.e. from several different sources) may make
things finally click.<P>
     I include the Freer & Perdue book on the recommended list as
an alternative casebook and as an additional source of problems
to help sharpen your understanding of the material.  I will
periodically post the answers to some of these problems to our
discussion bulletin board if several students end up buying the
book. The order of coverage in the Freer & Perdue book is also
closer to my own organization of the material, and Prof. Perdue's
approach especially, to many of the issues, is close to my own.
As I prepare individual lessons, I will be using this book along
with the Marcus, Redish & Sherman text.<P>
     Two of the other sources listed (Shreve & Raven-Hansen;
Glannon) have been particularly popular sellers through the NESL
bookstore in past years.  The Glannon book, although somewhat
dated in parts, and although it does not cover all aspects of the
course, has particularly good problems and explanations for the
things it does cover.  The Shreve & Raven-Hansen book provides
solid and readable hornbook type coverage of almost all the
material covered in the course.<P>
     The Friedenthal, Kane & Miller book is a slightly more
detailed but still very readable treatise type hornbook.
Although less well known, the Tepley & Whitten hornbook offers
similarly comprehensive and readable coverage, plus numerous
illustrations (modeled along restatement lines) that provide
concrete examples of the principles being covered. I plan to
consult some of the Tepley & Whitten illustrations when
constructing my own hypotheticals.<P>
     A slightly more theoretical treatment of issues can be found
in James, Hazard & Leubsdorf, Civil Procedure (Little Brown, 4th
Ed. 1992), for those willing to delve deeper (be aware, however,
that this treatise predates any 1993 rules changes).  Truly
comprehensive treatment of CivPro issues can be found in the
multi-volume treatise by Wright, Miller et al., which is worth
consulting if you want to dig deeply into the case law in any
particular area.  For quick and dirty black letter summaries of
the law, you might look at Clermont, Civil Procedure (West Black
Letter Series, 4th Ed. 1995) (it comes with a diskette version
from which you can build and modify your own outlines) or Kane,
Civil Procedure in a Nutshell (1996); I welcome information of
what other published sources you find helpful, so I can share
what works with future students.<P>
     Do not expect "magic bullets" from any of your study aides,
however.  No secondary source can successfully transform complex
ideas into simple ones. There are two ways in which the material
in CivPro (and many other law school courses) is difficult. At
the first level, a good secondary source can give you answers.
Thus, when the problem is decoding a statute's words, or
understanding what a doctrine is supposed to mean in its own
terms, a good secondary source may help you "translate" legal
conversation or doctrine into easier terms and/or cause you to
assimilate concepts through repetition and/or application. This
understanding of what the law says or what the rules are is only
half the battle, however. (Hopefully as you become proficient in
the language of the law, many of your "translation" problems will
diminish -- look around Thanksgiving at a case that gives you
fits now, and you'll be surprised how much your "legal reading
comprehension" skills have improved).<P>
     The second kind of difficulty involved in reading law school
material is inherent in the nature of the issues raised by the
material.  In much of the law there are no clear answers.  This
being so, it is no good to keep banging your head against the
books looking for them. A good secondary source instead helps you
become comfortable with legal lack of certainty.  The
clarification and reinforcement which a secondary source provides
on this second level is to get you increasingly comfortable with
the idea that, where there is no one firm answer, there still may
be agreement about what are the key questions and what are the
different possible answers to these questions.  Your goal in such
situations is to learn how to make alternative arguments, and to
learn how to explore the consistency and implications of these
possible arguments.<P>
     Although the above two layers of difficulty are present in
all law school courses, CivPro is deemed by most students a
particularly difficult course.  One reason is unavoidable when
CivPro is taught in the first year, as it is at most law schools.
The CivPro course, since it is has no independent substantive
content, must always depend on the substantive material you will
study in other courses to provide grist for its procedural mills.
The cases you read in CivPro are never just about civil
procedure, they are also about contract law, employment law,
property law, constitutional law, tort law, etc. And the problem
is, of course, that you have not yet learned the content of these
other subjects.  Your CivPro readings cannot be stripped of
substantive context and still make sense. This is true both as a
practical matter, and often also because the substantive law
context of the case is important to understanding the effect or
purpose of the civil procedure doctrine or rule.  In other words,
sometimes the civil procedure rules are the way they are because
of their interrelation with the substantive content of other
courses.  What this means for you now, however, is that CivPro is
asking twice as much of you as your other courses, for you must
assimilate both substantive and procedural meat for this course.
While the substantive knowledge thus gained in CivPro hopefully
will reinforce your substantive knowledge in your other courses
(when you later there again encounter the substantive ideas in
more detail), that doesn't make it any easier for you now in the
CivPro course.<P>
     A second reason CivPro probably is deemed particularly
difficult is because it is the course which is most Aforeign@ to
newcomers and is most an Ainsiders@ course (i.e. a lawyer's
course).  You probably walk into law school with some
preconceived notions, or at least some feel for what the debate
should look like, regarding when people ought to have to pay
others for harms they cause (e.g., Torts) or when they ought to
be forced to keep their promises or do something (such as pay
damages) if they break their promises (e.g., Contracts).  Very
few of you walk into law school with any appreciation or feel for
why the rules and doctrines of procedure make a tremendous
difference in outcomes, or what procedural rules and doctrines
should look like.  Learning and thinking about such things begins
your transformation from layperson into lawyer. CivPro, probably
more than any of your other courses, demands that you start
thinking like a lawyer in order to understand what is going on in
the course.<P>

<H4>Preparation for Class</H4>
     I expect all students to be prepared for all class periods
and will feel free to call on students randomly. This is true
regarding all assignments, even in situations when I may pre-
assign some material to particular students or groups of students
for the next class period. Although pre-assigned students should
be especially prepared to "carry the ball" for the material
assigned, other students (the remainder of the class) can be
expected to be called on to reinforce, explain, clarify, explore
or disagree with the points brought out in regard to the same
material. I will also always feel free to call on students who
have previously recently been called upon.<P>
     Class participation will be included in the final grade for
the course, leading to a possible + or - adjustment to the final
grade for exceptionally strong or exceptionally weak class
performance (e.g., a B on the final exam could be adjusted on the
basis of class participation to a BB or a B-). Be ready to
contribute productively to the class.<P>
     As you prepare for class, ask yourself questions such as:
Why was this particular case or reading assigned -- what point(s)
should I be getting out of this reading beyond the importance of
the litigation to the particular participants? Which particular
facts, if any, are important to the court's (or writer's)
reasoning -- if those facts were changed, how would that (would
it?) affect the point being made? How does the point of this
reading reinforce, contradict, or complement points made through
other readings in the course -- if there is contradiction,
especially on the same issue, which position seems best? Are
there issues or material the writer is leaving out or failing to
address that might be important -- what alternatives would
thereby become more persuasive if these other factors were
considered?<P>
     To be ready for class discussions, you must understand the
material assigned to a pretty good degree before class starts.
This is not the kind of course where you can come to class hoping
passively that the material will be handed to you.  For most of
you, CivPro will only start to make sense when you come to class
having wrestled with the readings beforehand.  You should show up
ready to apply concepts from the readings to fact patterns you
have not seen before, and ready to discuss purposes behind CivPro
doctrines and rules. This means you must be solid before class
about what concepts and facts are in your readings.  To do this
you will often need to read the material assigned more than once,
sometimes in conjunction with a hornbook or other study aid.  So
long as you eventually Aown@ the material, as proven by your
ability to use it, explain it, and criticize it, I do not care
how you come to possess this knowledge.<P>

<H4>Out of Class Exercises</H4>
     Multiple choice exercises, problem sets, or other
assignments may be administered periodically throughout the
semester as a way for both me and you to check your knowledge of
some of the concepts we have encountered or will be encountering
in the course. Some of these assignments will be mandatory;
others are optional. Your performance on these assignments will
not directly count towards your grade, except that failure to
complete a mandatory exercise will count negatively towards the
class participation portion of your grade. A substantial
percentage of my mid-year (and final exam) multiple choice
questions (it has been at least 50% in the past) are taken
verbatim from or are modified versions of exercises handed out or
assigned during the course.
<P>
<H4>Mid-year Exam</H4>
     Your mid-year exam will be a combination essay and multiple
choice exam, and will count 30% of your final grade for the
course. This mid-year exam will be a two to three hour exam, with
one to three essay questions and 16 - 24 multiple choice
questions.

<H4>Out of Class Questions</H4>
     NESL prides itself on being a place where effective
classroom teaching takes place, but there are inevitably times
when what is covered or discussed in class does not make sense at
the time, and/or that you will wish to explore things covered in
class in more detail out of class. I encourage such explorations
and want all of you to become CivPro gurus.<P>
     There are at least two ways out-of-class explorations can
occur: 1) electronically, and 2) face to face.  We will be
experimenting fairly extensively this semester with an electronic
bulletin board for our course. So that you can ask more
questions, so that others can benefit from your questions, and so
that there is equal access and efficient use of all our time, I
encourage you to ask questions electronically before setting up
any face to face appointments.  You can e-mail questions to the
bulletin board any time you are at the law school by logging on
at the workstations in the Computer Media Center (CMC), located
in the library basement. The Netscape PCs (just outside the CMC)
also provide telnet access to student accounts. Ask anyone who is
on duty at the CMC for help in using the machines and obtaining
access to the bulletin board.  You can also log on remotely if
you are equipped with internet access at work or at home (your
computer needs to have a modem and some kind of terminal
software, such as Procomm, etc).<P>
     The address of our bulletin board will be:<I> civpro-cox@nesl.edu</I>. Our electronic bulletin board will be a <U>closed</U>
list, meaning that only members of our class can post to and read
from the list.  This means that the first time you use our
electronic bulletin board you must join the list. To do this,
log onto the computer (for telnet use) and send an e-mail message
to: <I>civpro-cox-request@nesl.edu</I>.  In the body of the message put
<I>subscribe </I>. You can then use our civpro bulletin
board to read and send messages. If you encounter any problems in
getting onto or using the electronic bulletin board for our
course, ask any of the staff in the CMC for help. If your problem
is a fairly technical one (beyond how do I) and/or if you think
there is a problem in the system itself, you should ask John
Francis or Tabor Wells to look into it so that our system can be
fully operational for all students.<P>
     When you post messages to the list, you may post
anonymously, use a pseudonym, or identify yourself -- whichever
you prefer. To post anonymously, you may need to follow special
instructions which the library staff is in the process of
developing, but which should not be too complicated. When a
question is posted by a student to the list, you should try your
hand at answering it or discussing it on the list for the benefit
of all. I will lurk on the list and periodically make comments
on questions and discussions that appear on the list, after there
has been some student discussion. I will also periodically post
questions, answers, assignments, and other material to the list,
so you need periodically to sign on and see what is going on.<P>
     Apart from the list, you may also query me directly by
sending an electronic message to my personal e-mail address:
<I>scox@fac.nesl.edu</I>, but I will probably refer any CivPro questions
to the CivPro list, and delay my answer until later to that list.
Therefore, unless your question involves something other than
course-related material, it makes sense to send course-related
questions to the list first. Should you encounter any difficulty
in posting to the list or receiving info from the list, you
should contact the library staff, especially those in the CMC.
You can also try the special e-mail address for problems:
<I>problems@nesl.edu</I>.<P>
     In addition to electronic contact, you are welcome to make
office visits. For any such face to face appointments, please do
the following: 1) Write down your question(s) in advance and
bring your writing with you to our face to face meeting. This
writing doesn't need to be long or particularly formal, but you
do need to have something in writing. Writing down your concerns
or questions will help you more efficiently identify what it is
that confuses you or what it is about which you wish to know
more.  Additionally, the writing (which you should leave with me)
will give me a written reminder of what troubled at least one
member of the class. I can then share later with the class by
posting to the bulletin board (anonymously, so far as you are
concerned) some of these areas of concern, plus any answers we
were able to develop, all of which might be helpful to your
fellow class members. 2) Please also ask your question(s) of one
or more of your classmates before coming to any face to face
meeting (if you have posted your question to the bulletin board,
you have done this). I especially encourage questions that have
come out of study group sessions, and I encourage office hour
team visits by several students at the same time. While you are
certainly welcome also to visit alone, your visit should usually
be as partial proxy for others who share the same concern and who
will want to hear you report back to them with more questions or
answers.<P>
     My office hours for face to face meetings will be: Monday
1:00 to 4:00 p.m. and Thursday 2:30- 5:30 p.m. Face to face
appointments at other times, given sufficient advance planning,
are welcomed.  My office is Room 432 (past the faculty
secretaries' work area, in the corridor where faculty restrooms
are located).  Electronic questions can, of course, be posted at
any time. We will also probably periodically hold some group
question and answer sessions if we can find good time slots and
available evening classroom space.<P>


     Welcome to law school and to Civil Procedure! Bring your
enthusiasm, curiosity and dedication, and I hope to convince you
that CivPro is the first year subject you should come to know and
love.

