     The following list of expected reading assignments is
subject to modification during the semester. Updated assignment
sheets may be placed on the electronic bulletin board or handed
out in class; in-class oral announcements may also be made as
necessary during the semester to modify or supplement the
assignments here given. Because so many different books are
included on this reading list, it is also quite possible that
some page number errors or omissions may be present on these
sheets; please draw any errors to my attention ASAP for the
benefit of the entire class.<P>

<H4>I. Introduction to Forum Shopping 101</H4>
<H5>Assignment for Monday, 8/26:</H5>
<UL>

   <LI> <I> Read:</I> <BR>    Buffalo Creek pp ix-69 (Prologue plus chs I-VI);
          My main focus will be the legal issues raised in Ch VI
          (pp 52-69); you need to read the preliminary chapters
          so you will have enough factual information to know
          what this suit is potentially about.
    <LI> <I>Assignment:</I><BR>    Identify the legal issues being considered by
               the plaintiffs' attorney in Chapter VI about how
               he should bring suit. Be ready to talk in class
               about these legal issues, and be ready to refer to
               specific portions of the Buffalo Creek text for
               support.

    <LI><I> Foci: </I>  <BR>  Introduction to the strategy of procedure;
          overview of the civil litigation process

     <LI><I>Supplemental Readings:</I> <BR>You might find helpful, for this
     assignment, one or more of the following:<BR>
	<UL>
	<LI> Federal Rules pp 47-48
	<LI>          Freer & Perdue pp 1-12; 16-21
	<LI>          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 1-7
	<LI>          Glannon pp 417-21 (for a more full overview of what
happens in civil litigation, you might find helpful the rest of Ch 25)
	<LI>          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 17-21
	</UL>
</UL>


<H4>II. The Subject Matter Jurisdiction of Federal Courts
    (Why do we call them courts of limited jurisdiction?)</H4>

<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 8/29:</H5>
  <UL>
<LI><I> Read</I>: <BR>    Federal Rules p 814  (28 U.S.C. Sections 1331 &
     1332);<BR>
          Handout (U.S. Const., Art. III, Sections 1 & 2 [1] &
          [2]; Art. VI [2])<BR>
   <LI><I>  Skim:</I> <BR>    Federal Rules pp 814-22, looking for other
          examples of original jurisdiction and at least one
          example of "exclusive" jurisdiction.<BR>
    <LI><I> Pre-read:</I><BR> Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 837-53 (including
     notes).  Although we will not cover some of this material in
     detail until Tuesday, it makes sense to initially read the
     material as a block.<BR>
    <LI><I> Read: </I> <BR>   Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 837-47 (including
notes);
          any supplemental case(s) or problem sets on diversity
          jurisdiction

   <LI> <I> Foci: </I>  <BR>  Explore what it means to describe federal courts
          as courts of limited jurisdiction; explore the limits
          on diversity jurisdiction.

    <LI><I> Supplemental Readings</I>:<BR> You might find helpful, for this
     assignment, one or more of the following:
          <UL>
<LI>Federal Rules pp 73; 77-84
<LI>          Freer & Perdue pp 165-91; 259-61 (don't worry about the
<LI>          collateral attack issues; we will return to these in
<LI>          the second semester)
<LI>          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 8-13; 23-51
<LI>          Glannon pp 55-70
<LI>          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 101-06; 111-23
<LI>          Tepley & Whitten pp 48-56; 59-63; 83-112
</UL>
</UL>  

