</UL>
</UL>

<H4>IV. The Muddle Called Personal Jurisdiction</H4>

<H4>Part One: Territoriality</H4>


<H5>Assignment for Monday, 9/30:</H5>
    <UL>
<LI>
<I> Read:</I><BR> Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 666-82 (including notes)

    <LI><I> Foci:</I> <BR>    Pennoyer and the territorial power theory of
          personal jurisdiction;
          applying Pennoyer and exploring its limitations

     <LI><I>Supplemental Readings:</I><BR> You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
         <UL>
<LI> Freer & Perdue pp 25-37
<LI>          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 95-101; 106-20
<LI>          Glannon pp 3-21 (this plus next 2 assignments)
<LI>          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 23-30 (Skip [B][2] for now);
         pp 41-46;
<LI>          Tepley & Whitten pp 220-60
</UL>
</UL>

<H4>Part Two: Introduction to Minimum Contacts
</H4>
<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 10/3:</H5>
   <UL>
<LI>
  <I>Read:</I>  <BR>   Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 682-97 (including
          notes);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 800-02

    <LI><I> Foci:  </I>  <BR> the shift to International Shoe's minimum contacts
          approach; litigating jurisdictional disputes

     <LI><I>Supplemental Readings: </I><BR>You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
         <UL>
<LI> Freer & Perdue pp 37-48; 249-51 (we will examine Rule
        12 in more detail later, so don't worry about its
       intricacies for now); 256-59
<LI>          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 101-06; 120-29; 182-90;
        648 (paragraph in middle of page)
<LI>          Glannon pp 3-21
<LI>          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 46-51
<LI>          Tepley & Whitten pp
 261-65 (in some ways it makes sense
          to read all the way from 261 to 336, but perhaps this
          is only possible before exams -- Tepley & Whitten
          organize all the personal jurisdiction cases around
          some good unifying points and questions)
</UL></UL>
<H5>Assignment for Monday, 10/7:</H5>
    <UL>
<LI>
<I> Read:</I> <BR>    Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 697-705 (focus on Gray
          and the note cases for the Astream of commerce@ issues
          for this day=s assignment);
          any supplemental case, problem set or other assignment
     given

   <LI><I>  Foci: </I><BR>    applying and trying to understand the implications
          of International Shoe's minimum contacts approach (take
          #1 of several takes); introduction to personal
          jurisdiction problems in Astream of commerce@
          situations
     <LI><I>Supplemental Readings: </I><BR>You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
         <UL>
<LI> Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 135-38 (we will be
looking at some of these cases in more detail later)
<LI>          Glannon pp 3-21
<LI>          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 51-53; 56-61;
<LI>          Tepley & Whitten pp 315-18 (plus see above re: reading
     more material as a block)
</UL>
</UL>
<H4>Part Three (An Aside): Concepts that Cut Across Minimum Contacts
Lines</H4>

<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 10/10:</H5>
 <PRE>    Read:     Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 697-705 (including
          notes) (focus on Gray and the notes following for the
          long arm statute interpretation issues for this day=s
          assignments);
          Federal Rules pp 492-95; 919-25 (FRCP
          4(e),(f),(h),(k),(m) & (n); Advisory Committee Notes to
          1993 Amendments));
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 705-07 (including notes);
          Omni Capital handout;
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
          assignments given

     Foci: state and federal long arm statutes; personal
     jurisdiction in federal courts

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 122-23; 112-13
          Freer & Perdue pp 61-62; 125-32
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 138-47; 162-66
          Glannon pp 23-40 (Ch 2)
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 25-27
          Tepley & Whitten pp 276-80; 348-50; 353-66
</PRE>
<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 10/17:</H5>
 <PRE>    Read:     Federal Rules pp 492-95 (FRCP 4);
          Federal Rules pp 599-600 (Forms 1, 1A & 1B);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 807-16 (including notes);
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
          assignments given

     Focus: Mullane notice requirements

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 97-111; 113
          Freer & Perdue pp 133-49
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 166-82
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 89-91; 94-99
          Tepley & Whitten pp 336-48; 350-53
</PRE>
<H4>Part Four: Continuing the Quest for the Meaning of Minimum
Contacts</H4>

<H5>Assignment for Monday, 10/21:</H5>
<PRE>     Read: Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 752-67 (including notes)

     Focus: Shaffer

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Freer & Perdue pp 95-108
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 148-61
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 61-70 (you may wish to skip
          [C][2] for now)
          Tepley & Whitten pp 265-71 (but see also above re:
          reading more material as a block)
</PRE>
<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 10/24:</H5>
  <PRE>   Read:     Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 789-96 (including
          notes);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 722-25 (including notes 1 &
          2);
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
assignments given

     Focus: general vs. specific jurisdiction

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 123-24
          Freer & Perdue pp 85-94
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 123-25
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 79-82; 30-32; 53-54
          Tepley & Whitten pp 282-90 (but see also above re:
          reading more material as a block)
</PRE>
<H5>Assignment for Monday, 10/28:</H5>
 <PRE>    [make law review article and/or case assignments, if this
     has not been done earlier]
     Read:     handout on other nations= approaches to personal
          jurisdiction;
          any other supplemental case(s), problem sets or
          assignments given

     Focus: consider whether the American approach to personal
     jurisdiction is enlightened or misguided

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Freer & Perdue pp 123-25
</PRE>

<H4>Part Five: More Principles that Apply Regardless of What Minimum
Contacts Means</H4>

<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 10/31:</H5>
<PRE>    Read:     Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 796-800 (including
          notes);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 802-06 (including notes);
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
assignments given

     Foci:     consent/waiver of personal jurisdiction
          objections; a forum selection clause=s impact on
          personal jurisdiction issues

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 124-25; 94-95
          Freer & Perdue pp 94-95
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 101-06; 158-60
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 32-36
          Tepley & Whitten pp 200-03; 307-08
</PRE> 
<H4>Part Six: Wallowing in the Muddle of Minimum Contacts</H4>

<H5>Assignment for Monday, 11/4:</H5>
  <PRE>  Read:     Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 707-22 (including
          notes);
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
assignments given

     Focus: applying and trying to understand the implications of
     International Shoe's minimum contacts approach: take #2 of
     several takes: WWVW and more -- of sovereignty,
     foreseeability and the stream of commerce (again)

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Freer & Perdue pp 49-61
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 129-36
          Glannon pp 3-21 (this plus next 2 assignments)
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 70-77
          Tepley & Whitten pp 293-95; 306-08 (but see also above
          re: reading more material as a block)
</PRE> 
<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 11/7:</H5>
  <PRE> Read:     Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 722-28 (including
          notes -- some of this is previously assigned material);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 728-43 (including notes);
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
assignments given

     Foci:     applying and trying to understand the implications
          of International Shoe's minimum contacts approach: take
          #3: Calder, Keeton and more -- exploring the effects
          test; take #4: does Burger King add two-part
          clarification or double confusion?

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Freer & Perdue pp 62-78
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 134-35; 145-47
          Glannon (see above)
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 86-88; pp 77-79;
          Tepley & Whitten pp 290-91; 297-98; 301-02; 310-22 (but
          see also above re: reading more material as a block)
</PRE>  
<H5>Assignment for Wednesday, 11/13:</H5>
    <PRE> Read:     Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 743-51 (including
          notes);
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
assignments given

     Focus: applying and trying to understand the implications of
     International Shoe's minimum contacts approach, take #5:
     total disagreement about stream of commerce in Asahi

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Freer & Perdue pp 78-85
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 136-38
          Glannon (see above)
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 83-86
          Tepley & Whitten pp 295-300 (but see also above re:
          reading more material as a block)
</PRE>
<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 11/14:</H5>
  <PRE>  Read: Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 771-89 (including notes)

     Focus: applying and trying to understand the implications of
     International Shoe's minimum contacts approach, take #6:
     Burnham's insanity, including disagreement about
     International Shoe basics

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Freer & Perdue pp 108-23
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 158-62
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 67-68 (although I disagree
          somewhat with the tone of this summary)
          Tepley & Whitten pp 271-76; 280-82; 327-29 (but see
          also above re: reading more material as a block)
</PRE> 
<H4>
V. Some Final Restrictions on (or Possibilities for) Forum
Shopping: Venue, Transfer and Forum non Conveniens
</H4>
<H5>Assignment for Monday, 11/18:</H5>
   <PRE>  Read:     Federal Rules p 821 (28 U.S.C. Sections 1391,
     1392);
          Federal Rules p 823 (28 U.S.C. Sections 1404, 1406);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 816-24 (including notes);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 767-71;
          supplemental materials on transfer (Hoffman and
          Goldlawr);
          supplemental materials on choice of law and transfer
          (Klaxon and Van Dusen);
          any other supplemental case(s), problem sets or
          assignments

     Foci:     venue, transfer of venue in the federal system,
          and intro to choice of law problems in the federal
          system

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 89-94; 96-97; 134-35
          Freer & Perdue pp 221-37
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 79-86; 90-92; 212-17
          Glannon pp 97-115
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 143-47, pp 148-53
          Tepley & Whitten pp 162-203 (especially 170ff); 214-18;
          406-08
</PRE>
<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 11/21:</H5>
   <PRE> Read:     Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 824-36 (including
          notes);
          any supplemental case(s), problem sets or other
assignments given

     Focus: forum non conveniens

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 135-38
          Freer & Perdue pp 238-48
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 86-89
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 148-50
          Tepley & Whitten pp 205-14
</PRE> 
<H5>Assignment for Monday, 11/25:</H5>
    <PRE> Read:     Federal Rules p 823 (28 U.S.C. Section 1404);
          supplemental materials on Stewart and Ferens

     Foci:     more on transfer of venue and federal choice of
          law problems, and further introduction to Aeerie@ Erie
          problems

     Supplemental Readings: You might find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Freer & Perdue pp 235-37
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 216-17
          Glannon pp 183 (for hypo facts Q#1); pp 185-87; 194-95
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 174-77 (although it doesn't
          address Stewart)
          Tepley & Whitten pp 409-13
</PRE>

<H4>VI. Getting the Law Suit Started (and Trying to Identify Policies
Behind and Effects of the Federal Rules) [this is the start of a
unit which will continue after the break]
</H4>
<H5>Assignment for Monday, 12/2:</H5>
  <PRE>  Read:     Federal Rules pp 491; 498-500; 502;  (Rules 1, 7,
          8, 10);
          Federal Rules pp 599; 600-602 (Forms 2, 4, 5, 9, 11,
          12);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 114-34 (including notes)

     Focus     - notice pleading

     Supplemental Readings: You may find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 49-53; 54-57
          Freer & Perdue pp 319-36; 342-46
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 238-56; 266-83
          Glannon pp 427-44
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 187-203; 212-15
          Tepley & Whitten pp 478-97 (=historical background);
          497-509 (=federal rules)
</PRE> 

 <H4>    Additional Assignment:</H4> 

<PRE>You will be asked to turn in, at the
beginning of class on Thursday, December 5, a portion of a draft
of a Complaint for one of the Plaintiffs in the Buffalo Creek
tragedy (you pick a person described in the book or invent a
fictitious victim, in line with descriptions in the book). Your
Complaint should be prepared as if you would eventually file in
Federal District Court for the Southern District of West
Virginia. You should allege two theories of liability: negligence
and negligence per se (for the negligence per se claim, don=t
worry about particular statutes --- make up hypothetical state or
federal coal mining statutes or just leave blanks). You will be
asked to compare your Complaint before turning it in on Thursday
with at least nine other CivPro students (combined study groups
OK) and submit for the group of ten or more students only one
Complaint, signed by all ten or more of you as attorneys for the
plaintiff, with each of you also thereby certifying that you
prepared individual drafts prior to comparing and combining (or
selecting best of the ten) as your submission for group credit.<P>

     You have already read enough of the Buffalo Creek book to
complete the above assignment. I will be making subsequent
assignments in the second semester under the assumption that you
have read the entire book.  If you have not done so, you should
therefore read the rest of the book over the semester break.<P>
</PRE>
<H5>Assignment for Thursday, 12/5:</H5>
   <PRE>  Read:     Federal Rules pp 499; 505-08  (Rules 8, 12, 13);
          Federal Rules pp 605-06 (Forms 19 & 20);
          Marcus, Redish & Sherman pp 170-72; 144-50; 180-96
          (including notes)

     Foci:     the defendant=s response; introduction to
          overlap/interrelation of pleadings with res adjudicata
          issues

     Supplemental Readings: You may find helpful for this
     assignment:
          Federal Rules pp 117-35; 138-52
          Freer & Perdue pp 350-57; 655-65 (don't worry too much
          about the technicalities of 1367 yet; we'll be
          returning to that statute in the 2d semester in greater
          detail); 249-56 (now's the time to look at this
          assignment a second time for the Rule 12 subtleties)
          Friedenthal, Kane & Miller pp 284-93; 295-302; 349-55;
          639-42
          Glannon pp 277-88
          Shreve & Raven-Hansen pp 215-27
          Tepley & Whitten pp 509-21; 887-91
</PRE>


<H4>Mid-year Exam (worth 30% of final grade):
     Thursday, Dec.19, 6:00 p.m.</H4>

Review sessions will be scheduled for times other than regular
class meeting times, and will include sessions during the reading
period.<BR><BR>
