<H1>Criminal Law - Section A -- Professor David Siegel</H1>
<H2> Syllabus (First Half) </H2>
<H3> Fall 1996</H3></CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>

           
                                
<H4>Materials:</H4>
<PRE>
CB = Casebook - Dressler
SM = Supplemental Materials (Duplicated)

Office: 407
     Hours: Office hours are as listed below.  Please feel free to drop by whenever you wish with
questions or comments.  If you need to meet sometime other than these hours, let me know and
I can schedule an appointment anytime.  I would like to personally meet everyone in the class,
so come by to introduce yourself at some point.

      Monday: 9:00 a.m. - 11:00 a.m.
      Tuesday: 2:00 p.m. - 4:00 p.m. 
      Wednesday: 2:00 p.m. - 4:00 p.m. 
      Thursday: 9:00 a.m. - 11:00 a.m.


Telephone: (617) 422-7270.  The local number is 270.  The number will roll to voicemail; please
leave a message.
 
Email: dsiegel@faculty.nesl.edu.  I will try to post notices or changes to everyone's email
address as well as in a traditional notice on the wall.  I check my email frequently, and
encourage you to send questions, comments or other thoughts via email.  

Materials: The case book is Cases and Materials on Criminal Law by Joshua Dressler (West). 
(There is no annual supplement to the casebook.)  Volume I of the supplemental materials has been
duplicated and is available in the bookstore.  Volume II is coming with this syllabus. 

Assignments: In addition to the exams, there will be three types of assignments for this course. 
Both written assignments (case brief and bench memo) must be typed.

1)  Reading assignments - Daily reading assignments are listed below.  Casebook readings are "CB,"
listed by pages.  Supplementary materials are "SM," listed by volume and page.  Some of the
readings are denoted as background ("Bkgd.").  These will assist your understanding of the materials
discussed in class and should be read, but because of time constraints we will not discuss them
during class. Handouts, which are brief precis of the subjects to be covered in the class, are in the
Supplementary Materials.  Please bring the relevant handout to class for the discussion of the
reading. 
2)  Case Brief assignments - 
Brief Writing: Everyone will be assigned the task of preparing a short brief for the prosecution or
defense for one of the major cases to be discussed in class.  An assignment list will be distributed
at the end of the first week of class.  These briefs must be typed, double-spaced, 12 (twelve) point
type with 1 (one) inch margins and may not exceed 4 (four) single-sided pages.  
     Write the brief as if you were presenting the case to an appellate court made up of judges
other than those who heard the case and rendered the opinion in the materials.  Focus your brief  on
the principal issues for which the case is reprinted.  Review the entire opinion of the assigned case,
not just the portion excerpted in the casebook.  You may also consult any other materials or sources
you wish.  The brief should forcefully outline the principal arguments supporting your side's
position.  Your brief is due in class on the day your case is discussed.  Late-filed briefs will have a
grade deducted for each day they are late.  I encourage you to see me outside of class concerning
your briefs.

Oral Argument: In addition to preparing the brief, you will be responsible for articulating your
position concerning the case during the class in which we discuss that case.  Each side will have 2
minutes to articulate its position.  Throughout that class, you may be called upon to provide
additional expertise in discussing the case.  If for any legitimate reason you will be absent from class
on the day your case is to be discussed, it is your responsibility to find someone else to make your
oral argument for you and to notify me in advance of the situation. 

3) Bench Memo Assignment - At the end of class on September 9, an assignment to write a bench
memo for a judge will be distributed.  The bench memo will cover the subjects in the first five
classes.  Your completed, typed, bench memo is due at the beginning of class on September 19.

Exams: There will be midterm and final examinations for this course.  The midterm will be a closed
book, in-class, multiple choice exam given on October 21.  It will cover the materials addressed in
classes 1-15.  The final exam will be given on December 10.  It will be an open book exam which
will cover all material in the course, but will focus primarily on material covered in classes 17-28.

Class Participation:  In addition to presenting your side's position of the case you are assigned for
your case brief, everyone will be called on throughout the semester.  The purpose of calling on
people is to facilitate intelligent discussion, not engender fear, anguish or humiliation.  If, through
some personal emergency, you have been unable to prepare for a particular class, a note before class
will ensure that I do not call on you for that class.  If you are repeatedly unable to prepare for a class,
this affects the grade for class participation.

Grades:  Your grade in the course will be determined as follows:
1.  Case Brief: 5%
2.  Bench Memo: 15%
3.  Class Participation: 5%
4.  Midterm Examination: 25%
5.  Final Examination: 50%
Class
