<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL:  Criminal Law Model Brief</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Criminal Law "A"</H1>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Model Brief</H2>
<HR NOSHADE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Brief on behalf of Appellants Thomas Dudley and Edwin Stephens </H3>





<P>     This brief is respectfully submitted on behalf of Appellants Thomas Dudley and Edwin
Stephens, in support of their appeal of their convictions before the Honorable Huddleston, J. at
Exeter.  </P>                 <H5>      Issues</H5>
    <PRE>       A
     WERE THE APPELLANTS' ACTS, WHICH SAVED THE LIVES OF THREE
INNOCENT PERSONS, JUSTIFIED BY THE EXTRAORDINARY CIRCUMSTANCES IN
WHICH THEY WERE PLACED, THROUGH NO FAULT OF THEIR OWN, SUCH THAT
THEY CANNOT FORM THE BASIS OF CRIMINAL LIABILITY?
                               B
     IS A SENTENCE OF DEATH APPROPRIATE FOR APPELLANTS WITH NO
PRIOR CRIMINAL RECORD AND  OTHERWISE UNBLEMISHED CHARACTERS WHO
ACTED UNDER UNIQUE CIRCUMSTANCES IN ORDER TO SAVE INNOCENT LIVES?

</PRE>
<H5>Facts</H5>
<PRE>
     On July 5, 1884, the appellants, their companion Brooks and the deceased were tragically
marooned when their vessel sank on the high seas, leaving them 1600 miles from shore.  Left in
an open boat, the four men were adrift without water or food, save two pounds of turnips.  After
four days, they caught a small turtle, which they consumed on the twelfth day of their odyssey. 
On July 18, the appellants discussed their predicament with Brooks.  Brooks offered no
suggestion as to how they might survive.  On July 24, Brooks again refused to discuss strategies
for survival.  Appellants discussed their having families, the importance of their being able to
survive in order to care for their families and the desperateness of their situation. 
     By July 25, they had been without any other food for over a week, and they had caught very little
fresh water.  Their position was believed to be over a thousand miles from land.  No vessels had
been seen or were anticipated.  The deceased, who had been laying prostrate in the floor of the
boat from some days, showed little sign of life.  The appellants then determined that they would
soon die without sustenance, and thereupon hastened the deceased's inevitable demise.  They
consumed his remains for four days, and only on the fourth day were they rescued.  The fact
finder found that had the appellants not acted as they did they "probably" would not have
survived, and that given the deceased's condition he was "likely to have died before them."    
Law
ATHE APPELLANTS' ACTS WERE JUSTIFIED BY THE EXTRAORDINARY
CIRCUMSTANCES IN WHICH THEY WERE PLACED, THROUGH NO FAULT OF
THEIR OWN, AND SHOULD NOT FORM THE BASIS OF CRIMINAL LIABILITY
BECAUSE THESE ACTS SAVED THE LIVES OF THREE INNOCENT PERSONS.

     The principle that necessity will justify otherwise criminal actions done in extraordinary
circumstances is well-established.  See generally United States v. Nye, 27 F. Cas. 210 (C.C.D. Mass.
1855)(No. 15, 906); United States v. Staly, 27 F. Cas. 1290 (C.C.D.R.I. 1846)(No. 16, 374); cases
cited in American Law Institute, Model Penal Code, Sec. 3.02 at 10, n. 1.  There are numerous
accounts over the past 150 years of shipwrecked sailors being forced to resort to feeding on the
remains of one of their own, who died of exposure to the elements or at their hands, without criminal
prosecution.  See generally, Simpson, A.W.Brian, Cannibalism and the Common Law (Chicago
1984) at 95-145.  Lord Bacon has written:
          Necessity carrieth a privilege in itself...[I]f a man steals viands to
          satisfy his present hunger, there is no felony nor larceny.  So if divers
          [sic] be in danger of drowning by the casting away of some boat or
          barge, and one of them get to some plank, or on the boat's side to
          keep himself above water, and another to save his life thrust him from
          it, whereby he is drowned, this is neither se defendendo or by
          misadventure, but justifiable.
          
               The appellants acted in order to save their own (and their companion Brooks') lives.  Their
food had long been exhausted, their water was gone and they had no hope of being rescued in the
immediate future.  They quite reasonably believed their situation to be one of imminent, life-threatening peril for all concerned.  As Lord Bacon has noted, actions taken under such
circumstances are not felonies, and they should therefore not be criminal in this case.
                                
                                BTHE APPELLANTS' OTHERWISE UNBLEMISHED CHARACTERS AND THE
UNUSUAL CIRCUMSTANCES UNDER WHICH THESE OFFENSES OCCURRED MAKE
THEIR PUNISHMENT WITH DEATH UNFAIR, UNJUST AND INEFFICIENT.

     The appellants in this case have been condemned to death.  They have never before
committed a criminal offense.  They are never likely to be in a position to commit such an offense
again, and can profit society and their family's much if their lives are spared.  Few people are ever
likely to be in their position.   The appellants need not be deterred from committing such an act
again; if they were ever in such a position they have already lost their honest record, their unsullied
reputations and their professional livelihood.  No principle of justice or equity requires that they also
forfeit their lives.
     Their actions, even if criminal, were done under circumstances which would test anyone's
fortitude.  Few people would hesitate to put their lives before those of another; even fewer would
make the decision to do so when placed under circumstances of extreme thirst, hunger and exposure. 
The fact that these otherwise law-abiding persons did nothing more than what most people would
have done in their place, wrong though it may have been, does not merit the ultimate punishment.Conclusion
     In conclusion, the appellants respectfully submit that their actions were justified and thus
cannot constitute a crime, and ask that their convictions be therefore set aside or, in the alternative,
that their sentences be reduced.

</PRE>

<DIV ALIGN=CENTER>

