<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Criminal Law A - Bench memo assignment</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Criminal Law "A"</H2>
<HR NOSHADE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>BENCH MEMO ASSIGNMENT - POSSIBLE ANALYSES</H3>


<PRE>
           
                                
     This writing assignment has few single "correct" answers, most of the issues it raises are
open to multiple interpretations.  These are set forth in the footnotes.  The purpose of the exercise
was to challenge and thereby improve your analytic skills.  Do not despair if your paper did not
mention every issue identified.  You were limited to a relatively few pages, and I had far more time
to reflect on the problem than you did.  Even if you did not identify a possible issue noted here, you
should understand all those noted.  Please see me if you have questions.

     On September 15, 1996, defendant Big Bill was trying to pull into a parking space.  Victim
Little John squeaks his Yugo in just before Bill can pull into the space.   John, a strapping 4'11" tall,
gets out of the car and walks off.  Miffed, Bill yells at him.  "Hey, Shorty, I was going to take that
space."  John stops and looks at him.  "What did you call me?" he asks.  "Shorty," responds Bill. 
"I thought so.  That's twice you've said that."  Officer Smith, who has observed this exchange,
arrests Bill and charges him with criminal harassment.  Upon searching Bill, the officer finds a
pocketknife in Bill's pocket.  Bill has no prior criminal record, works in a homeless shelter and was
recently nominated for a Nobel Peace Prize.

     Public outrage over Bill's conduct moves the legislature of the State of Confusion to enact
a criminal harassment law.  Prior to the adoption of this statute, Confusion had no statute specifically
proscribing harassment.  It did, however, have common law prohibitions against disorderly conduct,
vagrancy and public annoyance.  These common law prohibitions were identical to current
Massachusetts General Law Chapter 272,  53.  On September 16, 1996, the legislature enacts and
the executive signs the Confusion Anti-Harassment Law.  Immediately, the League of Confusion
Organizations (LOCO), a coalition of political extremists of the left and right, challenges the law. 

      Bill is indicted in the alternative for common law criminal harassment and Criminal
Harassment in the First Degree.  Before trial, Bill's lawyer challenges the indictment on numerous
grounds.  Bill's case is consolidated with LOCO's.

     You are the law clerk to the Judge before whom the cases are pending.  LOCO seeks a
temporary restraining order to halt enforcement of the statute, and Bill's lawyer seeks dismissal of
the indictment.  The Judge has several concerns about the statute.  She asks you to separately
analyze for both Bill's and LOCO's cases the applicability of any or all of the following rules and
doctrines: 1) The Legality Principle, 2) The Rule of Lenity, 3) Vagueness, 4) Overbreadth, 5)
Proportionality under the Eighth Amendment and 6) General principles of punishment.  She also asks that you assess the applicability, if any, of the Supreme Court's decisions in R.A.V. v. City of
St.Paul, 505 U.S., 120 L.Ed.2d 305, 112 S.Ct. 2538 (1992) and Wisconsin v. Mitchell, 113 S.Ct.
2194 (1993).

             The 1996 Confusion Anti-Harassment Law
                                
     Sec. 1.   Findings:  The legislature hereby finds that certain groups, classes and
     individuals in this State have been subject to harassment, intimidation and persecution
     based upon their immutable characteristics, that such actions are inimical to the public good
     and have been disfavored at common law.  

     Sec. 2.  Criminal Harassment in the Second Degree: Any person who expresses views,
     opinions or statements designed solely to harass, intimidate or persecute another based
     upon their immutable characteristics is guilty of the offense of criminal harassment of the
     second degree.

     Sec. 3: Criminal Harassment in the First Degree:  Any person who engages in criminal
     harassment who:
     a) possesses a deadly weapon while engaging in criminal harassment, or
     b) has previously been convicted of criminal harassment,
      is guilty of the offense of criminal harassment of the first degree.

     Sec. 4: Penalties.

     a) Criminal Harassment of the Second Degree is a misdemeanor, punishable by up to 1 (one)
     year incarceration and a file of up to $1,000.
     b) Criminal Harassment of the First Degree is a felony, punishable by 10 (ten) years'
          incarceration and a fine of up to $50,000.

</PRE>

