<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Housing Discrimination Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Housing Discrimination Law -- Ms. Sheila Mondshein</H2>
</CENTER>
<A NAME = "top">
<HR>

<BR noshade>



<H3>Course Information	</H3>							
      This course will give you an introduction to the rapidly burgeoning field of housing discrimination law by focusing  on the federal Fair Housing Act (Title VIII), which prohibits discrimination in private and  public sector housing on the basis of race, religion, color, national origin, sex, disability, or familial status (families with children under 18).  In recent years, many significant federal court and administrative law judge decisions have been issued interpreting the provisions of Title VIII, and states and localities have enacted their own fair housing legislation. <P>

      In view of these facts I have decided not to use  a commercially published casebook for course assignments,  but will  rely primarily on readings selected from the developing case law, which will be distributed weekly to the class.  I will also draw on  the experience I have had as  Associate Regional Counsel at the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development to enhance the curriculum with actual cases and problem situations handled by that agency as well as with relevant policy issues.  <P> 

      This approach should prepare you academically and practically  to represent clients who are  involved in specific discrimination disputes as well as advise clients with a need for general guidance --- whether as landlords, managers, sellers, real estate brokers or salespersons, advertisers, mortgage lenders, insurers, appraisers, developers, community planners, or special  interest groups.<P>

	If you have any questions, feel free to contact me by calling 965-3878.<P>


     <A HREF="housing2.htm">Click here for  the course syllabus.  
</A><BR><BR>

<CENTER>
