<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Housing Discrimination Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Housing Discrimination Law -- Ms. Sheila Mondshein</H2>
</CENTER>
<A NAME = "top">
<HR>

<BR noshade>



<center><H3>Syllabus</H3></CENTER>	

<H4><CENTER>HOUSING DISCRIMINATION LAW</CENTER> </H4>

<H5>Part I.   The Fair Housing Act (Title VIII) and 42 U.S.C.    1982 - Basic Features</H5>
<UL>

<LI>Class 1 <BR>
Introduction to residential segregation and discrimination
Housing discrimination law prior to 1968<BR>
<LI>Class 2 <BR>
Legislative history, intent and constitutionality of Title VIII<BR>
Scopes of coverage<BR>
<LI>Class 3 <BR>
Prohibited bases of discrimination (race, color and national origin; religion; sexual discrimination and sexual harassment; handicap; and familial status discrimination)
Proper parties for liability
<LI>Class 4 <BR>
Theories of liability and standards of proof - disparate treatment and disparate impact
</ul>

	
<H5>Part II.   Substantive Prohibitions of Title VIII and Sample Cases</H5>

<UL>
<LI>Class 5<BR> 
Discriminatory refusals to sell or rent and other practices (e.g. steering and exclusionary zoning)<BR>
Discriminatory terms, conditions, services and facilities
<LI>Class 6 <BR>
Discriminatory advertising and statements<BR> 
Discriminatory financing and related transactions, including mortgage redlining <BR>
<LI>Class 7 <BR>
Unlawful coercion, intimidation, threats and interference <BR>
Other provisions (e.g. failure to make reasonable accommodations and to permit reasonable modifications for the disabled; affirmative fair housing duties)
</UL>
 

<H5>Part III.   Enforcement Procedures and Remedies
</H5>
<UL>
<LI>Class 8 <BR>
Title VIII administrative enforcement by U.S. Department of H.U.D. or certified local fair housing agencies 

<LI>Class 9 <BR>
Department of Justice Title VIII enforcement<BR> 
Private enforcement by direct court actions 
<LI>Class 10 <BR>
Litigation procedures and issues (e.g.  statutes of limitation, class actions, damages, attorney's fees, preclusion of claims, settlements) 
<LI>Class 11 <BR>
Proof issues (e.g. burdens of proof and production, testers and other sources of evidence, use of statistics, expert witnesses) 
</UL>

<H5>Part IV.   Other Fair Housing Sources
</H5>
<UL>
<LI>Class 12 <BR>
U.S. Constitution (Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments); Title VI of Civil Rights Act of 1964; and Section 504 of Rehabilitation Act 
<BR>
<LI>Class 13 <BR>
Other federal sources (e.g. Americans with Disabilities Act, Executive Orders); state and local fair housing laws <BR>
<LI>
<LI>Class 14 <BR>
Recent developments and trends <BR>
Insights and conclusions
</UL>

