<html>
<head>
<title>Legal  Research Syllabus</title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">
<h1>Legal  Research Syllabus</h1></A>
<h2>Fall Semester 1996</h2>

<strong>SECTION A:  Sandy Lamar (slamar@nesl.edu) - tel.  617-422-7331.  Class meets
Wednesdays, 2 - 2:50, Room 305.</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>SECTION B:  Barry Stearns (bstearns@nesl.edu) - tel. 617-422-7332.  Class meets
Tuesdays, 10:55 - 11:45, Room 304.     Please note  - Tues. Sept. 3 is a Mon.  schedule. Meet
in Room 501 on Thursday, September 5, 10:55-11:45. </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>SECTION E:  Helen  Litwack (hlitwack@nesl.edu) - tel. 617-422-7436.  Class meets
Wednesdays, 6:55 - 7:45, Room 304.</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>TEXT:  Kunz, Schmedemann, Downs &amp; Bateson, <u>The Process of Legal Research, 4th  ed.</u>
(Little Brown 1996).     Reading Assignments are to be done before the class meetings.  The
reading assignments include many    illustrations which should be examined carefully
before class meets.  <em>Bring the book to each class.</em>  </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>LRA's :  You will meet formally, with your Legal Research Advisor and your Legal
Methods group, the first two weeks    of the Legal Research course (time/place TBA). 
Thereafter, LRA's will be available in the library for hands-   on training and help with the
assignments. <em> Do not be afraid to seek help from Reference Librarians or any LRA. </em>   </strong>

<p><strong>The  Problem Sets found in the back of the text must be turned in to your LRA for grading
at the time he or she specifies, but no later than 5 pm on Friday of the listed week.  Every
person must turn in the exercise.  Collaboration   between two people on the underlying
research is acceptable; copying another's work product is not, and groups of three or more
may not work together.  <em>Limited resources are required for many users on some assignments. 
Avoid book crunch by working ahead and doing exercises out of order - e.g. work on
electronic resources if the books are being used heavily.  Reshelve the books so others may use
them.</em></strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>CALR:  All Legal Research students are required to attend two 90 minute lessons in
Computer Assisted Legal    Research.  As assigned by your instructor, you must attend
Lexis or Westlaw training before the CALR   exercises are due on Oct. 25, and complete a
class in the other online system before Moot Court.  </strong>

<p><strong>Classes in use of CD-ROM's and the Internet for legal research are recommended but not
required.</strong>

<p><strong>These classes are TBA.  Signup sheets for all classes may be found at the Circulation Desk
in the Library.</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>GRADING:  The LR component of Legal Methods is worth a total of 100 points: the exam
is worth 45 points; Exercises    due the first 8 weeks are worth 5 points each (45 pts); the 4
CALR exercises due 10/25 are worth 2.5 points    each (10 pts).   LRA's will give full points
to on-time assignments done correctly, signified by a check ().     Exercises that are late or
inadequate will receive a -.  </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
