<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Personal Income Tax 1 -- Professor Salter</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER><A NAME = "top">
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2> PERSONAL INCOME TAX "A" - PROFESSOR SALTER</H2>
<H3>  COURSE INFORMATION</H3>
<H4>Fall, 1996</H4>

</CENTER>

<HR noshade>


  <PRE>    
Required:   

  Wile, Federal Income Taxation:  A Casebook on the Basics 
          ISBN  0-314-04915-0

  Posin, Federal Income Taxation of Individuals, with Diagrams
         for Easy Understanding of the Leading Cases 
          and Concepts  (2d ed.)  ISBN  0-314-01832-8

  Current copy of basic sections of the Internal Revenue Code and
    associated regulations:  the West version is in larger print.
      (West,  Selected Tax Statutes (1997) ISBN 0-314-09751-1)


Preparation for classes:

     Read the assigned material.  Be prepared to examine the
relevant parts of the Internal Revenue Code and regulations, and
to relate statutory language to assigned cases and similar
hypotheticals.   

In "reading" the Code, it is usually a good idea to look over the
part to be studied rather quickly before reading the other
materials, to get a rough idea of what the language and structure
may be.  Then read the assignment, seeing how the courts and
commentators describe the Code and its working in the particular
situations examined.  Then go back to the Code and read it more
carefully.  

Learning to use the Code is an important part of this course.

You are also expected to be familiar with the facts of assigned
cases and hypotheticals, and to understand the sources of tax law
as they are applied in them.  You will be asked to participate in
class discussion, and your work will be part of your overall
evaluation.  It is not just a matter of memorizing the language
and facts:  you must be prepared to struggle with difficult
analyses and applications.  A good mark is earned by
demonstrating preparation, attention, and effort in working with
the materials.  Merely memorizing a "correct" answer is not the
skill upon which you will be evaluated.  You will be able to
refresh your memory in class and on the exam by referring to the
Code, your books and your notes.

Other exercises include a library assignment (required but
ungraded), a one-hour mid-term (objective), and a two-hour final
(one hour objective, one hour short essays).  There will be a
short writing assignment, discussing the realization concept and
its applications.  It is due on the last day of classes.  

</PRE>

