<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: War Crimes</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">
<CENTER>
<H1>New England Center for International Law & Policy</H1>
<H2>Yugoslavia War Crimes Project</H2></CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<H3>A. Description:</H3>
                  
     The Office of the Prosecutor of the International Tribunal for
the Former Yugoslavia has entered into an arrangement with the New
England School of Law, whereby NESL students can undertake legal
research projects for the Prosecutor.  NESL is one of only two law
schools in the world with this relationship with the War Crimes
Prosecutor.  Students can get 1 credit for researching and writing
a short memo (15-20 pages) and 2 credits for completing a longer
memo (20-25 pages) or two shorter memos.  A memo of 25 or more
pages can be used to fulfill the UCWR.  There is no pre-requisite
and any second, third or fourth year student may participate, but
students who have taken international law, criminal law, evidence
and criminal procedure will have first priority in case of
overenrolment.<P>

<H3>B. Procedure for Signing Up:</H3>
     Students wishing to enroll in the Yugoslavia War Crimes
Project must sign up using a "Student Request Form" available at
the Registrar's Office for an independent study with Professor
Scharf, Ward, or Siegel.  For a 1 credit independent study, the
Code Number is IS401D.  For 2 credits, the Code Number is IS402D. 
If you are a second-year student, you must also fill out a "Waiver
form," since independent study is normally for students in their
last year of school.<P>

     If you wish to get UCWR credit, you must fill out an "UCWR
Registration Form."  The UCWR codes are as follows: Scharf - 776,
Ward - 793, and Siegel - 777.  You will need to be sure to attend
the "mandatory writing seminar" and the "UCWR Advanced Computer
Assisted Legal Research seminar" offered early in the semester.  <P> 
  
<H3>C. Choosing Your Issue:</H3>
     The Office of the Prosecutor has provided a list of issues for
which it needs research and analysis (attached).  As soon as
possible (and no later than September 9), you should drop by
Professor Scharf's office to pick an issue from the list (first
come, first choice).  At that time you will be assigned a
supervising faculty member: Professor Scharf, Professor Ward, or
Professor Siegel.<P>

     Within a week, the Office of the Prosecutor will fax a more
detailed description of the issue, including an explanation of the
context in which it arises.  You will then be matched with a lawyer
from the "Public International Law and Policy Group," who will give
you guidance and supervision in researching and writing the memo. 
The Group is a collection of former government lawyers and experts
in international law committed to providing pro-bono legal service
to foreign governments and international organizations, including
the War Crimes Tribunal.           <P>                  

<H3>D. Due Dates:</H3>

    <UL>
<LI>   September 6 - You must attend a one-hour introduction to
     the War Crimes Tribunal at 3:00 pm in Room 505.<BR>

<LI>     (2)  By September 9, you must meet with Professor Scharf to
  receive an issue and supervising faculty assignment.  You must
also submit all required forms to the Registrar.  <BR>

<LI>     (3)  A general workshop on researching international law will
be scheduled with Law Librarian Sandy Lamar at a mutually
     agreed upon time during the week of September 9.<BR>

<LI>     (4) October 15 - A Typewritten, detailed outline of your memo
     is due (3 pages maximum).

<LI>     (5) November 12 - Polished first draft of your memo due.

<LI>     (6) November 22 - first drafts returned to students with
     Professor's comments.  You should thereafter meet with the
    Professor to discuss the comments.

<LI>     (7) December 6 - Final drafts due (copies of all cited
  material must be appended to the draft).
</UL>

<H3>E. Grades:</H3>

     Your grade will be based on three factors: <UL>
<LI>
(1) how well the
memo is written (organization, style, grammar, proper blue book
form);
<LI> (2) how well the memo is researched (number, variety and
quality of sources); and 
<LI>(3) how sophisticated is the analysis. </UL>
You will likely need to conduct much of your research at the other
law libraries in the area.  Your grade will reflect the quality of
both your first draft and the final product.  In addition, failure
to adhere to due dates for drafts and for the final memorandum will
result in a reduction of your grade.<P>

<H3>F. Format:</H3>

     The War Crimes memo is to be in the form of a Legal
Memorandum.  It should begin with "I. Introduction and Summary of
Conclusions."  This initial section should set out the issue the
memo addresses and the conclusions you have reached based on your
research and analysis.  This should be followed by a section
entitled "II. Factual Background."  This brief section should
summarize the context in which the issue arises.  The bulk of the
memo should be the third section, entitled "III. Legal Discussion,"
which can be subdivided into as many subsections as is necessary. 
You should append to the final memorandum (due December 6), copies
of the relevant portions of the sources you have cited for use by
the Office of the Prosecutor.<P>


     The memo should be typed double spaced in 12 point font. 
Please be sure to number your pages.  The memo should have a cover
page, with your name, a title that reflects the issue, and an
indication of whether the paper is for the UCWR.  You should
include a cite for every statement that is not general knowledge or
your own analysis.  The first draft due on November 12, 1996, is
not to be a "rough draft," but rather a fully researched, complete,
polished product.  Carefully edit and proofread the first draft
before handing it in.  (Note, proofreading means more than just
using the spell check on your computer.)  The better your first
draft, the more you will benefit from the reviewers' initial set of
comments.<P>

     The reviewers' will provide both substantive and technical
comments in the margins of your first draft.  The next two pages
contain a list of the technical points that are frequently made on
student papers.  You should read through them carefully before
writing your paper (and again when you are polishing the first
draft), so that you will be sure to avoid these kinds of mistakes. <P>

<PRE>
                   GUIDE TO TECHNICAL COMMENTS

Abbreviation  Meaning

agmtX         lack of subject-verb or noun-pronoun agreement

awk.          awkward sentence or paragraph construction.  
              sentence or paragraph should be completely
              rewritten for better flow and clarity

blk.qt.       quotations of over 50 words should be indented
              in single-spaced type without quotation marks.
              Footnote goes after the last period of the quote 

beef up FN    need to include more information with the footnote

bl. bk.       consult the bluebook for proper form (e.g.,
              inappropriate signal used in footnote, need to
              abbreviate title of case or periodical, etc)

cite or FN    need a footnote to support assertion

First         avoid first person references to the author in the
personX       text

fix supras    supra or infra cites do not correspond with correct 
or infras     footnotes numbers

fix quote     quotation marks go on the outside of periods or
marks.        commas.  They go on the insides of semicolons.  

fgmt.         fragment: not a complete sentence; usually missing
              verb or subject
  
gmr.          basic grammatical problem (e.g., ending sentence
              with a preposition; or beginning sentence with And,
              But or However)

move to FN    this information distracts from the flow of your
              analysis or is too minor to include in the main
              text; move it to a footnote 

org.          sentence or paragraph needs to be reorganized

paraphrase    too many long quotations.  Your paper should not
              look like a string of quotes.  You should
              paraphrase quotes whenever possible.
    
passiveX     avoid passive voice by inserting the "Actor," e.g.
             change "The paper was given to the professor" to
             "The student gave the paper to the professor."  
                               -5-


punct.        punctuation: improper use or placement of commas,
              semi-colons, quotation marks, etc.               

rn.on.        run-on sentence

splt.inf.     avoid split infinitive ("to boldly go") 

stress        reorganize sentence so that important information
              is at the end and is not lost at the beginning or
              buried in the middle 

substructure  Need more subheadings
 
too long      Sentence or paragraph is too long or short.
or too short  Paragraphs should be between 3-5 sentences in
              length.  A sentence should not be over 4 lines 
              long.
       
trans.        work on transitions, intro and concluding
              sentences, and internal road markers (e.g., "There
              are three reasons.... First, .... Second, ....
              Finally, ....") 

typo.,        need to proofread! (note, I have little patience
or sp.        for poor proofreading)

uncl.         meaning of the sentence is unclear or confusing

uncl.ref.     unclear reference: ambiguous pronoun

wdy.          wordy: need to avoid redundancy, unnecessary
              words/phrases

wd.ch.        word choice: inappropriate word used, or repeated
              use of the same word
</PRE>


*If you are unfamiliar with any of the above listed terms, you
should consult Strunk and White or another guide to good writing.<BR>
   <CENTER>

