<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Library Newsletter</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P>

<H3>Boston Public Library: <I>The</I> Source for Government Documents</H3>


You may find occasion to stroll to the elegant and venerable Boston Public Library at Copley Square for a government document we don't have and can't read full-text on WESTLAW, LEXIS, or the Internet.<P>

The BPL is an official depository of the following: U.S. Government Printing Office, U.S. Patent and Trademarks Office, Massachusetts, United Nations, GATT, the Danube Commission, and an affiliate depository for the State Data Center.  It houses more than three million government documents in all.<P>

Ninety-nine percent of the government documents in NESL's collection are cataloged on Portia (online catalog).  But if your desired document originates from the Federal Judicial Center, Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts, National Institute of Justice, etc., check Stack 4 on the library's second floor, as there may be a very few smaller pamphlet-type documents that have not been individually cataloged.<P>

If we don't have what you need in-house you can fill out an Inter-Library Loan request form at the Circulation desk and NESL's dedicated library staff will scour the earth to locate your government document and deliver it to your doorstep.  Although New England School of Law is supposed to be able to borrow BPL's materials through the mail on inter-library loan, in practice, this can be difficult to effect.<P>

Or, you can directly search BPL's Research Library catalog (which includes government documents)  on the World Wide Web, via Netscape from the four Internet terminals in the basement.  The librarians at the front Reference desk and back reference offices can also access this website from their terminals, as can faculty at their desktops.  The address is: <A HREF="http://www.bpl.org">http://www.bpl.org</A>.  The link is under "Search our Catalog and Databases."  You'll note, you have the option there of clicking on either "Research Library" (which catalogs the print format (Government Documents) or on "U.S. Government Databases" [which catalogs the CD-ROM databases]).  There is the self help "how to search" link as well.  Please note that, while you can access Boston Public Library through a menu item on Portia, e.g. choosing, "D: Connect to Other Databases,"  and then selecting the Boston Library Consortium and Boston Public Library, you are only reaching the Circulating Collection catalog, not the Research Library.<P>

In addition to government documents, the catalog of the Research Library also contains law-related social science materials.<P>

Occasionally, (O.K., often) you will try to connect and receive the error message "Unable to Find Application."  I suspect that only our Computer Services Reference Librarian, Sandra Lamar, and her cohorts in the Computer Media Center know what this really means, and they're not telling!  The less technologically-advanced of us can assume it means the line is busy and try again later.<P>

If computer access is blocked or you don't have a computer, you may telephone the Catalog Information Desk at (617) 536-5400 ext. 256 and a BPL staffer will search for up to three titles in their catalog for you.  The extension to reach the Government Documents librarians themselves is 226.  BPL's telephone reference services TTY line for hearing-impaired is 266-9302.<P>

If you decide to visit BPL in person, Government Documents is on the Lower Level of the McKim Building, which is the older portion of the structure, facing Dartmouth Street.  If you haven't seen the magnificent lobby of the McKim Building, it is worth a trip for its own sake.  The hours are Monday through Thursday 9:00 a.m.-9:00 p.m., Friday and Saturday 9:00 a.m.-5:00 p.m., and Sunday 1:00 p.m.-5:00 p.m. (Sunday hours effective for Oct.-May 1st only).<P>

BPL's Research Library collection is non-circulating, but xerox machines are available at the Government Documents area (taking change, $1s and $5s).  Freely accessible on the shelves are some of the same materials we have at NESL, such as federal and Massachusetts codes, the National Reporter System, digests, legal encyclopedias, etc., but for other government documents you must fill out a request slip and the librarian retrieves the materials from closed stacks.  You need a BPL library card to request material from the closed stacks.  However, library cards are free for Boston residents and cards from any of the Boston suburbs (Brookline, Cambridge, Newton, etc.) will do.  Nonresidents can obtain a free courtesy card.  Apply for new library cards on the second floor of the library.<P>

On a recent visit to the Government Documents Room, I had to ask the librarian to log me on to the Research Library Catalog as it did not appear as a menu item on any of the dozen of so terminals in the room, but the librarian told me that, ordinarily, at least one of the public terminals will have it.  If so, you'll see a menu page headed: "Boston Public Library: Local & Internet Databases."  The Research Library Catalog will be: "1.  Spectrum PAC Module" or "8.  Government Documents."  The librarian assured me they are the same thing!<P>

Other terminals around the room had various CD-ROMs, approximately 30 CDs in all.  As in our library, some are networked: others you will have to request at the desk.  A few of the more interesting CDs I noted were:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Government Documents Department State & Local Index (indexes more than 10,000 documents of Boston City Government agencies and Massachusetts State Agencies, as well as selected civic groups, research institutions and public policy organizations, examples of which are the Massachusetts Tenants' Association, the Conservation Law Foundation, the Massachusetts Bar Association, etc.)<p>

<LI>FBIS- foreign radio and television broadcasts (including selected foreign newspaper and periodical articles that you might find as well on Lexis)<p>

<LI>British Parliamentary Documents<p>

<LI>Statistical Abstract of the United States and Government Printing Office Catalog (both of which NESL has in print format only)<p>

<LI>Other census, and miscellaneous trade/business information<p>

</UL>

Thinking of the Boston Public Library as one of your resources is one way you can take full advantage of having chosen this "downtown" law school at which to pursue your degree.  BPL can be a useful supplemental site for alums as well, in that it has full core collection of federal primary statutory and case law, the regional reporters, the Massachusetts Practice series, and a CD-ROM product to search Massachusetts cases comparable to what we have.  (NESL has "CaseBase" and "West's Massachusetts Decisions" on CD-ROM, whereas the BPL has a CD published by Michie.)  As usual, if you have any questions about any of this, please ask!<P>

<HR NOSHADE>
