<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Library Newsletter</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P>

<H3>Book Review: <I>Legislating Privacy</I></H3>

<I>Priscilla M. Reagan, Legislating Privacy: Technology, Social Values, and Public Policy, University of North Carolina Press: Chapel Hill and London (1995).</I><P>

<I>Helen Litwack</I><P>


The New England School of  Law Library has recently acquired this thoughtful analysis of the way Congress has dealt with privacy issues.  While I have not comprehensively reviewed the literature on this topic, I can still recommend this book to the NESL community, either as a good jump-off point for in-depth legal research of for general interest browsing.<P>

Reagan, former congressional staffer at the Office of Technology Assessment, divides privacy into three main areas: (1) Information Privacy; (2) Communication Privacy; and (3) Psychological Privacy.  The author further develops her analysis of congressional action by separately considering factors involved in legislative policy-making.<P>

The author continually compares and contrasts the tension between Congress and the Court.  In addition to reviewing specific federal privacy legislation, she provides insight into why Congress and the courts have acted as they have on this issue.<P>

There are quite a few statistical tables (Harris polls on changes in how people have viewed privacy issues, etc.)  The chapter on privacy in American society is full of interesting tidbits.  For example, in 1753, Benjamin Franklin, as postmaster general, issued a regulation requiring postmasters to take an oath not to open mail.<P>

Students or attorneys doing research in this area will appreciate the review of the seminal scholarly literature in the field and the appendices of congressional activity on the three types of privacy (information, communication, and psychological).<P>


<HR NOSHADE>
