<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Library Newsletter</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P>

<H3>Net News at New England: Get Caught in the Web</H3>

<I>Sandy Lamar</I><P>

The easiest way to explore the World Wide Web is through a graphical browser like Netscape, which is currently provided by the NESL library on four student research stations and on all faculty and library staff workstations.<P>

Netscape is, of course, only a means to an end for the legal researcher.  The quantity and quality of legal resources are proliferating on the Web every day.  Any computer attached to the Internet can make documents available, and over the last year we have seen huge amounts of legal materials become available.  For example, did you know that recent First Circuit decisions are now available on the Internet;  that you can download IRS forms; that United Nations conference materials are available, or that law students have pages on the Web specifically to help or entertain other law students?<P>

This is a wonderful development.  Students working on research papers will appreciate that many of the documents available on the Internet are simply not available on Lexis or Westlaw.  Those of you who are getting close to graduation will appreciate the amount of primary material and government/administrative documentation which is being mounted on the Internet and which provides an alternate source for this material.  Even through a commercial provider like Netcom or Massinternet, Netscape access to this material may be cheaper than LEXIS or WESTLAW access.<P>

There are still drawbacks to researching on the Net, where you may be faced with huge amounts of information being mounted onto a structure with no central database directory, and no real indexing; there is often no way (yet) to authenticate or verify information, other than by going to a source which appears reliable.  The search engines may not give you the kind of sophisticated searching, and relevancy, which LEXIS and WESTLAW  users take for granted.<P>

In spite of the drawbacks, which are being  addressed quickly, the ease of Netscape's graphical access and the sheer amount of legal information available means that legal research on the Internet will continue to gain  popularity with  legal researchers.<P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<A HREF="apr96.htm">Table of Contents</A>


