<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Library Newsletter</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE><P>

<H3>LEXIS/NEXIS News</H3>

<I>Sandy Lamar</I><P>


Positions Available:  LEXIS/NEXIS will be hiring student associates for the Fall semester.  The preferred student will be available for training in the library this Summer.  If you are interested, please drop off  a resume with Sandy Lamar in the library.<P>

<B>Summer Access:</B>  Do not be cut off needlessly this Summer!  Watch your welcome screen over the next month for the opportunity to extend your password electronically.  You need to be able to enter the name of the professor or class you will be involved with.  Remember, Computer Assisted Legal Research on LEXIS is just for educational purposes and cannot be used for law firm research.  It can be used to help with your Upper Class Writing Project, a Law Review article, or Summer class work.<P>

<B>Software:</B>   If you are using an old version of the LEXIS Windows software, pick up one of the new packages now available in the LEXIS Training Room.  In my opinion the new search software is greatly improved, with an easier Windows front end and Lexform built in.  By running downloaded documents  through Lexform, cases pulled up into your word processing program are stripped of those annoying hard returns, the additional headers, and  fancy end statements.  It makes it much easier to incorporate quotations into your paper or brief.  Checkcite is included, so you can automatically Shepardize and Autocite cites from your research paper.<P>

The software package also includes student office software, giving you use of a "toolbar" and  Folio Views. The toolbar allows for quick switching back and forth, from one application to another, just like the one on the LEXIS machines in the training room.  Folio Views is an electronic publishing tool which can be used as a means of displaying and organizing downloaded documents, adding class notes, or creating student outlines.  It is not for the computer novice, but is very powerful if you take the time to learn how to use it.  You can create your own casebook, with notations, highlighting, and cross-references.<P>

<B>Six Suggestions for Better Searchings:</B><P>

<OL>
<LI>Use the segments command to search within fields, e.g. ".SE; dissentby(thomas)"
<LI>Use special segment terms e.g. "allcaps(AIDS)" or "nocaps(doe)"[as in deer, not a name]
<LI>Use ".more" to find documents that resemble the document you have currently retrieved.
<LI>Use ".keep" to save a search for 24 hours in your log.
<LI>Use ".save" to set up an eclipse search, and be informed automatically about new results.
<LI>Use print manager ".pm" to cancel print requests.
</OL>

<HR NOSHADE>
