<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Library Newsletter</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE><P>

<H3>WESTLAW News</H3>

<I>Information supplied by WESTLAW</I><P>

<B>Tips for Retrieving More Relevant News Articles on WESTLAW:</B> Have you ever searched for articles on a well-known company and retrieved too many?  Or have you tried to find good, substantive articles on a popular news topic, only to retrieve documents that discuss your issue tangentially?  The following search tips can help you pinpoint  more relevant articles.<P>

<B>Search the Title and Lead Paragraph:</B> You can limit a Terms and Connectors search to the title and lead paragraph portions of articles.  For example, if you need articles that significantly discuss the new lobbyist disclosure law, you can restrict your search to the title and lead paragraph (also known as the summary) by typing ti,su(lobby!/s disclos!).<P>

<B>Use Relevance Ranking with Terms and Connectors:</B> The Terms and Connectors search method retrieves all articles that satisfy your search request and arranges them by date, with the most recent articles first.  Did you know that you can also sort your Terms and Connectors search result by probable relevance?  To change the Terms and Connectors retrieval order to relevance ranking, access the Options Directory by typing opt.  Under Search Features, choose Terms and Connectors result rank order and then follow the on-screen directions.  (If you want subsequent search results to be arranged by date, be sure to return to your Options Directory and change the setting back.)<P>

<B>Search Topical News Databases and State News Databases:</B> When you search for articles in a news database customized to a particular topic, you are more likely to retrieve relevant results.  Topical news databases are available for a wide range of subjects, including bankruptcy (BKRNEWS), communications (COMNEWS), health (HTHNEWS), environment (ENVNEWS), tax (TAXNEWS), education (EDNEWS) and more.  State news databases will be available soon, including Massachusetts (MANEWS), Connecticut (CTNEWS), Rhode Island (RINEWS), and Maine (MENEWS).<P>

<B>Use a Natural Language Search:</B> When you want to retrieve the most relevant articles quickly, use a Natural Language search.  Because Natural Language automatically sorts your search result by probable relevance, you will not need to browse through a long list of documents to find the best ones.  Even advanced researchers find that a Natural Language Search often produces better results than a sophisticated Terms and Connectors query.<P>

<B>What is the Meaning of....?:</B> Do you ever need to know how a particular word or phrase has been interpreted by a court?  Now you can use the words and phrases field (wp) in any WESTLAW case-law database to determine the meaning of a word.  For example, to determine the meaning of reasonable accommodation, type: wp(reasonab!/s accommodat!)<P>


