<CENTER>
<H1>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2>Library Newsletter</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE><P>

<H3>Book Review: <I>Dead Man Walking</I></H3>

<I>Brian Flaherty</I><P>

"Dead man walking" is the prhase called by inmates when a death row prisioner is seen on his way to or from the excercise yard. It also serves as a metaphor for the central action in Sister Helen Prejean's book. Sister Prejean served as a spiritual advisor to two men on Louisiana's Death Row; ultimately, she accompanied each to the electric chair. Elmo Patarick Sonnier, a man she describes as handsome and shy, was involved in the heinous murder of a young couple. Robert Willie, who she describes as equally charming but "more simple and direct," was responsible for a horrific string of rapes and murders. Though the two crimes are unearthed and described in great detail, it is the ordinariness of the two men which is told as the most haunting part of the tale. The two condemned "dead men" are seen doing familiar things such as watching basketball, telling stories, and walking.<P>

More to the point, however, <I>Dead Man Walking</I> is an eloquent paean against the death penalty, exceptionally well researched and passionately told. After her first encounter with Patrick Sonnier, she begins to read up on capital punishment as it is doled out in the United States. What she discovers horrifies her, and is told to horrify the reader: history and statistics both demonstrate conclusively that the death penalty is racially biased. If the victim of the crime was white, the perpatrator is far more likely to be condemned to death than if the victim was black. The Supreme Court, faced with "irrefutable evidence" of this, wrote in McClesky v. Kemp (1987) that there exists in captal sentencing "a discrepancy that appears to correlate with race," but that such inequities are "an <I>inevitable</I> part of our criminal justice system." According to the highest court in the land, such racism is acceptable, even if it involves the taking of a human life.<P>

As a result of her experiences with the two men, Sister Prejean becomes a crusader against the death penalty. <I>Dead Man Walking</I>, her memoir of this crusade, is filled with depressing tales of capital injustice and a passionate chronicle of her fight against a system admittedly rife with racism and classism. She is forever quoting <I>Reflections on the Guillotine</I> by Albert Camus, from which essay she gleans a kind of rational guidance. Perhaps the most interesting conflict in the book is her relationship with the families of the victims. The father of one of the victims, Vernon Harvey, is as outspoken in favor of the death penalty as she is against it. They become consistent friends in person.<P>

The academy award-winning movie based on the book tells the tale of a Catholic nun's experience with a death row inmate. Its emotional impact, however, is based more on the situation; a nun trying to accept the fact of horrifying violence done by a man she's committed to help. The film shows her fustration with a criminal justice system that is biased and profoundly irresponsible. It is not, however, the witness against the death penalty that the book is; film is not the proper medium for the statistical evidence of racism and classism which solidifies the arguments of the book. In the end, both the book and the movie have individual merits, and for anyone with even a passing interest in the death penalty in the United States, both are highly recommended.<P>

<HR NOSHADE>
