<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Criminal Law "A" Handout 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">
<CENTER>
<H1>Criminal Law "A" -- Professor David Siegel</H1>
<H2> Handout 1: Overview </H2>
<H3> Fall 1996</H3></CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>

           
                                

<PRE>


I.   Overview of Criminal Law
     A.   What criminal law is: 
          1.   System of social control
          2.   System of moral hierarchy
     B.   Type of system
          1.   Principally legislatively-defined system of crimes,
          2.   With judicially-created or interpreted restrictions upon 
               a.   legislature's ability to define and create crimes and 
               b.   executive's enforcement of laws prohibiting them.
II.  Substantive criminal law of every state and U.S. is different.  The Model Penal Code has
     influenced many "modern" codifications, although nowhere wholly adopted.
     A.   Part I - "The General Part"
          1.   The basic framework for identifying criminal responsibility, whether a
               criminal act has occurred and what defenses might exist.
          2.   Study general part when evaluating definitions of specific crimes.
          3.   Note especially:  1.12 (Burden of Proof); 2.01 (Genl. requirements of
               culpability; 2.03 (Causation); 2.04 (Mistake); 2.06 (Liability for conduct of
               another); 3.02 (Necessity); 4.01 (Insanity); 5.01 (Attempt)
     B.   Part II - The "Specific Part"
          1.   The sections dealing with the definitions of specific crimes.
                         2.   Note especially  210.0-210.6 (homicide); 213.0 -213.6 (Sex Offenses)             Procedural Overview of a Criminal Case
I.   Incident occurs which may be a crime
     A.   Decision: Has there been a crime?  If so, is it worth reporting?
     B.   Who decides: Police or private citizen (or public prosecutor, if "incident" is result of
          an ongoing investigation)
II.  Charging Stage 
     A.   Decisions: 
          1.   Sufficient evidence to charge? Is there probable cause to believe that a crime
               has occurred and that defendant committed it?  
          2.   If so, what crime or crimes?  
          3.   Will the defendant be arrested immediately, summoned to report or will the
               case be presented directly to the Grand Jury?
     B.   Who decides: The decision to charge can be made by police, private citizens or a
          public prosecutor, and varies by jurisdiction.  (In Mass., can be any of these. 
          Mass.R.Crim.Pro. 4(b)).  The nature of the charge is usually initially selected by the
          police or even a clerk, sometimes under direction of a magistrate or occasionally a
          public prosecutor.  The decision to seek immediate arrest or use a summons or order
          to appear may be made by administrative policy or court rule.
III. Initial Appearance or Arraignment (may occur within hours for an arrestee, may occur
     later for a defendant not in custody, some jurisdictions have two separate proceedings, an
     "initial appearance" and an arraignment," some only "arraign" on indictments)
     A.   Decisions or Actions:
          1.   Setting terms of release (i.e., bail, own recognizance, electronic monitoring,
               non-monetary sureties, etc.)
          2.   Informing Defendant of Rights (to counsel, trial, to plead not guilty,
               informing of charges)
          3.   Establishing counsel (identifying retained counsel, appointing counsel for
               indigent defendants)
     B.   Who decides or takes action: Judicial Officer (may not be a true "judge," may be a
          commissioner, magistrate, assistant, etc., may not even be a lawyer.  Factors to be
          considered in setting terms of release are now usually set by statute.
IV.  Grand Jury Consideration (no federal constitutional right to grand jury consideration,
     although many state constitutions afford it, can usually be waived)
     A.   Decision: whether there is probable cause to believe crime has occurred and that
          defendant committed it; if so an "indictment" is "returned" or "found", if not, a "no
          bill" or "no true bill" is returned.
     B.   Who decides: Panel of private citizens, usually under public prosecutor's direction,
          which reviews only the prosecution's evidence, without presence of defendant,
          defendant's counsel or adherence to rules of evidence or procedure. 
V.   Discovery and Pre-Trial Litigation (Scope, period and form varies widely by jurisdiction. 
     Some jurisdictions have close to open or "full" discovery akin to civil procedure, most have
     much more limited discovery procedures than in civil cases)
     A.   Actions
          1.   Discovery (by both defendant and prosecution)
          2.   Identification of certain affirmative defenses which require specific or
               complex rebuttal proof (e.g., Insanity, Alibi)
          3.   Challenges to the charging instrument (e.g., invalidity of indictment),
               mechanism (e.g., defects in grand jury proceedings) or  the authority to
               prosecute (e.g., to dismiss because statute is unconstitutional)
          4.   Challenges to evidence to be used (suppression of physical evidence,
               statements, etc.)
     B.   These decisions are usually made a "true" judge, although not necessarily the one
          before whom the case will be tried.
VI.  Trial or Settlement (90%+ of state criminal cases resolved by plea agreements)
     A.   Choosing trier of fact
          1.   Trial may be before a jury or judge alone (federal constitutional right to jury
               trial applies to "serious cases," those carrying over 6 months' imprisonment).
          2.   Jury selection ("voir dire") done by judge alone or judge and lawyers.
               a.   Partial jurors removed with "challenges for cause".
               b.   Jurors opposed to party's case removed through non-discriminatory
                    exercises of "peremptory challenges."
     B.   Opening statements (may or may not be made; defense may in many jurisdictions
          reserve opening until after prosecution's case).
     C.   Prosecution bears the burden of proof, so presents its case first.  Defense has
          opportunity to confront and cross-examine prosecution's witnesses.
     D.   After prosecution's case, defense may seek judgment of acquittal/required finding
          of not guilty.
     E.   Defense may, but need not, present evidence (which may, but need not, under
          privilege against self-incrimination, include defendant's testimony).  Prosecution
          cross examines defense witnesses.
     F.   If defense presents evidence, prosecution may offer rebuttal evidence.
     G.   Closing arguments (may or may not be given).
     H.   Jury instructions/"charge" (either or both sides may seek particular ones).
          1.   Instructions explain relevant law to jurors.
          2.   Defense must request instructions it wishes in order for the failure to have
               given such instructions to be recognized as error on appeal.
          3.   Standard for weighing evidence is that there must be proof beyond a
               reasonable doubt of all elements of the offense.
VII. Deliberations and rendering of verdict
VIII.     Sentencing
     A.   Usually by judge in non-capital case, though in some places by the jury.
     B.   Usually done by jury in capital cases, though not always.
     C.   Increasingly, judge sentencing now done by "guidelines" or "grid."
IX.  Appeal
     A.   Standard of appeal for sufficiency of the evidence is heavily weighted against the
          defendant to insure finality of criminal process.  Conviction upheld if, viewing all
          evidence in light most favorable to the prosecution, any rational trier of fact could
          have found all the elements of the offense beyond a reasonable doubt.  Jackson v.
          Virginia, 443 U.S. 307 (1979).
     B.   Standard on appeal for giving an incorrect jury instruction or failing to give a
          required one, if it was requested, is de novo (i.e., would it have influenced a
          reasonable juror); if it was not requested, is it nevertheless "plain error" (i.e.,
          fundamental miscarriage of justice).
X.   Post-Conviction Remedies

</PRE>

<CENTER>

