<CENTER>
<H1>Criminal Law - Section A </H1>
 <H1>Professor David Siegel</H1>
<H2> Handout 2 - class 2  </H2>
<H3> Fall 1996</H3></CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>

           
                                
<H4>Principles of Punishment - Utilitarianism & Retributive Justice</H4>
<PRE>



                                      Criminal Law - Section A 
                                              Handout - Class 2
                                

                                
I.   Justifications of Punishment: Two basic schools of thinking
     A.   Utilitarianism
     B.   Retributive Justice (or "Deserts" or "Just Deserts") 

II.  Utilitarianism (Jeremy Bentham): What punishment ("pain") or legal rule will promote the
     greatest benefit ("pleasure") at the least cost?

     A.   Punishment itself, for utilitarians, is "mischief"; it is to be used only to the  extent
          absolutely necessary.

     B.   What is the difference between "mischief" and "pain"?

     C.   Bentham identifies four circumstances in which punishment should not be inflicted.

          1.   Are these four circumstances really different?  How?

          2.   What would be the modern legal terms for these four circumstances?

III. Retributive Justice (Immanuel Kant): What penalty is imperative according to law for this
     offense?

IV.  Comparison of the two schools of thought

     A.   What is meant by the statement that retribution is "backward looking" while
          utilitarianism is "forward looking" with respect to punishment?

     B.   Which school of thought requires an independent theory of morality, i.e., an
          understanding of what conduct is wrong apart from what conduct should be
          punished?

     C.   Is it possible to have a mixed theory of punishment?  Can one believe that an
          offender should be punished if and only if the offender has committed a previously
          defined offense and the punishment of this offender is a net social benefit?

</PRE>

<CENTER>

