<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Criminal Law "A" Handout 4</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">
<CENTER>
<H1>Criminal Law - Section A<BR>
 -- Professor David Siegel</H1>
<H2>Handouts - class 4 </H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3> Fall 1996</H3>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>




<H4>Limits on the Scope of Acts which may be Criminalized I
 (Legality Principle, Common Law Crimes, Vagueness, Overbreadth & Lenity)</H4>

<PRE>
I.   THE LEGALITY PRINCIPLE: Acts are only criminal which have been previously defined
     as such.  Purposes of the Legality Principle:

     A.   Provide notice of potentially illegal conduct (i.e., to guide conduct)
     B.   Restrict arbitrary prosecutorial actions and enable effective judicial review
     C.   Enforce separation of powers (how?) because of
          1.   The undemocratic nature of the judiciary?
          2.   The judiciary's slow responsiveness to changing conditions?
          3.   Judicial rules being fashioned in case-specific contexts?
II.  COMMON LAW CRIMES: The Legality Principle without a Statute (who defines crimes?)

     A.   Legality principle can criminalize that which has not been statutorily criminalized if
          act was recognized as an offense at common law, i.e., it was a "common law crime"
          (criminal law's version of "original intent" analysis).

          1.   Existence of offense at common law provides notice to defendant.
          2.   Body of common law permits judicial review of prosecutorial action.
          3.   What limits arbitrary enforcement?  (Isn't a case which requires a judicial
               opinion to declare that there is such a crime per se arbitrary?)

     B.   Legality Principle's analogue in statutory construction is the Rule of Lenity.

III. THE VAGUENESS DOCTRINE (The Legality Principle applied to unclear statutes): A
     criminal statute which is so unclear in definition or operation that it does not give a person
     of ordinary intelligence notice of the conduct which it prohibits and does not restrict arbitrary
     enforcement violates due process.

IV.  THE RULE OF LENITY (a.k.a. "Criminal Statutes are to be strictly construed"): When
     multiple interpretations of statute available, one more lenient to the defendant is preferred. 

V.   How do you implement these principles in a particular case?
     A.   If the statute is unambiguous and unambiguously covers the conduct at issue, the
          doctrines don't apply. (The per se rules about drunk driving, eg. 0.10% = DUI)

     B.   If statute is clear, but there is ambiguity concerning whether it applies to the
          situation, look to the common law (CL) to determine if CL covered the situation. 
          Legislature is presumed familiar with CL, so 

          1.   If CL terms used, legislature meant to embody them and continue their CL
               meaning. (Keeler, majority- term "human being"?  Term isn't explicitly used;
               Keeler, dissent - says majority misreads CL, CL meaning really the reverse).

          2.   If CL terms NOT used, legislature may have meant to abandon them, but
               more likely meant to just leave the CL in place.

          3.   If CL terms/rules explicitly disavowed, legislature meant that, follow statute. 

          4.   What about a general disavowal of the CL but no specific rule to replace the
               CL's specific rule for a particular situation? (Keeler).  Two possibilities:

               a.   CL [generally] disavowed, so disregard CL and do reverse of CL?

               b.   Where CL specifically covered particular situation, and statute which
                    generally disavows the CL does NOT make a particular provision for
                    this situation, follow CL.

     C.   If statute is NOT clear (VAGUENESS), see if the meaning can be discerned by
          persons of ordinary intelligence through prior judicial interpretations (in that or any
          other jurisdiction), so that it

          1.   puts people of ordinary intelligence on notice what conduct is prohibited and 

          2.   protects against arbitrary enforcement (i.e., allows objective review of
               enforcement and adjudication).

     D.   Interpretation of the statute's meaning is guided by these principles:

          1.   Statute as interpreted should not proscribe otherwise legal conduct
               (OVERBREADTH),

          2.   Statutes are presumed constitutional and there is a judicial preference against
               invalidating them, and

          3.   If multiple interpretations are available, RULE OF LENITY suggests giving
               defendant the benefit of the most favorable one.



</PRE>

<CENTER>

