Limits on the Scope of Acts which may be Criminalized II  (Status Offenses)

I.   Robinson v. California, 370 U.S. 660 (1962)
     A.   What was constitutionally invalid about Robinson's conviction?
          1.   For the Court?
          2.   For Douglas?
          3.   For Harlan?
     B.   Was the constitutional infirmity the criminalizing of a status or the criminalizing of
          the status of having a disease?

II.  Powell v. Texas, 392 US 514 (1968) 
     A.   Can Powell be consistent with Robinson?
     B.   What policy reasons might explain the difference in the results?
III. What does it mean to call something a "status" offense?
     A.   Specialized meaning in context of juvenile practice.
     B.   Retributive/just deserts v. utilitarian view of status offenses.
     C.   Reasons disfavoring the criminalization of status.
          1.   The problem of defining status by reference to behavior: if the condition of
               doing a prohibited act is the status, what is left for the criminal law to
               restrain?

          2.   What is the appropriate time frame?  When does an act become involuntary?

          3.   Establishing the standard for avoiding the status: how strong a character
               should the law presume everyone has?    
               
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT14-B14-71</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA009-000089-B038-264</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://library.nesl.edu:80/crmlaw06.htm 38.232.116.6 19970222125621 text/html 4454
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 12:46:50 GMT
