Content-length: 4278
</DOCHDR>
The Act Requirement (Actus Reus, Voluntariness, Omissions) and
The Guilty Mind I (Mens Rea)
 

I.   Mens Rea and Actus Reus: "There are two components of every crime.  One is objective --
     the actus reus; the other is subjective -- the mens rea.  The actus reus is the culpable act itself,
     the mens rea is the criminal intent with which one performs the criminal act.  However, mens
     rea does not encompass the entire mental process of one accused of a crime.  There is a
     certain minimal mental element required in order to establish the actus reus itself.  This is
     the element of volition."  State v. Utter, 479 P.2d 946, 948 (Wash Ct App. 1971). 

II.  The Requirement of an Act which is Voluntary (Martin v. State, 17 So.2d 427 (Ala. 1944)).
     A.   Other meanings of the term "voluntary" (common sense, criminal procedure) 
     B.   What was Martin's "act"?
          1.   An "act" can be simply being somewhere (e.g., criminal trespass).
          2.   What are the elements of Martin's offense?  

III. The Requirement of a Voluntary Act: Element of Prosecution's Case or a Defense? (Utter)
     A.   Lack of capacity to be criminally responsible v. Lack of a voluntary act
          1.   Different burdens on the parties
          2.   Different consequences of Defendant's success 
     B.   Would Utter's demonstrated unconsciousness have wholly exonerated him?

IV.  Aspects of "Voluntary Act"
     A.   Involuntary Acts v. Non-Acts  (Note 3, p. 87)
     B.   Harmful Acts done Willingly v. Acts Willingly done to Harm (Note 4, p. 87)
     C.   The Multiple Personality Case: Whose volition? (Dea Wheaton, Supp. Mat. II- 
     D.   Epileptic Seizures-what's the appropriate time frame for evaluating the involuntary
          act?  (Compare to the time frame problem in Powell v. Texas, when the chosen act
          becomes a compulsion and so a status.)  Two approaches: Decina and Martin.
          1.   What is the prohibited conduct in each case?
          2.   Is there a difference in the type of harm at issue which affects the type of
               protection the law provides?

V.   The Model Penal Code Approach: Defining by Exclusion (Secs. 1.13 and 2.01) .

VI.  Why have an Actus Reus Requirement for Crimes?
     A.   Avoid punishment for "evil thoughts"?
     B.   Requirement of an identifiable event reduces danger of multiple or arbitrary 
          prosecution and punishment
     C.   Why restrict actus reus to voluntary acts?
          1.   Deterrence: the law can't deter the involuntary movement or spasm.
          2.   Just Deserts: fundamentally unfair to criminalize involuntary movements. 
          3.   Voluntariness implies concept of baselines for behavior or conduct. 

VII. Omissions - "Negative Acts"
     A.   The Common Law Rule - no duty to aid, so no liability for failure to aid.
     B.   The Recognized Exceptions to the General Rule
          1.   Statutorily created duties
          2.   Duties based upon status or relationship
          3.   Duties arising from contract
          4.   Duty arising from a voluntary assumption of care + seclusion of helpless one
          5.   Duty based upon creation of risk or peril

VIII.     The Historic Requirement of an Intent to do Wrong or a Guilty Mind: Mens Rea
     A.   Two uses in cases
          1.   "Culpability Meaning": Intent to do any socially undesirable conduct 
               (having a morally culpable mind set)
          2.   "Elemental Meaning": Intent to do or achieve a specific wrong, now or in the
               future 
     B.   The Common law often conflated the two meanings of mens rea (as in Regina v.
          Cunningham); the Model Penal Code uses only the "elemental meaning of the term,"
          but some jurisdictions (including Massachusetts) have not adopted a Model penal
          Code-based codification.
     C.   Can criminal liability arise without mens rea (culpability sense)?  Yes, strict liability.
          1.   Sometimes called "absolute liability" (see Regina v. City of Sault Ste. Marie)
          2.   Note this is not "vicarious liability," which involves holding one liable for
               the criminal acts of another.
</DOC>
