<TITLE>NESL: Criminal Law Handout 7</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Criminal Law "A" - Handout 7</H2>
<HR NOSHADE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Guilty Mind II (Specific v. General Intent,
The Common Law Formula, The Model Penal Code Formula)</H3>


<PRE>
I.   Specific Intent v. General Intent (Model Penal Code eliminates distinction) 
     A.   It is often said that certain crimes are "specific intent" crimes while others are
          "general intent" crimes.  This distinction is probably best understood only in the
          minds of the users of this archaic terminology.  Nevertheless, many survive.
     B.   Specific Intent Crimes
          1.   Where mental state set out is intent or, occasionally, knowledge.
          2.   Where intent relates to mens rea rather than only actus reus (e.g., an
               "intentional taking" relates only to the actus reus, an "intentional taking with 
               intent to permanently deprive owner of possession" relates to mens rea also)
          3.   Types of "Specific Intent"
               a.   To do a specific wrong in the future separate from the actus reus (e.g.,
                    assault with intent to...murder, rob, rape, etc.; also taking with intent
                    to defraud)
               b.   A specific motive or purpose (e.g., with intent to cause pain)
               c.   With knowledge of certain attendant circumstances (e.g., crimes
                    involving doing almost anything to minors)
     C.   General Intent Crimes - Where no specific mental state is required in statute, or the 
          mental state is recklessness or negligence.          
              
II.  Transferred Intent - If the harm intended does not have to be the precise harm which results,
     does the party to whom the harm occurs have to be the precise party to whom the harm was
     intended? People v. Czahara

III. The Continuing Vitality of the Common Law Formula: Commonwealth v. Ruddock (Willful
     v. Wanton acts).

IV.  The Model Penal Code Formula establishes degrees of culpability based wholly on the
     offender's mental state.
     A.   Purposeful or intentional
          1.   The conduct or the result must be the actor's conscious purpose.
          2.   This is a distinction the common law did not recognize.
     B.   Knowing
          1.   The third prong of the old "specific intent" (i.e., doing an act with knowledge
               of attendant circumstances)
          2.   The conduct or result must be practically certain to occur.
          3.   Exception: Willful blindness is equivalent to knowledge; a conscious effort
               to ignore obviously raised suspicions does not avoid "knowledge."  U.S. v.
               Jewell; Model Penal Code 2.02(7).
     C.   Reckless - conscious disregard of risk 
     D.   Negligent - lack of awareness of risk

V.   Bad Grammar can send you to (or keep you from) Prison - In a statute with multiple actus
     reus elements, to which does the mens rea term apply?  
     A.   The Common Law Rule: Absent a stated mens rea, the offense (or here, the element)
          required no specific mens rea and was a strict liability offense (i.e., no mens rea
          required).
     B.   The Model Penal Code Default Rules
          1.   A single Mens rea term modifies every material element unless a contrary
               purpose plainly appears (2.02(4)).
          2.   Absent a stated mens rea, at least recklessness is required for all material
               elements.  (2.02(3)).



</PRE>

<CENTER>

