<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Criminal Law Handout 8</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Criminal Law "A" - Handout 8</H2>
<HR NOSHADE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Guilty Mind III (Strict Liability, Mistake of Fact)</H3>


<PRE>
    The Guilty Mind III (Strict Liability, Mistake of Fact)
                                
I.   What is Strict (Criminal) Liability?

     A.   v. "Vicarious Liability" (i.e., liability for conduct of another)

     B.   v. "Absolute Liability" (sometimes used as a synonym for strict liability, sometimes
          used for those offenses for which mistake of fact or having taken reasonable care are
          not defenses; see Regina v. City of Sault Ste. Marie)

II.  Reasons to have (or not have) Strict Liability
     A.   Reasons favoring Strict Liability
          1.   Protection of "social interests" so important it requires extra care by those in
               a position to harm it, so extra incentive to avoid harm is also necessary.
          2.   Administrative convenience given large number of cases.
          3.   Small penalties and minimal stigma these offenses carry minimize harm of
               not requiring mens rea (i.e., no one really considers these crimes anyway).
     B.   Reasons opposing Strict Liability
          1.   Retributive Justice: It is wrong to punish the "unintentional wrongdoer"
               because they no notice of or knowledge that conduct was improper.
          2.   "Social interests" basis for strict liability not compelling because
               a.   Important interests are protected by prohibiting both strict liability
                    and mens rea offenses,
               b.   It imposes an unnecessarily high incentive to take care; a person who
                    is already as careful as possible can't be any more careful.
               c.   No deterrence possible if there is no benefit to having been careful.
          3.   Administrative convenience basis for strict liability is illusory because the
               same evidence which must properly be heard at sentencing (that the offender
               was careful) could be heard at trial, and regulatory offenses of businesses
               would more rationally be effected through civil penalties the cost of which
               a business could integrate into it cost structure).
          4.   Any conviction necessarily carries some stigma.

III. How to Determine whether a statute imposes strict liability (per Morisette v. U.S., 342
     U.S.246, 72 S.Ct.240, 96 L.Ed. 288 (1952).

     A.   Did legislature include a mens rea term?  If not, proceed.
     B.   Is offense "negative," i.e., requires neglect of a statutorily-imposed duty?  If so,
          proceed.
     C.   Is offense against general public welfare, rather than persons or property?  If so,
          proceed.
     D.   Is offense's penalty "relatively small" (i.e., < year's incarceration)?  If so, proceed.
     E.   Does penalty not "gravely besmirch" offender's reputation?  If so, strict liability may
          be presumed.  Otherwise, court will read in mens rea requirement.

IV.  Mistake of Fact

     A.   Common Law Rule: 
          1.   Specific Intent Crimes: Unreasonable Mistakes of Fact are a defense.
          2.   General Intent Crimes: Only Reasonable Mistakes of Fact are a defense. 

     B.   Model Penal Code Rule: A mistake of fact (or law) is a defense whenever it
          negatives the degree of culpability required for the offense. (Sec. 2.04)(1)(a).

     C.   An approach to determining mistake of fact problems
          1.   First, is crime specific intent, general intent or strict liability?
          2.   Then, follow appropriate rule
               a.   If strict liability: mistake of fact irrelevant.  NO DEFENSE.
               b.   If specific intent crime: does mistake relate to specific intent portion
                    of the offense?
                    (1)  If yes, use elemental analysis of mens rea (i.e., does mistake
                         negate the specific intent element?)
                    (2)  If no, follow rules for general intent offense.
               c.   If general intent crime: do "culpability" analysis, i.e. did D act with
                    morally blameworthy state of mind?
                    (1)  Usually
                         (a)  If mistake REASONABLE, then D not morally
                              blameworthy and is acquitted
                         (b)  If mistake UNREASONABLE, D is morally
                              blameworthy and guilty.
                    (2)  Alternatively
                         (a)  Moral Wrong Doctrine: Even if D's mistake is
                              reasonable, was D's conduct nevertheless immoral? 
                              If so, D held responsible for risk that immoral
                              behavior actually proved illegal, no defense.
                         (b)  Legal Wrong Doctrine: Even if D's mistake is
                              reasonable, was D's conduct nevertheless illegal
                              (albeit under a lesser offense)?  If so, D held
                              responsible for crime D believed he was committing,
                              rather than one he would have been committing
                              absent mistake.  Note if there is no lesser included
                              offense, D not guilty.

</PRE>

