<HEAD>
<TITLE>NESL: Criminal Law Handout 9</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A NAME="top">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>New England School of Law</H1>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Criminal Law "A" - Handout 9</H2>
<HR NOSHADE>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Guilty Mind IV (Mistake of Law); Causation</H3>



<PRE>         
                                
I.   Common Law Maxim: Mistake (or Ignorance) of the law is no excuse.

II.  Model Penal Code Approach (2.04(1), 2.04(3))
     A.   A mistake of law is a defense if it negatives the culpability required to establish the
          material element of the offense.  
     B.   A belief that conduct does not constitute an offense is a defense when
          1.   The statute defining the offense has not been made public, or  
          2.   The defendant acts in reasonable reliance upon official statement afterward
               determined to be wrong.
     C.   Proof that defendant did not operate under a mistake of law is NOT an element of the
          offense.

III. Aspects of Mistake of Law
     A.   Mistake about the law defendant allegedly broke v. Mistake about another law which
          led to defendant violating law allegedly broken
          1.   A mistake about the law defendant is charged with allegedly breaking is
               classic "mistake of law"; it is what the common law maxim was directed
               against.
          2.   A mistake about a collateral law may deprive the defendant of the required
               mens rea, if the law allegedly violated has a specific mens rea requirement.
     B.   Both common law and the Model Penal Code are very hostile to a mistake of law
          defense, much more so than to a mistake of fact defense.  Why?

IV.  The Policy Arguments concerning the Mistake of Law Defense
     A.   Is it fairer to recognize or not recognize the mistake of law defense?
     B.   Is it more just to recognize or not recognize the mistake of law defense?
     C.   Does it encourage or discourage law-abiding conduct to recognize the defense?
     D.   Is it administratively easier to recognize or not recognize the defense?

V.   Causation
     A.   Conviction requires that defendant's conduct have been both actual cause (or "cause
          in fact") and legal cause (or "proximate cause") of the prohibited result.
          1.   Actual cause - essentially "but-for" causation
               a.   Can be concurrence among multiple defendants (if each is a
                    "substantial factor" in producing prohibited result), see Oxendine v.
                    State (p. 176)
               b.   Susceptible to breaking of causal chain by independent intervening
                    causes, though not by foreseeable consequences.  See Kibbe v.
                    Henderson, at p. 183.
          2.   Legal cause - "is less a matter of applying hard and fast rules than it is an
               effort by the factfinder to determine, for reasons of social policy or out of a
               conception of justice, on whom to impose criminal penalties." Dressler, at
               181.
               a.   Criminal victims are taken as they are found.  See, State v.
                    Cummings, at p. 187 (majority).
               b.   Proximate cause can not be coincidental; i.e., it must be causally-related.  See, State v. Cummings, at p. 187 (dissent).
     B.   Model Penal Code Approach: Section 2.03 - But-for causation plus any additional
          causal requirements the law imposes.  Note especially secs. 2.03(2)(b) and
          2.03(3)(b).  Should the word "just" be eliminated or retained without brackets?  
</PRE>


