<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="kable_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212></P><CENTER><P><IMG SRC="kable.gif" HEIGHT=42 WIDTH=143></P></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>Kable is the UK's leading specialist publisher and researcher about public-sector information systems, providing market intelligence and strategic planning advice. Its clients  include suppliers selling IT/comms equipment and solutions to the public sector, consultancies and government bodies.</P><P>Kable's publications include in-depth IS Market Profiles, subscription services, pathfinding studies and the <B><I>Signposts to Government</I></B>independent guide to information-age government. </P>

<P>Kable undertakes custom market research and consultancy, advising awide range of private and public sector clients, in the UK and internationally.</P> 
<H3>Kable Products and Services</H3>
<H4>Custom Research and Consultancy:</H4>
<P>Kable undertakes custom market research and consultancy on a confidential basis, advising a  wide range of private and public sector clients in the UK and internationally. The company provides private research, special projects, strategic advice, specialist services, seminars and training.</P><P>We operate in four modes: </P>
<UL><LI>as knowledge manager, presenting and prioritising issues</LI>
<LI>as catalyst, generating debate and challenging received wisdom</LI>
<LI>as coach and partner, listening and advising</LI>
<LI>and as investigator, researching, analysing and presenting custom research</LI>
</UL>
<P>As well as specialist studies, Kable has experience in large scale market research. </P>
<P>Kable aims to help its clients achieve the following: </P><UL><LI>focus sales and marketing  propositions more effectively </LI><LI>communicate better and target the right people </LI><LI>inform the business planning process fully </LI><LI>improve risk analysis </LI><LI>work for common good/best practice </LI>
<LI>form opinion and policy.</LI></UL>
<P>Our work matches a civil service insider's knowledge with a common-sense, business like perspective.</P>
<H4>Market Profiles:</H4>
<P>Kable publishes a regular series of in-depth market profiles covering the six main public sector IS/comms markets. These are based on in-depthinterviews, market research and budget documents, and provide an invaluable mine of hard facts and data on public sector buying patterns and trends. Extensive tables give detailed budget breakdowns for hardware, software,comms and services. </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<LI>Civil Service IS Market Profile</LI><LI>Defence IS Market Profile </LI><LI>Police IS Market Profile</LI><LI>Healthcare IS Market Profile </LI><LI>Higher Education IS Market Profile</LI> 
<LI>Local Government IS Market Profile</LI></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>Subscription Publications:</H4>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Kable Cuttings:</B> weekly: 1,595 per year, paper; 3,595, e-mail, site licence.<BR>This is Kable's highly respected news scanning and abstracting service. Considerable market intelligence goes into the compilation, which is a major time-saving device, enabling readers to stay on top of key developments while reducing the strain on your in-tray. Public sector IT and information policy news and issues are covered in eight concise and regular sections: General, Central Government, Defence, Education, Law and Order and Emergency Services; Local Government; the NHS; and Contracts Tendered and awarded. Kable Cuttings is published weekly (46 issues per year).</P>

<P><B>The Kable Briefing: </B>monthly: 395 per year, paper; 895,e-mail, site licence. The authoritative market analysis newsletter on public-sector information issues and their commercial implications. The Kable Briefing gives an insider's view of the rules of the game, analysing important developments. Written by top specialists and journalists, the publication uniquely identifies the key people and what they think. The Kable Briefing is published 10 times per year.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE><H4>Special Reports:</H4>
<P>Kable has led the way in publishing independent studies of the effect of the information age on the UK public sector. In November 1995 it published the much-acclaimed Tomorrow's Town Hall followed in May 1996 by An Insight into Labour's Information Systems Policy for the Public Sector. The companyis currently researching and preparing to publish Citizen Direct, a visionary study on the shape of central government in the early 21st century seen from the perspective of an ordinary citizen. </P>
<H3>Kable People </H3><UL><LI>William Heath, Director</LI><LI>Karen Swinden, Director</LI><LI>Mark Hudson, Director</LI></UL><P>To contact Kable staff, please use the <A HREF="../contact.html">Contact</A> section.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
