</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>UK public expenditure - personal service pressures and IT</H3>

<P>Over a thirty year period, the proportion of the UK's gross domestic product which has been spent by all layers of government has shown sharp fluctuations but this has not necessarily been due to changing governments.  If there is an overall trend, it is only very mildly upwards. During the whole period public spending has fluctuated between 39.5% and 49.5% of  GDP, while taxation has only fluctuated between 33% and 39%. In 1995/96 expenditure was 43% of GDP, and is likely to have fallen only marginally in 1996/97.</P>

<P>Taking the period 1979/80 to 1994/95, the proportions spent on some items,
have, however, fallen sharply: for example, defence fell from 4.6% to 3.2%, and housing from
2.9% to under 1%.  Health spending has, however, increased from 3.8% to 4.6%. Education has
shown little change at around 6% of GDP. Social security has increased from 10.1 to 12.5% of GDP.</P>

<P>There is very little notable change which has taken place in spending on
total wages and salaries, or in the total purchase of goods and services from the private
sector, during this period. In fact UK government consumption of goods and services in national accounts terms, which excludes transfers(ie social security, pensions etc), at 21.2% in 1995 was notably above the EU average of 18.7%.</P>

<P>The Conservatives who have been in office for nearly 18 years, can claim to have held back to a remarkable extent the rise in the range of transfer spending which is broadly categorised as social security. The upward pressures on social security spending have been wide-ranging: an increase in the retired population, much higher structural non-employment, a doubling of claimants for invalidity benefit, increased claims for in-work benefits for those on low wages, and finally the divestment of public housing stock and the provision of housing benefit rather than actual accomodation to those who cannot afford market rents. When all these trends are taken into account, it has required considerable economies to keep down social
security to its current level.</P>

<P>Since the real size of national GDP itself has increased over the same period, it is often noted that the "real" level of spending on services like health and education has also increased, a claim which seems paradoxical to those working in or using these services, for whom financial constraints seem to have tightened and morale to have consequently fallen. There are two aspects to these public services.</P>

<P>The first and most crucial, in both health and education, is the need for direct person-to-person service, the availability of which cannot be increased by technological advances. For these services, spending must remain constant as a proportion of GDP for the real value of the service not to deteriorate, since reduced staff numbers will inevitably reduce the service and, if professional pay is reduced in relation to pay in the rest of the
economy, the morale and status of the profession will fall.</P>

<P>The second aspect is the administrative side of service provision. Until recently productivity gains were confined mainly to mining and manufacturing. But private sector
services such as banking have also in the last ten years or so been increasing productivity.
Unfortunately, the trend in public services such as health and education has been in the other
direction, since most changes have increased rather than reduced the need for administration.</P>

<P>With both major parties committed not to increase public spending in relation to GDP, the challenge for whatever government emerges from the forthcoming election will be to reverse this process of increased spending on administration, and so to maximise the human resources
available for the direct provision of services at a human level. The new information technologies have the potential to help this process, but they are also a major expenditure item in themselves.</P>

<P>December 20, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
