<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Big bidders in Accord</H3>

<P>The Department of Social Security is cranking up its computer systems in an effort to get a grip on its bureaucratic costs and fraud.  On December 12, it announced a shortlist of suppliers bidding to supply a 1.6 billion system called Accord, which stands for access to corporate data.</P>

<P>The bidders invited to the next stage are:</P>
<UL>
<LI>AFFINITY, a consortium led by Electronic Data Systems (EDS) in partnership with IBM;</LI>
<LI>ARCWAY, a consortium of Bull Information Systems, SEMA and Syntegra, British Telecoms systems integration subsidiary;</LI>
<LI>ICL in partnership with Andersen Consulting and CCN.</LI>
</UL>

<P>A further bidder, Philips, failed to make the shortlist.</P>

<P>The Accord project sprang out of an initiative called the Departmental Change Forum, which Peter Lilley, the secretary of state for social security, announced in February 1996.  The new structure relies on a common source of data called the Shared Systems Infrastructure (SSI).  The successful bidder for Accord will deliver the technology, under a private-finance initiative deal.</P>

<P>The new system will form part of a massive infrastructure to share data across different departments and agencies, with the idea of cutting losses to fraud.  The government says that fraudulent social security claims add up to 1.4 billion a year.  On top of this, the Benefits Agency wrongly paid 652.9 million of income support in 1995-96, because of errors, according to a report by the National Audit Office.</P>

<P>It will be interesting to see where and how the huge planned cost and fraud savings actually accrue. The system will have to be pretty successful to give any measureable payback for the 1.6 billion implementation cost.</P>

<P>December 16, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
