<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Hidden costs and hidden barriers to getting wired</H3>

<P>Is Net connectivity cheap? You may think so, but have you taken enough account of the phone bill component? According a recent study by the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), the phone bill accounts for around 70 per cent of the full costs of Net access for a user who spends 20 hours a month online during the daytime. In other words if you're paying 10 a month for net access, add a further 23 for the monthly cost of the phone bill -- so the total bill is around 400 per year per person.  Bell Atlantic has estimated that customers with Net access spend between 30 and 100 times as long on the phone as the average subscriber.</P>

<P>Another hidden Net cost has been labelled "cyberskivving" - which speaks for itself. However, corporate fears may be exaggerated here, as it is mainly first time users who spend a lot of useless hours surfing around the Net. More experienced users soon learn not to let the clock run away with itself.</P>

<P>In government, there are still excessive concerns about "cyberskivving" as well as security, both of which do need to be looked at but shouldnt become real barriers to allowing broad access to the Internet for civil servants. A valid parallel may be with the arrival of the telephone, which took a surprisingly long time to reach the desk of every clerical worker - though the benefits were rapidly appreciated by converts to the new medium. Cultural barriers are the hardest to breach.<P>

<P>In the meantime, watch out for close scrutiny of phone bills - and make sure that Net surfing ultimately focuses on real information benefits.</P>

<P>December 16, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
