<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Analysis: the MoD struggles to count its capital</H3>

<P>The Ministry of Defence's Capital project, launched in May 1996, faces steep technical hurdles (See <A HREF="../news/nb6.12cap.htm"> capital punishment</A>). But there are also underlying problems to be tackled before the first computer goes live. Here is a (relatively) jargon-free primer.</P>

<P>Capital was driven by two imperatives. One was internal; the need to find better budgetary
and planning tools to support the MoD's 1991 New Management Strategy,
under which budgets were delegated to top-level and subordinate
budget-holders.  The other imperative was external; the need to
move all public accounts to a resource basis. This means
counting the true cost of an activity, including the use of
underlying assets, rather than simply counting the money spent
in a given year.</P>

<P>As in all IT projects, the first problem was to assess the
business issues.  For the in-year management of cash, the
existing process, there is little difficulty in defining what is
needed. (However the need to simplify the coding of spending
into fewer categories raises difficult issues.  The main one
is just how many sub-divisions does a budget need to split into
for local control and for higher level review and analysis.  The
answer should certainly be less than the 5000-plus  that existed
at the start of the New Management Strategy!)</P>

<P><B>What price a tank?</B><P>
The next -- and more difficult -- issue was what had to be done
to achieve full resource accounting.  Issues here included the
ownership of existing assets and their values.  Should a tank in
service be the property for budgetary purposes of the Commander
in Chief, whose front-line units deploy the tank,  or of the
Quartermaster General, whose staff are responsible for its
maintenance?  And what about a future tank - is the Chief of
Defence Procurement to own the project until delivery to the
front line?  And on what financial basis?</P>

<P>Real estate presents similar difficulties: is the value to be current use -- who
else would want a tank training area? -- or alternative use?  The
Duke of York's Barracks in the King's Road, London, is a nice example!</P>

<P>The final, and most intractable, issue concerns the whole
process of resource allocation.  Under the current long-term
costing process, the MoD takes a 10-year view.  The first three years are controlled by the
results of the annual public expenditure survey, announced in
the November Budget.  Each of armed service and the central MoD is
responsible for "bidding" for the resources which it feels it
needs to meet the objectives set it by the Annual Defence Plan
for the next three years.  It must also project these costs
forward (at constant prices) to allow for known or expected changes in later years: for
example, the introduction into service in five years time of Eurofighter or new radio
communications systems or whatever.</P>

<P>Each submission also covers costings for
new items that the individual service would like to bring in to
the programme -- and, less popularly, for items that could be
removed from the programme without damaging capability, to make
room for changes elsewhere (or for cuts in future public spending
rounds).</P>

<P>These additions and reductions, known as "alternative assumptions",
can exceed 1,000 in a bad year.  They are the
subject of debate and negotiation until a 10-year programme,
within the agreed and projected funding limits, is defined.  The
process is time-consuming -- and, arguably, does not really
address the major issues of changes in force capability as
technology changes and, increasingly important with the end of
the Cold War, as the nature of the defence requirement itself
changes.</P>

<P><B>Planned obsolescence</B><P>
Is 10 years a sensible timescale?  A new warship can take at
least this length of time to reach the design stage and will then
be in service for a further 20 to 30 years, or even
more. The gestation of a new aircraft or tank can be at least
as protracted.  But the pace of change of technology is
increasing, so there is a real danger that new equipment will
always be out of date before it comes into service.  The
only answer is to rely more on regular updates in
basic equipment that is designed for maximum flexibility.</P>

<P>To what level of detail should the programme be planned?  For
the early years, when there will be little change, it could be
argued that the top-level and lower budget holders could -- and
should -- be in charge of all that is needed, provided only that they live
within the resource levels allocated at the end of the public expenditure round
and meet their objectives as defined in the Defence Plan.  But
this would reduce the central programme's ability to
interfere, thus weakening its power.</P>

<P>For the later years, the centre should perhaps concentrate only on the
big issues such as new equipment, major changes in deployment or
tasks, or reacting to major demographic changes.  Again this will
weaken its ability to interfere -- perhaps a good thing.  But
until these issues are resolved, in a resource budgeting
context, progress on Capital will be difficult.</P>

<P>A final issue: should the debate be limited to the MoD or
should Parliament and the general public not have the
opportunity to put a view?</P>

<P>December 9, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

</BODY>
