<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Boo HISS</H3>

<P>MPs slam hospital computer initiative</P>


<P>A 106 million scheme to demonstrate the benefits of computers in National 
Health Service hospitals has received a severe ticking-off from the House of 
Commons Committee of Public Accounts.</P>
<P>The project, called HISS, was hurried in inception, delayed in execution and may 
have harmed the quality of care in some hospitals picked as pilot sites, the 
report says.</P> 
<P>The committee was particularly scathing about a system funded by the initiative at 
City Hospital, Nottingham.  The MPs said they were "astonished" that the 
Nottingham scheme went ahead.</P>
<P>HISS, which stands for hospital information support system, was launched at the 
end of 1988.  The idea was to integrate all the management systems in major 
hospitals, leading to big gains in efficiency.</P>
<P>The Department of Health agreed to pay for a series of demonstrator sites at 
large hospitals to prove the concept, which it managed through the NHS 
Executive.  However, the two leading suppliers of NHS computers, ICL and SMS, declined to 
bid for the contracts.  The first three went to McDonnell Douglas (now MDIS), 
HBO, a specialist healthcare software firm based in Atlanta, and Oracle.  Other 
major contracts went to IBM in partnership with GTE and Hoskyns (now Cap 
Gemini), whose software partner Gerber Alley was taken over in turn by First 
Data, and HBO.</P>
<P>The Commmittee of Public Accounts held hearings on the initiative in May 1996 
after the National Audit Office published a critical report of six sites.  The 
NAO found that the pilot sites had been chosen too hastily, the projects had 
been poorly run, fell behind schedule and had been inadequately evaluated.
The committee's report, published on December 5, echoes this criticism, 
sometimes in less temperate language.  The MPs said they were "concerned" about:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Delays of between eight months and three years to all six projects the NAO 
inspected</LI>
<LI>Damage to the quality of care at these hospitals when expected benefits did 
not materialise</LI>
<LI>The NHS's failure to make best use of existing hospital computer projects, 
four of which were already in progress, before signing the first round of HISS 
contracts</LI>
<LI>The rushed choice of the first three hospitals, which resulted in two of them 
being unready for the task ahead.</LI>
</UL>
<P>As for the costs and benefits: "The six projects visited by the National Audit 
Office were expected to cost some 88 million, with offsetting cash savintgs of 
41 million. The NHS Executive have now reduced their estimate of offsetting 
cash savings sharply, to between 27 million and 30 million. We are dismayed 
that the net cost of the six projects may now be as high as 61 million, and 
that the increase in net costs of some 14 million has to be met from other 
budgets, with a consequential adverse impact on patient care in the hospitals 
concerned."</P>
<P>The NHS Executive has always maintained that the HISS project, which it 
continues to support by maintaining an organisation called HISS Central Team, is 
a success.  In a terse statement on the report, the NHS Executive's chief 
executive, Alan Langlands, said: "We will study the report's conclusions and 
recommendations carefully. We fully agree with the emphasis in the report on 
evaluation and the NHS Executive will publish an evaluation of the initiative."
This official evaluation, called PROBE, was due to be published in October 1996.</P>

<P>December 9, 1996</P>


<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
