<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><img src="pu_line.gif">
<blockquote>
<H3>NHS Clearing Service</H3>


<P><B>Purpose:</B>  To exchange information between the "purchasers" and "providers" of 
medical care set up by the National Health Service reforms in 1991.  Under the 
reforms, health authorities and some family doctors, called fundholders, buy 
treatment from NHS hospitals.  Information to support these transactions is 
encoded in standard "contract data sets".  The clearing service is supposed to 
ensure that these data sets go to the right place, via an NHS-wide computer 
network.</P>

<P><B>Contractor:</B> AT&T was awarded a contract to set up the system under the Private 
Finance Initiative in September 1995.  It agreed to have a system, called 
ClearNET, running in pilot form by April 1996 and across the whole NHS by April 
1997.  It was the first IT contract awarded by the Department of Health through 
the Private Finance Initiative.  AT&T agreed to set up the system at its own 
risk, and bill according to useage under a tightly controlled pricing formula. 
The unsuccessful bidders were Hoskyns (now Cap Gemini UK) and SEMA.</P>

<P><B>Progress:</B> Technically, the project appears to be running on schedule and has 
overcome delays in the procurement process. Its problems stem from politics and 
the structure of the NHS.  These fall into three main areas.</P>
<UL>
<LI> Concerns about security.  The British Medical Association said that the 
clearing service would build up a national database of information about 
individual patients, identifiable through NHS numbers.  It demanded extra 
measures to protect confidentiality.  The Department of Health has agreed to 
test a method of encrypting data, with an algorithm called Red Pike, across the 
network.</LI><BR>
<LI> Users' reluctance. Although the system is in theory mandatory for NHS 
organisations, individual hospitals and GPs have been reluctant to sign up.  
Some already subscribe to local clearing services which were set up by regional 
health authorities, which were abolished in April 1996.  Others have signed up 
to the clearing service, but are sending data by courier rather than across the 
network.</LI><BR> 
<LI> Uncertainty over future demand.  When it won the contract, AT&T said it 
expected the number of transactions the service carried to grow to 400 million a 
year by the end of the century.  This seems unlikely.  In summer 1996, in an 
attempt to reduce bureaucracy, the Department of Health ruled that hospitals 
would not need to exchange data about emergency admissions from outside their 
area. </LI>
</UL> 
<P>Meanwhile, the Labour Party has said that, if elected, it will end the 
need for individual contracts for treatments to be exchanged, and to create 
longer-term partnerships between health authorities and hospitals. It hopes to 
cut the number of contracts exchanged by 90 per cent, which would be bad news 
for AT&T.</P> 

<P>December 9, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government <pre></pre>&copy; <a href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

</BODY>
</HTML>
