<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>IT for All - but what does it do for me?</H3>

<P>Hot on the heels of its information policy green paper <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/citu/gdirect/ind1.htm"> Government.direct</A>, the government launched its IT for All campaign on December 3. But does it add up to much?</P>

<P>The purpose of IT for All is to encourage techno-sceptics and technophobes to take a more positive view of IT's impact on our lives. This is a worthy aim, and makes a refreshing change from most IT missionary activity which preaches to the converted.</P>

<P>Research commissioned for this campaign (and based on a survey of over 3,000 carried out by BMRB in August) shows that 55 per cent of the population are either afraid of computer technology, unconvinced of its value or alienated by it.</P>

<P>The government's argument is that unless the benefits of IT are sold more successfully to this very significant chunk of the population, "we will  not become an information society" and "we will get left behind".</P>

<P>Does this matter? The two-hour parade of speeches from leading government and industry figures (including contributions from the top men in BT, Microsoft and Dixons) kept emphasising the "very major benefits" of IT, which will "enhance our lives". But no-one spelt out what the benefits could be for individuals. Bringing home the message to the computer-shy needs something more imaginative than this - with many concrete examples of how IT does make a big difference. It is not inspiring to be told that the UK as a whole will
win out in world markets only if society becomes highly IT-literate -- try telling that to someone who never quite gets round to learning how to operate a PC.</P>

<P>It's also not quite clear what IT for All really adds up to - raising public awareness doesn't take you very far, especially if the public you're trying to reach are not information-oriented. The bulk of the programme on offer consists in "partnership projects" with private sector companies such as IBM, BT, Mitsubishi Electric, ICL, Dixons and Microsoft. Essentially, these companies will promote the benefits of IT to their customers in an "IT for All" context - not exactly boldly going where no man has been before. Thus, there doesn't seem to be much behind the hype. However, at least senior figures in government are beginning to take the IT revolution on board, even if most of them never touch a keyboard.<P>

<P>More telling an explanation of why the government appears now to be embracing IT as an electoral goodie was the assertion by Ian Taylor, Minister for Science and Technology, that "the information-related sector now provides more new jobs than any other".</P>

<P>Now there's a real vote winner, more tangible than asserting that "IT is good for you".</P>

<P>December 6, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
