<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>CHOTS marches on</H3>

<P>The MoD's 300 million Corporate Headquarters Office Technology System, CHOTS, has won a new lease of life.</P>

<P>In November, the project's latest versions, CSV 7 and CSV 8, which are supposed to bring the system into the Windows age, received their Equipment Committee Approval. Conformance testing of  CSV 7 was due to begin at Swindon and Blandford in December. If all goes well, users will start receiving the new system by the middle of 1997.</P>

<P>In the meantime, an army of consultants will be going around the 11,000 CHOTS users to ask them if they want the CSV 7 or CSV 8 systems. CSV 7  will allow the users to run ICL Office Power and Microsoft Office under emulation in a multi-level secure environment.  CSV 7 will support 16-bit applications, whereas CSV 8, which should begin comformance testing next year, will support 32-bit applications under Windows NT. CSV 8 users will be able to run Microsoft Office natively, but they will not  have the same flexibility in security as CSV 7 users.  CSV 8 will run in two secure modes; Restricted High or Secret High.</P>

<P>Over the next two to three years, the MoD will replace 11,000 CHOTS terminals with CSV 7 or CSV 8 systems.  The infrastructure will also have to be upgraded to support a predicted increased in data volumes.  The total cost of the CSV 7/8 programme will some 175 million, of which the new hardware and infrastructure will cost 110 million, or 10,000 per terminal with the balancing paying for project staff  (mainly consultants) , user support (1,200 per user per year) and training.</P>

<P>Linking CHOTS to other MoD systems is still proving difficult.  The Procurement Executive (PE), based at Abbey Wood in Bristol, has been told by the security boys not to connect its DAWN system to CHOTS.  This is because DAWN is in turn connected to the Navy Net system which has a gateway to the Internet. This means that some 4,500 PE workers will not be able to communicate with the rest of the MoD until the problem is solved.</P>

<P>December 5, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
