<H3>BRIEFBITES</H3>

<H3>MPs cant start me up</H3>

<P>Parliament is still holding out against the march of Microsofts Windows 95 operating system, a Parliamentary reply by Gary Waller MP, chairman of the House of Commons Information Committee suggests. On December 10, he told MPs that the House encourages the use of Windows 3.11 while the reliability of network use of Windows 95 is being assessed. 
Mr Waller was answering a barrage of questions from Ann Winterton about the Parliamentary Data and Video Network (PDVN), currently being installed.  She wanted to know how much the PDVN network is costing, and why the director of communications has refused to link up computers running Windows 95.</P>
<P>Mr Waller could not answer the first question. The cabling, he said, is being installed in conjunction with electrical rewiring, telephone cable renewal and associated asbestos removal, so there is no figure for the PDVN work.  But for fans of Windows 95, he said that changes to the PDVN are currently being tested with a view to offering this service in the new year.</P>
<P>December 15, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A 
HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A>Ltd, 1996</P>


<H3>Net offer to schools</H3>
<P>CableTel has announced fixed-rate charges
for Internet access to help schools manage their Internet
budgets and overcome the deterrent of high and unpredictable
online charges.<BR>
<I>TES</I> 13 December 1996</P> 	
<BR> 	

<H3>Hackers target Pentagon</H3>
<P>The Pentagon's computer systems were
attacked about 250,000 times last year, and in about 160,000
cases hackers succeeded in penetrating the systems, according to
the US Defence Department.<BR>
<I>FT</I> 12 December 1996</P> 	
<BR> 	


<H3>Floppy returns</H3>
<P>The IR has shelved plans to 
let self-employed people complete tax returns on floppy discs.<BR>
<I>Computer Weekly</I> 12 December 1996</P> 	
<BR> 	

<H3>Sharing the DSS</H3>
<P>The ITSA has named the 
consortia selected to move to the next stage of the Accord
project, to provide a shared systems infrastructure for the DSS.
They are: Affinity (led by EDS, partnered with IBM), Arcway
(Bull, Sema and Syntegra) and ICL (leading a consortium which
includes Andersen Consulting and CCN). (See also NEWSBITES.)<BR>
<I>IT Services Agency PR</I> 12 December 1996</P> 	
<BR> 	

<H3>CCT for the chop?</H3>
<P>A Labour government would 
abolish CCT, confirmed Geoff Hoon, shadow minister for IT, at
last week's Softworld forum for local government.<BR>
<I>Computer Weekly</I> 12 December 1996</P> 	
<BR> 	

<H3>EU tackles net content</H3>
<P>The EU Telecommunications Council 
agreed a resolution on illegal and harmful content on the
Internet, based on the self-regulatory principles of the UK's
NetWatch scheme, said DTI Minister, Ian Taylor.<BR>
<I>Hansard</I> 6 December 1996</P> 	
<BR> 	

<H3>More or Less?</H3>
<P>Arguments continue to rage about whether
the Government's "extra" cash for schools is an increase of
5.5per cent (according to the Chancellor's Red Book) or a cut of
1per cent-2per cent (according to some local authorities).<BR>
<I>TES</I> 6 December 1996</P> 	
<BR> 	


<H3>IT key to police efficiency</H3>
<P>Acpo President and Chief
Constable of Dyfed-Powys Police, Ray White, told chief police
officers that there is a need to make provision for considerable
investment in new technology to improve efficiency.<BR>
<I>Police Review </I>6 December 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>IT hit in council budget cuts</H3>
<P>Council spending on IT services
is budgeted to fall by 3per cent this year to 1,040m, a 14per
cent decline from its 1993 peak, according to Socitm's annual
survey of trends in local government.<BR>
<I>Public Finance</I> 6 December 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Red Pike; publish and be damned?</H3>
<P>The NHS Executive should publish the Red
Pike encryption algorithm, according to a report commissioned by
independent security specialists. The report says that the NHS
Executive is keeping the algorithm secret because of misguided
conservatism.<BR>
<I>HSJ</I> 5 December 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Expected errors</H3>
<P>The Government is playing down
problems with the Job Seeker's Allowance payment system,
claiming the system's reported faults are in line with
expectations.<BR>
<I>Computing</I> 5 December, 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Defence Pact</H3>
<P>Racal, Siemens Plessey and ITT are to
combine their bids for the 2bn contract to replace the Army's
battlefield radio system. The agreement is designed to give the
three companies a share in the Bowman battlefield radio system.<BR>
<I>FT</I> 4 December 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Cyber School</H3>
<P>The 1,100 pupil Linlithgow Academy has
become the first secondary school in Scotland to be fully
networked - linked to both a local area network and via a broad
band cable link to the Internet.<BR>
<I>Guardian</I> 3 December 1996</P>	
<BR>
<H3>Labour NHS U-Turn </H3>
<P>Labour will today abandon its
outright opposition to GP fundholding, announcing plans for a
