<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206></P><BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Virtual Union? Sitewatch on the EU</H3>

<P>The main European Commission site <A HREF=http://www.europa.eu.int/>Europa</A> is an interesting mirror of the union itself.  On the surface the site promises to be useful and informative, but delving beyond the first stage it turns out to be difficult to use, clumsily put together and badly inter-linked.  Putting together the main EU server was never going to be easy. It is a huge task, laying out and linking information (in nine languages) which can answer all the questions that governments, businesses and people need to know.  But if you can't do it on a web site, how is it going to work in reality?</P>

<P>I didn't expect the site to be advanced enough to order services over the net so the intention was to find out the folloiwng: who my MEP is; how to e-mail an EU commissioner; how to apply for EU loans (as a school or small business); and to find all the latest EU news and business.</P>

<P> The results on the whole are rather disappointing. Much more work needs to be done by the EU to provide a really user-friendly information resource - moreover, one which addresses the needs of actual citizens out there on the net. Don't expect governments to do it for you.</P>

<H4>News</H4>
<P>Only the last quest listed above was successful through the Europa<A HREF=http://www.europa.eu.int/en/whatsnew.html> What's New</A> section, which is a fairly useful direct news resource.</P>
<H4>Schools</H4>
<P>The <A HREF="http://www.europa.eu.int/en/record/apeei.htm"> Action Plan on Learning in the Information Society</A> (one of the 'other documents' under 'On the Record') is a worthy committee/directive to encourage the speeding up of schools' espousal of the internet.  It aims to get schools interacting and participating in 'interconnect multimedia discovery classes' and funding is available from the EU and public/private partnerships. Unsurprisingly there is no information on how to apply for funding; perhaps a few dedicated teachers with months to spare could chase up the departments mentioned (via fax, phone & letters naturally) to find out how to qualify.</P> 
<H4>Courts</H4>
<P>The Europa home page - The Unions Institutions - Who does what - illustrates the inherent problem of the site. If you access the Court of Justice here, a short synopsis of the institution is given, instead of linking to the main <A HREF="http://www.europa.eu.int/cj/index.htm"> The Court of Justice to the European Commission</A> site. Pointless.  At the CJ site, although lots of case decisions are available, they are only organised by case title and not cross referenced by subject - so unless you know what you're looking for it's useless.</P>
<H4>Maastricht</H4>
<P>OK, lets try something simple; find the Maastricht treaty using the Europa search engine. Everything listed in the search result is related to the treaty but not the thing itself.  That is because it is formally known as <A HREF="http://europa.eu.int/en/record/mt/top.html"> Treaty on European Union</A>. Nothing is straightforward here.</P>
<H4>MEPs</H4>
Who is my MEP? The simplest way to enable people to find their MEP would be to use a clickable map interface, whereby clicking down through successive geographical levels gives the answer.  But the new <A HREF="http://www.europarl.eu.int/sg/tree/en/default.htm"> European Parliament home page</A>, members list, is still under construction. I would have thought that this was the most basic information required and surely the easiest to give?</P>
<P>The result of a  general net search on MEPs (not through the Europa search engine) is two Labour MEPs! 
<A HREF="http://www.poptel.org.uk/eluned.morgan.mep/"> Eluned Morgan</A> and
<A HREF="http://www.poptel.org.uk/john.tomlinson/"> John Tomilinson.</A>  
Mr Tomlinson's site was the best overall and incidentally he was the first MEP with a web site.  Starting with the message "Fraud Information Wanted", he has incorporated a fraud reporting service on his site.  As President of the first fraud enquiry committee, he will investigate all allegations.  He also gives details of how to submit evidence anonymously via a re-mailer service.  Very handy if you didn't know how to send e-mail without revealing your identity.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://eubasics.allmansland.com/parliament.html#xtocid118357">How is the European parliament composed</A> lists MEPs grouped under their affiliations to political groups, so although this gives the fullest list of e-mail accessible MEPs, I still don't know who my MEP is.  This MEP listing isn't part of the Europa site, but is an <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/">I*M Information Market</A> an EU site generally dedicated to IT projects.  Accessing 'related WWW sites' - European Union - <A HREF="http://eubasics.allmansland.com/"> EU basics FAQs</A> there is very helpful information about the EU, composition, departments and institutions etc.  A much needed resource.</P>

<H4>Commissioners</H4>
<P>Locating the e-mail addresses of commissioners on the Europa server was impossible. The I*M's <A HREF="http://eubasics.allmansland.com/commission.html#xtocid1183530"> EU basics questions about the commission</A> (access EC on the net - then E-mail connectivity) should have been the answer.  It states that most people working at the European Commission should now be reachable though the Internet at the address
(given_name_initial.surname@mhsg.cec.be). For example (J.Santer@mhsg.cec.be) but this is purely fictional because this address system applies only to the Commission's staff (civil servants), rather than the Commissioners (politicians). Who on earth knows the names of civil servants working for Neil Kinnock? </P>

<H4>Federal Trust</H4>
<P>If the official sites can't help me perhaps the <A HREF="http://www.compulink.co.uk/~fedtrust/"> Federal Trust</A>, a pro European UK think tank may be taking the initiative of spreading the good word.  Their <A HREF="http://www.compulink.co.uk/~fedtrust/EMU.html">online report of evidence to House of Lords European Communications committee</A> has the statement "Less positive, however, is the tone of public debate in the United Kingdom where a distorted and limited view of economic and monetary union has been allowed to develop."  But their own extensive research into the benefits  of EMU is in book form (which can be ordered from their site), but surely the information should be free.  If the Federal Trust wants to see the Euro come into existence, it would be in their interests to offer more than the simplified memo that is on their site. As a sideline, all mentions on this site of monetary union is that it <I>will</I> take place in 1999, but on the official Europa site the word <I>planned</I> is used. Hmmm.</P>

<H4>Your rights</H4>
<P>The <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Regional/Regions/Europe/European_Union/">Yahoo </A>pages on the EU is a good basic listing for anyone who really needs to spend many frustrating hours searching through reports and directives.  And the <A HREF="http://citizens.eu.int/en/index.htm"> Citizen first</A>, gives information of your rights as an EU citizen. But no guides as to the benefits that being in the EU may bring.</P>  

<P>Researched and reviewed by Louise Burton</P>


<P>December 9, 1996</P>
<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

