<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Capital punishment</H3>

<P>Project Capital is heading for a spot of bother. This ambitious project to
enable resource-accounting within the MoD is due to go live in April 1998.  But
insiders at the MoD predict that it will go the same way as previous defence IT
mega-projects.</P>

<P>Capital involves a number of demanding requirements:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Integrating multiple pieces of software</LI>
<LI>Installing these programs onto many different hardware platforms</LI>
<LI>Fundamental changes in the MoD's business and accounting procedures</LI>
<LI>A change in management culture</LI>
</UL>
<P>Coopers & Lybrand has the contract to integrate and implement the software
(which in some cases consists of 75 integrated Oracle modules) onto the users'
technical architecture. It seems, however, that the MoD has not yet sorted
out the network/hardware requirements.</P>

<P>The cost of providing the hardware and communication infrastructure apparently
has to be borne by the MoD's Top Level Budget (TLB) holders and has not been
included in the project's costs. Consequently, Coopers is apparently unable to
start the integration process because many of the MoD departments do not
have the infrastructure available, or the money to provide one,  in one of
the toughest funding years for a long time.</P>

<P>With only some 20 million being allocated in the initial project for hardware,
there is a potentially serious shortfall in funding. Although the MoD
originally intended to run the Capital software on its infrastructure
architectures such as Chots, Cash and LITS, delays to these programmes,
coupled  with technical restrictions, means that many MoD sites may have to
buy additional hardware and communications.</P>

<P>December 6, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
