<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Clarke spends to save</H3>


<P>The 1996 Budget might have been bad news for alco-pops, but could be good news for 
suppliers of information systems -- especially if they offer a long-term prospect of cutting the cost of government.</P>

<P>In his speech on November 26, Chancellor Kenneth Clarke announced that he would make
available 800 million over the next three years for an initiative called "spend to save".  This money, spent "in a well-planned and measured way" would achieve savings of 6.7 billion in social-security and tax fraud, he claimed.</P>

<P>This is music to the ears of purveyors of technology to identify benefit claimants and to match files across government departments.</P>

<P>It is also an admission that pure private finance will not be enough to pay for such systems. At the launch of the green paper Government.direct, ministers maintained that savings in paperwork alone would pay for the new technology.  The chancellor's admission that some pump-priming is necessary shows that he has done some homework and knows that big 
savings arise only late in a project's life-cycle.</P>

<P>Other highlights of the Budget included (full speech available<A HREF="http://www.hm-
treasury.gov.uk/pub/html/budget96/speech.html"> here</A>) a pledge that  public spending would not exceed 40 per cent of national income in 1997.</P>
 
<P>Despite this, the Chancellor said he had found more money in three voter-sensitive areas:
<UL> 
<LI>Education gets an extra 830 million, channelled largely through local authorities.  Over the next two years, higher education will receive an extra 280m, including an extra  20m for science equipment. (However, of the extra 40m for FE next year, almost half is to be clawed back, on the grounds that colleges will benefit from pensions savings and European cash.)</LI>
<LI>Law enforcement (police and prisons) will receive an extra 450m.</LI>
<LI>Health receives an extra 1.6 billion, an increase of 2.9 per cent in real terms.  This comes on top of investment raised through the private finance initiative, which has so far been slow to take off.</LI>
</UL>

<P>December 2, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
