<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Web goes on the beat</H3>


<P>The next time you want to identify a villain or recover stolen property, will you look on the Internet?  Kable's latest survey on IT in British police forces, published on November 15, suggests that the Net will become an important crime-busting tool.</P> 
<P>It finds that every police force surveyed (more than three quarters of the total) was on the net, though three had not yet begun to use it.  One interviewee predicted:  "It will be a place where people will be able to browse recovered property, descriptions of wanted people, all the items that make television programmes like Crimewatch compulsive viewing for so
many."</P>
<P>One fifth of forces said the Net would help the investigation of crimes. </P>
<P>The survey found that Britain's police forces will spend 307 million on IT and
 communications in 1996-97, a decrease of 3 per cent on last year.</P>
<P>One reason for the drop is spending on communications hardware is on hold while forces wait for the Public Safety Radio Communications Project.  This attempts to update radio communications with more secure and flexible digital technology. The first contracts are due to
 be signed in early 1997.</P>
<P>The survey also reveals worries about the National Strategy for Police Information Systems (NSPIS).  While nearly everyone agrees that the strategy is a good idea, there are 
worries about the choice of projects and the bureaucracy surrounding them. (See <A HREF="is21.10pcplod.htm"> PC Plod</A>)</P>
<P>The report also reveals strong feelings about the project to implement IBM's Automated
Fingerprint Recognition System, which was cancelled in a widely-publicised row.  Two
lawsuits are now pending, between the consortium of forces using the system and IBM.</P>
<P>One interviewee commented: "The consortium was assured by IBM that it would have a
 fully operational system within the early years of development. It was not realised that the
 processing power was not there... It was like trying to drive a Rolls Royce with a Mini engine.
 The system didn't have the power."</P>
<P>Others, however, said the IBM system had worked well. In one murder inquiry:</P>
<P>"We found a mark in blood, but were not sure which finger it was. Within one hour of that
 mark being received, we were able to identify a youngster who had previously been cautioned.
 As well as identifying the offender, this brings a considerable saving of effort and money in a
 major investigation."</P>
<P>More worrying, the survey suggests that cultural barriers remain in the quest for more
 effective policing.  One IT manager (with experience in the private sector) commented:</P>
<P>"The force cannot cope with a cut in expenditure or...a drive to improve productivity.  It is
 not in its culture.  The problem is that police officers get no training in general management,
 so it's only luck if they've got general management skills when they get to the top.  The 
administration is appallingly inefficient, it is not managed properly."</P>

<P>Kable Market Profile: Police Information Systems 1996/97
3,650 from <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A></P>

<P>November 15, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
