<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Nothing fishy about Red Pike</H3>

<P>Red Pike, the encryption algorithm developed by the British government's
security services, contains no hidden "trapdoors" according to a an independent
study.  The government is promoting Red Pike as an alternative to
publicly-available encryption algorithms for protecting sensitive data on
networks.</P>
 
<P>Red Pike is a secret algorithm, which the government claims is suitable for
protecting data classified as "restricted". Its first test is likely to be on
the NHS-wide network.</P>

<P>The choice of Red Pike, which was developed by a department of Government
Communications HQ in Cheltenham, aroused suspicions in the computer security
community. Why is the government refusing to publish the algorithm, to allow it
to be tested by security experts? Had the spooks built in a trapdoor to allow
covert surveillance? The British Medical Association, anxious to protect
confidential medical data, demanded an independent examination. 
The NHS Executive commissioned an assessment by a specialist firm, Codes &
Ciphers Ltd. Its report condemns the government for failing to publish the
algorithm -- but says that it appears to be secure.</P>
<P>The report says that:</P>
<UL>
<P><LI>Red Pike is a "well designed algorithm" and that its key, 64 bits long, is
tough enough to resist the type of challenges most likely to be made on it.  It
would, however, be vulnerable to attacks by intelligence agencies or other
organisations with budgets of tens of millions of pounds. Whether such attacks
are a likely threat is a matter for the NHS to judge.</LI></P>

<P><LI>On the trapdoor theory:  "We have tried very hard to find such a trapdoor and
have failed. In fact, we are as confident as we can be after a three month study
involging a ream of four people, that no such trapdoor exists."</LI></P>

<P><LI>The government's refusal to publish the algorithm is "driven by misguided if
understandable conservatism".</LI></P>
</UL>
<P>In any case, the report says, if Red Pike is used by an organisation as large as
the NHS, it will inevitably come into the public domain.  This is even more
likely when other government data-sharing projects, of the kind envisaged in the
Government Direct green paper, go on line.</P>

<P>Today, debate about encryption algorithms is confined to academics, intelligence
agencies and specialist companies. In the future, it looks like becoming a hot
political and commercial topic.</P>

<P>November 8, 1996</P>
<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
