<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Government Direct: coming soon to a public service near you</H3>

<P>The British Government has relaunched its information technology services under a newbrand name in the hope that it proves a vote-winner in the election run-up.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/citu/gdirect/ind1.htm"> Government Direct</A>, a green paper published on November 6, is a vision of user-friendly government services delivered electronically to people's homes and businesses.  Roger Freeman, public services minister, spoke of "bringing government to the people rather than people to the government".</P>

<P>However, the government provided little idea of how these new systems will be paid for.  It is also likely to face a rough ride where the new strategy clashes with concerns over privacy and data protection. Last, but not least, opposition politicians will paint the initiative as a marketing exercise with little substance behind it.</P>

<P>Anticipating this last criticism, the government announced three pilot projects (all launched today) which will bring on-line government services to the people in electronic "one-stop shops".</P>
<OL>
<P><LI>Direct Access Government.  This is a one-stop information shop on the Internet, allowing citizens to call up government forms and details of regulations. It is being tested at Citizen's Advice Bureaux in Norwich, Manchester, Bolton and Carlisle.</LI></P>

<P><LI>Public touch-screen terminals to give one-stop access to  information from tax, national insurance and VAT agencies.  Six pilot terminals have been set up in England, in government offices, at Manchester airport and at a branch of Natwest Bank in Walthamstow, London. The terminals are designed to allow members of the public seamless access to information from all three agencies. They will be able to order leaflets -- and to comment on the usefulness of the system. When questioned by Signposts, however, Mr Freeman showed little knowledge of how the system would be evaluated, and how it would be paid for if rolled out nationally. "We haven't put a finite time on the pilot", he said.  He hinted national roll-out might be done in partnership with a private company through the private finance initiative, but gave no further details.</LI></P>

<P><LI>ScotLIS, a land and property information system for Scotland. This system allows access to information held as text, photographs and digital maps by both private and government agencies.  Housebuyers will be able to call up information about ownership, planning restrictions and even photographs of individual properties.  The scheme is being piloted in Glasgow.</LI></P>
</OL>

<P>Mr Freeman and his colleagues Ian Taylor, minister for science and technology, and Michael Jack, financial secretary to the Treasury,  promised a barrage of new initiatives to flesh out the policy further.  Mr Taylor said that he would announce a new programme called "IT for All" in December.</P>

<P>Much, however, depends on finding a way for private industry to foot the bill for these systems. "I confidently expect this will be the basis for many private-sector developments based on the basic information from government databases", Mr Freeman said. The idea is for private contractors to take over the delivery of information and services, to be paid aproportion of the savings achieved by cutting paperwork and reducing the number of clerical civil servants.  Will any private company take this risk?</P>

<P>Another snag, as Mr Freeman acknowledged, is that paper and electronic systems will have to run in parallel for many years to come.</P>

<P>The whole announcement revived memories of the 1982 Information Technology Year, master-minded by Kenneth Baker (who bears a striking resemblance to Mr Freeman). That initiative gave us a generation of kids weaned on BBC microcomputers.</P>

<B>Comment: weasel watch -- some line-by-line scrutiny of the green paper</B>
<P><B> Paragraph 6.22:</B> "The government expects the savings which would follow... to more than pay for the new infrastructure".  Would this not be unprecedented?  Computers cost money.  To save money, you must take something away.  Just what does government plan to take away?</P>

<P><B> Paragraph 3.3</B> "The touchscreens have provided job-seekers with a feeling of empowerment and a sense of real control...". This doesn't sound like any touchscreen we have experienced. Is it possible really to empower the unemployed and actually give them control? </P>

<P><B> Paragraph 3.4</B> talks of "a more proactive style of benefit delivery... aided by sympathetic use of data comparison...".  Fraudsters wouldn't call data-matching "sympathetic".  While effective at deterring fraud, such powerful procedures make better protection for privacy essential.  Nice adjectives won't be enough. </P>

<P><B> Paragraph 6.12</B> refers to the project to link aspects of the criminal justice system.  What the government doesn't say is that the project has existed since the 1980s and achieved frustratingly little.</P>

<P><B> Paragraph 8.15</B> is about systems that handle sensitive personal and commercial information.  "Government computer systems... have a history of very high standards" as, apparently, do banks, building societies and insurance companies.  Would anyone care to argue the toss on this one?</P> 
<P><A HREF="is6.11crit.htm">Government Direct: a personal critique</A></P>

<P><A HREF="is6.11kabres.htm">Kable's response</A></P>

<P>November 6, 1996</P>
<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
