<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Hansard on the Net</H3>


<P>With little fanfare, the British parliament has made the biggest step towards
opening up its proceedings to the public since allowing television cameras into
the House of Commons in 1989.  From the opening of Parliament this year on October 23, the Hansard official record has been freely available on the Internet at the<A HREF="http://www.parliament.uk/"> Parliament</A> site.</P>  
<P>Each day's proceedings goes up at 12.30 the following day. 
The parliamentary home page is surprisingly coy about its new feature. Browsers
have to click on "Search the Parliamentary Publications Database" before seeing
anything about Hansard.</P>  
<P>Could this bashfulness be to protect the newly privatised HM Stationery Office,
for which Hansard is an important money earner? Perish the thought.</P>
<P>The innovation does, however, put Britain among the front rank of nations with legislatures open to public scrutiny through IT.  The pioneer was Sweden, whose parliamentary text database, Rixlex, has been open to the public since 1993.  It contains motions, reports, parliamentary minutes and lists of speakers.  The country's 349 MPs are all equipped with computers
and modems, both at the office and at home. </P> 

<P>November 4, 1996</P>
<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
