<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Auditors denied access to outsourced IT systems</H3>
     
<P>Local authorities and NHS organisations are doing a poor job of 
auditing the security and management of their IT systems, according to 
a survey by Cipfa.  The report paints an alarming picture of public 
organisations' complacency over  computer disasters.</P>

<P>Cipfa, the  Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy, 
says that auditors in many types of public bodies fail to review a 
wide range of IT management procedures. The survey, of 1,500 public-sector 
organisations, showed that only half were auditing the acquisition and 
management of systems, IT strategy, assimilation of new technology, 
implementation of EU regulations and performance measurements.</P>

<P>Fewer than half of the sample had reviewed security in all their IT 
operations over the past two years.  One third had not examined the 
security of their departmental systems, and one quarter had not looked 
at their central systems. 
Only one fifth of the bodies said they had  recently reviewed 
procedures for recovering from disaster.  One third had not reviewed 
their virus controls and only just over half had reviewed the security 
of their networks.</P>

<P>The findings apply particularly to local government, which accounted 
for 57 per cent of the survey replies.  The rest of the responses came 
from the NHS (18 per cent), education bodies (13 per cent), housing 
associations (8 per cent) and central government (3 per cent). 
The survey identifies a worrying long-term trend: auditors at 29 per 
cent of organisations which "outsource" IT to contractors are denied 
unrestricted access to their systems.  Vernon Poole, head of IT audit 
at consultants Aid to Industry, and the IT audit representative on 
Cipfa's audit panel, warned: "This has grave implications for 
auditors.  It means that they need to know the terms of the agreements 
that their authorities are signing with suppliers."  Auditors should 
make sure that contracts include unrestricted access to systems, he 
said.</P>

<P>Partly as a result of the findings, Cipfa is to beef up its efforts to 
help IT audit. It will reissue its  computer audit guidelines next 
year, together with an executive briefing for managers and an ongoing series of technical briefing for auditors.  It also plans to launch a training initiative.</P>
     
<P>Douglas Hayward, journalist</P>

<P>November 1, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
