<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Sick drivers and healthy claimants (sic)</H3>

<P>Which would annoy you more: to have someone medically unfit to
drive crash into you, or see someone fitter than you are
claiming 50 a week invalidity benefit?</P>

<P>The government is keen to avoid such messy situations, which is
why both the DSS Benefits Agency and DVLA have professional
medical groups. These check people's eligibility to benefits and
drivers' licences respectively.</P>

<P>Both DSS, BA and DVLA are extensively computerised, yet there is
no exchange of medical records. This means it is too easy to
tell BA you are sick and need money at the same time as telling
DVLA you are well enough to drive. The result is too many sick
drivers, healthy claimants, and doctors paid twice over for
giving the government two different versions of the same story.</P>

<P>This should change, says Dr Margaret Harris, who has worked at
both agencies. Linking and merging the two systems would reduce
fraud, save medical fees to doctors, and improve road safety.</P>

<P>Dr Harris' idea illustrates precisely the weaknesses of
compartmentalised or 'smokestack' government, which is what the
CITU Green Paper on government computerisation, due to be
published 3pm on Wednesday 6 November, is meant to address.
There are factors of data protection and patient confidentiality
to take into account, but the main question is why hasn't anyone
taken this obvious step sooner?</P>

<P>Perhaps they will soon. Dr Harris this week received a public
award in the 1996 Adam Smith Institute/Ernst & Young Economy in
Government competition, and her idea has now won powerful allies.</P>

<P>William Heath, Kable Director</P>

<P>November 1, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
