<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<img src="is_line.gif">
<blockquote>
<H3>Wiring the health service: mission impossible? </H3>

<P>The government has set out an ambitious vision for  the National Health Service in its white paper A Service With Ambitions.  There is one snag: to achieve the goal of delivering "patient-centred" healthcare efficiently needs good IT.  At the moment, this is missing.  The NHS has become a byword for failed computer projects.</P>

<P>This is not a British phenomenon. All over the world, healthcare has
proved far more difficult to computerise than other industries.</P>

<P>The consequences are terrifying. Up to one quarter of paper medical records
are missing at any one time. A billion paper messages circulate around
the NHS, by post or courier, every year. Each costs 10 times as much as
an electronic message to send.</P>

<P>Meanwhile, patients endure millions of unnecessary laboratory tests
and X-rays a year because results from previous tests are not available.
A significant number die because pharmacists misread doctors' handwriting
on prescription forms. And, a century after the birth of &quot;scientific&quot;
medicine, doctors and managers still lack solid information on which treatments
work, and what they cost.</P>

<P>The NHS has made several attempts to get out of this mess. Most have
had little effect: projects have been too small for the size of the service
or have been mishandled. Some have failed spectacularly at a cost of many
millions of pounds, leading to political embarrassment which creates a
vicious circle of secrecy and new rules, leading to further waste. Today,
when an NHS hospital buys a computer system, the cost of the procurement
process can exceed the cost of the system itself. </P>

<H4>Paperless practice</H4>

<P>Recent efforts have fallen into three main phases.</P>

<P><B>1) GP computers.</B> The big success story of British healthcare
computing: more than 70 per cent of GPs use a computer in their consulting
room. This is possibly the highest percentage in the world.</P>

<P>Perhaps 10 per cent of GPs rely entirely on computer records. (Any such
figure is a guess because doctors who fail to keep paper records are breaking
their conditions of service with the NHS.)</P>

<P>The main reason for this success is subsidy. GP computers benefitted
from the 1982 Information Technology year. Later, two companies, AAH and
VAMP, supplied systems free by selling information gleaned from them to
drug companies. </P>

<P>When these schemes collapsed in 1990 the government stepped in with
a programme of reimbusement. Its motive was to help establish GP fundholders
as centrepiece of the 1991 NHS reforms, which created an 'internal market'
of purchasers and providers.</P>

<P>In all, the government spent 130 million on subsidies.</P>

<P>It also subsidised a clinical coding system called Read (after its inventor,
Dr James Read) which converted the language of general practice into simple
numerical codes. </P>

<P>Britain's GPs are among the most computer literate in the world. The
only drawback is that they use a large number of incompatible systems.</P>

<H4>Market forces</H4>

<P><B>2) Hospital computing.</B> In contrast to their colleagues in general
practice, only 2 per cent of Britain's hospital doctors work on computers.
This is despite attempts to computerise NHS hospitals going back to the
days of batch-processing mainframes.</P>

<P>With hindsight, these were doomed: hospital clinicians (doctors and
nurses) need information at the bedside, which implies portable wireless
terminals. Another failing was the lack of a way of converting the complex
language of medicine into computer codes.</P>

<P>As a result, the NHS and its suppliers developed hospital systems to
feed the needs of central statistics (known in the jargon Koerner returns)
rather than helping the direct process of care. Doctors and nurses had
little incentive to make such information accurate. </P>

<P>By the mid 1980s, most acute hospitals had patient-administration systems,
typically running on proprietary ICL mainframes. The NHS itself developed
and maintained much of the software, though the US company SMS made inroads
with a system running on Digital hardware.</P>

<P>The late 1980s saw a major shake-up. Margaret Thatcher's government
saw the NHS as an intractible problem -- a legacy of otherwise discredited
Socialism that was costing more each year yet was highly popular with voters.
(In fact, the UK spends under 7 per cent of its GNP on healthcare, one
of the lowest figures in the OECD and half the American percentage.) </P>

<P>The government rejected advocates of outright privatisation, but decided
instead to introduce a market-driven philosophy which it hoped would contain
costs, and erode the differences between NHS and private organisations.</P>

<P>To the prime minister's fury, a major stumbling block was the NHS's
inability to find the cost of its activities. Advisers pointed out that the only way
to rectify the position was to upgrade massively hospitals' IT. The model
was the US, where systems routinely produce comprehensive and up-to-date
itemised bills for each patient. Any hospital without such systems would
quickly go out of business.</P>

<P>In December 1988, the Department of Health launched a programme called
HISS, for hospital information support systems. The idea was to demonstrate
the advantages of comprehensive linked systems which would collect information
from the process of care, rather than as a bureaucratic afterthought.</P>

<P>Department of Health officials talked about investing 2 billion
installing HISS throughout the NHS. Not surprisingly, the first three pilot
projects, at Darlington, Greenwich and Nottingham City hospitals, attracted
huge interest from US companies.</P>

<P>Two notable exceptions were the NHS's leading hospital systems suppliers,
ICL and SMS. They both told the government that the integrated systems
specified were too complex and expensive. Indeed, by the time the first
contracts were awarded, the cost per hospital had risen from a predicted
2 million to closer to 8 million.</P>

<H4>Disasters and deaths</H4>

<P>The projects went ahead nonetheless, with several large contracts placed
between 1990 and 1992. In all, HISS spent just over 100 million.
In the meantime, however, trouble was brewing on the NHS computing scene.
It surfaced first in West Midlands region, where managers had aggressively
adopted the new private enterprise style. QA Business Services, a spin-off
company collapsed within months of being awarded the contract to maintain
the most widely used hospital system software.</P>

<P>Another West Midlands project, Healthtrack, failed spectacularly.</P>

<P>Meanwhile in Wessex, an ambitious scheme conceived in the 1980s for
a region-wide computer network collapsed after spending 40 million
with little benefits. (The scandal lead to extended criminal and civil
court proceedings, but only one person was convicted).</P>

<P>Finally, in autumn 1992 an expensive computerised despatch system for
London Ambulance Service failed, allegedly leading to several deaths. NHS
computing became synonymous with expensive disaster and political backing
largely evaporated. </P>

<H4>Strategic visions</H4>

<P><B>3) National network:</B> The end of 1992 saw one final major initiative.
The NHS Information Management Group, a Civil Service agency of the NHS
Executive, launched an ambitious Information Management and Technology
Strategy.</P>

<P>This aimed to create a computerised health service, reducing waste and
leading to electronic medical records. The strategy depends on several
key infrastructure projects. These include:</P>

<UL>
<LI>A new NHS number for every patient, replacing more than 20 previous
incompatible formats of number.</LI>

<LI>An NHS-wide computer network, carrying voice, data and broad-band messages.</LI>

<LI>A computer system called the Administrative Register to store basic
details about every patient.</LI>

<LI>A computer language of health, based on the Read Codes, a Crown-copyright
system of coding medical terminology.</LI></UL>

<P>According to the National Network strategy, 90 per cent of NHS organisations were supposed to be connected to the NHS network by 1997; all GPs surgeries were supposed to be computerised and all acute hospitals to have integrated systems by 2000. Although the strategy is still in operation, none of these targets is likely to be met.</P>

<H4>Query over project planning competence</H4>

<P>The early 1990s rush of scandals lead to new controls being placed on
IT investments of more than 1 million, which delayed big hospital
projects. From 1995 onwards, the Private Finance Initiative brought development
to a halt while systems suppliers tried to find new ways of funding projects.
So far only a handful of computer schemes have gone through the process.</P>

<P>Meanwhile, further scandals loom on the horizon. In April the
National Audit Office report on HISS found that the project had cost more
than 100 million and brought little benefit to patients. The House of Commons Public Accounts Committee condemned the projects management in a report published in December.</P>

<P>Further evidence of mismanagement surfaced over the Read Codes project.
The most sophisticated version of the codes, Version 3, fell behind schedule.
A political furore erupted when it emerged that the company with the sole
licence to distribute the codes was owned by the NHS offical running the
development effort.  In December 1996, the NHS executive replaced the official in question, but the blow to the codes credibility remained. </P>

<P>Finally, professional medical bodies, lead by the British Medical Association, condemned the
NHS-wide network as a threat to confidentiality between doctors and patients.
After a year of acrimonious dispute, the two sides referred the issue to an expert committee, which was due to report in spring 1997.  It will almost certainly recommend tough and expensive measures to prevent the aggregation of sensitive medical data.  </P>

<P>The whole future of the wired NHS is once more uncertain. While there
are centres of excellence -- work on electronic patient records at Burton
and Wirral hospitals has won wide acclaim -- there is a danger that the
successes of the past 10 years may be discredited by association with bigger
failures.</P>

<P>Michael Cross </P>

<P>December 16, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

