<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>The Virtual Nation</H3>

<P>Satellites. Pornography. Freedom of speech. International crime. By now, we're 
thoroughly used to hearing about how electronic networks are able to circumvent 
the laws of national governments. Sometimes we see this as a triumph of the 
individual over state repression (Chinese democracy activists), sometimes as a 
terrifying omen of future global lawlessness (paedophilia and terrorism).</P>

<P>But behind all these varied manifestations lurks the spectre of a new world 
order, the dim hope or fear that these are the birth-pangs of a new entity. Are 
we witnessing the arrival of the 'virtual nation' - a free state in cyberspace 
which will be able to operate independently of national governments, and 
eventually supercede them? And if so, will it be a benevolent, egalitarian 
utopia or a hydra-headed haven of piracy and terrorism?</P>

<P>Of course, there are no shortage of people on the net who believe the virtual 
nation is already here. <A HREF="http://www.libren.com/cgi-libren/tlnews.cgi">Terra Libra</A> are offering passports and citizenship of it, and the <A HREF="http://www.prairienet.org/community/religion/idf/hometown.html">Ithaca Hours</A> site 
gives chapter and verse on how to set up an independent, non-taxable currency by democratic 
consensus. But are these gestures in the direction of virtual nationhood, or 
genuine steps towards it?</P>

<P>Have we been here before? Like many new technology issues, there's more of a history to these ideas than many people assume. New nations, or at least 'temporary autonomous zones', are a 
fairly constant feature of civilisation, where the most obvious historical 
antecedent of cyberspace is the high seas. Pirate (or corsair) republics 
flourished up and down the North African coast for centuries, answerable to 
no-one but their own rough-and-ready parliaments. More idealistic pirates also 
created free-men 'utopias' , like the Libertatia colony in Madagascar. The 
United States, as a pioneer nation, was in many ways a more permanent 
manifestation of these bulwarks against monarchy and tyranny.</P> 

<P>Nor did the eventual exploration of the globe put an end to the new nation: this 
century has seen dozens of small-scale 'model countries', set up for reasons, 
practical and ideological, of almost every political hue. Pirate radio 
operations like Sealand off the Essex coast, land-rights direct action like the 
Native American occupation of the 'republic' of Alcatraz, ships in international 
waters flying flags of convenience from Liberia or Panama, 
principalities-turned-tax-havens like Andorra and Liechtenstein, 
back-to-the-land Luddite communities, religious apostates like the ill-fated 
Jonestown colony, Ayn-Rand-inspired libertarian secessionists like Oceana. (Many 
of these are cited in Hakim Bey's wild and witty anarchist tract, <A HREF="http://www.memoria.com/bey/">The Temporary 
Autonomous Zone</A>.</P>

<P>It comes down to taxation: they can get our money -
Simply to set up as a new country breaks no laws. Anyone can declare their own 
home a sovereign nation, and many have ('King' Richard Booth of Independent 
Hay-on-Wye, for example). You can mint coins and print stamps, and defray costs 
by selling these novelty items to philatelists and coin-collectors. But, sooner 
or later, the nation-state which believes it has a claim on your territory will 
come after you for taxes. At this point you either go to war, fight their claim 
legally (and expensively), or pay up and settle for being a nation in the eyes 
of stamp-collectors alone.</P>

<P>This is exactly the same dilemma which any networked 'virtual nation' faces. To 
supplant the nation-state, it must be fiscally independent. And to do this on a 
supra-national level, it must operate outside a global banking system which is 
set up to enforce the nation-state's right to tax. By this criterion, a 'model 
virtual nation' like Terra Libra is really no more than a libertarian 
entrepreneurs' club - and still has the NSA to answer to if it ever attempts to 
be anything more.</P>

<P>Of course, electronic commerce is a tool which allows people to move 
fast, and stay a step ahead of nation-state pursuers. The internet is 
undoubtedly democratising this type of activity, formerly the domain of the 
criminal and super-rich: organisations like <A HREF="http://www.britnet.co.uk/scope/">Scope International</A> offer pricey tip-sheets on dual nationality, the Perpetual Traveller ethos and zero-tax enclaves like Campione d'Italia in Switzerland. But beneath the heady libertarian rhetoric of ultimate freedom, tax-dodging in cyberspace is the same as the real world: you may be able to start a business anonymously in Panama without your lawyer even knowing who you 
are, but are you really going to transfer thousands across to someone you've 
never met with an anonymous email address in Helsinki? (Tax haven advice abounds 
on the net: try <A HREF="http://www.caxoffshore.com/">here</A>).</P>

<P>And then, there is the fact that global money traders in big banks have already withered the powers of national finance ministers - to the point where nation states are even contemplating banding together to grab back what power they can from 'virtual' markets: witness the European Unions monetary union plans.</P> 

<P>Even if total financial independence is something of a Holy Grail, the 
internet already offers many specific ways of diminishing national jurisdiction. 
Information, for example. In the UK much of what is covered by the UK Official Secrets Act 
is available through the Freedom of Information Act in the States, and much 
restricted Stateside information can be accessed from the UK.</P> 

<P>Some nations - Turkey, for example - offer military data on other countries which are 
classified in their state of origin. Satellite servers, bypassing national 
telecoms, make supra-national 'data-havens' entirely realistic (see <A HREF="http://www.forests.com/cfpvideo/"> CFP's 
resources</A>). </P>

<P>So even if the full-blown challenge to the nation-state remains more slogan than reality, the virtual nation is at least a metaphor for a genuine sea-change: the skull-and-crossbones 
is already flying with renewed vigour in cyberspace's international waters.</P>

<P>Mike Jay</P>

<P>November 22, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

</BODY>
