<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>What I'd Like the Government to Provide on the Web ...</H3>

<P>"Electronic era government" is becoming fashionable. But what does this mean for the ordinary citizen? To coin a phrase, where's the beef?</P>

<P>There's not much central government information on the Internet at present that is really useful to voters (though there are some useful services available from local councils;<A HREF="../sitewatch/fr.index.8.11.htm"> see our local governemnt sitewatch</A>).  But there could be.  What could the state provide online that it doesn't at present? Is there anything that couldn't go "on the Net", in some part?</P>

<P>This is a personal wishlist of things Id like to see provided by local or central government via the Web. I firmly believe government could do all this, and more, over the Web at low cost.</P> 

<H4>Snail mail online</H4>
<P>For starters, why isn't the post office on the Web? All the overnight-delivery systems<I> FedEx</I>, <I>UPS</I> already have package tracking systems on the Web. Why can't we simply bring up the Royal Mail Web site, type in a street address and receive the full post code in short order, like you can in the <A HREF="http://www.usps.gov/ncsc/">US</A>? Instead you have to dial 0345 111 222, go through a human operator and get patched through to a directory-enquiries-like recording that is so incomprehensible you often have to go back to the human operator to get the postcode, anyway. How VERY efficient. I asked the (human) operator at the postcode hotline why you can't get postcodes off the Web, and she said, "The what?"</P>

<P>Or if you're moving house, why  doesn't the Royal Mail offer a free moving service on the Web (for the US version, <A HREF="http://www.usps.gov/moversnet/">click here</A>). Let's beat the US Postal Service to offering stamps over the Web -- or at the very least have 24-hour over-the-phone stamp orders and stamps-by-mail, like the USPS's 1 800 STAMP-24. And the USPS site does offer some assistance with mailing: "What would you like to mail? A Letter, A Large Envelope, A Postcard, A Package, A Large Package", which the post office most certainly does not.</P>

<P>The Office of Fair Trading has a Web site. You can order free brochures on your consumer rights, how to buy shoes, et cetera, but the site has a disclaimer: "If you e-mail us, please leave your name and an address or telephone/fax number because we cannot yet answer all enquiries by e-mail." Ahem. How very wired.</P>

<H4>Rail rail...</H4>
<P>Now, strictly speaking, British Rail no longer exists and certainly is no responsibility of the government's. But the rail system in Britain is still meant, to the best of my knowledge, to represent "public transport". Its schedules are probably a matter of public record and it is surely in the public's interest to know these schedules in advance. According to AltaVista, British Rail timetables for the Cambridge-London and Cambridge-Stanstead routes are available from <A HREF="http://cygnus.csi.cam.ac.uk/CambArea/Trains/">Cambridgeshire County Council</A>.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.cse.ucsd.edu/users/bowdidge/railroad/rail-gopher.html"> The Railroad-Related Internet Resources</A> page offers links to Railroad Timetables on the Internet, but goes on to say, "British Railways timetables are not available on the Internet, but are sold on floppy disk", which you can purchase from a snail mail address in London. Hmph.</P> 

<P>Once you're actually in London, you're in better luck; there's the <A HREF="http://www-mice.cs.ucl.ac.uk/misc/uk/london/tube/TubeRoute.html"> London Tube Journey Planner,</A> an experimental system for finding the best route between two places on the Underground. But it's not a public service; a BT employee has developed it entirely in his spare time and is testing it purely for his own interest.  Westminster (and Camden, and  Islington, and Southwark, and...and...) Council, eat your heart out. </P>

<H4>Council info - conspicuous by its absence</H4>
<P>Westminster City Council, which might be expected to provide money for such an endeavour, merely offers to send "a copy of our colour brochure or our detailed business briefing sheets" if you snailmail the Councils Principal Officer at City Hall. Or you can try <A HREF="mailto:bmurray@erwestm.demon.co.uk">e-mailing him or her</A>. But god forbid they should have the brochure on the Web site for you to download (as <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/citu/gdirect/ind1.htm">CITU</A> has done with its Green Paper).</P> 

<P>And Westminster's site, as far as I can tell, offers NOTHING in the way of contacting your representative, finding out about parking, or noise violations, or access for the disabled; nothing so useful as being able to renew your library books over the Web (and I happen to know that Westminster's library system is totally computerised). Why not? What's so difficult about any of these things that we can't have them NOW?</P>

<P>Liz Bailey</P>

<P>November 22, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

