<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   
<TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META 
NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" 
ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>IT on the never-never</H3>

<P>The Private Finance Initiative takes off</P>

<P>The Lord Chancellor's Department, which runs Britain's law courts, has 
decided 
to leap from the age of the quill pen to the age of the microchip without 
buying 
a single computer.  Instead, it has signed up Electronic Data Systems, 
the 
world's largest computer services company, to deliver IT services to 
county 
courts through the Private Finance Initiative (PFI). </P>
<P>Under the seven-year contract, the computer system will not cost the 
taxpayer a 
penny until it is up and running.  If it turns out to be a turkey, EDS 
will 
carry all the risk.</P>
<P>Anyone who has bought a sofa on hire-purchase, or accepted a "free" 
mobile 
phone, will spot the snag.  Such deals always cost more in the long run 
than an 
outright purchase.  This applies particularly to public investments, 
because 
governments (even the British, with a credit rating currently worse than 

Italy's), can borrow money more cheaply than commercial firms can. 
But there are good reasons for funding government IT projects through the 
PFI, 
and it is likely to become more commonplace under any shade of 
government. </P>
<P><B>Slow start</B> Norman Lamont, John Major's first chancellor of the 
exchequer, 
launched the private finance initiative (PFI) in November 1992.  
Ministers 
intended it mainly to support big infrastructure projects such as roads, 
bridges 
and hospitals.  Such large and complex projects take a long time to plan, 
and 
nothing much happened.</P>
<P>Kenneth Clarke, the present chancellor, gave the programme a boost by 
setting up 
the <A HREF="http://www.pfp.gov.uk">Private Finance Panel</A>, which 
describes itself as a limited company supported by HM Treasury.  This had 
a budget of 2.5 million in 
1996 to promote the PFI.  More importantly, Mr Clarke decided that in 
future all 
capital projects should be tested to see if funding is available through 
the 
PFI.</P>
<P>In his budget of November 1995, Mr Clarke said that PFI contracts 
worth a 
minimum of 14 billion would be signed by April 1999. </P>
<P>With this backing, PFI contracts were signed to provide everything 
from prisons 
to tube trains to information systems.  Especially information systems.  
Government agencies have a dismal record of installing computer systems 
on time and within budget: private contractors say they can do better if 
left to get on with the job.  The contractor has an incentive to get the 
system working, rather than blindly following a changing 
and over-detailed specification created by multiple levels of 
bureaucracy. 
That's the theory.  In practice, so far, the PFI has created its own 
bureaucracy.</P>
<P><B>Encyclopaedia Bureacratica</B> In theory, the PFI is about 
flexibility. 
"Deals, not rules," is a maxim of the Private Finance Panel.  In 
practice, deals 
involve a formidable amount of paper: the contract concerning the 
rebuilding of 
Walsgrave Hospital, Coventry, runs to 17,000 pages, almost as long as the 

Encyclopaedia Britannica. </P>
<P>The documentation surrounding IT projects is not as weighty, but has 
its own 
special complications.  
<P>These include: </P>
<UL>
<LI>Payment by results.  It is difficult to find ways to bill users for 
an IT 
service without creating a disincentive to use it. </LI>
<P><LI>Technological change. Few contracts signed in 1994 would have 
considered the 
Internet, and most would have assumed that dumb terminals would disappear 
under 
the onslaught of Windows PCs.  Chances in the IT industry since then have 
turned 
both assumptions upside down.  How is it possible to write a contract to 
take 
care of such eventualities? </LI></P>
<P><LI>Residual and sale values of systems.  A related problem.  
Contracts must be 
written to take account of the value of systems if transferred to another 

company at the end of the contract.  It is very difficult to predict the 
value 
of a computer five or seven years into the future. </LI></P>
<P><LI>The process excludes the experts. The Computing Services and 
Software 
Association warned in November 1995 that smaller, innovative firms, could 
be 
squeezed out of government IT work because PFI contractors need to 
demonstrate 
extraordinary financial viability. </LI></P>
</UL>
<P>Despite these difficulties, several major IT contracts have already 
gone 
through. </P> 
<P>They include:</P>
<UL> 
<P><LI>Nirs 2:  Andersen Consulting agreed to supply a system to hold the 
national-
insurance records of 50 million people (see <A 
HREF="sp13.9nirs.html">Projects watch</A> ).  The contract 
was worth 150 million. In the event, Andersen failed to deliver on time, 
and 
paid compensation. </LI></P>
<P><LI>ClearNET. This is a national clearing house set up by AT&T to 
handle contracts 
in the NHS "internal market".  Although the procurement, in 1995 was 
delayed 
because of hold-ups in Treasury, AT&T says it made up the time and the 
system is 
ready to connect every NHS organisation by April 1997. </LI></P>
<P><LI>TAFMIS. This MoD information system, supplied by EDS, is billed 
according to a 
complex formula based on the functionality of each terminal, the 
performance of 
the system and the amount of downtime. The Excel spreadsheet used to 
calculate 
payments is lodged in escrow to prevent disputes. </LI></P>
</UL>
<P>Interestingly, the PFI has also provided an early-warning mechanism 
for projects 
that should not go ahead.  One example is the NHS Administrative 
Register, which 
is supposed to store basic information about every individual in the UK.  
Before 
putting the project out to PFI, the Department of Health paid contractors 
8 
million to develop and pilot the software.  But when companies were asked 
to 
take on the risk through the PFI, they warned that it did not look 
viable.  The 
project is now on hold while the Department of Health works out what to 
do. </P>
<P><B>Does it work?</B> So far, it is too early to judge the performance 
of PFI 
against conventionally funded IT schemes.  However, experience with 
initiatives 
such as Competing for Quality and Compulsory Competitive Tendering 
suggests that 
there is at least a one-off gain when contractors are forced to look at 
their 
costs. So far, the PFI has had one ambiguous effect: the Confederation of 

British Industry predicts that publicly-sponsored capital spending is set 
for a 
12 per cent fall in real terms between 1992-93 (when the PFI was 
launched) and 
1998-99. </P>
<P>Even before the results come in, two recent initiatives suggest that 
the pace of 
awarding PFI contracts for information systems will speed up. 
In March 1996, the <A 
HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/citu/cituhome.htm">Cabinet Office's Central 
IT Unit</A> (CITU) took over responsibility from the Private Finance 
Panel for coordinating PFI work on information technology .  This should 
reduce the log-jam of IT 
projects caught up in the system. </P>
<P>Meanwhile, on November 6, 1996, the Government Direct green paper 
called for 
suggestions for partnerships with industry to deliver new online 
services.  The 
idea is to pay for such schemes out of the money saved by cutting 
paperwork. 
Despite some reservations about the PFI, Labour would probably follow a 
similar 
route in government. In May 1995, Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, 
announced 
plans for a 'Public/private taskforce whose role would be to move 
projects 
ahead'.  He said that Labour would speed up the PFI by identifying 
priorities. 
One would be the 'information superhighway'. </P>
<P>Politicians everywhere are suckers for schemes that allow them to 
fulfill 
promises without raising taxes -- even if future generations have to pick 
up the 
bill. </P>

<P>Michael Cross</P>

<P>November 18, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable 
</A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

</BODY>
</HTML>



