<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Spooks, cyphers and clippers</H3>

<H4>A quick guide to the encryption debate</H4>

<P>Once upon a time, only spies, academics and the mildly paranoid needed to worry about cryptography. Online government changes all that: it involves huge amounts of personal information travelling around networks and privacy must be paramount.  But it is hard for a beginner to know where to go for information.  Luckily, there's a lot of good stuff on the Net.  Here is a guide.</P>
<P><B>Spooky origins</B> Computing, cryptography and the secret state have been intertwined as long as computers have existed. The first programmable digital computer, Colossus, was developed in Britain in February 1944, to help decipher German codes. Today the issue remains as live as ever as governments around the
world, including the British, are attempting to prevent codes that their
computers cannot break from becoming widely available.</P>
<P>The British government is prepared to allow strong cryptography - but only if it can tap into your coded messages. And that, a growing body of experts argue, is an unacceptable violation of the right to privacy. Unbreakable encryption must no longer be restricted.</P>
<P>Yet until recently there has been little demand for cryptography to be made widely available to the general public. Telephone networks, except in special case, operate without encoding their contents. Outside government, only banks have historically been allowed to use computer generated encryption technology, using a system, <A HREF="http://www.rsa.com/rsalabs/newfaq/q64.html"> DES</A>. developed by IBM in collaboration with the US government.</P>
<P><B>Enter the Net</B> Increasingly a demand for powerful cryptography has emerged, because of the sudden explosion of the Internet. While nobody, ironically, is concerned that anybody claiming to be the card holder can order goods by credit card over the phone, it is perceived to be too risky to e-mail your card number to a vendor. After all, there is a lack of confidentiality (who
else could read this), authentication (who really sent that), integrity (was that what was sent).</P>

<P>Existing cryptographic technology can easily solve these problems. This is how it works <A HREF="http://www.rsa.com/rsalabs/faq/">(for a full account click here)</A>.</P>
<P>Messages, fund transfers, sound files or whatever are encrypted using a
very long number - a key. Keys are measured by their length in binary
numbers (bits), so a 56-bit key is 56 binary numbers in length - a very
long number. The longer the key, the more secure the code. Unless there is
a design flaw in the system (more frequent than you might think), a
would-be codebreaker has to try every single permutation in turn.
If the number is long enough, that takes years to crack.</P>
<P><B>Public keys</B> But there was a serious problem holding back the use of cryptography across computer networks. Both sender and recipient must have the same key. So somehow these keys, known as secret keys, have to be shared. That's easy between friends, but difficult for, say, any site undertaking a high volume of on-line transactions - unless you want all customers to call in and read
out an enormous number each time they want to buy your product.</P>
<P>In 1976 a solution was developed: <A HREF="http://www.rsa.com/rsalabs/newfaq/q3.html"> public key
cryptography.</A> An algorithm generates two different, but linked, keys (again very long numbers). Yet because of the mathematical relationship between the two, one can decrypt what the other encrypts and vice versa. But you cannot use the same key twice. A user keeps one of these keys, called the private key, and then makes the other, the public key, widely available, for example by posting it on their home page (or advertising it in a newspaper). Now anybody, even if they've never communicated with the receiver before, can send the receiver an 
encrypted message. And, assuming that the receiver kept its key secret, the 
sender knows that only the receiver can read what they've sent.</P>

<P>Authentication and integrity emerge from the reverse process. A sender encrypts their message with their private key, adding a special digital signature. Again, assuming that the sender has kept their key private, a receiver, decoding their message, and the signature with their public key can be sure it comes from them. The drawback is that public-key cryptography is slow. So the public key system is only used to communicate the secret keys, which are in turn used to encode and decode the actual message.</P>
<P><B>Arms control</B> The most common public key system used in software by most leading software vendors was developed in 1977, and is called <A 
HREF="http://www.rsa.com/"> RSA,</A> after the initials of its three 
creators. There's a catch. Encryption that would take existing 
computers years to crack is seen by governments, and in particular the law 
enforcement and intelligence interests, as a threat. Imagine organised crime 
being able to transfer funds with the impunity afforded by strong 
cryptography; or a prosecution failing because the encrypted contents of a 
hard drive could not be broken into.</P>
<P>Governments controlled the use of encryption by restricting by export  controls. In both the UK and US encryption over particular strengths is effectively classed as a munition. And before the Net, there was kept closely confined to banking and government: the UK's centre of encryption expertise is the little known <A HREF="http://www.cesg.gov.uk/cesghtml/index.htm"> CESG </A>(Communications and Electronics Security Group), a division of spy-agency Government Communications HQ.</P>
<P>In April 1991, in the US, policy changed with the Clipper Chip <A HREF="http://www.eff.org/pub/Privacy/Clipper/"> proposal</A>. The US government <A HREF="http://www.cdt.org/crypto/index.html">(the best starting point for the US debate is here)</A> agreed to allow public access to encryption, hard wired to a special chip, which could be placed in phones and modems and the like. But in turn, the administration effectively insisted that it could read any encrypted messages, by means of a system called "key escrow" (renamed, once escrow gained a bad name, "key recovery").<P>
<P>In a key escrow system, somebody holds a copy of your keys, allowing the holder, in principle, to tap into communications and, if the keys are unique, to pretend to be you. In the Clipper proposal, the federal government proposed that it would hold copies of the Clipper chip keys. Clipper chips never happened - the furore, together with weaknesses in the system architecture have meant that it was never introduced. Export controls remain. The US, where most of the world's technology companies are based, prevents companies from exporting encryption keys longer than 40 bits. Some critics in the UK, such as <A HREF="http://ds.dial.pipex.com/gladman/index.html"> Brian Gladman</A>, see this as an example of US information imperialism. The export restrictions mean that stronger crypto systems can be used within the US, up to 128 bits in fact, but not abroad.</P>
<P><B>British blueprint</B> But escrow lives on - and at this point the UK
enters the picture. <A HREF="http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk:80/users/rja14/">Ross 
Anderson</A>, the most outspoken critic of escrow, offers the following history. In mid 1994, the UK government saw no need introduce any controls, and certainly no Clipper chips, on the internal use of cryptography. But Dr Anderson claims in 1995 pressure was applied by the US government to introduce a software only key escrow system. The debate became a hot topic when the Department of Health announced plans to set up an NHS-wide computer network. In April 1996, following complaints by the British Medical Association, about the threat such a network would pose to confidentiality, the NHS Executive published a study by Zergo, a security consultancy. "The use of encryption and related services with the NHSnet", sounded the alarm by suggesting in an appendix that a nationally managed public key crypto system would require key escrow. Meanwhile, within government, CESG have developed a blueprint for an encryption system for central government that supports escrow.</P>
<P>In June 1996, the Department of Trade and Industry <A 
HREF="http://dtiinfo1.dti.gov.uk/cii/encrypt/">announced</A> that government would bring forward legislation to require such a system, although it is not clear how all encompassing the legislation will be. No legislation, however, is planned this side of a general election.</P>
<P>The new, software-based, escrow model - which is also being pushed in the US (Clipper III) - was different to the Clipper chip model. For non-government users a network of trusted third parties would be created. These third parties -  perhaps banks or trade associations, but not government bodies - would hold copies of keys. These could be accessed by law enforcement agencies with a warrant obtained under existing phone-tapping legislation. This could allow easy access to highly sensitive information: the BMA is concerned that such a system could allow access, through a trusted third party, to medical records, which today are controlled by doctors.<P>

<P>In the UK the situation is currently on hold. Strong encryption cannot easily be developed internally, because the UK lacks any strong software companies. Despite pressing the US government for a relaxation of the export controls and largely opposing escrow, the US technology industry cannot ignore the administration.</P>
<P>One, illegally exported, strong encryption system exists: <A 
HREF="http://www.ifi.uio.no/pgp/"> PGP</A>  (Pretty Good Privacy). This was devised by American <A HREF="http://www.pgp.com"> Phil Zimmerman</A> in direct opposition to the clipper proposal, and was posted on the Net and downloaded around the world. <A HREF="http://www.ifi.uio.no/pgp/">PGP </A> is still readily available, but is poorly supported and not easy to use. Zimmerman remained unprosecuted and the US government dropped its case against him in January 1996.</P>
<P><B>A way ahead?</B> Escrow itself is not necessary to creating a successful encryption system, one that allows all the benefits of confidentiality and authentication. Systems can be created in which third parties - known in this sense as certification authorities - issue keys to users, and certify them. They can hold back-up copies, if a user wishes, to be sent to the user if the original keys are lost. But these back-ups are not to be passed on to other agencies. For an example, see <A HREF="www.verisign.com">Verisign.</A></P>
<P>If such a system were permitted, coupled with the free availability of strong cryptography, it would be the first time in the era of computing that individuals and businesses would be able to communicate information that the state cannot immediately intercept and understand. A final privatisation - that of cryptography - is the prospect.</P>

<P>Daniel Sabbagh Reporter, Business & Technology</P>

<P>November 15, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

