<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3> Government Direct: a personal critique</H3>

<P>Fancy an ID card, a DSS stripe card, plus an Information Society Initiative smartcard with 27
difference government logos along the bottom?</P>

<P>Thats what might happen unless departments stop battling over turf and government accepts
that IT makes a fundamental strucutural rethink essential.
Of course, the government cant say that in its new green paper on IT, because Government
Direct is produced just a few months before a difficult general election, and a mutinous civil
service is the last thing it needs.</P>
<P>Given this pressure, we have to question whether Government Direct is about reality or mere
public relations.
Let us be charitable: these are important issues.</P>
<P>Over the years, government has spawned many initiatives to tell everyone else how to use IT.
Now Government Direct shows that politicians see votes in making government use IT
properly itself.
It is not, however,  a blueprint of the future government machine that people and business
want.  Nor, beyond its commitment to involving private sector resources under the Private
Finance Initiative, is it a strategy of how to get there or to address the complex management
issues involved.</P>
<P>The purpose of a Green Paper is to ensure that public opinion is seen to be taken into
account. Government Direct  raises  good questions, and we hope the Central IT Unit gets
plenty of lively feedback, especially from those best able to articulate the views of taxpayers,
consumers and concerned libertarians.</P>
<P>Government Direct talks of issues that appeal to people and businesses generally:  better and
faster government services,  lower cost of ,government, more accountability and openness
less fraud.
This is good news, whichever party you vote for.</P>
<P>But some will be made to feel a little queasy.  Those might include  fraudsters, people with
higher than average concern about privacy and personal liberty, and many public servants
who expected a job for life and are comfortable with the status quo.</P>
<P>The Cabinet Office's message that some form of electronic authentication will be essential for
people to take advantage of access to digital services is irrefutable. This is a central issue.
Of course what matters is not what government says at this stage, but what it does.  It says it
wants deregulation, yet it passes more laws.</P>
<P>It says it wants to tax less, yet general expenditure increases every year. It says it want to
encourage young people in their technology endeavours yet it bans gatherings at which their
technological music -- envy of theworld -- is played.</P>
<P>Britain is a tolerable place to live. One might argue that part of the reason is because
government is as ineffective as it is.
There is a serious risk that IT could change all that, making government more ruthless and
mechanical than people would be comfortable with. IT is a productivity aid. The risk is that
government uses it to do more unnecessary things: to create more regulations faster, to
complicate further the tax and benefits systems, to invade privacy and to undermine liberty.
When more becomes possible, minorities will clamour for more to be done. Politicians will
have to be extremely determined act in the interests of the silent majority.</P>

<P>Government is too complex and expensive. So, too, are most bigcomputer projects. Adding
more computers to the existing government machine will not solve anything without the
determination to simplify government as well as automate it. Re-engineering government is a
management issue, not an IT one -- throwing computers at the problem wll not help.</P>

<P>There are many good questions in the Green Paper. What is needed now are some good
answers, sent to CITU,  please, by February 1997.</P>

<P>William Heath, Kable</P>

<P>November 6, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

