<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Labour's puts information policy at the centre of its vision of government</H3>

<P>"The duty of an Opposition is very simple...to oppose everything, and propose nothing," said
the 15th Earl of Derby (see <A HREF="nb25.10comp.htm">Quotes competition</A>). Labour's Derek Foster set out to prove him wrong, with a vision of what IT would do for government, speaking in London on 28 October at a smart card conference organised by the Civil Service College and Demos.</P>

<P>Mr Foster opened his remarks with the Biblical quotation "Where there is no vision, the people perish."<P>

<OL><P>The vision he outlined was in five parts:</P>

<P><LI>To engage citizens in the process of government, "Labour will put the citizen in the driving
seat, renewing their confidence in the governing process ... IT services will enable
government to consult citizens on a wide range of issues." Use of new technology could
revolutionise Citizen's Charter complaints procedures, and people could get information about
entitlements through teletext.</LI></P>

<P><LI>To make government more accountable, giving citizens greater access to government
information with the brisk introduction of a Freedom of Information Act.</LI></P>

<P><LI>To make government more accessible, simpler, user focused and user friendly.</LI></P>

<P><LI>Rapid regulation, ie faster regulatory processes for small businesses. "The average small
engineering firm in Blackpool has not one, but 36 returns to regulators each year. It's not
surprising that separate reports published today by the CBI and the Bankof England claim that
small firms are being stifled by regulation and lack of funds. Labour is determined to cut
through the swathe of bureaucracy to allow businessmen to concentrate on business not
regulation."</LI></P>

<P><LI>Mr Foster promised to make government more efficient. "If government is going to use IT to communicate with the people, it must first master the art of communicating with itself. A
coordinated computer system, linking various departments, will be a powerful tool for
transfoming the way Whitehall operates both internally and externally."</LI></P>

</OL>

<P>He accused the Conservatives of being "locked in the mindset of downsizing government.By
contracting out government in order to reduce public expenditure and cut tax, they were
contracting out the management of change. He roundly criticised the quality of government
services and fraud levels.</P>

<P>"The Green Paper may address some of these issues, yet the Tories have no strategy for IT,"
he said.</P>

<P>In New Labour speak, he identified three stakeholders: first, the citizen as taxpayer, and next the citizen as user of public and civil services. To these he added those who worked in the
public services. Their morale was crucial, he said; sullen staff would resist change.</P>

<H4>Comment:</H4>
<P>We see here a carefully crafted New Labour policy stance on government IT. However, it is
hard to see any startlingly clear "blue water" between these ideas and the drift of current Tory
thinking - except for the Freedom of Information Act proposal. (One of the proposals in the
green paper which is also included in Labour's plans, for a coordinated computer system
across Whitehall, was leaked last month in the Financial Times.)</P>

<P>The timing of Foster's delivery must owe more than a little to a desire to pre-empt many of the ideas likely to be included in the government's green paper, due to be published on November
6.</P>

<P>However, it is significant that Mr Foster puts taxpayers first, recipients of services second and staff third. In due course perhaps he may add IT suppliers as a legitimate fourth stakeholder in the computerisation of government.</P>

<P>His worries about contracting out the management of change will strike a chord with some
commentators. What is unclear is that Labour has cracked the thorny IT management problem
of just what to centralise and just what to devolve. Anything done centrally will require not just vision, but competent management and strong political will. In this area Labour, however
much it deserves its chance, is inevitably unproven. But at least it seems to be thinking along
the right lines.</P>

<P>See also<A HREF="nb1.11plan.htm"> "Government direct" Green paper predictions</A>) and <A HREF="is25.10party.htm">Party games; IT issues for the general election</A>.</P>

<P>William Heath, Kable</P>

<P>November, 1 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

