<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="is_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206> </P><BLOCKQUOTE><H3>Public sector IS market worth over 5 billion annually </H3><P>It is remarkably difficult to find official information on how much money the British public sector spends on its information systems and technology. But research by Kable can fill the gap. In 1995/96, the total identified public-sector IS spend was  5.1 billion, according to Kable research and estimates (see table below). </P><P>This excludes public sector IS spending by other emergency services (excluding police), doctors, dentists, some executive agencies and quangos, TECs, LECs, courts and the security services - and excludes IT spending which has not gone through central IT budgets. Note that IS expenditure by FM/outsourced contractors on behalf of government is also excluded.</P><P>The single biggest spending area (outside central government as a whole) is local government, coming in at an estimated 1.1 billion. </P><P>The second biggest IT spender is education (schools and higher education combined), where total estimated external and staff IT expenditure in 1995/96 was 780 million. This is followed by the Ministry of Defence, with a total of 750 million. In 1995/96, it budgeted to spend nearly 160 million on personal computers alone.</P><P>Fourth was the NHS, at an estimated 600 million, including an estimate for staff. </P><P>Next was the Department of Social Security, at 370 million, followed by the Police, at 385 million. In 1996/97 police external IT expenditure is set to drop by 3% (see Kable's POLICE IS MARKET PROFILE, 1996/97). </P><P>Other big central government spenders include the Inland Revenue (247 million) and the Employment Department (136 million).</P><P>Recent reports by Kable break the figures down much further. The table below gives some of the highlights.</P><H4>UK Government IT Expenditure, Budget 1995/96</H4><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1 WIDTH="75%" ><TR><TD><CENTER><P><B> million</B></P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P><B>External spend b </B></P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P><B>Staff</B></P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P><B>Total c</B></P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Central/civil government a</TD><TD><CENTER><P>1283</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>278</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>1561</P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Local Government</TD><TD><CENTER><P>690</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>380 </P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>1070</P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Defence</TD><TD><CENTER><P>617</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>133</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>750</P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Public healthcare</TD><TD><CENTER><P>498</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>100 </P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>598</P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Police</TD><TD><CENTER><P>316</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>69 </P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>385</P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Schools</TD><TD><CENTER><P>...</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>...</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>400 </P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Higher Education</TD><TD><CENTER><P>...</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>...</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>380</P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>TOTAL c</TD><TD><CENTER><P>...</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>...</P></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P>5144</P></CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>a. NHS Executive/DoH expenditure is included in central government. MoD spending is excluded, and is covered in the Defence sub-head.<BR>b. External spend covers hardware, software, external services (facilities management, consultancy, hardware maintenance etc), telecoms and supplies.<BR> c. Excludes public sector IS spending by other emergency services (excluding police), doctors, dentists, some executive agencies and quangos, TECs, LECs, courts and the secu