<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><img src="pu_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE><H3>Inland Revenue Self Assessment</H3>

<P><B>Purpose:</B> The Inland Revenue's introduction of self-assessment, CESA (Computerised Environment for Self-Assessment) is the biggest reform in the administration of income tax in more than 40 years. </P>

<P><B>Contractor:</B> EDS, the world's largest computer services firm, has a 200m contract to develop the software and to operate systems. This is part of a landmark contract awarded in 1994, under which EDS took over all the Inland Revenue's information processing. The Chancellor, Kenneth Clarke, set April 1997 as an immovable deadline for self-assessment.</P>

<P><B>Progress:</B> The first release consists of management accounting information, the second release will deal with the actual forms and will be released by April 1997 and the third release, dealing with compliance, should be ready by March 1998.</P>

<P>Press reports say the project ran into problems early in 1996 when EDS realised that the first release would not be ready to come into use by the deadline of November 4. There were several reasons, including the fact that the user-interface software was two months late in arriving and full of bugs.</P>

<P>The contractor tackled the problem with older software. </P>

<P> In the event, the self-assessment system went live as planned on November 4. David Courtley, managing director of EDS's Public Sector Strategic Business Unit told, analysts on November 15 that the whole project is "running on schedule". The project will be fully onstream in early April 1997, when 8.5 million new tax forms are due to go out during a sensitive election period.</P>

<P> Meanwhile, on October 24, the newspaper <I>Computer Weekly</I> reported that it had received documents showing that the Inland Revenue had made an important policy switch. The documents propose that staff working overseas for the system's database supplier, Oracle, should have access to material in the system. </P>

<P> On 14 November the newspaper published a letter by Michael Jack, a Treasury minister, in which he denied misleading Parliament over the issue. "There are no secrets, and no risks to security of taxpayers' data," he wrote.</P>

<P> <B>EDS's</B> relationship with the <B>Inland Revenue</B> continues to have a high political profile. On November 14, in response to a parliamentary question, the Treasury revealed that it had paid the company 356.7 million for computer services since 1994 and 59.4 million for assets transferred when the contract started in July 1994.  The total value of the EDS contract with the Revenue is now put at 1.6 bn over the 10 year conract period, according to recent parliamentary questions put by the Labour MP, Mr John Hutton. This represents an increase of 60% above the original figure announced in 1994.  The Revenue said that the rise reflected several factors including inflation and extra work awarded -- such as the provision of statistical services.  There has been speculation that some of the increase is due to unforseen problems associated with CESA (see above).</P>

<P>November 22, 1996</P>

<pre></pre>&copy; <a href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 1996
</blockquote>
</BODY>
