<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   
<TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META 
NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) 
[Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" 
VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><img src="pu_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>NHS Administrative Register</H3>

<P><B>Purpose:</B> to compile a national database of information about 
people eligible for treatment by the <A 
HREF="../issues/is30.9health.html">NationalHealth Service</A>. The 
Administrative Register will contain names, addresses, NHS numbers and 
details of doctors and hospitals with which the individual is registered. 
It will contain no clinical information. The main purpose is to ensure 
that NHS computers know they are dealing with the right patient when they 
exchange information connected with running the NHS internal market. It 
will also open up the possibility of creating on-line electronic medical 
records.</P>

<P><B>Contractor:</B> The Department of Health says it plans to pick a 
supplier for a private finance initiative contract from the following 
short-listed bidders: AT&T with Easams, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu with 
IBM, SEMA,and Siemens-Nixdorf Information Systems. It originally wanted 
to place a contract before the end of December, for the register to be 
running by April 1997.</P>

<P><B>Progress:</B> Dubious. It is not clear how the successful supplier 
will be able to charge NHS hospitals and other organisations for the 
information. One of the Administrative Register's main functions, to 
verify the new NHS number, will be carried out by an interim tracing 
service due to be launched in January. The British Medical Association 
and other professional medical bodies are also worried about the threat 
of the register and other connected systems may pose to confidentiality 
between doctors and patients. The Administrative Register procurement is 
already running behind schedule and may be further delayed, or dropped 
entirely.</P>

<P>On October 24, the <I>Health Service Journal</I> reported that the NHS 
Executive was on the verge of shelving the project while a credible 
business case could be constructed. Officially, the Administrative 
Register is being "re-phased". But few expect it to emerge from the 
process intact.</P>

<P>Following the report, Ken Jarrold, the NHS director of human and 
corporate
resources, wrote to suppliers saying that "timing of the implementation 
will be
resolved shortly".</P>

<P>At least one of the four on the short-list, Siemens Nixdorf 
Information Systems,
has dropped out.</P>

<P>November 8, 1996</P>

<pre></pre>&copy; <a href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 1996
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
