<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><img src="pu_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Post Office benefits</H3>
<P><B>Purpose: </B>To install an automated benefits system for the twenty-first century. Swipe  cards will replace passbooks in an attempt to reduce benefit fraud, producing an annual saving of 150,000,000.</P>

<P>Unlike today's passbooks, the card will be checked for fraud, forgery and theft every time it is used. Another advantage of swipe cards is that they will contain less readable information than passbooks do. (Passbooks assist thieves in several ways by having information about the age of the claimant, the post office where benefit can be claimed and when the next payment can be collected. They are worth up to 7,000 on the blackmarket.) The new cards will have no details except the claimant's name, national insurance number, the card number, expiry date, a helpline number, a magnetic stripe and a Braille dot. </P>

<P><B>Contractor:</B> Pathway, a consortium led by ICL with De La Rue, Girobank and the Irish Post Office. The same consortium developed a system for 600 personal computers in Irish post offices and installed the Lottery computers. </P>

<P><B>Progress:</B> The private finance initiative contract calls for the system to begin being implemented by 1998 with the actual implementation taking two to three years. This may seem a long time -- but consider the fact that the system will need to handle 19 million people's accounts and keep track of transactions worth around 19 billion a year.</P>
<P>September 30, 1996</P><pre></pre>&copy; <a href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 1996</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
