<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   
<TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" 
CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY 
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sd_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 
WIDTH=212></P><BLOCKQUOTE><P>The Signposts Directory</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Initiatives on the internet</H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/ccta/mill/mbhome.htm">
CCTA Milennium Bomb</A> 
"The problem is a technical one. The solution is potentially one of the
biggest logistical and management headaches you may have ever
encountered..." That date change nightmare in full.</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ispo.cec.be/infosoc/promo/seminar/eeci.html">
European Electronic Commerce Initiatives</A> 
Set up after a European sponsored workshop in early 96.  With contact
details for E cash demos to an EDI based trading system for European
businesses.</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www2.cordis.lu/esprit/src/invencom.htm">
Electronic Commerce: Inventory of Initiatives</A> 
Inventory of initiatives started at the Euro meeting (see above) - more
contact details</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.isi.gov.uk/">
Information Society Initiatives</A> 
DTI's service to encourage business to take advantage of new media</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ghbg.org.uk/isi/isi_main.htm">
Global Highways Business group</A> 
UK Information Society Initiative:
Created from DTI site pages but useful as it focuses on data protection,
information security and fraud.</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/citu/gdirect/ind1.htm">
Government Direct</A>  The site of the green paper published on November 
6, 1996, detailing the government's vision of user-friendly government 
services delivered electronically to people's homes and businesses.</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.wolfenet.com/~success"> Terra Libra</A> (Free 
Earth) "Are you tired of government oppression?  Are you being 
impoverished by confiscatory taxes?  Do you yearn to be free?  Would you 
like to enjoy the fruits of your labor?  You can now become a Citizen of 
the world's first truly FREE country". This is real innovation on the 
net. You can even apply for your Terra Libra passport - unfortunately not 
free.</LI>
</UL>
<P>Should your site be included here? <A HREF="mailto:kable@kable.co.uk">Mail</A> your details and we'll review it for the next update.</P> 

<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable 
</A>Ltd, 1996</P>
