<TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" 
CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY 
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sd_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 
WIDTH=212></P><BLOCKQUOTE><P>The Signposts Directory</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Media</H3>

<P>A round up of the main media sites on the net.  The result is very
varied.  Some offer so little you wonder why they bothered, others are
experiments to see if they can make money here.  One of the problems 
facing the big publishers is how to charge for access to 10 years of 
digital archive material?  How do you stop one subscriber uploading it 
all for everyone else to get free?
 Interesting gossip about the Electronic Telegraph is that they have one 
of the best 'tracking' devices attached to their site.  When you've accessed them they know who you are and where you go next (and next and next....) The Fourth Estate tries the Big Brother act.</P>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/">
Journal of Information, Law & Technology</A>
An e-journal bursting with information relevant to anyone working or
publishing on the net.</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.bbc.co.uk/">
BBC</A> Radio Times online with trashy graphics.</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.emap.com/media/">
Emap publications </A> All their computer & IT magazines - LAN, PC User 
etc.</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.emap.co.uk/">
Emap's media magazines </A>  Broadcast, Av Magazine, Press Gazette</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/wired/">
Wired </A>- Funky techno magazine</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/wiredsource">Wired Source</A> - a new service from Wired Magazine - aiming to become the most powerful and succinct information resource on the net. Very US focused. Has  categories on US government and politics, giving online searchable access to the Congressional Record (US equivalent of Hansard) etc.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ft.com/">
Financial Times</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.standard.co.uk/">
London Evening Standard</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.guardian.co.uk/">
Guardian/Observer</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.nytimes.com/">
New York Times</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.wsj.com/">
Wall Street Journal</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.lastampa.it/">
La Stampa </A>- Leading Italian paper</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.welt.de/">
Die Welt </A>- Leading German newspaper</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.the-times.co.uk/">
The Times & Sunday Times </A> Register to access - with links to other 
News International sites</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.iib.com/">
Internet Intelligence Bulletin </A> Subscription news service for the 
public sector</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/">
Electronic Telegraph </A> Have to register to use - then they spy on 
you.</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.economist.com/index.html">The Economist</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.computerweekly.co.uk/emo.html">
Computer Weekly</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.vnu.co.uk/">
Mag.net </A> IT business coverage from VNU newspapers & magazines.</LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.forteantimes.com/">
The Fortean Times </A> Journal of Strange Phenomena.  Great transfer from 
print to the online version with an article archive and fabulous hot 
links. </LI>

</UL>

<P>Should your site be included here? <A HREF="mailto:kable@kable.co.uk">Mail</A> your details and we'll review it for the next update.</P> 

