<DOCHDR>
http://www.kable.co.uk:80/sitewatch/fr.index.22.11.htm 194.112.40.47 19970105184105 text/html 10563
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 05 Jan 1997 18:40:23 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.5
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 10391
Last-modified: Tue, 26 Nov 1996 19:22:48 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   
<TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" 
CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY 
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 
WIDTH=206></P><BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Semi-autonomous or semi-accountable? - Executive agencies on the 
net</H3>

<P>Government semi-autonomous executive agencies (sometimes lumped in 
with non-governmental "quangos") employ two thirds of all civil servants 
and deliver almost all central government services. As they raise their 
profile on the Internet, Sitewatch goes in search to see what services 
and information they offer via the net. A pattern emerges early on - if 
the agency's function is to take your money, the site is often packed 
with information and very useful; if however you're a claimant these 
sites will give you no guidance.</P>
<H4>Benefit</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk//benefits/ba.htm">The Benefits 
Agency</A> administers the benefit payments to 20 million claimants
has 69,000 staff and handles 80 billion of taxpayers' money annually -- 
but this site is not designed for employees or claimants.  There is no 
information on entitlement and although it gives a full list of the 
benefits 
that it handles, none of these are hot-linked.  It would be very easy for 
each 
type of benefit to have details for claimants; and calling the 'media 
enquires' 
telephone number, there are no immediate plans to provide this data.
The <A HREF="http://www.ferret.co.uk/">Ferret Information 
Systems</A> site, with the world's first web benefits calculator is where 
to 
go to find out if you qualify for support. The National Audit Office's 
report 
on <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/nao/appr3.htm"> Benefits Agency 
Appropriation Accounts 1994-95</A> actually gives away much more 
information on the aims of the agency.</P>
<H4>Contributions</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/dssca/cahome.htm">The 
Contributions Agency</A> site is information rich-- very helpful if 
you're 
an employer, employee or self employed.  It seems if it's your money 
they're after the site bends over backwards to help (you can't actually 
order 
hard copies of forms etc over the net -- but I'm splitting hairs). This 
is a very 
useful resource with a link to the Inland Revenue site, facilitating the 
full 
exploration of any enquiry.</P>

<H4>Child Support</H4>
<P>The high profile <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/csa/cshome.htm">Child 

Support Agency</A> is probably the most contravorsial agency.  
This is a very well laid out hypertext site with practically everything 
you 
would need to know.  It makes very interesting reading as most of the act 

which gives the agency its powers is here.  <I> The tiny carrot and the 
big 
stick</I> - When the 'absent parent' is contacted, a deferred payment 
period 
is offered (eight weeks) if the forms are returned promptly. If the forms 
are delayed they 
assess your ability to pay, with a kindly reminder that it will probably 
be 
higher. All the information is here, except how to appeal if the 
assessment is wrong.  It is also quite clear that the people they are 
most 
concerned with are the ex's of those who claim income support.</P>

<H4>Tax</H4>
<P>As government divides and devolves its responsibilities it is offen 
hard to remember which departments have changed and into what. The 
structure is complex, people are unsure where accountability lies, as the 
Prison Service debacle demonstrated. The <A 
HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/inrev/irhome.htm">Inland Revenue</A>
is one of the few sites that recognises that most people don't care how 
departments are structured as long as they provide the services required; 
they are working on linking the Contributions Agency and HM Customs & 
Excise to the IR site.  There is lots of useful stuff here -- under 'self 
assessment' all the final forms for the new tax returns can be viewed. 
Adobe Acrobat Reader has to be downloaded but the software is free and 
available here.  There is a useful listing of IR booklets and leaflets, 
some of which are available on the 
net and they deserve a big pat on the back for that.  There is also 
interesting 
news on the EDS partnership and the transfer of staff from the IR to EDS 

-- technology certainly pushes change.</P>
<H4>Defence</H4>
<P>The corporate blurb says that <A HREF="http://www.dra.hmg.gb/">The 
Defence Evaluation and Research Agency</A> "is a leading research and 
technology organisation with a turnover of  $1.5 bn and 14,000 staff".  
Is this some large private armament company's home page? Under 'mission' 

the story begins to unfold: "with 90% of turnover coming from the MoD". 
Under 'framework' the term 'next steps agency' leaps out and the fact 
that DERA is <I>owned</I> by the secretary of state for defence but has 
to operate in a commercial manner.  This is the old Defence 
Research Agency merged with the Chemical and Biological Defence 
establishment (and others). Euphemism alert - for all the latest on 
biological and chemical defence, press the  'Protection of Life Sciences' 
button. 
The "next step" for this agency is partial privatisation, but do we 
really need to worry about a defence organisation (with chemical weapons) 
that lists under its links page the Oxford Diocesan Guild of Church Bell 
Ringers?</P>
<H4>Employment & Education</H4>
<P>The <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/dfee/dfeehome.htm">Department for 

Education and Employment</A> site, one would think should help people in 
search of work or 
training.  Accessing 'life-long learning' then 'motivating individuals' 
offers the 
worst sort of management-speak, completely useless blurb on the meaning 
of the word and how hard it is to motivate people. Lots of laudable aims 

under 'national targets for education and training', but it is all aimed 
at 
employers and nothing for the people who are supposed to be the 
beneficiaries of all this research and funding.</P>
<H4>Roads</H4>
<P>The <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/hiagency/highhome.htm">Highways 
Agency</A> site contains a consultation document on 'regional traffic 
control 
centres' focusing on a future that is 'strategic network management' -- 
when 
we'll all have in-car-systems directing us away from traffic jams.  This 
is all 
very well for the future but what about now? They could be offering 
information on all the planned road works across the country, so that I 
could plan my journey and miss the congestion now and not wait until 
2025. And now the cones hot-line is no more, one would have thought this 

would be the place to complain, but sadly not. maybe we'll have to wait 
until the key parts of this agency are privatised or outsourced.</P>
<H4>Car Licences</H4>
<P>The <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/dvla/dvla.htm">DVLA</A> web site 
offers 
very little apart from the basic information on duty rates and how to buy 
"attractive" 
licence plates. The site also states "With few exceptions all VEHICLE 
LICENCES will be renewed only at the post office" but there is no 
information on what those exceptions might be. One incredibly useful 
service they could offer would be a listing of all stolen vehicle 
registration 
plates and chassis numbers but they don't even have a contact e-mail 
address for comments or suggestions. And anyway, why can't we send DVLA 
forms in via the net?</P>
<H4>Environment</H4>
<P>The<A HREF="http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk"> Environmental 
Agency</A>, which has taken over from the National Rivers Authority, 
HM Inspectorate of Pollution and parts of the Department of Environment, 

is very nicely laid out site -- lots of bullet points and PR fluff.  This 
can be 
a little disconcerting when under the list of their responsibilities 
comes 
"Responsible for the disposal of radioactive waste at 8,000 sites".  I 
hope 
they do it as neatly and tidily as they've done this site.  They do get a 
massive bonus point 
for allowing members of the public to e-mail them of any environmental 
incident under 'feedback'.</P>
<H4>Join a Quango</H4>
<P>If you think you could do any better or want to join the gravy train 
then 
this is the site for you <A 
HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/co/paulft2.htm">Cabinet Office Public 
Appointments Unit</A>. Top tips on how to put yourself forward for a 
position on one of the many committees, boards or agencies -- and also 
the only site to use the word Quango.</P>

<P>Researched and reviewed by Louise Burton</P>

<P>November 22, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A 
HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

