</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206></P><BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Local Government: The Good, The Bad and the Ugly</H3>

<P>As more and more local councils go online, Sitewatch has focused its 
spotlight on the service and usefulness of these sites.  The criteria for 
assessment was based on whether the site offered anything genuinely useful 
that either couldn't be done in any other way or added a valuable asset to 
the community that it serves.   Most of the sites visited were quite poor, 
many hardly understanding the purpose of having a site at all.  Most 
surprising was how few gave information on council business or 
encouragement to the local people to become involved.</P>

<H4>First the good news:</H4>

<P><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/oxcis/">Oxfordshire County Council Internet 
Service.</A><BR>
A great site that publishes council documents and reports 
and strategies as well as giving the information on when the council sits and 
discusses certain topics.  One would think this is standard and although I 
haven't looked at every site, this is the first that gives this vital information.  
This is a document centre and other parts of the county i.e. 
<A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/oxcis/html/529/CEA4.1">Oxford City Council</A> list 
all the local services.</P> 

<P><A HREF="http://dspace.dial.pipex.com/town/parade/ni30/index.htm">The Flintshire 
County Council</A> is new so at present serves the Disability Action Centre 
and is offering free web space to disabled groups in Wales. Although a new 
site there are already several very useful sites supporting people with a 
range of disabilities and illnesses.  Flintshire social services deserve high 
praise indeed for offering a unique service to their community.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.netlink.co.uk/users/moray/mcouncil.htm">Moray - Malt 
Whiskey Country, Scotland</A>.  Not all the Scottish sites are this good but raise your glasses to Moray council. With useful local information, links to twinned towns around the world and they are working on putting up the council minutes.  If some can do it why not all?</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/cheshire/">Cheshire County Council</A> has lots of useful 
information, including how to trace your family tree and how long you can 
keep a CD ROM from the library. But again it's telephone numbers only - maybe I'm asking for too much - but this should be about getting local people more involved with government not just a listings service.</P>

<H4>Now the bad news:</H4>

<P>This is quite harsh on <A HREF="http://www.artec.org.uk/council/index.htm">Islington Council</A> as it is well laid out, but again no actual services are accessible via the net.  They do have useful clickable maps for locating libraries etc and thorough information 
about all their services.  Islington do have a home library delivery service 
which would be excellent if a book could be ordered by e-mail - but this is 
not offered.  Services for disabled people (Islington provides a laudable 
range) should offer ample opportunity for experimentation (i.e. renewing 
library books, requesting help etc), but all that is given is more listings.  The 
welfare benefits section is excellent, with details of entitlement with 
hypertext categories by an applicant's needs and personal details.  But the 
seemingly endless listings do hit snags. If you click the  "Business" icon, then 
access anything under "Personal services" an advert for a local business 
directory is displayed - coming out in book form.</P>

<P>Lots of the sites are like the <A HREF="http://www.gn.apc.org/hf/intro.html">
Hammersmith & Fulham Web Site</A> - which is little more than a glorified 
phone list.  Departments and services are listed with a contact number only, 
none are contactable directly via the net and the only e mail address is for 
feedback.  Someone should sell these people a server or show them how to use it 
properly.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.manchester.gov.uk/">Manchester City Council's Web Pages</A>, 
doesn't fare much better although it is possible to order an e-mail copy of 
the city guide.  How novel, actually using the medium as it was devised.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.kent.gov.uk/kcc/kcchome.html">Kent County Council</A> - Horribly 
familiar by now.  The education sections are often the most interesting 
parts of these local government sites - where schools have put up their own 
site.  Although not very adventurous, it's heartening to see that pupils and 
staff, often working after school, are experimenting.  There are pleas for other 
schools to interact with them and if this can be encouraged these sites could 
really take off.

<H4>And the downright ugly</H4>

Many of the worst sites are like <A HREF="http://www.northumberland.gov.uk/">Northumberland Council's</A> (and there were loads) - their site lists tourist information only.  Not only does it have nothing for the local community but the background screen is so horrid, one wonders what sort of tourists they wish to attract. A complete waste of money.  

<H4>And finally the fantastic</H4>

<P>Check out <A HREF="http://www.gold.net/users/fu30/localtxt.htm"> UK Local 
Government Web Site</A>  A full list of all the UK governments that are online, compiled by Keith Edkins and his family.  Worth checking out your own local site and then 
badgering the hell out of them until they provide you with information that 
you can really use.  Jo Edkins list of web sites for primary schools is also a 
remarkable piece of research, with listings from maths sites, geography, 
history through to religion.  Perhaps Northumberland council could hire this 
enterprising family?<P>

<P>Researched and reviewed by Louise Burton</P>


<P>November 8, 1996</P>
<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

