<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206></P><BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Singapore: "Disneyland with the death penalty"</H3>

<P>As the only country in the world with an evangelical mission to get wired, Singapore deserves a Sitewatch to itself. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.gov.sg/">The Singapore Government's Internet Web Site.</A>
The jumping off station to sites for organs of state, statutory boards, government online services and of course government ministries.  A glance at this menu gives a hint at how the country is run.  They even have a Ministry of Community Development - there for the  "strengthening of families, a cohesive, compassionate and robust society".  Unfortunately, the Singapore Family Values sub-site was still under construction.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.ncb.gov.sg/"> National Computer Board</A> 
Is the place to go to piece together the governments' intentions. IT2000 - A vision of an intelligent island, "where the use of information technology is pervasive in every aspect of its society - at work, home and play" - lays out Singapore's plan to become a "global hub".  Check out "Improving Quality of Life" there is a shuddering quality that accompanies the anodyne tone - when they say pervasive they ain't kidding.</P>

<P> Which leads us deftly on to <A HREF="http://www.spinet.gov.sg/">The Singapore Police</A>; the URL contains the word "spinet" - you're letting it out of the bag here boys.  The universal police links is an extensive round-up and useful for comparing the services offered by the countries featured.  The Singapore site doesn't supply any hard crime facts of figures but there are some real gems.  Under FAQs - gang involvement - discover the penalties for associating with gang members - a fine of up to $3,000 and/or 3 years. As they tell you  "Gangs are illegal in Singapore!" (their ! not mine).  If you get into a fight - this comes under rioting  with up to five years imprisonment - that's without any weapon being used and no injuries.  Don't even stay away from home if you're under 16.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.mha.gov.sg/cnb/">Central Narcotics Bureau</A>
The main graphic is of a young, handsome cop holding a gun with the fabulous strap line "Dare to Strike". All drug offences are seizable offences, with mandatory minimums, maximums and the death penalty for trafficking over a certain amount.  Anyone caught in possession of a certain amount of a drug is presumed to be trafficking - and the quantity is not large - and if caught then all your assets can be seized. There is also a Supervision Division who make regular and surprise urine tests on any offender. The laws against drug abuse are designed to hurt.</P>

<P>If they get you you'll end up under the jurisdiction of <A HREF="http://www.mha.gov.sg/sps"> The Singapore Prisons Service</A>.  
This really is rehabilitation from compulsory punitive measures through to religious counselling (also compulsory) they <I>will</I> adjust your "behavioural" problem.  The helpful list of prisoner types includes corrective trainees, preventative trainees(?) and prisoners detained under the President's pleasure.  Also gives penal history and a drugs history (these guys are obsessed) read about operation 'Ferret' when 6,647 addicts were committed for treatment.</P>

<P>The<A HREF="http://www.gov.sg/mincom/mincompr/"> Ministry of Communications</A> site is typical of the central government sites. PR fluff pieces and (yet another) mission statement with very little actual information. But you can read every speech Mr Mah Bow Tan has made recently.</P>

<P> <A HREF="http://www.gov.sg/parliament/">Parliament House of the Republic of Singapore</A>, doesn't fare much better. There is useful information on current topics but the archive is less than it should be from a country with such an internet mission.  The virtual tour seems to have disappeared too - which is a great shame.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.sg/infomap/cmsoc/muis/gateway.html">The Islamic Gateway to Singapore</A> was easily the best site.  The Hyper Qu'ran project is phenomenal - in Arabic, English (every Muslim state's language is represented here) - with audio commentary, explanations and beautiful Arabic script.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.asianconnect.com:8080/nlline">The National Library Online</A> does offer a good service.  As a library user you can renew your books even have them delivered to your home.  The reference service, where staff will help you locate information would be great but they do have censorship in Singapore so lots of books aren't available.  They hold none of William Gibson's works (the originator of the term cyberspace as well as the Disneyland quote) - and he could be considered subversive only if you're a total control freak.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.sgh.gov.sg/">Singapore General Hospital</A> Everyone has a damn mission statement in this town - a hospital - what else where they thinking of doing?  Although well laid out this is another poor site, no hard information is given.  Compare this with public-sector sites in the UK which are designed for professionals but the public aren't excluded and one begins to feel that the Singaporean people are being conned.  Too much gloss and no substance.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.gov.sg/agc/agcciss/lawnet/">LawNet Singapore</A>
The last port of call to check the constitution of the Republic of Singapore.  There is a freedom of speech, assembly and association clause but with so many codicils that it makes a mockery of the idea. The Intelligent Island? I believe it, but intelligence has many meanings these days.</P>

<P>Researched and reviewed by Louise Burton</P>

<P>October 25, 1996</P><P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
