<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206></P><BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>The fourth estate under review</H3>

<P>Hold the front page. Newspapers and magazines are still the best places to start 
for all kinds of information about what government is up to.  But publishers are 
still in two minds about the Net.  Some, especially the dailies, will post their 
entire content free (in exchange for some information for their marketing 
departments).  Other journals are loathe to put much more than a subscription 
form on the Net, lest they lose a paying reader. Others try the middle road, 
with a taste of the contents.</P>

<H3>Here are this week's hot scoops...</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://magnet.vnu.co.uk/">mag.net</A>

<P>Culled from the pages of VNU's myriad publications, more than you ever probably 
wanted to know about the IT industry.  Just because the information's been 
posted on the Web, doesn't make it any more accurate than in print. But it's all there and easily accessible.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.FT.com">Financial Times</A>

<P>All the stuff you'd expect, plus good daily updated technology news. Useful archival search database.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.telegraph.co.uk">Electronic Telegraph</A></P>

<P>Honest about why it wants your personal information. Even so, this is one of the best free, daily updated news sources on the web, with plenty of hypertext links around the stories.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.janes.com">Janes</A>

<P>Eeeyow! Dackadackadacka! Boom! Not quite. Photo of the week is an 
electromagnetic launch system under development in the Netherlands. So much 
quieter than those messy old rockets and shells.  The site also answers a 
question that has puzzled generations of warship-spotters: "Who is this Jane 
character, anyway?"</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.hsj.macmillan.com">The Health Service Journal</A></P>

<P>Crisply presented digest of inside information on the NHS, treading the delicate 
path of extracting just enough from each article.  Let down by tedious 
registration procedure. Tip: if you don't have a job title, just enter none!.</P>


<H3>And this week's boozy old hacks</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.compulink.co.uk/~private-eye/">Private Eye</A></P>

<P>Surely shome mistake?  Where's the Street of Shame and Footnotes? Loved the 
Netballs, though, especially the classic: "I don't think censorship should be 
banned".</P> 

<P><A HREF="http://www.computerweekly.co.uk">Computer Weekly</A></P> 

<P>Now this one should be banned from the net. At least until they get rid of those 
awful staff portraits. Does anyone really want to know what Tony Collins looks 
like? Otherwise solid stuff from the IT world's favourite  comic.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.healthworks.co.uk/hw/biz/bjhc.html">British Journal of Healthcare 
Computing</A></P>

<P>Thought this was the place to look for hot news about the NHS's tortuous 
computing strategy? Think again: it lists only the contents of each issue. To get 
more, you need to subscribe. No fools, these people. 

<P><A HREF="http://www.emap.com/lgc/chronicle/aboutlgc.htm">Local Government Chronicle</A></P>

<P>Same problem: the venerable Chronicle's site isn't much more than a publisher's 
brochure.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.newscientist.com/">Planet Science</A></P>

<P>Pioneering and award-winning site of the exciting weekly New Scientist. Still an 
unbeatable read. But isn't it time they updated the tedious and kilobyte-
consuming Saturn logo, which takes several minutes to load?
</P>  
<P>October 21, 1996</P>
<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P></BODY></HTML>
