<P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206></P>

<H3>UK political party sites on the Web</H3>

<P>As the British political party conference season reaches its climax,
all the contenders are polishing up their Web sites to reach the audience
beyond seaside conference halls. The results are mixed.</P>

<P>In ascending order of cringe-worthiness we present:</P>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.libdems.org.uk/">Liberal Democrats:</A> Those crinkly
eyes -- it has to be Capt Ashdown, gazing into the middle distance (or
middle ground?). But the best of the major parties' sites: these people
take the Net seriously. Pity it's not reciprocal. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.unite.net/customers/alliance/">Alliance Party of
Northern Ireland:</A> Another doomed cause? The voice of decency hasn't
been updated since 28 August. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.snp.org.uk/">Scottish Nationalists:</A> No question
about who is the enemy: the British Labour Party. Lots to read, lots of
links. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.wales.com/political-party/plaid-cymru/englishindex.html">Plaid
Cymru:</A> Plaid Cymru ar y We. Don't panic; the pages are a model of bilingualism.
Apart from the paper on devolution, which is available only Yn Saesneg.
All predictably earnest stuff. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.irlnet.com/sinnfein/index.html">Sinn Fein:</A>
Not many jokes here, either. But at least you can read An Phloblacht without
having to hand money to nervous young men in North London pubs.</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.uup.org/">Ulster Unionists:</A> More red, white
and blue than a Coleraine kerbstone. AND VERY LARGE TYPE. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.Referendum.org.uk/">The Referendum Party:</A> Britain's
(or Mexico's?) Man of Destiny, Sir James Goldsmith, pitches his tent without
gimmicks. The real fun should begin with the party conference on 19 October
when we're promised a full list of candidates. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.junius.co.uk/">Revolutionary Communist Party:</A>
Hot-links to Get the Met off the Net campaign. Right on.</LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.poptel.org.uk/Labour-Party/">Labour:</A> New Labour,
new slogans. Every ten minutes. Check out the virtual conference, complete
with a Member's Area (if you have your membership number to hand). Hot
links to exhibitors, with the League Against Cruel Sports adjacent to Lloyd's
of London. Bring back the smoke-filled room. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.conservative-party.org.uk">Conservative Party:</A>
More eyes, this time demonic. Excellent graphics -- but a little feeble
to give over so much space to attacking a party which has been out of power
for 17 years. However the Prime Minister has a message to the online community,
including the extraordinary phrase: &quot;It was not the State that created
the Internet.&quot; Actually, John, it was. But we know what you're getting
at.</LI>
</UL>

<P>October 4, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A>
Ltd, 1996</P>

