<P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206></P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Sitewatch selection by Kable of some of the best and worst public-sector
Websites.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="top5.gif" ALT="Top 5" HEIGHT=53 WIDTH=66></P>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.nhm.ac.uk">Natural History Museum:</A> Well stuffed
and well presented and bang up to date with news of our Martian chums </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/">HM Treasury:</A> Sterling
design and a solid critical mass of information (though where are the ministers'
email addresses) </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk">CCTA</A>: Solid stuff. The most comprehensive
guide to public-sector sites - but even more useful as a searchable database
of government press releases.. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.army.mod.uk">The Army:</A> Join the professionals.
We almost did: completing the quiz takes you straight into a recruiting
form. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/co/cohome.htm">Cabinet Office</A> (office
of public service): About as exciting as an HMSO toilet roll, but does
have email adresses for two ministers: Roger Freeman and David Willetts</LI>
</UL>

<P><BR>
<IMG SRC="bottom5.gif" ALT="Bottom 5" HEIGHT=36 WIDTH=101> </P>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.xtreme.co.uk/intro.html">Xtreme.co.uk:</A> Illegible
public health warning about the dangers of snowboarding: a triumph of design
over content </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.winchester.gov.uk/">Winchester City Council:</A>
Adds little to the phone book </LI>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/oxcis/">Oxford City Council:</A> Oh
dear!</LI>

<LI>GCHQ: So well concealed, we couldn't find it. (Don't be fooled by the
<A HREF="http://www.gchq.co.uk">Global Cybercafe Headquarters</A>!)</LI>
</UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>September 30, 1996</P>

