<TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META 
NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) 
[Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" 
VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 
WIDTH=212> 
</P><BLOCKQUOTE><H4>BRIEFBITES ARCHIVE</H4>

<H4>November</H4>
<H3>Web doctor</H3>
<P>Some patients are visiting their
doctor with lengthy print outs on their diagnosis, gleaned from
the Internet. But consultants say that patients can misinterpret
information intended for doctors and some people may tap into
biased sources of information.<BR>
<I>Guardian</I> 19 November 1996</P>
<BR>
<H3>Defenceless?</H3>

<P>Technology experts are warning
that the country's entire defence infrastructure will fail at
the end of the century unless immediate action is taken to
rectify a serious flaw inherent in many of the MoD's computer
and satellite communication systems.<BR>
<I>Sunday Business</I> 17 November 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Wired schools</H3>

<P>Figures released by the CCA reveal
that over 1,000 schools have now been connected by their local
cable company.<BR>
<I>Inside Cable</I> November 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Outsource - or else</H3>
<P>Ministers have decided to press ahead with draconian changes to the 
white-collar tendering regime that will force councils to expose more 
services to competition.<BR>
<I>Public Finance</I> 15 November 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Happy Hampshire</H3>
<P>Hampshire collected a BT/Sunday Times Superhighway Award for its Web 
site, one of the largest information sites in the UK with 250,000 pages.<BR>
<I>Bournemouth Evening Echo</I> 15 November 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Court out</H3>
<P>IT equipment serving six courts, including Huddersfield and Dewsbury, 
is working near capacity and the overload is reported to be causing
delays.<BR>
<I>Huddersfield Daily Examiner</I> 14 November 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Benefit Cards</H3>

<P>Social Security Secretary, Peter Lilley, has launched a 120m PFI 
project to introduce plastic payment cards for the 19m benefit claimants, 
replacing order books and Giros by the end of the century.<BR>
<I>LGC</I> November, 15 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Lits grinds to a halt</H3>

<P>IBM last week halted work on the cost management software part of the 
RAF's controversial Lits project. IBM blames the pace of change in the 
RAF for the project's demise.<BR>
<I>Computer Weekly</I> November, 14 1996</P>
<BR>
<H3>Crown not-so-copyright</H3>
<P>The Government is simplifying Crown copyright licensing to make it 
easier for electronic publishers to include official material in 
databases.<BR>
<I>Computing</I> November, 14 1996<P>
<BR>

<H3>Court online</H3>

<P>The House of Lords will this week become the first British court to 
publish its  judgements on the Internet. It will be published on <A 
HREF="http://www.parliament.uk"> Parliament's</A> home page.<BR>
<I>Guardian</I> November, 11 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Can't pay, more tax</H3>

<P>The Government grudgingly admitted this week that nearly 300,000 of 
Britain's poorest taxpayers may have paid too much tax because it failed 
to remedy computer errors at the Employment Service.<BR>
<I>Guardian</I> November, 9 1996 </P>
<BR>

<H3>Cyber-skivving</H3>

<P>Are you supposed to be reading this? A new survey purports to show 
that employees are abusing Internet access. "Internet abuse in the workplace 
is rampant," says the report. The survey found that people believed time 
spent accessing the Internet is "not productive" and that "personal browsing 
was a major time waster".</P>

<P>Don't panic. The report was commissioned by UW Software, which 
promotes a Java program that monitors which sites employees are browsing.  Not that 
Signposts readers should be worried anyway.<BR>
November 8, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> 
Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>

<H3>US Hackers target UK police telephones</H3>
<P><I>Phrack</I>, a US magazine for telephone hackers, explains how 
two telephone numbers belonging to Lothian and Borders police can be 
used to make free calls.<BR>
<I>Daily Telegraph</I> November, 1 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>PFI concessions spread</H3>
<P>New rules designed to kick-start
the PFI in local authorities north of the border have been
announced by the Scottish Office. The concessions are along the
lines of those announced in England and Wales last month.<BR>
<I>Public Finance</I> November, 1 1996</P>
<BR>

<H4>October</H4>

<H3>IR savings</H3>
<P>The provision of computer services to
the IR by EDS is estimated to have saved the department
220m-225m, close to the amount predicted, said Treasury
Minister, Michael Jack.<BR>
<I>Hansard</I> October,29 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Crown copyright</H3>
<P>From 1 November a new generic licence
is available to cover reproduction of electronic and microform
formats of Crown copyright quasi-legal material, said Chancellor
of the Duchy of Lancaster, Roger Freeman.<BR>
<I>Hansard</I> October, 29 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Multi-million Whitehall network</H3>

<P>A government Green Paper, due
out next month from Citu, will propose spending hundreds of
millions of pounds to link departments like social security, the
DVLA and health to reduce spending and cut fraud.<BR>
<I>Computer Weekly</I> October, 24 1996 	</P>
<BR>

<H3>Queen's quick review</H3>

<P>The Queen's speech included:  -
measures to widen the role of nurses, dentists and pharmacists
and to allow GPs to hold surgeries in supermarkets;  - new
powers for schools to deal with disruptive pupils and to select
pupils; - the spread of grant-maintained schools;  - a crackdown
on benefit fraud through measures including computer
cross-checking of claims;  - the creation of a National Crime
Squad and a Criminal Records Agency. <A HREF="nb25.10queen.htm">(See 
Queen's speech)</A><BR>
<I>Daily Telegraph</I> October, 24 1996</P> 	
<BR>

<H3>Racal starts contract negotiations</H3>

<P>The MoD has started contract negotiations with Racal Radar Defence 
Systems,
as prime contractor for the radar and mission system upgrade of
Sea King AEW2 helicopters.<BR>
<I>Defence News Analysis Bulletin</I> October,21 1996 </P>
<BR>

<H3>Bangemann's back-off</H3>

<P>The European Commission has resisted the temptation to embroil itself 
in a fruitless attempt to regulate the Internet.  
Martin Bangemann, commissioner responsible for industrial affairs, said 
on October 16 that measures to "clean up" the Net should be based on 
existing national definitions of illegal material, enforced as far as possible 
through self-regulation. "What is criminal off-line will also be criminal 
on-line," he said. 
This appears to cover child pornography and - more problematically -
instructions for building nuclear weapons. The EC will present its 
proposals to member states for consideration at the end of November. <BR>
October 21, 1996 Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Land Ho</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/landreg/home.htm"> HM Land 
Registry</A> is the latest government agency to post a site on the Web. 
It's the latest step in a process that has been going on since the registry's formation in 1862,  in an 
attempt to simplify the business of proving who owns which piece of land. 
The land register has been open to the public since 1990: it contains 
some 16 million titles. This is not comprehensive because registration is not 
compulsory until land is sold.  It's also still on paper.  The agency claims that 
the register will be "fully computerised" by 1998.<BR>
October 21, 1996 Signposts to Government &copy;<A 
HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Red card</H3>

<P>The Data Protection Registrar has repeated her concerns about 
government plans for national identity cards.</P>

<P>The registrar, Elizabeth France, said that two factors had constrained 
her comments: first, the government has not revealed the purpose of the 
scheme, and had outlined it only in broad detail.  So her comments could relate only 
to general issues of data protection and privacy.</P>

<P>She describes as "disappointing" the fact that the government sees no 
need for new laws to control a central database for identity cards. Signposts has already
identified the lack of such a database as a weak point in the scheme (see 
Kable article<A HREF="sp13.9card.html"> Identitly cards: do the numbers 
add up?</A>).  "It is disappointing that the government has not accepted that an identity card database must 
be developed from scratch and could not be based on the existing driving 
licence system."</P>

<P>Ms France also calls attention to practical difficulties with the 
card, such as the issues that would arise when the holder of a combined driving licence 
and identity document was disqualified from driving.</P>

<P>The full text of the response is available on the <A 
HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/dpr/dprhome.htm">
registrar's home page</A>:</P>
October 18, 1996 Signposts to Government &copy;<A 
HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Clinton's link</H3>

<P>The information superhighway is back on the US political agenda.  
President Bill Clinton has anounced plans to provide free access to the Internet to 
every school in the US.  He also launched a scheme called Next Generation 
Internet to link 100 institutions with broad-band optical fibres, at a cost of 500 
million dollars.  The Financial Times reported on October 11 that it was not 
clear who would pay.<BR>
October 18, 1996 Signposts to Government &copy;<A 
HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>CRIS scores</H3>

<P>The Metropolitan Police's crime analysis computer CRIS has claimed its 
first arrest. The Daily Telegraph reported that officers used the Crime Report
Information System to build up a picture of a wave of car crimes 
committed in southwest London.  With this information, officers set up a decoy car and 
made an arrest in two hours.<BR>
October 18, 1996 Signposts to Government &copy;<A 
HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
<BR>

<H3>Legal IT goes private</H3>

<P>Private contractors will supply IT to key components of Britain's 
legal system under two new contracts:</P>
<P><B>County courts:</B> EDS has won a contract from the Lord 
Chancellor's Department to provide systems for 250 county courts in 
England and Wales. <BR>The contract, arranged through the private finance 
initiative, is worth between 20 million and 25 million. According to 
the newspaper <I>Computer Weekly</I>, EDS's bid was half the value of the 
other short-listed bids, from SEMA and Siemens Business Services. </P> 
<P><B>Prosecution:</B> The Crown Prosecution Service has awarded a 
contract worth 1.5 million to AT&amp;T to update accounting systems and 
to run them for four years from April 1997. The unsuccessful bidders were 
Chessington Computer Services and CFM Northern Ireland. <BR>Under the 
contract, AT&amp;T will supply a financial accounting program called 
Renaissance CS, from Ross Systems UK.<BR>
October 3, 1996 Signposts to Government &copy; <A 
HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A>Ltd, 1996</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
