<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Signposts to Government</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="sw_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206></P><BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>The National Health Service online</H3>

<H4>The mother of all NHS sites</H4>

<P>The web site of NAHAT,<A HREF="http://www.nahat.net"> the National Association of Health
Authorities and Trusts,</A> is undoubtedly the best starting point for an
exploration of health service sites. Its 'Gateway' pages carry an exhaustive
catalogue of national and international links, from healthcare journals,
public health sites and medical schools to alternative medicine and 'foot
health' links. The site has other uses, too, including news, and a live
online debating board for NHS hot topics, which was set up in association
with HealthCare Today. The latter is currently under-used,
but has potential - post something provocative!</P>

<P>The NAHAT gateway links to all the health authorities and NHS trusts which
have their own web sites - currently numbering only about 30 sites, but more than 400 organisations. The following is a lightning tour of the best
and worst among these pioneers.</P>


<H4>Healthy specimens</H4>

<P>Among <B>health authorities</B>,
<A HREF="http://dspace.dial.pipex.com/town/parade/al22/index.htm"> Bradford</A>has a fairly good
standard site, with some interesting health-related links. 
<A HREF="http://www.dorset.swest.nhs.uk/"> Dorset </A>has managed an attractive spinning logo
and an innovative clickable map. 
<A HREF="http://www.iwha.swest.nhs.uk/"> The Isle of Wight</A> has a conveniently downloadable public health report. And the <A HREF="http://www.lewisham.gov.uk/lslha/lslintro.html">Lambeth, Southwark and Lewisham</A> site has an exemplary hyper-text directory of local GPs by postcode.</P>

<P>As for <B>trusts</B>, <A HREF="http://www.pavilion.co.uk/HealthServices/BrightonHealthCare/">Brighton Health Care</A>
 was the first on-line in 1995, and carries a range of departmental information; a news
magazine; and reports of every board meeting. <A HREF="http://www.ihi.aber.ac.uk/bgh/trustjj.htm">Ceredigion and Mid Wales</A>
 has organised its site into an inventive structure, which guides people round according to what type of user they are, e.g. GP,  patient. <A HREF="http://kryton.cr.man.ac.uk/index.html">The Christie Hospital</A> has an extensive site befitting such
a large cancer care centre, with useful information about cancer support
services and worldwide links. And who could resist its 3-D picture gallery
(don your 3-D specs), with such groovy highlights as a Nuclear Pore
complexed from Xenopus Oocyte Nuclear Envelope X 300,000 (approx.)?</P> 

<P><A HREF="http://dspace.dial.pipex.com/town/plaza/ff62/">Dewsbury Health Care</A> has some
interesting insights into its hospital radio channel - although no sound
files here yet. <A HREF="http://www.innotts.co.uk/nadt/orgs/healthshop.html">Nottingham Community Health</A> has some lively 'Health Shop'
pages, disseminating safe sex and drug use/abuse information to young people. <A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/pinderfields/">Pinderfields
Hospital </A>and the <A HREF="http://www.rbh.nthames.nhs.uk/Royal Brompton
</A> sites are both highly-developed.</P>


<H4>Suitable cases for treatment</H4>

<P>Then there are the not so good efforts. Many sites have got no further than a home page - too many to mention. But surely the worst is the link to <A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/~healthdv/nlhct_m.htm">North Lakeland Healthcare's</A> so-called site  - no more than an image, really. <A HREF="http://www.ich.ucl.ac.uk/">Great Ormond Street's</A>  pages are disappointing, too - not the worst, but one expects better than a collection
of dry text-based pages from an organisation so much in the media and public
eye. And <A HREF="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/IT_KAHNT/">Kircaldy's </A> site is not so hot either- it doesn't seem to have been updated since February 1996.</P>


<H4>The governments effort</H4>

<P>The <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/doh/dhhome.htm">Department of Health's </A>home page is pretty good for a government department - OK, that's not saying all that
much - with a range of key publications available in various formats, and
the NHS league tables downloadable in Adobe Acrobat. Its events diary is
useful, too, with key dates for the health diary. But here again, NAHAT's
gateway page is your best starting point for an exploration of other
government health-related sites, UK and international.</P>


<H4>Centre of Excellence</H4>

<P>Another site worth visiting is the <A HREF="http://www.healthcentre.org.uk/findex.htm">Health Centre</A>. The centre, in its own words, is "intended to act as a guide to the huge amount of medical and health information that is available on the world wide web. Our links are mainly to UK sites, but where no UK alternative exists, some international sites are included". The Health Centre is maintained by Dr David Rayne, a North Yorkshire GP. It is a well-organised and clearly laid-out site, and a useful springboard to further health-related exploration for patients and professionals alike.</P>

<P>Dan Jellinek, Editor of Healthcare Today and of the <A HREF="http://www.iib.com">Internet
Intelligence Bulletin</A>.</P>

<P>December 9, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

