<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><H3> National strategy or PC Plod?</H3></P>

<P>It  was not until the end of 1994 that the 51 police forces in England, 
Scotland and Wales thought it necessary to start work on a common 
approach to information systems.</P>

<P>When the Home Office launched the National Strategy for Police Information 
Systems (NSPIS), it was welcomed by users and suppliers, who applauded 
the aim of cutting out wasteful duplication of IT efforts.</P>

<P>Making the strategy work, however, is an uphill struggle.</P>

<P>The strategy picked five key applications, to be developed by selected 
lead forces, together with work on an NSPIS technical architecture. This 
is being developed centrally, under the Police IT Organisation (Pito), 
itself set up earlier this year.</P>

<P>The NSPIS architecture is based on an open, distributed client/server 
approach, using modular or reusable components, common interfaces  and 
interoperable, portable products.</P>

<OL><P>The key NSPIS systems are:</P>

<LI>Custody, which records basic information about anyone in custody. It  is being 
developed jointly by 
Avon & Somerset and Greater Manchester Police.</LI>

<LI>Case preparation, being 
developed by Greater Manchester Police.</LI>

<LI>Command & control, being developed by 
the Metropolitan Police.</LI>

<LI>Management information, being developed by Hertfordshire and 
the Metropolitan Police.</LI>

<LI>Crime & incident reporting, being developed by 
West Yorkshire.</LI>

<LI>Vehicle procedures/fixed penalty office, being 
developed by Leicestershire. </LI>

</OL>

<P>There are also plans for a legal database 
system and the Holmes 2 system for major investigations, for neither of 
which a lead force has yet been appointed.</P>

<P>Two years down the line, concern is growing about the length of time it 
is taking to roll out even these initial NSPIS projects, while in the 
meantime, spending on local IT projects has all but stopped as forces 
defer decisions until NSPIS standards are confirmed.</P>

<P>Spending on IT has not dried up completely.  Last year, the police spent 
more than UKL 100 million on IT and many forces are continuing to invest in 
computer systems. But it would clearly be foolish to embark on any 
major investment at this time, a fact that those on both sides of the 
market are finding frustrating. </P>

<P>So what is holding up the NSPIS? There does not seem to be a lack of 
political willpower.  The home secretary, Michael Howard, has underlined the 
need to co-ordinate IT activities across the UK's police forces, and the 
formation of Pito has helped focus development and administrative work.</P>

<P>But there have been technical problems from the start with the scale and 
scope of NSPIS. </P>

<P>Initially, the Home Office identified 38 software 
applications it felt police forces might want, which had to be whittled 
down to a more manageable five initial projects.</P>

<P>Then there are technical problems in scoping the individual applications. 
A command and control system for a rural force differs greatly from that 
needed by the Met and it proved more difficult than originally expected  
for the lead development forces to define core systems.</P>

<P>While forces wait for NSPIS, they are having to make difficult decisions 
about what to implement in the meantime. Chief Inspector Stephen 
Bowley, head of communications and technical services for 
Nottinghamshire Police, says one of the major difficulties is keeping 
staff aware of developments.</P>

<P>Others point out that while top level strategies are necessary, so are 
cost-effective and practical solutions to help the everyday work of 
police forces around the country.</P>

<P> See previous article: National<A HREF="sp13.9cops.html"> Police IS stratergy </A> will it happen?</P>

<P>Jane Dudman, journalist</P>

<P>October 21, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

