<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Kable's preliminary response to the green paper Government Direct</H3>

<P>The main issues the government needs to address which are not explicitly covered in the
Green paper are:</P>
<UL>
<LI>How to ensure that adding new IT does not merely add cost to already complex and
expensive government procedures</LI>
<LI>How to reshape govermment to an optimal structure to address peoples needs, using IT
where appropriate. This requires a decision of just what that structure should be, and winning
the support of the senior civil service for undertaking the fundamental changes that will be
necessary.

<P>Given that, consulting people about computerising government is a good idea.
The Green Paper is obviously the result of hard work by the Central IT Unit.  It raises
important issues about people and businesses in Britain and their future relationship with the
tate. One effect of the dawning information age is that those entrusted with running national
government must expect to do so in a different environment. To a limited extent it is one they
create, but largely it is thrust upon them.  People will be better informed about alternatives --
even able in some cases to choose under what jurisdiction they conduct their business.
If they want to pay far less tax or to enjoy services of the highest quality and efficiency, they
will make this more obvious in future.</P>

<P>In an information age, it will be possible to have government that is more clearly
accountable and far more open. People will be more aware of this, and better able to
command the information necessary to express themselves effectively on given issues.
In response to the specific questions raised:<P>

<P><B>Paragraph 4.5</B> People and businesses want convenient access to services. The
very existence of different levels and types of government body, indeed of many non-
government bodies, is an irrelevance to most of us.  There is no reason why much of
government should be any more evident to us than, for example, the banks automated
clearing system BACS. To achieve unified service delivery would be a huge achievement, but
one for which, perhaps unfairly, people won't give any credit. It's simply how things ought
always to have been done. Adopting a customer-focused approach is anyway a matter of
culture, not of technology.<B> Paragraph 5.8</B> The principles look right. Government needs to
instil confidence beyond the stage that people's concerns have yet reached. The implications
of what government is now discussing will take time to sink in.  We believe government must
lead public opinion towards demanding a high standard of privacy across all systems. A start
might be routinely to encrypt any personal data on systems that are outsourced.</P>

<P>Accessibility is key, and the flexible approach suggested seems sensible, but much
manual processing will have to be abolished if there are to be savings. Under the
rationalisation heading let us simplify not merely systems, but government.<B> Paragraph
6.12</B> Come on, you know the implications of service rationalisation. Loss of jobs for many
people who have spent entire careers on a premise of job security.  Loss of status for people
who have patiently worked towards the top of the pile. Anyone inside government who dares
to suggest the sort of service rationalisation that is now possible can expect to be stabbed in
the back repeatedly.</P>

<P>On the plus side, rationalisation will improve delivery, cut costs, reduce fraud and improve
accountability. Apart from complaining, the only information people are prepared willingly to
tell government more than once is the minimum needed to gain access to the data and
services to which people are entitled. They can do this quickly and easily with their
independently issued and branded intelligent token.</P>

<P><B>Paragraph 6.12</B> The implications of sharing data between departments are
incalculable. Surely there is much information that each government department should
routinely make available which it currently does not. Surely, too, there are areas where
personal data should be shared or consolidated to save money, improve service and prevent
fraud (such as the Benefits Agency and DVLA medical records example set out recently by Dr
Margaret Harris <A HREF="nb1.11dvl.htm"> Sick Drivers and Healthy Claimants</A>).</P>

<P>Some personal data should not be shared, and surely departments already are far too
ready to share data about people and businesses which they should not. We have yet to see
principles emerge to help define which is which.E-mail is fast and convenient, but sometimes
unreliable.  If uderlying processes, for example for replying to minsterial correspondence, are
unwieldy, then switching to e-mail does not improve matters. Volumes can get out of control
and cause frustration.</P>

<P><B>Paragraph 6.18</B> We already see electronic provision of information supporting the
Citizen's Charter. As people get better informed about service levels, they will become
increasingly frustrated and vocal. Complaints and litigation against public services are at
record levels, despite improvements.  Making complaining possible on-line will further open
the floodgates. This is healthy, even if the symptoms will be annoying. There is scope for
better design and better communication skills (eg in the performance indicator spreadsheets
and CD-ROM), but much of this can simply be left to the media.</P>

<P>The other ingredient will be information age tax-awareness initiatives, such as the <A HREF="http://www1.ifs.org.uk/index.htm">Institute
of Fiscal Studies</A> model. Put together, better service data and better cost data are likely to prove a highly effective catalyst.</P>

<P><B>Paragraph 6.27</B> It is realistic to acknowledge the difficulties in large IT projects,
and sensible to ask industry to put its money where its mouth is. Our concern is that the
procurement procedure not be too bureaucratic, and that government retain control to do less
in future, or to do things differently without being held to ransom by a supplier with an effective
short-to-medium term monopoly in a given area.</P>

<P><B>Paragraph 8.11</B> We think the Cabinet Office approach to electronic signatures
makes far more sense than the Home Office's driving licence/ID card plan <link> Howards ID
card: do the numbers add up?. People accept they must show their faces to buy a pack of
cigarettes; similarly it is common sense they must identify themselves electronically to gain
access to digital services. Consumers and business will dictate just which technology is
accepted.  People will want their cards to contain additional functions that are for their own
benefit or under their own control.<B> Paragraph 8.14</B> We think government can best
protect individuals with a principle insisting that data relating to people or businesses is
wherever possible encrypted or stripped of recognisable personal details so that, for example,
the hospital accountant invoicing a vasectomy case does not know the patient's name.</P>

<P><B>Paragraph 8.21</B> The data donor model is government-centric. The alternative is
to hand the data over to individuals. In the example given, the driver provides a smart card
containing evidence of insurance, MoT, registration and with funds and receives the tax disc
without needing to give name or any other personal details. In any event you might as well do
away with car tax discs if you are reading licence plates electronically.<P>
<P><B>Paragraph 9.4 </B> To ask how electronic service-delivery might be arranged to bring
the greatest benefit to people and businesses is a good question. Need the Green Paper ask
any other? <B> Paragraph 9.10</B> Incentive pricing may cause some shock. The principle
seems fair and straightforward (but then so, some would argue, was the poll tax).</P>

<P>We would just add that hacker (<B>para 8.18</B>) is no more a synonym for expert
criminal than psychopath is a synonym for civil servant.  Bruce Sterling, sci-fi guru, reminds us
that the finest software pioneers were proud to be called hackers. What better ally could
government security experts have than computer whizz-kids who breach their defences for
sport and then tell how they did it? The sensible thing is not to enrage them by being smug at
how internationally respected your experts are, but to set up a secure target and offer a cash
prize for anyone clever enough to crack it, as long as they share their secrets.</P>

<P>We look forward to providing a fuller response with work arising from Citizen Direct, an
independent industry-funded contribution to this vital debate spearheaded by Kable.</P>

<P>November 6, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

</BODY>
