<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><H3>MoD procurements are late on parade</H3></P>

<P>Procurement and approvals procedures at the Ministry of Defence are not capable
of keeping pace with changes in technology and business practices, according to
a new report from <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A> (Due out in December).</P>

<P>The report, <A HREF="../contact.html"> Defence IS Market Profile 1996-99</A>, aims to identify the main factors
holding back successful use of IT in the MoD (as well as giving extensive details on IT spending, related issues and budget plans to 1999).</P>

<P>This matters.  The end of the Cold War brought big changes to the jobs carried
out by the armed forces.  One example is the move towards 'purple' operations,
with the Royal Navy, the Army and Royal Air Force acting under a unified command
structure.</P>

<P>One example is the Joint Rapid Deployment Force, a mobile formation which can be
despatched at short notice.  To control and communicate with this new force, the
MoD needed a joint command system (JCS).</P>

<P>Rather than taking a "big bang" approach to the procurement, the MoD decided to
buy the 192 million system in three stages, with upgrades implemented as
necessary. The contractor is EDS.</P>

<P>The Kable report shows that this flexible approach is unusual. Respondents said
that cumbersome approval processes causes frequent delays, and that by the time
systems go live the technology has moved on. The classic example is the MoD's
head office system, CHOTS.</P>

<P>October 18, 1996</P>
<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
