<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Blair: market will rule the educational superhighway.</H3>

<P>A Labour government will invite private-sector bids for a franchise
to supply online material to Britain's schools, opposition leader Tony
Blair told his party conference on October 1. The Internet, new technology
and a new shape for government all featured in the speech, aimed at presenting
Labour as a credible and innovative party of government after 17 years
in opposition. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://194.128.87.80/scripts/browse.exe?823&0">The speech in
full</A> </P>

<P>The word &quot;technology&quot; featured five times in the speech. But
most of the promises were stronger on sentiment than detail.</P>

<P>Mr Blair tried to build on his announcement the previous year that he
had won a commitment from British Telecom to cable schools for free. &quot;The
cable industry and BT have now given us a commitment to keep costs to our
schools for access to the Internet and Superhighway as low and predictable
as possible. And they have given a commitment to achieve real reductions
in prices for those schools.&quot; </P>

<P>Mr Blair said that a commission of independent experts chaired by Dennis
Stevenson would report later this year on the final building block, access
to hardware so that &quot;in time, no child will be without access to a
computer and no school unable to use them properly&quot;.</P>

<P>Mr Blair conceded, however, that hardware and connections were not enough
on their own. &quot;What matters in the end though, is the educational
material that comes down those cables, into those computers and into the
mind of the child.&quot;</P>

<P>The best way to procure such material, he said, was through the free
market, as with textbooks. &quot;Competition will ensure the prices are
low.&quot; &quot;In government, we will be inviting bids for a franchise
to provide the specialised education network.&quot;</P>

<P>&quot;Our aim is for every school to have access to the superhighway,
the computers to deliver it and the education programmes to go on it. With
the University for Industry for adult skills, this adds up to a National
Grid for Learning for Britain,&quot; he said. </P>

<P>Mr Blair also hinted that Labour has been considering recent thinking
on ways to streamline the machinery of government. </P>

<UL>
<LI>&quot;We spend &pound;300 billion a year in the public sector, but
a lot of what government does isn't about helping us to achieve. It's stopping
us achieving.&quot;</LI>

<LI>&quot;If you are a young person leaving school, leaving home and looking
for a job you can have to contact 11 government offices not one.&quot;</LI>

<LI>&quot;We will introduce a programme to reform government. Our aim is
to coordinate services across government using the advantages of the technology
now available, to provide a modern and up-to-date service for the customers
of the state.&quot; </LI>
</UL>

<P>October 3, 1996 </P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy; <A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html">Kable</A>
Ltd, 1996</P>
