<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Signposts to Government</H2>
<H3>A web site about a new type of government: online government.</H3>

<P>For decades, governments have struggled with a central dilemma: improving public services means throwing more money at them. This means either borrowing money - and building up the kind of public deficit the US accumulated in the 1980s - or raising taxes. Yet tax rises are politically taboo today: only one major British political party, the Liberal Democrats, is likely to go into the upcoming election with a pledge to raise income taxes. </P>

<P>There is a third way: improve the efficiency of government services through information technology. Britain and other Western countries are on the verge of this breakthrough.</P>

<P>The process will not be painless. </P>

<P>Politicians may shy away from these difficult debates. Signposts to Government does not. Our news section, <A HREF="fr.index.html">Newsbites</A> carries weekly updated hot news. 
<A HREF="../issues/fr.index.html">Issues</A> contains background material and opinion from all sides of the story.
<A HREF="../projects/fr.index.html">Projects</A>
 follows the progress of major government investments in IT. </P>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Coming soon... </H3><UL><LI>Signposts Directory: the definitive guide to government on the Internet</LI></UL><P>Email news and comments about the site to: <A HREF="../../../../signposts@kable.co.uk">signposts@kable.co.uk</A></P><P><B><I>Signposts to Government</I></B> is an independent service, produced by Kable and sponsored by 

<A HREF="http://www.compaq.com">Compaq</A>, 

<A HREF="../eds/index.htm">EDS,</A>

<A HREF="http://www.eyi.com">Ernst and Young</A> 

and <A HREF="http://www.oracle.com">Oracle.</A></P>

<P>Any views expressed are not necessarily those of the sponsors. </P>

