<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3><B>Exclusive: why civil servants fight shy of the Internet</B></H3>

<P>Fears about security are the main factor holding back government organisations'
use of the internet, according to new research carried out by Kable. However
people who do not use the net are more likely to be worried than people
with experience. </P>

<P>The survey, Internet Usage in Government, was carried out by Kable for
<B>Mercury Comunications. </B>This summary of findings is available exclusively
on <B><I>Signposts to Government</I></B>. The survey found that in the:
</P>

<H3>Civil Service </H3>

<P>Users: Three quarters of Internet users had been on the net for more
than six months. However 17 per cent installed in the previous six months
and 10 per cent are in the process of doing so.</P>

<P>Non users: 35 per cent said they were evaluating the Internet, 27 per
cent were considering it and 30 per cent had no plans to implement it.
Only 8 per cent claim never to have thought about it. </P>

<P>Only 28 per cent of users said they had a security policy. </P>

<P>Respondents did not have a high opinion of the government's grasp of
internet issues: only 23 per cent of those surveyed rated it as excellent
or very good. </P>

<P>And only 13 per cent of users and 8 per cent of non users mentioned
the idea that the internet might improve local access to public records,
or demand for greater access to government information. </P>

<H3>Health service </H3>

<P>Relatively few people used the Internet. The big worry was poor security.
Over a quarter (26 per cent) of users had installed it in the previous
six months, half for more than six months and the rest were in the process
of doing so. Of non-users, 34 per cent were evaluating the internet and
51 per cent considering it, 10 per cent had no plans to do so and only
5 per cent claimed to have not even thought about it. </P>

<P>In healthcare, only 42 per cent of internet users had a security policy.</P>

<H3>Education </H3>

<P>It was hard to find any non users. This sector has more experience than
any other and did not regard poor security as a major issue. Opinions were
divided equally on whether the introduction of the information superhighway
in government had raised any new policy issues: 43 per cent believe it
has, 43 per cent believe it had not. </P>

<H3>Police and criminal justice</H3>

<P>Another new user. Of surveyed organisations connected to the net, 67
per cent had installed it in the previous six months. Only 11 per cent
of users had it for more than 6 months. Of non users, 55 per cent were
evaluating the internet and 18 per cent considering it. 27 per cent had
no plans to implement it.</P>

<H3><B>Education</B> </H3>

<P>Education leads usage 130 out of the 220 organisations surveyed used
the net, ie 59%. Educational establishments lead the way, with 98% of those
surveyed using the net - not too surprising, given the dominance of students
in surfing the net. the breakdown for the other sectors surveyed was as
follows: civil service, 53%; health, 48%; and police/criminal justice,
45%. </P>

<H3>Sample profile</H3>

<P>220 different departments, agencies or organisations were researched,
covering the civil service, health, education and the police/criminal justice.
The target interviewee was the individual responsible for the organisation's
internet policy. The most typical job title was IT director or manager.</P>

<TABLE BORDER=1 >
<TR>
<TD>
<TABLE>
