<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Reinventing government</H3>

<H4>Ideas from the architect of Next Steps</H4>

<P>Many people think the British government has been extensively remodelled
in recent years. </P>

<P>Not far enough, argue Sir Peter Kemp and David Walker in a paper for
the European Policy Forum. Their views will carry weight: Kemp was the
architect of the government's &quot;next steps agencies&quot;. </P>

<P>So far, they say, remodelling has been &quot;confined within an inherited
structure of departments and committees... in Whitehall the new management
has been grafted onto a system of rewards, expectations and expectations
which, at least until recently, has escaped attention&quot;. </P>

<P>The authors believe that while &quot;information technology is a tool
of government; it is also a challenge. Yet how many ministers or civil
servants understand even the basics?&quot; </P>

<P>Sir Peter believes that government departments and agencies still have
a long way to go before they achieve real reform. The problem can be summed
up in the word &quot;departmentalism&quot;. &quot;The way government looks
determines how it looks to the world,&quot; say the authors. &quot;At a
time when corporate leaders are moving to the 'boundaryless organisation',
Whitehall shows us some of the most vigilantly policed and ferociously
guarded boundaries of all.&quot; </P>

<P>That is not to say that things cannot change. For example, executive
agencies can still offer the opportunity to create &quot;lean and mean&quot;
central departments, which, while retaining control and maintaining accountability,
leave time for thought about the big issues. </P>

<P>The report comes up with some suggestions as to how departments should
look in the future. </P>

<P><B>Prime Minister's Department:</B> The prime minister should have a
fully fledged department responsible for making the leader more aware of
what other parts of government are doing; and of bringing forward projections
and descriptions of the outside world, both foreign and domestic. In particular,
it should be responsible for reviewing the horizontal aspects of government
running across departments and agencies. Its creation calls into question
the existence of the Cabinet Office, described in the report as &quot;a
loose, baggy monster containing all sorts of things such as science and
technology foresight&quot;. </P>

<P><B>The Treasury:</B> The Treasury should undergo a purchaser/provider
split, with the purchaser being the Chancellor of the Exchequer.</P>

<P>The holder of this office would be responsible for the condition of
the economy, including money supply, aggregates, prices, national income
and the economic impact of government. Running alongside the Chancellor
of the Exchequer's Department would be a new Department of the Budget.
With its own minister, it would take over and enhance the functions of
the Chief Secretary to the Treasury, as the senior progress chaser on spending
plans. It would match spending with government income and be better placed
than the Treasury to rein in tax cuts and tinker with allowances.</P>

<P><B>Department of Social Security:</B> This should transmute into a Department
of Personal Income, responsible for collecting income tax and national
insurance contributions and making payments (ie pensions and income support).
The DPI could keep the Inland Revenue's personal taxation divisions, but
its corporate and special investigations work could pass to a Department
for Business.</P>

<P><B>Ministry for Civil Society: </B>The authors propose a Ministry for
Civil Society that would &quot;manage the various ways in which the state
connects with the country at large&quot;. This would include liaison with,
and payment of grants to, local authorities; the promotion and overseeing
of charities; regional governance; families; gender; race relations; immigration
and border controls. &quot;These functions,&quot; say the authors, &quot;are
largely local or domestic and areas where the state treads lightly.&quot;
It would also have responsibility for civil courts and settling disputes,
and could look at overseeing the chartered professions.</P>

<P>A better machine: government for the 21st century, by Sir Peter Kemp
and David Walker. Price &pound;7.50, available from the European Policy
Forum, tel 0171 222 0733.</P>

<P>September 30, 1996</P>
<pre>


</pre>
&copy; <a href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 1996</BLOCKQUOTE>

