<H3>Projects watch: NIRS2</H3>
<P><B>Purpose:</B> To create an on-line database of National Insurance 
records for 50 million people, for use by around 7,000 authorised staff 
of the Department of Social Security to replace the outdated NIRS 1 
system.</P>
<P><B>Contractor:</B> A Private Finance Initiative contract worth 110 
million awarded to Andersen Consulting on April 27, 1995 by the DSS and 
the Benefits Agency. </P>
<P><B>Progress:</B> This system is supposed to be up and running by 
February1997 with further features released by April 1999. Andersen ran 
into problems in February 1996 when it realised that because of the level 
of programming required, even with extra staff, it could not complete the 
project in time.<BR>After negotiations with the DSS, the contractor will 
be allowed to release a limited version of the database by 1997 with the 
full version usable by the second deadline of 1999. <BR>Andersen had to 
pay compensation of 12m to the DSS and 13m to keep NIRS 1 running until 
NIRS 2 is fully functional. </P>
<P>September 30, 1996</P><pre></pre>&copy; <a 
href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 
