</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="is_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> </P><BLOCKQUOTE><H3>Identity cards - will the numbers add up?</H3><P>The British government's planned national identity card will need anew national database of citizens if it is going to work, research by Signpostscan reveal. This is because existing systems of national identity numbersare either inadequate or already compromised. </P><P>The plans for a voluntary national identity card have already causedhuge political controversy. In public, the main row was over the use ofthe national flag (the Union Flag) alongside the European Union's 15-staremblem. Behind the scenes, however, lurk more complex technical issues.Resolving them will require setting up new government information systemsand most likely a new national ID number.</P><P>Three types of card are planned.</P><P>1) Photo driving licence.</P><P>2) National ID card for non-drivers.</P><P>3) Combination ID card and driving licence, in an agreed format foruse as a travel document throughout the European Union.</P><P>The main problem is checking eligibility. Unlike several Continentaland Scandinavian countries, there is no national identity numbering systemin Britain. </P><P>The implications for data-matching will interest the Data ProtectionRegistrar. In her 1996 annual report, she commented: </P><P>&quot;There are acknowledged limitatons and deficiencies in officialdocumentation and government databases. Whether an authoritative, accurateand effective identity card scheme could be developed from the existingdocumentation and databases is open to question.&quot;</P><P>All candidates for source databases are flawed.</P><P>1) <B>National insurance number.</B> Advantage: a relatively recent,well- maintained number. Drawback: many living individuals (mainly elderlywomen) have never been issued a number. Meanwhile, some have been issuedto foreign nationals. </P><P>2) <B>Passport office number.</B> Advantage: issued only after checkon eligibility through citizenship. Drawback: the existence of 'Jackal'passports (named after the Frederick Forsyth novel which explained theprocedure) issued in the name of dead individuals. </P><P>3) <B>NHS number.</B> Advantage: the NHS in England and Wales is currentlyissuing new 10-digit numbers to every patient on its register (in a similarformat to the Scottish number). If the project succeeds, it is likely toachieve the most comprehensive and robust national ID number. Disadvantage:to curb worries about confidentiality of medical records, the governmenthas repeatedly ruled out its use outside the NHS. The government has alreadydecided that the new NHS number will not appear on birth certificates.</P><P>4) The existing <B>driver number</B> from the Driver and Vehicle LicensingAgency's database is unsuitable because it is issued without verificationapart, presumably, from random and targeted checks to detect fraudulentapplications. No citizenship qualification is involved. </P><P>5) <B>Birth certificates.</B> These carry no proof that the individualnamed is still alive.</P><P>The Home Office's solution is for the government to use the DVLA database,cross-checked with the passport office. But will this be feasible? Turnto <A HREF="../issues/fr.index.html">Issues</A> in <B><I>Signposts to Government</I></B>for Sheila Beck's comment: The National Identity Card - a lost opportnity.</P><P>The debate is hotting up on other web sites.</P><P>Further information on the Home Office's Web site: <A HREF="http://www.coi.gov.uk/coi/depts/GHO/GHO.html">http://www.coi.gov.uk/coi/depts/GHO/GHO.html</A>But don't expect it to tell the whole story. For example, its list of 'whathappens in other countries' lists 14 states all but three of which haveidentity cards, but omits Ireland, Australia the USA and Japan which donot.</P><P>For a critical view, check out Privacy International's site: <A HREF="http://www.privacy.org/pi/">http://www.privacy.org/pi/</A>and Charter 88: <A HREF="http://gnew.gn.apc.org/charter88/online/pubs/idcards.html">http://gnew.gn.apc.org/charter88/online/pubs/idcards.html</A></P><P>Relavent information can also be found with the <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/dpr/dprhome.htm">DataProtection Registrar</A>.</P><P>September 30, 1996</P><PRE></PRE><P>&copy; <A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd. 1996 </P></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
