<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Brother, this is one big plan...green paper predictions</H3>

<P>Ministers look set to unveil their vision of Britain's
electronic government on Wednesday 6 November. The new green
paper on the theme 'government direct' will also be launched on
the net and CD-ROM, and draws on the work of a central IT unit
(Citu) set up in the Cabinet Office at the end of 1995. So
what's in it? Signposts predicts plenty of vision thing, and
specifics like:<P>

<UL>
<LI>law making the electronic signature valid, which would be a
world first and make Britain attractive as a location for
administrative and financial services businesses</LI>

<LI>all government forms to be available on the net</>

<LI>a Whitehall wide SMTP e-mail system, based on the existing
government data network (Racal) or government telephone network
(Mercury)</LI>

<LI>plans for public access kiosks of the sort local authorities
have been testing for some years</LI>

<LI>references to California and New Brunswick (where the issuing
of high-tech moose licences has been making waves)</LI>

<LI>a list of pilots and demonstrators, some projected, some new,
some past their sell-by date</LI>

</UL>

<P>If government is to cross-computerise, it will need new data
protection laws and really ought in the British people's
interests to commit up front to adopting privacy-friendly
technologies throughout systems that handle personal data. Don't
count on it, and watch this space.</P>

<P>You are unlikely to see in the Green Paper a full costing of the
sorts of changes envisaged.</P>

<P>Although the possible savings might be huge. The government
could save a large proportion (let us say half) of the 22bn
cost of running Whitehall. Furthermore computerisation could
save a significant proportion of the far larger 300bn
public-service programme budget, through the shift to self
service by the public, fraud reduction, better targetted
services and cheaper provision of information. Just what these
savings might be is effectively unobtainable owing to the
present structure of government accounts.</P>

</P>More seriously, we are unlikely to see a clear plan as to how to
manage the process of breaking down the the structure of
government from the present 'smokestack' where each department
and agency focuses on its mission and tells every other part of
government, in the words of one senior insider, to 'sod off and
mind their own business'. Any clear plan would raise the
question of huge job losses and massively antagonise entrenched
interests in the government machine.</P>

<P>A mutiny in the civil service is the last thing the government
needs this close to an election.</P>

<P>William Heath, Kable Director</P>

<P>November 1, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
