<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3> Party games: IT issues for the general election</H3>

<P>Technology has become fashionable again. Even politicians are talking enthusiastically about
it. Tony Blair's annual fugue to the nation at the Labour party conference contains a regular
endorsement of the magic of technology, music to a party which still attaches mystical
importance to Harold Wilson's "white heat" speech which heralded the end of 13 years of Tory
rule.</P>

<P>Although IT issues will not decide the result of the next election -- who cares when there's
taxation, European monetary union, and unemployment to argue about -- there is no doubt
that using IT intelligently as a means of developing policies has finally arrived. It is already
clear what issues are going to be raised.</P>

<P>There are five. Overall the defining feature is not controversy but a broad and optimistic
agreement:</P>
<UL>
<LI> <B>Schoolroom IT</B> "Education, education and education" - Tony Blair's repetition is apposite, as all parties share the ambition to turn schools into multimedia emporia. This year Mr Blair announced a Labour government would create a franchise for a specialised educational network, providing content for schools. Last year the party announced an intention to give schools on-line access for free with the help of BT, and created a commission (led by Pearson's new Chairman, Denis
Stevenson) to find ways of obtaining hardware and teacher-training. Also. the blueprint for
Labour's long-heralded virtual university for industry is finally going to be launched in
December. 
But Labour's message is hardly unique. The central theme for the Liberal Democrats'
manifesto will also be education -- although the party prefers to spend hard cash. Nigel Jones, the
Liberal's spokesman for Science, Technology and Consumer Affairs, says he has a promise
from Paddy Ashdown for a millennium billion -- a billion pounds to buy hardware and training
for schools. The Conservatives can respond in kind, with an existing schools on-line policy, that will spend a rather smaller 32 million, in a kit-buying and training initiative; a relationship with the University of East Anglia to develop educational software; and the desire of the cable companies and BT to give schools free on-line access.</LI></BR>

<P><LI> <B>Self-service government</B> This will be launched in a much trailed Green Paper due mid
November based around the idea of "Government Direct". It will offer the citizen and business
the prospect of being able to deal with all government services from a single electronic point of access (but not with smartcards, at least just yet). The Labour party is now appearing to
latch onto the idea, with a conference pledge from Mr Blair to "introduce a programme to
reform government. Our aim is to co-ordinate services across government, using the advantages of
technology now available".</LI></P>

<P><LI> <B>Cable industry policy</B> Finding things to do, or not to do with BT, now increasingly Britain's leading information services company. Here, at least, there's some controversy. While the Conservatives are happy with the Oftel-enforced status quo, Labour might hit BT for a share of its windfall tax on the utilities. Meanwhile the Liberals even have a standing policy to break up BT, although this is now under review. Labour will end the ban preventing the company delivering broadcast television down its pipes from 2001, as long as the schools are linked up for free; the government has no plans for review until, it says, greater competition materialises (given Cable & Wireless's new venture into cable TV, the time could now be right).</LI></P>

<P><LI> <B>Public sector outsourcing</B> The Conservatives are broadly satisfied with current
arrangements, give or take some readjustments to the private finance initiative (PFI) in response to
industry squeals. Labour's policies would alleviate some of the pressure to contract out. The
major difference is in local government, where compulsory competitive tendering for IT will be
introduced during the next Parliament by the Tories; Labour will scrap the compulsory element
in tendering across the board.
Centrally the changes will be far less, Labour, for example, will introduce a series of technical changes to PFI which the party believes will ensure the process is more strategically
managed.</LI></P>

<P><LI> <B>Vision</B> All parties agree on the importance of vision. Labour seems keen to strike poses reminiscent of US Vice-President Al Gore, while Ian Taylor, minster for science and
technology, prefers to emphasise a blokey British pragmatism, wryly noting how little Mr
Gore, for all his cyber-speak, has actually achieved. But the government is not fully immune
to visionary encouragement. It intends to launch a public awareness and community
technology campaign, IT's for all, to be launched in December, which even John Major has been
heard highlighting.</LI></P>
</UL>

<P>Rather more interesting is what's not discussed. What the parties share is a middle-aged optimism. Technology is seen as a tool for
liberating government or children (which plays well with baffled parents). The impact of
technology in public policy is stressed when it can be used to deploy good news; ignored
when it poses a threat. The reality of technology's amoral penetration into social life, and the
difficulties it can present are marginalised.</P>

<P>Take taxation, EMU and constitutional reform. In each case the impact of technology on a
fundamental policy has been ignored. Increasingly writers, such as Neil Barratt in his book
<I>The Future of the Cybernation</I> or Luc Soete at the 
<A HREF="http://www.ispo.cec.be/hleg/bittax.html"> University of Maastricht</A>, have begun to question how long existing taxation structures can remain viable in an age where money can be strongly encrypted and hidden on remote servers -- or where some goods can be paid for and distributed in unmonitorable on-line transactions.</P>

<P>With EMU, while arguments about sovereignty rage, there is almost no serious
recognition of the technology issues that underlie the change to a single currency. Yet
a recent report from software industry trade association, the CSSA, goes as far as concluding:
"IT is at the heart of banking. It may be that IT is the one issue which could stop EMU in its
tracks."</P>

<P>The EMU issue reflects a general trend: the poor recognition of how dependent the delivery of
changes in public policy is on IT. Nor is the real relationship between the introduction of
technology and its impact on employment effectively acknowledged. It is clear that the industry
has visibly created powerful global firms, but the pressures to automate services through
technology has made tens of thousands redundant in the banking sector alone.
The only solution to be offered is training -- and how appropriate is this, for example, to those
who find themselves in undesired early retirement?
Politicians' optimism should not surprise us -- creating a sense of possibility is fundamental to the
political enterprise. But that does not mean we should follow political fashion all the way down the garden path.</P>

<P>Daniel Sabbagh, reporter, Business & Technology</P>

<P>October 25, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

</BLOCKQOUTE>

</BODY>
