<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK=#"551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<IMG SRC="is_line.gif">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3> Millennium crisis for government computing</H3>

<P>If you haven't heard of the year 2000 problem, or the Y2K 
crisis as it is known in jargon, then count your blessings for being immune to
IT catch-phrases.</P>

<P>But you could also be dangerously unaware of an issue that, despite being over
three years away, is becoming an increasing subject for alarm.</P>

<P>It concerns the unknown number of information systems that are going to crash or
produce erroneous data when their internal clocks click over from the year 1999
to 2000. This could affect payroll systems, diarised automatic events and even traffic lights. Just how bad the situation could get is unknown. Information systems in the public sector are at least as vulnerable as
those in private business. But fewer options are open to fix them.</P>

<P>What's the problem? Put very simply, most older mainframe or mid-range software
- often based on the Cobol programming language -- was developed with only two
digits to represent the year. This made sense in the days when computer memory
was a scarce resource to be saved at any cost.  But it means that 
when we get round to the year 2000, or for some systems the year 2001, an
estimated 90 per cent of large-scale programs will run out of 
years, and either revert to a representation of the year 1900 or 
possibly crash the whole system.</P>

<P>Many business-critical systems in local and central government 
are based on legacy mainframe systems.  The year 2000 problem affects some newer
software developed by less forward-thinking companies.  So the 
implications are huge.</P>

<P>Roger Freeman, minister for public service, set out the government's response at
a conference in September.  He said, a little implausibly, that: "The deputy
prime minister (Michael Heseltine) and I have personally made sure that all
ministers and senior officials are aware of the problem and are putting action
plans in place."</P>

<P>The organisation charged with tackling the problem is the Central Information
Technology Unit (CITU), set up in 1995 to advise ministers on IT strategy.</P>

<P><UL>Mr Freeman said that CITU's activities would include:</P>

<LI>The Year 2000 Coordinating Committee "to promote awareness of the latest
developments to central and local government".

<LI>Publishing best-practice guidelines called the "Year 2000 Method".

<LI>Forging links with private sector to promote industry's awareness.

<LI>Disseminating advice and best practice via the Central Computer and
Telecommunication Agency's (CCTA's) Web site.  

<LI>Setting up an electronic discussion group via the Internet.

</UL>

<P>The CCTA's advice, for public and private sector, is to take the problem
seriously. By that it means start a "year 2000 project". Now.</P>

<P>Such a project should involve a "complete assessment of an organisation's entire 
systems portfolio and operating environment and, after the necessary code changes 
and/or re-engineering has taken place, the complete re-testing of the full
portfolio". </P>

<P>The Gartner Group, a firm of consultants which was one of the first to blow the
whistle on the Y2K issue, claims organisations must 
concentrate on project management so that they can "accurately determine
applications' exposure and begin corrective measures immediately".</P>

<P>There is a good reason for organisations to get on with fixing the year 2000
problem sooner rather than later. The sheer size of the issue means 
that demand for the sort of skills required - mainly Cobol programming 
and project management - means that every organisation in the land is going to be 
fighting for the same limited pool of skills.</P>

<P>This is likely to make life more difficult for the public sector because 
private companies will  find it easier to offer the sort of salaries that year 2000
saviours will be demanding.  Year 2000 project managers in private firms can 
already demand salaries in the range of 100,000 (despite the fact that no one
can say they have a proven track record in dealing with the problem). Some
estimates predict that by the eve of the millennium, Cobol programmers will be
able to command up to 150,000.</P>

<P>The Computing Software and Services Association, the industry's trade body, says
that organisations will have to pay up - and lock-in their managers contractually to
ensure they complete the project.</P>

<P> A survey by market research firm Spikes Cavell 
revealed that 68 per cent of companies have a strategy to deal with the 
year 2000 problem. But given the extra challenges posed in the public-
sector, there is no time for hesitation.</P>

<UL>Information on the Web: 

<LI><A HREF="http://www.year2000.com">Year 2000 Info Center</A>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ccta.gov.uk/ccta/mill/mbhome.htm">CCTA</A>

</UL>

<P>Daryl Willcox, journalist</P>
 
<H3> How to test your system: Official advice</H3>

<P> The NHS information management group, part of the NHS Executive, has produced the following  do-it-yourself guide to testing systems for vulnerability to the year 2000.  It stresses that it cannot take responsibility for any loss or damage caused.</P>

<P><OL><B>The tests:</B></P> 

<LI>Enter a post-2000 date into every date field of every system.  Check displays, printouts, age calculations, etc. for values that don't appear to make sense.  In particular, check that the systems sort correctly on ages and dates.

<LI>Disconnect the system from any external source of current date information, e.g. a network. Set the system clock to five minutes before midnight on December 31, 1999.  Close down your system, or if it is a PC, power it off.  After 10 minutes, restart it or power it on again and see what date is displayed.  This test exposes problems on most non-Pentium PCs.

<LI>Set the system date to January 1, 2000. Check it is accepted. Close down/power off the system, start it up again and see what date has been stored.

<LI>Set the system clock to five minutes before midnight on February 28, 2000. Power off the system. After 10 minutes, power it on again and see what date is displayed.  It should be February 29, 2000.

<LI>Set the system date to February 29, 2000. Check it is accepted.

<LI>See what day March 1, 2000 is.  It should be a Wednesday.

<LI>With the system clock set to today's date, try entering data for post-2000.

<LI>Set the clock to after January 1, 2000, and try the same thing.

<LI>With the system clock set to after January 1, 2000, check the age of patients, especially babies, born (a) before 2000 (b) after 2000.

<LI>With the system clock set to after January 1, 2000, check all results that depend on date of birth, e.g. pay grade in a payroll system. 

<LI>With the system clock set to after January 1, 2000, try running statistics or other reports for 1999. Try again for reports running over the 1999 year end.

<LI>With the system clock set to after January 1, 2000, try entering data with 99 as the year. See whether it is interpreted as 1999 or 2099, and whether that is correct in the context. Try the same for other years, eg 10, 20, 30 ...90.

</OL>

<P>October 18, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy<A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html"> Kable </A> 1996</P>

