<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><H3>Data detectives to sniff out fraud</H3>

<P>Peter Lilley, Britainis social security minister, has announced a major data-matching initiative to catch people who fraudulently claim state benefits.</P>

<P>He told the Conservative Party conference in Bournemouth on October 9, that a
new law would allow inspectors from other departments to trawl through records
of the Inland Revenue.  At present, this is allowed only where evidence of fraud
already exists.</P>

<P>The government was due to introduce the bill in the Queen's Speech on October
23. He described existing rules as "absurd..."  "We ought to be able to
cross-check this information to find fraudsters who are working and claiming
benefits, but unintended barriers prevent us."</P>

<P>The main barrier of course is the 1984 Data Protection Act, which lays down the
principle that data collected for one purpose should not be used for aother.  Mr Lilley
will argue that one of the purposes of collecting existing data on claimants is
to prevent fraud. Therefore, no conflict exists.</P>

<P>Nevertheless, he can expect a rough ride over the civil liberties issue.</P>

<P>Data-matching is a long-standing bogey of the privacy lobby.  Activists such as
Simon Davies of Privacy International say that the inability of government
agencies to cross-check their data easily and routinely is an important
safeguard. </P>

<P>Meanwhile, there is litle evidence that data-matching is cost-effective.</P>

<P>The US government tried it in 1977.  "Project Match" involved the Department of
Health and Human Services matching its records against federal payroll files to
detect discrepancies. According to Mr Davies' account in his book Big Brother
(Pan 1996), the project came up with 33,000 "raw hits", of which 7,100 were real
discrepancies. Of these, 638 were weeded out for investigation, 55 were
prosecuted and 35 convictions were secured, levying fines of less than $10,000.</P>

<P>"No one may ever know the extent of the distress and humiliation this caused to
tens of thousands of honest people but ironically, while the result of this
multi-million dollar exercise was so obviously a failure, the relevant
departments hailed it as a great success", Mr Davies says.</P>

<P>Australia has also tried data-matching. In 1993, more than 30 major projects
were under way. However, according to Mr Davies, a 1994 exercise in
data-matching carried out by the Australian Tax Office, involving comparisons of
20 million files, came up with no new cases of deception.</P>

<P>Mr Davies suggests that the failure rate of these matching programmes has been
unchanged sinced 1977.</P>

<P>The British government argues, however, that even if data matching does not
catch many offenders, it acts as a deterrent. In 1993, the government began
matching student grant files against those in benefit offices, to detect
individuals receiving student grants and social security benefits
simultaneously.</P>

<P>Campaigners also argue that data matching relies on an assumption of guilt,
turning the whole system of justice on its head. It encourages governments to
set up universal numbering systems, with their knock-on effects.</P>

<P>Data-matching opens up the possibility of the government creating profiles of
people likely to commit certain types of offence.  The classic example, is that
of the Thomas Hamilton, who killed 16 children and their teacher at Dunblane in
March 1996.  His obsessive and irrational behaviour was well known to several
public bodies, including education, government departments and MPs - yet his
licence to own firearms was cross-checked.</P>

<P>It is hard to argue against data-matching in cases like this.  The Dunblane
children had civil rights, too.<P>

<P>October 18, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
