<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<P><IMG SRC="is_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206> </P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Outsourcing</H3>

<P>If you want better public services, you have to spend more money on
them. Wrong, says the British government. It claims to be saving at least
240 million a year while delivering more effective public services.
The magic ingredient, it claims, is outsourcing. </P>

<P>In the IT world, outsourcing, or facilities management ('FM') means
the transfer of computer operations from within an existing organisation
to an outside specialist in providing such services. This is how the maverick
US presidential candidate Ross Perot, founder of EDS, made his fortune.
Many established IT firms moved into this market when profit margins from
building and selling computers shrank. </P>

<P>Compared with new technology frontiers outsourcing has something dull
and worthy about it; an IT market for managers and bean counters. Yet it
is rapidly becoming the place where the action is. .</P>

<P>Prompted by the government's Competing for Quality policy (1990), outsourcing
of computer systems has increased greatly in the civil service. The value
of contracts rose from 30m in 1993/94 to 211m in 1995/96,
according to Kable research; a sevenfold increase in just two years. </P>

<P>Outsourcing had already gained ground in some local authorities and
the NHS, which has transferred all its central administrative computers
to private contractors. One police force, Devon &amp; Cornwall, has now
gone the same route.</P>

<P>Competing for Quality led to a series of keen contests, or market tests,
between teams of civil servants in government departments, and FM services
companies such EDS, Cap Gemini and SEMA. </P>

<P>In many cases - the Northern Ireland civil service, the Inland Revenue,
or the Home Office - the in house team either did not compete or did not
win, and work was transferred. In others, it shaped up to the challenge.
Mike Allen's team at the Employment Department, for example, shaved costs
by 30 per cent to beat EDS.</P>

<P>Strenuous exertion is rarely comfortable or popular, and neither is
market testing in the civil service. Public-sector staff have bitterly
opposed the process. But for the wider public, the real question is: what
is the effect on quality of service, does outsourcing end up costing more
or less, and what are the long-term effects? </P>

<P>Savings are hard to calculate. Doing so requires comparisons against
an ever changing baseline. The costs of bidding tend to be high. The latest
official estimates, from the new 1996 Competing for Quality Policy Review,
based on work by Mori, a market survey company, suggest annual savings
from market testing to date of 240-280m. </P>

<P>People paying London parking fines or applying for driving licences
may detect with mixed feelings that such services are now more efficient,
although the new study is less categorical about service improvements generally
than earlier government claims. </P>

<P>The 244m a year figure is also rather less than the earlier government
claim of 544m a year. Newspapers have suggested that this accounts
for the delay in publishing the new report. Feelings about the issue run
high. One commentator went so far as to equate the government's attempt
to massage the figures with Soviet historians' covering up Stalin's massacres.
</P>

<H4>What the scrutiny report said:</H4>

<UL>
<LI>Between 1992 and 1995, the Competing for Quality scheme opened up government
activities worth 1.85 billion to competition.</LI>

<LI>Between 1992 and 1995, 20,186 staff left the civil service as a result.</LI>

<LI>Roughly the same number of people think that the quality of service
has improved, declined or stayed the same.</LI>

<LI>Net savings were between 240 million and 280 million.</LI>

<LI>The review recommends a more business-driven approach for the future,
concentrating on larger packages of services. </LI>

<LI>Winning government contracts is two to three times higher than the
cost of winning work in the private sector. At least 6 per cent of the
average contract price represents the suppliers selling costs. </LI>

<LI>Of 935 competing for quality reviews carried out, 70 involved IT support
services. The mean value was 6.65 million. </LI>
</UL>

<P>William Heath, Kable</P>

<P>September 30, 1996</P>

<PRE>
</PRE>

<P>&copy; <A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd. 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

