<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">
<img src="is_line.gif">
<blockquote>
<H3>National identity cards - a lost opportunity. A comment from industry</H3>

<P>Debate over a British national identity card has raged for many years,
but picked up a head of steam in 1994 when it became the focus of an ad-hoc
general committee of the cabinet, GEN 34. </P>

<P>The committee's role was to consider the use of card technology by government
departments. Smart cards were being pushed as the panacea for all government
ills and a great number of people involved in the technologies became excited
at the prospect of having found a problem to be addressed by their solution.
</P>

<P>I welcome the prospect of a card not for the control that it is feared
it might bring but as a proof that I am who I say I am, and that because
I am who I say I am I have a certain number of rights to demand things
from the state, and my rights as a British citizen when abroad. But I do
not see that this can happen if cards are to be issued by the Driver and
Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) as a new kind of driving licence. </P>

<P>The DVLA's system was set up not to ensure identity but to record information
about drivers. There are about 34 million drivers in the UK, but about
50 million records on the DVLA's database. One simple reason for this is
that there is no legal requirement to tell DVLA of someone's demise. It
is rather difficult to prosecute an individual for failing to inform you
of their death! </P>

<P>So, accepting that such a new law would be unenforceable, it should
be possible to allow government systems to be made aware automatically
of the issue of a death certificate. It is hard to see that it could be
argued that this cross-matching would infringe an individual's right to
privacy and simply seems to be a matter of common sense. </P>

<P>The improvement in the system by introducing a photo licence incorporating
a scanned image provided by the applicant also appears less than perfect.
Particularly if those photographs may be authorised by any one of 494,000
civil servants, as is the case with passport applications. Other methods
of checking are suggested but these remain unclear. Given the known deficiencies
in our numerous national systems, checking identity is not a simple task
and it once again raises the question of why the DVLA should become the
authority for checking personal identity. </P>

<P>If the national identity card is to address a deficiency in existing
systems, timing is crucial. The timescale for rolling out the photo driving
licence is extremely lengthy. The DVLA suggests that it sees most current
licences within seven years (when people change address, for example).
This is the point at which the DVLA will issue a new photo licence. </P>

<P>The slowness of this process, coupled with more stringent identity checks,
means that it will probably be at least seven years before 34 million of
the UK's 46 million adults have a card. Incidentally, if -- as suggested
-- these cards wear out on average every five years, a major replacement
programme will have to begin almost at once. </P>

<P>Of course had the government put the DVLA computer contract out to tender,
through the private finance initiative, the service supplier could have
taken on the risk of dealing with fraud and misrepresentation. The contract
might also have included a condition to update the technology to keep in
step with other government systems likely to emerge over the next 10 years
-- when you might just be receiving your first dumb photo licence!</P>

<P>Sheila Beck, Siemens Business Services</P>

<P>September 1996 </P>
<pre>


</pre>
&copy; <a href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 1996
</blockquote>
