<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<P><IMG SRC="is_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206> </P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>The case for intelligent tokens</H3>

<H4>Kable's response to the Home Office identity cards initiative </H4>

<P>Kable has submitted the following response to the Home Office's request
for comments on its proposals for a national identity card. </P>

<UL>
<LI>People in the UK do not want an ID card. A home secretary, however
competent or popular, who tries to introduce one in peacetime is turning
a tremendous opportunity into a potentially insurmountable problem. When
the man in charge of prisons, policing, and immigration control smiles
and offers up a photo card with national and EU symbols, people may infer
demonic eyes and fear he is motivated by dark forces. The emotional reaction
is perhaps because it offends people to suggest there is a general need
for them to prove they are who they say there are. Worse, he wants 15
for the wretched little piece of plastic.</LI>

<LI>People would however welcome the prospect of more efficient, cost-effective,
and secure access to a range of services, for example shopping, commuting
or travel abroad, or getting benefit, tax or health matters sorted. Sometimes
they may want to do these things at odd times of day, sometimes by telephone.
</LI>

<LI>In some cases, they may prefer to remain anonymous. </LI>

<LI>Computerised authorisation, transaction and payment systems could make
these services directly available to people, as long as they were prepared
to carry some sort of token offering foolproof standard machine-readable
identification. This might be a chip-bearing card, although many would
find a watch or other accessory more appealing. </LI>

<LI>At the other end of the transaction, computerised support systems would
offer the chance of huge fraud reduction across many public and private
businesses, and vastly better statistics on usage for service providers.</LI>

<LI>As well as identification, a secure intelligent token could if the
bearer wished carry electronic cash and domains of government and public-service
information such as driver, medical, tax or benefit records. </LI>

<LI>The outward branding on the identification device should be a matter
for consumer choice, just as it is already with credit cards. The brands
the Home Office offers - union and EU flags - appeal to some and offend
others. Other brands might be more neutral: those of banks, supermarkets
or local libraries. So-called affinity credit cards offer further proof
of how particular brands appeal to certain groups. It is not hard to see
people being proud of the National Trust card, the Swatch passport or the
Virgin earring that does everything necessary to let them hire a car (proof
of identity, driving authority and payment) without giving their name.
It starts to be credible that they might pay 15, or more. </LI>
</UL>

<P>In summary, diversity gives brand appeal its strength, and rarity its
value. </P>

<P>There is a brand for everyone, young or old, rich or poor. Many of people's
favourite brands have little to do with government; yet this does not prevent
them being used to achieve unambiguous identification. </P>

<P>Diverse branding of an intelligent token that carries authorised government
data is a more acceptable approach. It achieves the same result as the
home secretary's announcement, with perhaps a higher probability of acceptance
of the scheme and a lower risk that otherwise mild-mannered libertarians
will take to the street and riot.</P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="75%"></P>

<H3>Smart Card Symposium</H3>

<P>To hear about and discuss smart cards, public services and individual
liberty, those with 300 handy might spend 28 October at a symposium
at the Cafe Royal in London. </P>

<P>The Civil Service College, together with the think-tank Demos, has booked
a strong team with Roger Freeman, the Minister responsible for the government's
imminent green paper on computerised government, industry and consumer
group speakers.</P>

<P>Journalists seeking accreditation to the event, which is partially under
Chatham House rules, should contact Geoff Merchant on 01344 634072.</P>

<P>William Heath, Kable Ltd. </P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">September 30, 1996</FONT></P>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000"></FONT>
<P>&copy; <A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd. 1996 </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

