</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]"></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="is_line.gif" HEIGHT=33 WIDTH=206> </P><BLOCKQUOTE><H3>Fall in for the electronic battlefield</H3><P>Avoiding casualties in warfare is no longer a matter of mere humanitybut one of information management, according to one of Britain's most seniorservicemen, Air Chief Marshall Sir John Willis, vice chief of the DefenceStaff. </P><P>Sir John came up with this novel concept at a confidential seminar tothe IT industry. <B><I>Signposts</I></B> has seen a copy of the proceedings.</P><P>He told the audience: &quot;The ubiquitous media ensure that (warfare)is reported in great detail on our television screens each night. We, themilitary, have therefore to be acutely aware of the political nature ofeverything we are doing, the presentational aspects of it and the mannerin which information can be used and misused to affect the conduct of operations.</P><P>This leads to the need for the surgical application of force and toan emphasis on minimising casualties both as an act of humanity and asan act of information management. </P><P>This was what the audience wanted to hear. Surgical application meansputting much more computing power into battlefield weapons and communications.</P><P>For a start, today's soldier needs to identify his enemy, who no longerconveniently wears a different coloured jacket. &quot;The question whereis the enemy and how do I know when I am looking at him? will be an increasinglyimportant one and again, one which requires a comprehensive intelligenceand information network to attempt to answer, Sir John said. </P><P>Modern wars also tend to change their characters more quickly than theslogging campaigns of old: information systems must also be able to copewith a quick change from low intensity (peacekeeping) to 'high intensity'(all-out battle) operations. These systems will have to be cost effectiveand secure. The buzzphrase is battlefield management. </P><H4>Space command</H4><P>One indication of the importance of IT today: the Royal Signals has1,350 troops in former Yugoslavia, more than 10 per cent of the UK's entirecommitment to the NATO implementation force, IFOR. They communicate mainlythrough the Ptarmigan &quot;battlefield radiophone&quot; network designedby Plessey in the early 1980s. </P><P>This in turn is linked to satellite terminals. The smallest squad, intheory, is in contact with HQ. </P><P>Enhancing these links to provide a battlefield management system isa big opportunity for the computer and telecommunications industry. Overall,the Ministry of Defence plans to spend more than 7 billion on integratedcommand systems over the next 10 years. </P><P>Apart from battlefield communications, this may involve supporting atri-service agency to handle pay. </P><P>Much of the data traffic will travel via space. The Gulf War of 1991used 500 times as much satellite capacity as the Falklands War in 1982.In mountainous Bosnia, demand for small satellite receivers was so greatthat the Army had to equip some units with commercial units, communicatingvia Inmarsat satellites. </P><P>Although relying on American satellites for navigation and surveillance,the British armed forces are determined to keep an indendent network ofcommunications satellites. </P><P>The MoD operates three Skynet 4 satellites, in geostationary orbit 36,000kilometres above the earth. They cover the world from California to theFar East, relaying secure speech and data messages to land and mobile forces.In 1998-99, they will be replaced by three new Skynet craft, are now underconstruction. A Skynet 5 system for the next century is being designed.</P><P>&quot;We are entering an era of information warfare,&quot; concludedDr Roger Jude, director strategy and programme support, defence ICS strategy.Such wars will be fought in the sense of disrupting enemy electronic communicationsand also in the sense that the winning side will use information... asan asset equal in importance to equipment and materiel. An integrated communicationsinfrastructure, and also digitisation of the whole battlefield, are assuminga very high importance. </P><P>The new command chain is &quot;sensor to shooter&quot; -- a theatrecommander, acting from electronic intelligence (ELINT) and images fromremote sensors, calls up a Tomahawk cruise missile attack from a submarine.However this will work only if different services use the same command,digital mapping and weapons systems programs. The British and US armiesare both working on putting command information systems (CIS) into tanks,and eventually to make &quot;every soldier a data platform&quot;. </P><P>Such a concept is a big challenge to military traditions. As a modern-dayKipling might write:</P><P><I>Its Tommy this and Tommy that, </I></P><P><I>And cut it out, you creep, </I></P><P><I>But its noble band of cyber-warriors </I></P><P><I>When the modems start to cheep. </I></P><pre></pre>Michael Cross, Editor, <B><I>Signposts to Government</I></B></P><P>September 30th 1996</P><P>&copy; <A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd. 1996</P></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
