<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE></TITLE>   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000"><P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><H3>Queen's speech: data cops and cop-outs</H3></P>

<P>As Signposts to Government predicted, one of the bills announced in the Queen's speech on
October 23 includes a massive data-matching exercise to catch benefit fraudsters. The Fraud
Bill will allow officials to cross-check records at the Department of Social Security with those
held by the Inland Revenue and Customs & Excise.  It will involve the biggest data-matching
programme ever carried out in Britain.</P>

<P>It now seems the measures go even further than expected. The Financial Times reported on
October 25 that the bill will allow inspectors to raid the premises of local authorities.  The
target is housing benefit, seen as one of the largest burdens on the annual 90 billion social security 
budget.</P>

<P>The Data Protection Registrar is hosting a conference on data-matching on December 6.
Should be interesting.</P>

<P>Meanwhile, the Queen's speech confirmed that the Government has dropped the idea of
identity cards as too hot to handle.  There was no mention of any moves to bring into law the
measures proposed by the Home Office in August.  These were condemned by everyone from
the Data Protection Registrar to Tory Euro-sceptics to the IT industry.</P>

<P>See issues: <A HREF="sp13.9card.html">Howard's ID card.</A></P>

<P>October 25, 1996</P>

<P>Signposts to Government &copy;<A HREF="../kable/fr.index.html"> Kable</A> Ltd, 1996</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
