<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<P><IMG SRC="nb_line.gif" HEIGHT=39 WIDTH=212> </P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Identity cards - will the numbers add up?</H3>

<P>The British government's planned national identity card will need a
new national database of citizens if it is going to work, research by Signposts
can reveal. This is because existing systems of national identity numbers
are either inadequate or already compromised. </P>

<P>The plans for a voluntary national identity card have already caused
huge political controversy. In public, the main row was over the use of
the national flag (the Union Flag) alongside the European Union's 15-star
emblem. Behind the scenes, however, lurk more complex technical issues.
Resolving them will require setting up new government information systems
and most likely a new national ID number.</P>

<P>Three types of card are planned.</P>

<P>1) Photo driving licence.</P>

<P>2) National ID card for non-drivers.</P>

<P>3) Combination ID card and driving licence, in an agreed format for
use as a travel document throughout the European Union.</P>

<P>The main problem is checking eligibility. Unlike several Continental
and Scandinavian countries, there is no national identity numbering system
in Britain. </P>

<P>The implications for data-matching will interest the Data Protection
Registrar. In her 1996 annual report, she commented: </P>

<P>&quot;There are acknowledged limitatons and deficiencies in official
documentation and government databases. Whether an authoritative, accurate
and effective identity card scheme could be developed from the existing
documentation and databases is open to question.&quot;</P>

<P>All candidates for source databases are flawed.</P>

<P>1) <B>National insurance number.</B> Advantage: a relatively recent,
well- maintained number. Drawback: many living individuals (mainly elderly
women) have never been issued a number. Meanwhile, some have been issued
to foreign nationals. </P>

<P>2) <B>Passport office number.</B> Advantage: issued only after check
on eligibility through citizenship. Drawback: the existence of 'Jackal'
passports (named after the Frederick Forsyth novel which explained the
procedure) issued in the name of dead individuals. </P>

<P>3) <B>NHS number.</B> Advantage: the NHS in England and Wales is currently
issuing new 10-digit numbers to every patient on its register (in a similar
format to the Scottish number). If the project succeeds, it is likely to
achieve the most comprehensive and robust national ID number. Disadvantage:
to curb worries about confidentiality of medical records, the government
has repeatedly ruled out its use outside the NHS. The government has already
decided that the new NHS number will not appear on birth certificates.
</P>

<P>4) The existing <B>driver number</B> from the Driver and Vehicle Licensing
Agency's database is unsuitable because it is issued without verification
apart, presumably, from random and targeted checks to detect fraudulent
applications. No citizenship qualification is involved. </P>

<P>5) <B>Birth certificates.</B> These carry no proof that the individual
named is still alive.</P>

<P>The Home Office's solution is for the government to use the DVLA database,
cross-checked with the passport office. But will this be feasible? Turn
to <A HREF="../issues/fr.index.html">Issues</A> in <B><I>Signposts to Government</I></B>
for Sheila Beck's comment: The National Identity Card - a lost opportnity.
</P>

<P>The debate is hotting up on other web sites.</P>

<P>Further information on the Home Office's Web site: <A HREF="http://www.coi.gov.uk/coi/depts/GHO/GHO.html">http://www.coi.gov.uk/coi/depts/GHO/GHO.html</A>
But don't expect it to tell the whole story. For example, its list of 'what
happens in other countries' lists 14 states all but three of which have
identity cards, but omits Ireland, Australia the USA and Japan which do
not.</P>

<P>For a critical view, check out Privacy International's site: <A HREF="http://www.privacy.org/pi/">http://www.privacy.org/pi/</A>
and Charter 88: <A HREF="http://gnew.gn.apc.org/charter88/online/pubs/idcards.html">http://gnew.gn.apc.org/charter88/online/pubs/idcards.html</A></P>

<P>Relavent information can also be found with the <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/dpr/dprhome.htm">Data
Protection Registrar</A>.</P>

<P>September 30, 1996</P>

<PRE>
</PRE>

<P>&copy; <A HREF="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</A> Ltd. 1996 </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

