<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>The National Police IS Strategy -- will it happen?</H3>

<P>The national police IS/IT strategy, launched in 1994, is attempting
to manage the specification of police IT systems centrally, to cut costs
and speed up the exchange of informaton between police forces. Five applications
are top priority: crime reporting, custody, case-processing, command and
control and management information. In all there are 19 projects. </P>

<P>However the strategy's director, Mike Curtis has revealed that some
are slipping behind schedule. </P>

<P>He told the 1996 Association of Chief Police Officers conference that:</P>

<UL>
<LI>The vehicle procedures/fixed penalty office system was due to go live
in July. According to a spokesman for its supplier, MDIS, the testing phase
has found &quot;one or two small gaps in the requirement that need to be
plugged&quot;. The cost of this is being shared by MDIS and the lead force,
Leicestershire Constabulary. One other force has already contracted to
take the system and MDIS hopes to have six to eight forces signed up by
the end of the year.</LI>

<LI>The command and control project is also having its share of difficulties.
The scoping study stage has not yet been completed; there have been problems
in trying to get agreement on the projectis boundaries. The origianl plan
was that the user specification would be ready in September and the pilot
system would go live in the last quarter of 1998. Although the project
is running more than six months behind schedule, revised dates have yet
to been confirmed. </LI>
</UL>

<P>The six forces assisting the lead force (the Metropolitan Police) have
indicated that 1998 is a critical date for them. It is understood that
one or two chief constables have said that they need the system by then
or &quot;they walk away from it&quot;.</P>

<P>Meanwhile, press reports say that the Home Office is under pressure
from senior police technology experts to abandon its criminal intelligence
computer Holmes 2 because the introduction of the NSPIS standardised corporate
database will make it unnecessary.</P>

<P>Further reading: Police Market Profile, Kable 1995 </P>

<P>September 30, 1996</P>
<pre>


</pre>
&copy; <a href="../credits/fr.index.html">Kable</a> Ltd. 1996</BLOCKQUOTE>

