<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Our View of the Local Government Scene</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#808000" vlink="#800080" alink="#00FF00">
<p><a href="local.htm"><img src="images/lgovt.gif" alt="Local Government" align=bottom border=0 width=415 height=66></a></p>
<h3><img src="images/mayor1.gif" alt="Mayor" align=absmiddle width=52 height=150><font size=4><strong>OUR VIEW OF THE SCENE</strong></font></h3>
<p>The environment for the provision of public services presents significant challenges for local government and its suppliers.</p>
<p>Demand for service continues to rise while the resources for their provision are under constant pressure. </p>
<p>These conflicting aims can lead to a negative perception of local government by the public, a perception which is frequently undeserved.</p>
<p>Nevertheless, for historical reasons many local government organisations suffer from repetition of work, ineffective approvals processes and excess amounts of 
paperwork leading to errors and inefficiencies. </p>
<p>The need to provide value for money stimulates review of efficiency and effectiveness and moves the focus of attention back to the core activity. </p>
<p>&#160;Management responds to these demands in several ways:</p>
<ul>
<li>New internal markets spread awareness of financial discipline through the service delivery chain<br>
</li>
<li>Within local councils the autonomy of agency frameworks, new operational structures are developed to enhance customer service and strengthen financial 
management<br>
</li>
<li>The Compulsory Competitive Tendering (CCT) legislation introduces new supplier relationships and contractual regimes. In this environment, organisations 
require innovative solutions to meet their goals</li>
</ul>
<p>EDS contributes to this re-shaping process in partnership with local government organisations.</p>
<hr>
<ul>
