<html>

<head>
<title>Brent Council - Revenue and Benefits</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#808000" vlink="#800080" alink="#00FF00">
<p><a href="local.htm"><img src="images/lgovt.gif" alt="Local Government" align=bottom border=0 width=415 height=66></a></p>
<p><img src="images/mayor1.gif" alt="Mayor" align=absmiddle width=52 height=150><font size=4><strong>LONDON BOROUGH OF BRENT </strong></font><strong>Revenue and Benefit Service</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>EDS SAVES BRENT &#163;1 MILLION PER YEAR</strong></p>
<p>In May 1995, EDS signed an eight-year process management contract with Brent Council. It is the largest outsourcing agreement of its kind in UK local 
government. Under the deal, EDS has taken over all aspects of the Council&#146;s Revenue and Benefits service. </p>
<p>Our responsibilities include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Revenue collection</li>
<li>Benefits payments</li>
<li>Customer service</li>
<li>Cashiers</li>
<li>Operation of the IT infrastructure</li>
</ul>
<p>EDS was the unanimous choice of the all party committee. By selecting EDS, the Council choose a partner who has the skills and resources to deliver &#163;1 million of 
savings per annum. </p>
<p>The project began with a Business Process Re-engineering (BPR) exercise. The BPR consisted of a radical review of the existing business functions performed by 
all staff. By optimising the business processes, restructuring the organisation and supporting all changes with appropriate information technology, we are now 
transforming the service at all levels. The changes are taking place step by step and continuing over the life of the contract.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.brent.gov.uk/"><strong><img src="images/!brentep.gif" alt="Brent Council Logo" align=left border=0 hspace=0 width=142 height=137></strong></a>One key objective has been to ensure a smooth continuity of service. This was particularly vital during the early days of the project. The 
transition occurred with great efficiency due largely to the commitment and partnership between Brent and EDS staff. Two hundred and fifty 
Council staff transferred to EDS in the process in co-operation with their union. They moved over to EDS under TUPE conditions.</p>
<p>The BPR led the way to substantial new investment in training, technology and infrastructure. These have proved to be the vital tools in 
improving the quality of services and greater satisfaction for both Brent customers and staff.</p>
<p>EDS was able to exploit its internal expertise in many aspects of the project. We used our management consultants to foster the process of 
change. Meanwhile our in-house software developers designed the Viewstar imaging and workflow system. Considerable savings in the overall cost of the project 
were assisted by our world-wide purchasing power and ability to take advantage of economies of scale.</p>
<p>Brent can now boast a market- leading Revenues and Benefits Service, which utilises state of the art technology . Their office is now largely &#145;paperless&#146; and staff 
have changed the way the work beyond recognition. Most of the mundane repetitive tasks have been eliminated by the implementation of the imaging and workflow 
system. Access to their mainframe databases have been customised to make it as easy as possible to use. In all, the staff at Brent are now better able to focus on 
what matters most, the needs of the 100,000 people of the Borough of Brent.</p>
<p>Brent&#146;s confidence in EDS grows with each passing week in a variety of ways. But the Council&#146;s greatest vote of confidence came when it awarded EDS a further 
contract to take over their National Non-Domestic Rates business.</p>
<p>The main beneficiaries of the Brent-EDS outsourcing arrangement are our customers. They include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Brent Council &#150; commissioned the service and ultimately have responsibility for ensuring a quality service is provided</li>
<li>The DSS &#150; rely heavily upon EDS Brent for information</li>
<li>Housing Associations &#150; have many tenants in Brent on Housing Benefits</li>
<li>Advice Agencies &#150; such organisations as the CAB, for example, rely on EDS Brent to supply them with information about their clients&#146; claims</li>
<li>Brent Council Housing Service &#150; rely on EDS to supply a significant proportion of their rental income</li>
<li>Brent Residents &#150; claiming benefits and paying Council Tax</li>
<li>The Rent Officer Service &#150; requires information from EDS Brent</li>
</ul>
<hr>
