<html>

<head>
<title>Parking Committee for London</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#808000" vlink="#800080" alink="#00FF00">
<p><a href="local.htm"><img src="images/lgovt.gif" alt="Local Government" align=bottom border=0 width=415 height=66></a></p>
<h3><img src="images/mayor1.gif" alt="Mayor" align=absmiddle width=52 height=150><font size=4><strong>PARKING COMMITTEE FOR LONDON (PCfL)</strong></font></h3>
<p><strong>EDS HELPS CLEAR THE DOUBLE YELLOW LINES</strong></p>
<p>The Parking Committee for London (PCfL) is a representative body of London Boroughs established under the terms of the 1991 Road Traffic Act. Its primary 
responsibilities are to establish and implement a uniform parking policy for London. </p>
<p>In addition, the Committee is charged with providing an appeals adjudication service and co-ordinating the handover of enforcement powers from the Metropolitan 
Police to the Boroughs.</p>
<p>EDS won a five and a half year agreement to provide comprehensive IT and management services. Our main activities include an information management system 
and a public information service to support the Boroughs in their parking enforcement activities.</p>
<p>One of the most challenging aspects of this project is the communication s requirements. We are providing a series of links to connect each of the 33 disparate 
Borough systems to PCfL. Further links to PCfL include: the DVLA in Swansea, the Parking Enforcement Centre in Cardiff and the Foreign and Commonwealth 
Office .</p>
<p>When complete, these connection will provide an efficient method of passing information between all the parties involved in parking enforcement in London. </p>
<p>The PCfL handles an estimated 100,000 appeals per year. We are suing Document imaging technologies to support the Appeal Service. We also operate a 
24-hour telephone service to provide drivers with information on vehicles which have been clamped or towed away.</p>
