<html>

<head>
<title>Command support system</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#808000" vlink="#800080" alink="#00FF00">
<p><a href="defence.htm"><img src="images/defentx.gif" alt="Defence" align=bottom border=0 width=186 height=65></a></p>
<h3><img src="images/defence.gif" alt="Planes, tank and missile" align=absmiddle width=101 height=150><strong>COMMAND SUPPORT SYSTEM (CSS)</strong></h3>
<p><strong>CSS WILL HELP RN DEPLOY THE RIGHT FORCES TO THE RIGHT PLACE AT THE RIGHT TIME</strong></p>
<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) has awarded EDS a contract to develop a new information system which will revolutionise the Royal Navy&#146;s operational 
command capability at sea. Users will, for the first time, be able to exchange strategic information effectively, and produce and update plans and operation orders 
using a single system. </p>
<p>The new Command Support System (CSS) will enable the Royal Navy (RN) to apply modern IT to achieve a significant improvement in the effectiveness of 
maritime and amphibious operations. The multi-million pound contract includes hardware and software and integration with the RN communications network. CSS 
will be fitted to major and minor warships, including submarines, throughout the Fleet over an eight year period.</p>
<p>CSS will provide a suite of automated processing and display tools, comprehensive planning and decision aids, a communications network management system to 
enable effective ship-shore and ship-ship exchange, and all of the enabling hardware, software and support. Interfaces will be provided to other defence and allied 
information systems, facilitating improved Army, Navy and Air Force and political-military information exchange within joint and allied operations. A key 
component of the system is the Nauticus track management software, produced by INRI UK, which will manage all of the geographic and location data.</p>
<p>Mr M. Stapley, MOD project manager, said &#147;CSS provides a significant extension to command support systems afloat, and will be installed in a wide range of 
ships and shore HQs of the Royal Navy. It will greatly improve the timeliness of information available to maritime command, speeding up decision making, planning 
and dissemination.&#148;</p>
<p>The effectiveness of command at sea is being continuously improved by the growth in available data and global telecommunications. The EDS solution provides an 
open system architecture which offers an evolutionary system. This will enable all maritime commanders to take advantage of the rapid expansion of data from 
global surveillance devices, together with advances in commercial communications and information technology.</p>
<p>The contract award reflects EDS&#146; capabilities in the Naval sector, which the company is also applying to non-operational systems including the Naval Logistics 
Information System UPKEEP. The ability of EDS to develop effective operational systems rapidly was demonstrated recently with the timely initial deliveries of 
Pilot JOCS (Joint Operations Command System). All of these deploy modern, commercial off the shelf technology (COTS) to enable MOD to improve its conduct 
of operations. Using many common components, CSS is compatible with Pilot JOCS, both of which support emerging common operating environment standards 
designed to minimise costs, implementation risks and timescales.</p>
<p>Roger Gilbert, Managing Director of EDS Defence Division, said, &#147;CSS is a fine example of what EDS offers, allowing customers to capitalise on the abundance of 
data by converting this into useful information which can then be applied to potent effect. We are fully committed to this vital programme for the Royal Navy. The 
award endorses our position as the market leader in the design, supply and support of low risk evolutionary systems and reflects our understanding of today&#146;s 
challenging needs.&#148;</p>
<p>The UK design team developing CSS will be based at EDS&#146; UK Defence headquarters in Hook, Hampshire. The division has over 900 UK staff based at 7 
offices and covers the full spectrum of business and IT services, identifying and delivering value through consultancy, systems development, systems integration, 
systems management and business process management.</p>
<hr>
