<html>

<head>
<title>Naval Logistics Information System - UPKEEP</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#808000" vlink="#800080" alink="#00FF00">
<p><a href="defence.htm"><img src="images/defentx.gif" alt="Defence" align=bottom border=0 width=186 height=65></a></p>
<h3><img src="images/defence.gif" alt="Planes, tank and missile" align=absmiddle width=101 height=150><strong>NAVAL LOGISTICS INFORMATION SYSTEM &#150; UPKEEP</strong></h3>
<p>The Naval Logistics Information System UPKEEP is a fully integrated engineering and supply management system for the Royal Navy that will be used to support 
all the activities involved in maintaining the Fleet. Designed to enable the Naval Support Command to provide better service, more effectively and at less cost, by 
the end of 1999 UPKEEP will support over 12,000 users at more than 150 sites afloat and ashore around the world.</p>
<p>More than a new IT system, the full benefits, and the preservation of front line capability within budget constraints, come from improved business processes and 
working practices, many of which represent accepted best practice in industry. Benefits will accrue from global visibility of stocks, through-life monitoring and 
planning, and improved spares requirements forecasting based on better use of improved information.</p>
<p>UPKEEP will enable all the distinct organisations involved in maintaining ships, submarines, aircraft and auxiliaries, to initiate and control activity in an environment 
of cost visibility and shared information.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Developed and rolled out in parallel with emerging standards for Integrated Logistics Support (ILS), UPKEEP maximises use of commercially 
available products to ensure lower through-life costs, reduced integration risks and ease of training and use.</p>
<p>Accurate, up-to-date information available to all engaged in the support process is essential in order for the Royal Navy to meet its world-wide 
commitments with improved efficiency. UPKEEP will provide this common information source along with improved procedures, to ensure 
continued provision of a capable, operational Fleet. </p>
</blockquote>
<p>UPKEEP is the largest and most significant system in the Naval Logistic Information System Strategy (NLISS). It will provide a single system of streamlined and 
rationalised procedures that maintains a single repository of engineering and supply data, to improve Naval logistics.</p>
<p>The system replaces numerous separate and uncoordinated information systems, designed to make the management of data easier and to greatly improve the 
co-ordination of activities. Underpinned by a realistic plan, EDS&#146; transition from legacy systems addresses security, data cleanliness and data migration issues. A full 
management of change programme ensures maximised business benefit whilst minimising disruption</p>
<p>UPKEEP will help the Navy significantly to reduce costs. Ensuring the visibility of stocks world-wide enables better purchasing decisions to be made and 
stockholding reduced. Improved forecasting of spares will save time and money by getting their procurement and maintenance right first time.</p>
<p>Providing through life planning, UPKEEP will help the NSC to deliver the highest level of service with available resources. Redesigns based on in-service 
experience will make sure that the through life cost of all equipment is taken into account when it is bought. To aid this UPKEEP will improve the ease of collecting 
availability, reliability and maintainability (AR&amp;M) data.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>By optimising maintenance, updating and repair services, and the associated spares purchasing, supply and accounting, UPKEEP will help 
engineering and supply departments ashore and afloat keep the Fleet maintained.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
