<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Holiday Travel To Equal 1995's Record High, Says AAA</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="buckleupkidsinthebacka.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaacoolwebsites.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Holiday Travel To Equal 1995's Record High, Says AAA</h1></center>
MIAMI, Dec. 11, 1996 --  An estimated 38.5 million Americans will travel  100 miles or more from home during this Christmas-New Year's holiday -- a level that equals 1995's record-setting performance, according to AAA.
<p>
"Matching last year's record travel volume is even more impressive  when you consider that both holidays fall on Wednesday this year -- limiting holiday getaways for many Americans," said Graeme Clarke, senior vice president, AAA Products & Services. 
<p>
Last year, Christmas and New Year's fell on Monday and travel   increased a healthy 5 percent compared to 36.5 million in 1994.
<p>
During this Christmas-New Year's holiday, AAA estimates 31.6 million people will travel by automobile, light truck or recreational vehicle, down 1 percent compared to 1995's record performance of 32 million.
<p>
Holiday travel by airplane, bus, rail or ship is expected to jump 6 percent -- to 6.9 million compared to 6.5 million last year.  
<p>
The greatest number of auto travelers will originate in the West, with 8.4 million people on the roads and in the Southeast with 7.5 million.  Other regional projections are: Great Lakes and Midwest, both 5.5 million; and Northeast, 4.7 million.
<p>
Holiday travelers expect to visit the following destinations during the Christmas-New Year's holiday:  city, 43 percent; town/rural areas, 27 percent; ocean/beach, 14 percent; mountain, 9 percent; lake, 2 percent; state/national park, 2 percent; theme/amusement park, 1 percent; other, 1 percent; and don't know, 1 percent.
<p>
More than half of the holiday travelers -- 56 percent -- will stay overnight with family or friends, while 31 percent will stay at a hotel or motel.  Other planned accommodations include:  cabin or condo, 5 percent; camper/trailer/ RV/tent, 2 percent; boat/ship, 1 percent; other, 1 percent.  Four percent didn't know or didn't expect to stay overnight.
<p>
AAA's holiday travel projections are based on a national travel survey of 1,500 adults conducted the Travel Industry Association, which conducts special research for AAA.
<p>


<center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="buckleupkidsinthebacka.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaacoolwebsites.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><hr></center><img align="left" width=75 height=56 src="aaalogosmall.gif"><h6>&#169; Unless otherwise specified, all content within the AAA Online site is the property of the American Automobile Association, which reserves all copyrights. Copyright AAA 1996. This page was last updated on Thursday, January 2, 1997 at 6:49 PM. The webmaster for this site is <a href="mailto:webmaster@aaa.com">webmaster@aaa.com</a>. </h6>
