<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Driving Costs Up .7 Cent In 2nd Quarter,  AAA Says</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaaandnapaofferpartsprogr.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="texasstudentswinfordaaana.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Driving Costs Up .7 Cent In 2nd Quarter,  AAA Says</h1></center>
ORLANDO, Fla., July 15 -- Higher second-quarter gasoline prices have pushed up
the cost of owning and operating a new car by .7 cent since the end of March,
according to the American Automobile Association.
<p>
Motorists now spend an average of 43.4 cents per mile in vehicle-related costs. 
The increase brings the average yearly vehicle expenditure to $6,510, based on
15,000 miles of driving.
<p>
Driving costs during the first quarter were up .1 cent from AAA's initial 1996
driving cost figure of 42.6 cents per mile.  
<p>
AAA's study of driving costs is updated quarterly from computations made by
Runzheimer International of Rochester, Wis.  The management consulting firm
specializes in transportation, travel and living costs.
<p>
The increase in the driving cost is attributable to a 12.3 cent per gallon rise
in gasoline prices during the second quarter, AAA said. 
<p>
The average per-mile cost is determined by combining operating and fixed costs. 
During the second quarter of this year, motorists spent an average of 10.4 cents
per mile on operating costs such as gasoline, oil, tires and maintenance, up .7
cent from March.  Fixed costs, including insurance, depreciation, registration,
taxes and financing, averaged $13.55 per day, down 1 cent from March.
<p>
AAA's cost estimates are based on a composite national average of three
domestically built cars:  a subcompact Ford Escort LX, a mid-size Ford Taurus GL
and a full-size Chevrolet Caprice Classic.  
<p>
New England was the most expensive region to own and operate a car in the second
quarter, with total costs of 45.3 cents per mile.  Midwest motorist had the
lowest costs, paying 41.9 cents per mile.
<p>
Other regional costs were:  Mid-Atlantic, 44.2 cents; West, 44.2 cents;
Southwest, 43.4 cents; Great Lakes, 42.6 cents; and  Southeast, 42.1 cents.
<p>
