<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Texas Students Win Ford/AAA National Auto Repair Championship</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="drivingcostsup7centin2n.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="threesafetypatrollershonor.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Texas Students Win Ford/AAA National Auto Repair Championship</h1></center>
<p>
WASHINGTON, D.C., June 17 -- Combining speed and accuracy to repair a
deliberately "bugged" vehicle, a two-student team from Texas won the 1996
Ford/AAA STUDENT AUTO SKILLS National Quality Care Challenge -- a showdown of
the nation's top high school auto technicians.
<p>
Joshua Garrison, 18 and Josh Lamb, 19, from North Lamar High School in Paris,
Texas, competed against teams from each of the other 49 states.  Their
instructor is Bo Bolton.
<p>
"Joshua and Josh represent the kind of technicians needed to service today's
complex automobiles," said James Dunst, national contest manager.  "They not
only have mechanical ability, but they also are skilled in advanced computer
diagnostics."
<p>
Garrison and Lamb will share $41,000 in scholarships and prizes.  Bolton earned
the AAA Approved Auto Repair Quality Teacher Award and an expense-paid trip to
Walt Disney World.
<p>
The STUDENT AUTO SKILLS contest is held to encourage students to pursue careers
in automotive service and is jointly sponsored by the American Automobile
Association and Ford Motor Co.
<p>
Teams placing second through 10th received scholarship awards scaled from
$23,500 to $1,200 per team.  Second place went to Shannon Rowe, and John
Feiteira,IV, both 17, of Maui High School in Kahului, Hawaii.  Third place went
to Max Osmanski, 18, and Russell Brunette, 19, of Crivitz High School in
Crivitz, Wisconsin.
<p>
Each contestant took a written test Sunday, June 16, before opening their tool
boxes for Monday's competition.  The written test accounted for 40 percent of
each team's score.  Speed and accuracy in the "hands-on" contest accounted for
60 percent.
<p>
Approximately 6,000 students entered this year's AUTO SKILLS contest at the
state level.  Nearly $3 million in scholarships and prizes are being awarded.

