<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Three Safety Patrollers Honored for Saving Lives</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="texasstudentswinfordaaana.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="teenwinstrafficsafetyposte.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Three Safety Patrollers Honored for Saving Lives</h1></center>
<p>
WASHINGTON, D.C.,  May 21, 1996 -- Courageous action and quick thinking by
three school safety patrollers saved the lives of classmates in Florida,
Pennsylvania and Virginia and earned the young heroes the 1996 AAA School
Safety Patrol Lifesaving Medal, the American Automobile Association announced
today.
<p>
In a ceremony at the Committee Room of the Senate Rules Committee in
Washington, D.C., Sen. John W. Warner presented the patrol members with their
medals.  In addition to chairing the Senate Rules Committee, the senator is
chairman of the Transportation and Infrastructure Subcommittee of the
Environment and Public Works Committee.<p>

"The stories of courage demonstrated by these three youths are inspirational
to all Americans," Warner said.  "The job of safety patrol represents an
initial step in leadership and service to others.  These students risked
their own safety to save another person's life.  They are most deserving of
these AAA Lifesaving Medals, and I join their families, friends and
classmates in saying thank you and God bless you."
<p>
The three patrol members honored today were:
Shane Lee, 11, of Cherry Run Elementary, Burke, Va., who was involved in one
of the most unusual rescues in the history of the program.  Unbeknown to the
school bus driver, a six-year-old had lain down in front of the right front
tire. Hearing the sound of the air brakes being released, Shane turned to
wave goodbye to friends still on the bus and spotted legs lying in the street
in front of the wheels.  Shane ran to the bus, grabbed the youngster and
pulled him away just as the bus moved forward.
<p>
Esther Daniel, 11, of Trapnell Elementary School, Plant City, Fla., who
chased after a distraught five-year-old and caught her just before she
reached the wheels of a departing school bus.<p>

William D. Mace, 10, of Borland Manor Elementary School, Canonsburg, Pa., who
raced after a boy who had run into the path of an oncoming car and dragged
him to safety.
<p>
These courageous safety patrol members join the ranks of 325 others in 31
states and the District of Columbia who have been awarded the AAA Lifesaving
Medal since its inception in 1949.<p>
AAA has sponsored school safety patrols for 76 years. The safety patrol is an organization of boys and girls selected from upper-elementary and junior-high school levels to help classmates travel
safely to and from school. There are more than 500,000 patrol members
nationwide in 50,000 schools.  Educators regard the patrol movement as an
excellent safety educational device, as well as a means for developing
character and leadership.
<p>



