<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Teen Wins Traffic Safety Poster Award for Second Time</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="threesafetypatrollershonor.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaaremovestownfromlistof.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Teen Wins Traffic Safety Poster Award for Second Time</h1></center>
<p>
ORLANDO, Fla., May 15, 1996 -- For the first time in the 52-year history of
the AAA National School Traffic Safety Poster Program, the same student has
repeated as a Grand Award winner, according to the American Automobile
Association.
<p>
Seventeen-year-old Michael Barbano, a senior at Woodland High School,
Woodland, Calif., was named the Grand Award winner at the senior-high level
for the second year in a row.  Chosen from among more than 70,000 entries,
Barbano's poster depicts the slogan "Know Your Limits" and shows a car
crashing through a 55 mile-per-hour speed limit sign.
<p>
When he was a junior in high school, Barbano submitted a poster that was
picked from more than 74,000 entries for the Grand Award.  It illustrated the
slogan "Traffic signs and signals are for everyone."
<p>
Barbano, who will be attending San Francisco State University and hopes for
an eventual career in cinema and special effects, said he was surprised at
being selected a repeat winner.  "I had mixed feelings about the poster," he
said.  "At times I felt good about it, other times a little 'iffy.'"
<p>
"AAA has judged more than 1.5 million posters over the years and has never
had a student win top honors a second time," said Tom Culpepper, managing
director of AAA Traffic Safety & Engineering.  "This young man's achievement
is truly remarkable."
<p>
Each year the AAA Poster Program chooses four Grand Award winners o one at
each educational level: primary, elementary, junior and senior high school.
<p>
The Grand Award winner at the elementary level is Tobie Fishman, age 11, a
fifth grade student at Beth Jacob of Boro Park school in Brooklyn, N.Y.
<p>
The two remaining AAA Grand Award winners are sisters.
<p>
At the primary level: Mariah Hunger, age 6, a kindergartner at Moores Hill
School, Moores Hill, Ind.
<p>
At the junior high school level:  Lindsay Hunger, age 13, an 8th grader at
Moores Hill School, Moores Hill, Ind.
<p>
More than $17,000 in U.S. Savings Bonds is distributed as 154 prizes in 40
traffic safety slogan categories.
<p>
"The purpose of the AAA poster program is to help young people learn how to
behave safely when they interact with traffic," said Culpepper.  "This
knowledge is critical because traffic crashes are the leading cause of death
up to age 15."
<p>
Final judging of posters is performed by a National Board of Judges o a panel
of prominent individuals in the fields of education, art and traffic safety.
<p>
AAA reproduces many of the posters to teach other children about basic
pedestrian, bicycle, safety belt, alcohol, motorcycle helmet and driving
safety.  AAA clubs annually distribute more than six million reproductions of
the winning posters in AAA traffic safety educational materials and other
publications.
<p>
AAA is a not-for-profit federation of 112 motor clubs with more than 1,000
offices providing 38 million members in the United States and Canada with
travel, insurance, financial and auto-related services.
<p>

<p>


