<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Young Bicyclists Should Be Required to Wear Helmets, Says AAA</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaaremovestownfromlistof.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaaurgesstatestobecautiou.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Young Bicyclists Should Be Required to Wear Helmets, Says AAA</h1></center>
<p>
SAN FRANCISCO, May 1 -- All bicyclists under 18-years-old should be required
by law to wear a helmet, according to the American Automobile Association.
<p>
Delegates to AAA's 93rd annual meeting here called on states to adopt bicycle
helmet laws to protect younger operators and passengers.
<p>
Currently, 13 states have laws applying to young bicyclists.  Some local
ordinances also mandate helmet use.
<p>
Helmet use reduces the risk of serious head or brain injuries by 85 percent,
yet only 20 percent of bicyclists voluntarily wear helmets, according to AAA.
<p>
"Wearing a helmet is the single most important thing a bicyclist can do to
protect themselves," said James L. Kolstad, vice president of AAA Public and
Government Relations.  "By requiring helmet use by those under 18-years-old,
we can establish an important safety habit that will continue for life."
<p>


