<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Urges States to Pass Laws Aimed at Reducing Drunk Driving</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaaurgesstatestobecautiou.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaareceivesrecordnumberof.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Urges States to Pass Laws Aimed at Reducing Drunk Driving</h1></center>
<p>
SAN FRANCISCO, May 1, 1996 -- The American Automobile Association today
adopted national policies urging states to prohibit the possession of open
containers of alcoholic beverages in private passenger vehicles and trucks
and calling for blood alcohol testing for all adult pedestrian fatalities.
<p>
Delegates and auto club officials at AAA's 93rd annual meeting here asked the
22 states without "open container" laws to move swiftly in the interest of
public safety.
<p>
"Even low levels of alcohol affect driving ability," said James L. Kolstad,
vice president of AAA Public and Government Relations.  "Laws prohibiting
open containers can help keep even minimally impaired drivers off the road."
<p>
Blood alcohol levels of just .02 percent increase crash likelihood, with the
probability of a crash increasing significantly at .05 percent, AAA pointed
out.
<p>
AAA also called for an increased emphasis on efforts to combat the dangers of
pedestrians under the influence of alcohol.  The delegates approved a policy
advocating blood alcohol testing of all adult pedestrian fatalities.
<p>
The federal government estimates that up to 40 percent of all pedestrian
fatalities involve alcohol use by the pedestrian, but AAA says additional
information on the problem is needed.
<p>
"Many communities do not consistently test blood alcohol levels of pedestrian
fatalities," said Kolstad.  "Communities need this information to allocate
funds and effectively plan countermeasures."
<p>


