<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Receives Record Number of ERS Calls</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaaurgesstatestopasslaws.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="travelingmotoristsneedtoaa.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Receives Record Number of ERS Calls</h1></center>
<p>
SAN FRANCISCO, April 29, 1996 -- The American Automobile Association received
27.5 million calls in 1995 from members in need of emergency road service --
the third consecutive year of record call volume, AAA announced today.
<p>
 "Growth in AAA membership and regional weather conditions -- such as severe
cold snaps, floods and heat waves -- were the primary contributors to this
year's increase," said Paul Kindschy, director of AAA Emergency Road Service.
<p>
The record total was 2.6 percent higher than a year ago.  Since 1993, the
number of calls has increased by 23 percent, due primarily to harsh winter
weather, AAA said.
<p>
Forty-one percent of the calls to AAA in 1995 resulted in the vehicle being
towed for service, up 2 percent from the previous year.
<p>
"The complex technology on today's cars often requires sophisticated
equipment and computers for proper diagnosis and repair," said Kindschy.
"This can sometimes make roadside repair difficult."
<p>
Thirty percent of the calls to AAA were for vehicles that would not start.
<p>
"A failure to start is usually caused by a faulty battery or electrical
system," said Kindschy. "These problems often show up under extreme
temperatures, both hot and cold."
<p>
Other difficulties that required AAA's emergency assistance included
lockouts, 13 percent; flat tires, 11 percent; and out of fuel, 1 percent.
Miscellaneous problems, such as members in need of extrication and winching,
accounted for 4 percent of the calls.
<p>
AAA provides emergency assistance to members through a network of club- owned
fleets and 13,364 service contractors who operate 36,609 service vehicles --
the largest such fleet in North America.
<p>
Details of AAA's emergency road service program were presented to 1,100
delegates at AAA's 93rd annual meeting at the San Francisco Marriott.
<p>

<p>


<center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaaurgesstatestopasslaws.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="travelingmotoristsneedtoaa.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
