<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>New Car Driving Costs Up 1.4 Cents Per Mile</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="airbagssafetycanbedeadly.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="airbagssafetyseatscanbed.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>New Car Driving Costs Up 1.4 Cents Per Mile</h1></center>
<p>
ORLANDO, Fla., March 14, 1996 -- The average cost of owning and operating a
new car is 42.6 cents per mile, up 1.4 cents from a year ago, according to
the American Automobile Association.
<p>
The 1996 edition of AAA's "Your Driving Costs" reports motorists will spend
an average of $6,389 annually -- an increase of $204, or 3.3 percent over
1995.
<p>
The largest contributors to this year's increase are vehicle ownership costs
including depreciaton, up $97 from last year; insurance costs, up $63; and
finance charges, up $32.  The cost of licenses, registration and taxes
increased $12.  Total operating costs for gasoline, oil, tires and
maintenance are unchanged from a year ago.
<p>
AAA's cost estimates are based on computations made by Runzheimer
International of Rochester, Wisc., a management consulting firm specializing
in transportation, travel and living costs.
<p>
Driving costs data are reflective of personal driving and are comprised of
operating expenses (fuel, oil and maintenance) and fixed ownership costs
(finance charges, registration, insurance, taxes and depreciation.)  These
costs are significantly different from typical reimbursement payments for
business-related use of a personal vehicle.  Such payments usually cover
operating costs for actual mileage and only the portion of the fixed
ownership costs related to the business use of the vehicle.
<p>
AAA's cost figures are based on a composite national average of three
domestically built 1996 cars -- a subcompact Ford Escort LX, a mid-size Ford
Taurus GL and a full-size Chevrolet Caprice. These similarly equipped
vehicles included air conditioning, automatic transmission, power steering,
AM/FM stereo, driver- and passenger-side air bags, antilock brakes, cruise
control, tilt steering wheel, tinted glass and a rear-window defogger.  The
cost estimates are based on a four-year/60,000-mile ownership period.
<p>
New to this year's study are driving costs associated with a typical sport
utility vehicle.  AAA says the cost to drive a 1996 Chevrolet Blazer is 49.9
cents per mile  -- 7.3 cents more than the composite figure for passenger
cars.
<p>
The survey also reports the driving cost for a Dodge Caravan SE is 44.6 cents
per mile, up .8 cent from a year ago.  The information on the Blazer and
Caravan is not part of the composite national average, but is included in the
report to help buyers estimate driving costs for these vehicles.
<p>
"Your Driving Costs" is available through most of AAA's 112 affiliated clubs
in the U.S. and Canada.  Single copies also can be obtained by sending a
self-addressed stamped business envelope to:  Your Driving Costs, Box 75,
1000 AAA Drive, Heathrow, Fla. 32746-5063.
<p>



<center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="airbagssafetycanbedeadly.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="airbagssafetyseatscanbed.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
