<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Airbags, Safety Seats Can Be Deadly Combination If Not Used Properly</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="newcardrivingcostsup14c.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="topautostudentsgearupfor.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Airbags, Safety Seats Can Be Deadly Combination If Not Used Properly</h1></center>
<p>
WASHINGTON, D.C., March 8, 1996 -- Responding to heightened government
concern about serious injury and death to children caused by airbags, the
American Automobile Association today called on all motorist of safety seats
and airbags.
<p>
According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 15 fatal
crashes involving airbags have resulted in the deaths of four children in
rear-facing infant safety seats in the front seat have even have died from
safety bag deployment while the child was unrestrained orimproperly
restrained.
<p>
AAA is alerting its 39 million members and the public to the potentially
lethal consequences of not knowing where to put a child's safety seat in
relation to an airbag:
<p>
Install child safety seats in the back seat of a vehicle whenever possible.
<p>
Never put a rear-facing, infant safety seat in the front seat of a car
equipped with passenger-side airbags.  During a forward impact the airbag can
hit a safety seat with enough force to seriously
<p>
Older children in forward-facing safety seats may also be at risk in the
front seat of a car equipped with passenger-side airbags.  The safety seats
put the children several inches closer to the dashboard and increase the
possibility of injury when the airbag inflates.  If the child safety seat
must be installed in the front, the car seat should be adjusted as far back
as possible to maximize the space between the child and the airbag.
<p>
"Airbags saved 570 lives last year alone," said Tom Culpepper, managing
director, AAA traffic safety and engineering.  "Their safety value is
unquestioned."
<p>



