<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Top Auto Students Gear Up for High-Tech Auto Repair Contest</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="airbagssafetyseatscanbed.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="adviceforownersofflooddam.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Top Auto Students Gear Up for High-Tech Auto Repair Contest</h1></center>
<p>
ORLANDO, Fla., Feb. 7, 1996 -- The nation's best high school automotive
technicians will display their high-tech diagnostic and repair skills in the
1996 Ford/AAA STUDENT AUTO SKILLS National Quality Care Challenge, contest
officials announced today.
<p>
The AUTO SKILLS contest recognizes students who have the advanced skills
needed to properly service today's high-tech cars, said James Dunst, national
manager of the AUTO SKILLS contest. They are as good with a computer as they
are with a wrench.
<p>
The high-tech nature of modern auto repair, plentiful job openings and
competitive salaries should make automotive service an attractive career
choice for young people, according to Dunst.
<p>
It is estimated that the auto repair industry needs 80,000 new technicians
nationwide each year, he said.  Starting annual incomes for properly trained
technicians can reach $30,000.  Veteran technicians can earn more than
$75,000.
<p>
State-level AUTO SKILLS contests -- which involve more than 6,000 students
from 1,200 high school and vocational programs -- begin this month.  Written
qualifying test results will narrow the competition to approximately 500
two-student teams eligible to compete in statewide "hands- on" competitions
in April and May.
<p>
The "hands-on" portion of the contest requires two-member teams to compete
against each other and the clock in accurately diagnosing and servicing a
deliberately disabled Ford automobile.
<p>
State champions advance to the national finals in Washington, D.C. on June
17.  Approximately $3 million in scholarships and prizes will be awarded to
contest participants nationwide.
<p>

<p>

<p>


