<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Offers Tips for Travel During Extreme Weather</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="adviceforownersofflooddam.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="newcarsafetydevicesmaymea.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Offers Tips for Travel During Extreme Weather</h1></center>
<p>
ORLANDO, Fla., Jan. 11, 1996 -- A new winter storm targeting eastern states
could cause delays and dangerous conditions at airports and on roads still
being cleared from the Blizzard of '96.  To aid air travelers and motorists,
the American Automobile Association offers the following advice:
<p>
AIR TRAVEL TIPS
<p>
  Before you leave for the airport, call the airline to verify departure time
or any schedule change. Be patient -- call volumes skyrocket during inclement
weather.
<p>
  In stormy conditions, allow yourself more time to travel to the airport.
To avoid traffic congestion or parking hassles due to snow removal or
build-up, have someone drive you to the airport or take public
transportation.
<p>
  Don't leave home without your travel agent's phone number.  If you are
delayed or your flight is canceled, the agent has access to current airport
conditions and airline schedules and can suggest alternatives.  Many travel
agents have toll-free 800 numbers.
<p>
  Plan for the unexpected.  Travel with enough cash, travelers checks or
credit cards to cover the cost of an emergency stay at a hotel and extra
meals.  Pack a change of clothes and a few toiletries in your carry-on
luggage.
<p>
  If you're at the airport and your flight is canceled, get in line
immediately at either the ticket counter or at the gate to make alternative
flight arrangements.  Another option is to call the airline's toll-free
number to make reservations.
<p>
  Airlines are not obligated to pay for meals or overnight accommodations due
to adverse weather conditions.  Rather than looking for lodging at the last
minute, travel with some hotel information or immediately contact your travel
agent.
<p>
  If your flight is delayed or canceled, make sure you contact the hotel or
car-rental agency with your new schedule.  Some lodgings and car-rental
agencies charge for no-shows.
<p>
AUTO TRAVEL TIPS
<p>
 Be sure to equip your car with a winter survival kit including: flashlight,
blankets, booster cables, warning device (flares or reflective triangles),
small bag of abrasive material (sand or non- clumping cat litter) and small
shovel.
<p>
  Clear all snow from your vehicle, especially from windows and around
headlights and brake lights.
<p>
  If you leave the vehicle while warming your car's engine, make sure the
doors do not accidently lock.  AAA finds an increase in locked-out motorists
during cold and snowy weather.
<p>
  Fill your gas tank before the storm hits and keep the tank 
at least half full at all times.
<p>
  The width of many streets has been narrowed by piled-up snow. Proceed
carefully when approaching or passing other vehicles.
<p>
  Exercise caution if you pull off the road.  Snow could block your tail pipe
causing engine exhaust to back up into your vehicle.  Also, your car could
easily become stuck.
<p>
  If you become stuck in unfamiliar surroundings, stay with your car until
you can be rescued.  Tie a bright cloth to your antenna to alert rescuers.
Run the engine periodically for warmth, but keep a window open slightly on
the downwind side of the car to prevent a dangerous build-up of engine
exhaust.
<p>

<p>



<center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="adviceforownersofflooddam.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="newcarsafetydevicesmaymea.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
