<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Don't Take a Chance When Choosing An Auto Repair Shop</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="breakdownscanbetimeconsum.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="findingagoodusedcarhasbe.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Don't Take a Chance When Choosing An Auto Repair Shop</h1></center>
<p>
For some motorists, finding a reliable, honest auto repair shop is akin to
the search for the Holy Grail. Year after year, consumer surveys show that
poor quality car repairs are a major source of consumer complaints.
<p>
The American Automobile Association offers the following advice for choosing
a repair shop and ensuring that reliable work is done at a reasonable price.
<p>
Decide what kind of shop can best handle the work. You may not necessarily go
to the same place for all repairs. For example, one shop may specialize in
exhaust systems, while another may be excellent at finding an obscure
electrical problem. If your car is under warranty, you will
probably need to get it fixed at the dealer.
<p>
Look for AAA approved repair shops. These shops display a sign that says "AAA
Approved Auto Repair." To be AAA approved, repair shops must meet tough
standards for personnel, customer service, equipment and scope of service.
Mechanics must be certified by the National Institute for Automotive Service
Excellence (ASE). The approval process also includes a random survey of the
shop's customers.
<p>
"AAA Approved Auto Repair" facilities guarantee their work for AAA members.
In addition, AAA agrees to arbitrate any disputes between these shops and AAA
members. These repair facilities must abide by AAA's decision. "AAA Approved
Auto Repair" is offered by nearly 4,200 repair
facilities in 30 states and the District of Columbia.
<p>
Once you've decided on the repair shop, it's important that you and the shop
agree on what's to be done to your car. AAA offers these tips to help you
deal with the repair facility:
<p>
- Always make an appointment. If the shop owner knows you are coming and has
a rough idea of the problem, he can assign the right person to the job and
allow enough time to get it done properly.
<p>
- Don't tell the mechanic what you think needs to be fixed or replaced unless
it's obvious. Instead, describe the problem and its symptoms. Let the
mechanic determine what needs fixing.
<p>
- Always get an estimate in writing. Oral estimates can be disputed or
forgotten. This is particularly important when major work is involved, such
as an engine overhaul or transmission replacement.
<p>
- Insist that the shop call if the repair cost will exceed the estimated
price. But remember that it is difficult to predict the precise cost of a
repair until it is completed. Most written estimates contain a clause
allowing the actual cost to exceed the estimate by a certain percentage, such
as 10 percent.
<p>
- For major repairs, consider getting a second opinion, even if the car must
be towed to another shop. You may be charged for the estimate, but most shops
will deduct the price of the estimate if you get the repairs done there.
<p>
- Read the work order before you leave the shop. Be wary of blanket
statements such as "Check and correct transmission noise," or "Repair
engine." You could wind up with a new transmission or engine. Never sign a
blank work order, and never tell the shop personnel to "do what's necessary"
or "just fix it," unless the problem will clearly be covered under warranty.
And be sure a phone number where you can be reached is written on the repair
order.
<p>
- If the shop calls later and tells you that a different part of the car
needs work, approve only the original repairs unless you feel the extra work
is justified. If you were able to drive the car into the shop, you should be
able to drive it back out -- to another shop for a second opinion.
<p>
- Ask to see any replaced parts. You may even want to keep them, unless the
shop has to return them to the manufacturer for warranty or a specialist for
rebuilding. With the original parts and a well-documented repair receipt, you
have solid evidence if the work proves unsatisfactory.
<p>
- Before you pay the bill, be sure the repair order specifies the cost of
labor and the price for each part. The shop's warranty should be printed on
the bill. If not, ask for it in writing.
<p>
- Take a test drive. If the car isn't running right, don't take it home. If
you discover that the problem is not solved after you leave the shop, make an
appointment to bring the car back as soon as possible.
<p>
- Minimize your trips to the mechanic by following the maintenance schedule
for your car. A properly maintained car is less likely to need repairs. Also,
if you know your car's maintenance schedule, you're less likely to authorize
unnecessary work.
<p>

<p>


<center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="breakdownscanbetimeconsum.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="findingagoodusedcarhasbe.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
