<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Says Motorists Spend $1.7 Billion Too Much For Gas
</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="findingagoodusedcarhasbe.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="newaaaprogramhelpsparents.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Says Motorists Spend $1.7 Billion Too Much For Gas
</h1></center>

WASHINGTON, D.C., September 24, 1996 -- Motorists are wasting an estimated $1.7 billion per year buying premium gasoline they don't need, according to AAA.
<p>
Many drivers are falling for the "octane myth" in gasoline ads and are giving $1.7 billion to the nation's oil industry needlessly, AAA says.  Although premium gas sales are nearing 20 percent of total gas sold, less than 10 percent of cars actually need premium's higher octane.  With premium costing consumers about 15 cents more per gallon than regular grade fuel, a typical motorist using 650 gallons of gas could be wasting nearly $100 a year for unneeded premium.
<p>
The Federal Trade Commission this week charged a major oil company with misleading consumers by making unsubstantiated advertising claims for its premium gasoline.  The association noted the FTC has made similar charges against several companies, which all settled with the agency before they reached court.
<p>
AAA said consumers should realize that only exotic cars, some sport utility vehicles and vehicles with high-performance engines really need premium.
<p>
"Contrary to popular opinion, premium gas does not provide more power, doesn't improve performance, burn more cleanly, reduce engine wear or improve mileage," said Dave Van Sickle, AAA's director of automotive and consumer information.
<p>
AAA joined the FTC in reminding motorists that, despite what they hear on TV or the radio, premium gas is not necessarily higher quality than regular.  Federal regulations require that all gasoline at all octane levels contain sufficient detergent additives to keep engines clean.
<p>
"Vehicles that run well -- that do not knock or ping -- on regular grade gasoline will not benefit from using premium," Van Sickle said.  "If your owner's manual calls for premium, it should always be used.  If it doesn't, why spend the extra money?"
<p>
AAA said modern engines requiring premium fuel are equipped with electronic knock sensors for protection in case the wrong grade of gas is used.  As engines age, their octane requirement can increase slightly, caused primarily by the formation of deposits in the combustion chamber which can cause knocking.
<p>
"It's rare for an engine designed to run on regular to move up five octane numbers to premium because of engine deposits -- especially with the level of detergents being used in all gasoline today," Van Sickle said. "If you're using premium and your owner's manual doesn't call for it, you're probably spending more money for your gas than you need to be."





