<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>New AAA Program Helps Parents Fight High Crash Rate Among Teen-Age Drivers
</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaasaysmotoristsspend17.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="drivingcostsdownslightlyin.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>New AAA Program Helps Parents Fight High Crash Rate Among Teen-Age Drivers
</h1></center>
Washington, D.C., Sept. 26, 1996 -- In response to the significant increase in the number of teen-age motorists killed on the nation's roadways, AAA today introduced the "Teaching Your Teens to Drive:  A Partnership for Survival" program to help parents provide supervised driving experience to novice drivers.
<p>
AAA created the program to combat the high crash rate per mile among young drivers -- four times higher than among adult motorists.
<p>
Since the number of motor-vehicle crashes among 15- to 19-year old drivers hit a historic high of 5.6 million in 1979, the trend until the last two years has been downward, reaching 2.6 million crashes in 1992.  Since then the total has been increasing, with 2.7 million crashes in 1993 and 2.8 million crashes in 1994. 
<p>
"As the children of Baby Boomers reach driving age, we are seeing an increasing number of them injured or killed in motor-vehicle crashes," said James Kolstad, vice president, AAA Public and Government Relations.  "Action must be taken to curb this tragic trend."
<p>
AAA is concerned that teen-driver injuries and fatalities may continue increasing until 2010 when the number of teen-agers in the population reaches its peak.
<p>
Most  fatal crashes involving 15- to 17-year-olds are the result of driver inexperience, poor driving skills, risk-taking or poor decision making.  Contributing to the overall increase in teen-driver deaths is the 6.2 percent rise in alcohol-related fatalities since 1993.
<p>
"Today's teen-agers usually do not get the training, guidance and experience they need to be safe drivers," said Kolstad.  "Parents can turn this around by getting involved and helping young drivers get an adequate amount of well-supervised practice time."
<p>
The first program of its kind designed specifically for a burgeoning video/computer generation, Teaching Your Teens to Drive includes a colorfully illustrated handbook, detailed parent guide and live-action video.  A separate teacher's guide enables the program to be used as part of a school-based driver education course.   An interactive CD-ROM will be available next year.
<p>
"AAA believes parents are in a unique position to show their kids how to improve their driving choices, change risky behavior and begin to assume social responsibility," Kolstad said.
<p>
The problem extends beyond teen-age drivers to the young people riding with them.  Almost one-fourth of passenger fatalities involve 15- to 20-year-olds.
<p>
The Teaching Your Teens to Drive: A Partnership for Survival program and additional information is available from most AAA clubs or by writing to:  Teaching Your Teens to Drive, MS 76, 1000 AAA Drive, Heathrow FL  32746.


<center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaasaysmotoristsspend17.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="drivingcostsdownslightlyin.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
