<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Mark Edwards to Lead AAA Traffic Safety Department</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="drivingcostsdownslightlyin.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaasupportsnewapproachfor.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Mark Edwards to Lead AAA Traffic Safety Department</h1></center>
ORLANDO, Fla., Oct. 15, 1996 -- Mark L. Edwards, a former senior official with the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, has been named managing director of Traffic Safety for AAA, effective Sept. 30.
<p>
"Mark's expertise and experience in research and transportation safety issues will be a tremendous asset to AAA and to our wide range of traffic safety and education programs," said James L. Kolstad, vice president of AAA Public and Government Relations.
<p>
Edwards served as a division chief at NHTSA's National Center for Statistics and Analysis from 1987 to 1992 and was an engineering research psychologist for NHTSA's Office of Crash Avoidance Research from 1985 to 1987.
<p>
While at NHTSA, Edwards managed the statistical support provided to Congress, NHTSA program offices and the Department of Transportation for rulemaking, research and the development of highway safety initiatives.
<p>
Immediately prior to joining AAA, Edwards was a vice president at Star Mountain, Inc., where he was responsible for the Human and Information Technologies Division.
<p>
Edward's professional experience includes work on virtually all aspects of human performance in the transportation system, including roadway illumination and signage, assessment of driver performance, law enforcement tactics, regulation of drivers' crash and conviction experience and crash data systems.  He has written more than 100 papers and presentations on transportation safety and has served on numerous technical advisory committees.
<p>
Edwards holds a master's degree in psychology and a doctorate in human factors from Texas A&M University in College Station, Texas.  He earned a bachelor's degree in psychology from Lamar University in Beaumont, Texas.
<p>


