<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Supports New Approach For Child Safety Seats</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="markedwardstoleadaaatraff.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="crisisahead.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Supports New Approach For Child Safety Seats</h1></center>
WASHINGTON, D.C., Oct. 18, 1996 -- The American Automobile Association  said today it supports the concept of a uniform national standard for an improved child safety seat attachment mechanism.
<p>
At a public meeting here sponsored by the U.S. Department of Transportation, Mark Edwards, AAA's  managing director for traffic safety, said, "We believe that design changes which facilitate the secure attachment of child safety seats, such as the ISOFIX approach, can make a real contribution to the safety of children in automobiles."
<p>
ISOFIX (International Standards Organization-Fix) is a seating system developed in Europe that would involve four attachment points to the vehicle and a frame that would enable quick attachment of a child seat to a larger seat.  The system has not yet been adopted by standards organizations.
<p>
"On behalf of its 39 million members, many of whom are parents or grandparents, AAA supports the government's efforts to assure that child  safety seats can be securely and easily attached," Edwards said.
<p>
AAA noted that, in spite of child safety seat laws and improvement in seat design, there were 616 occupant fatalities in 1995 among children under five years of age.  Of these, an estimated 328 (or 57 percent) were totally unrestrained.  From 1982 through 1995, however, nearly 3,000 lives were saved by child restraints--proving their value.
<p>
During the 1970s, AAA and its affiliated clubs throughout the U.S. and Canada were leaders in the car safety seat movement.
<p>
AAA news releases are now available on the Internet.  Within 15 minutes of release, they will be available for download or fax through PR Newswire's site Company News On Call.  The address is:  http://www.prnewswire.com/cnoc.html and the search word is AAA.  Releases will remain available until one year after the release date.
<p>

