<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Cites Worst ATC Centers: Calls On Congress to Act</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="crisisahead.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaaidentifiesstateswithwor.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Cites Worst ATC Centers: Calls On Congress to Act</h1></center>
<p>
WASHINGTON, D.C., August 27, 1996 -- The American Automobile Association today
cited en route air traffic control centers in New York, Chicago, and Fort Worth
as having the worst equipment failure records in the nation during the last 16
months. Twenty en route ATC centers control aircraft at high altitudes between
cities.
<p>
AAA recently announced a nationwide campaign -- "Crisis Ahead: America's Aging
Highways and Airways" -- to bring to the attention of the American public the
rapidly deteriorating state of the nation's highways and air traffic control
system.
<p>
According to Federal Aviation Administration data, there have been 30 major
computer and power failures at en route air traffic control centers in the last
16 months. During this period, 21 of the 30 major failures were at three
centers: New York, Chicago, and Fort Worth. 
<p>
New York had eight incidents, including one of nearly six hours that affected
485 flights. Chicago had seven incidents, including a computer outage of 46
minutes that resulted in 313 flight delays. Fort Worth had six major ATC
failures, including a 14-hour power failure that resulted in 263 flight delays.
These delays do not include hundreds of others "downline" caused by the ripple
effect of the delayed aircraft arriving late at subsequent stops.
<p>
"These equipment failures are a prime example of the general deterioration of
our transportation system," said AAA President Robert L. Darbelnet. "This is not
a people problem. It is a hardware and under-investment problem." 
<p>
AAA, which has 938 U.S. travel agency offices that sell more than $1 billion of
air travel annually, called on Congress to take immediate steps to help fix the
nation's antiquated and failure-prone air traffic control system.
<p>
"Frequent system outages cause massive flight delays throughout the nation,
seriously affecting the plans of millions of air travelers and the nation's
business," Darbelnet said.
<p>
"Airline ticket taxes that provide 75 percent of the FAA budget expired Jan. 1,
1996," Darbelnet said. "Congress recently voted to reinstate them but only for
four months. Unless it acts soon to provide long-term financing, the FAA will be
left without critical operating funds."
<p>
AAA also called for removal of the Airport and Airway Trust Fund from the budget
process to assure that funds in the account are spent on upgrading the aviation
system rather than on lowering the deficit. The House has approved taking
transportation trust funds off budget, the Senate has yet to act. 
<p>
The FAA has estimated that on an average day there are some 700 flight delays of
15 minutes or more. The annual cost of these delays to airlines and their
customers is estimated at $3 billion.
<p>
In a national survey by AAA, seven in 10 respondents said they were concerned
with air safety and the increase in flight delays due to problems with the air
traffic control system.</PRE></HTML>


