<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Identifies States with Worst Bridges</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaacitesworstatccentersc.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="potholesaconstantsafetyand.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Identifies States with Worst Bridges</h1></center>
ST. CHARLES, MO., August 10 -- The American Automobile Association has
identified the 10 states whose bridges are in the worst condition.
<p>
AAA ranked the states and Washington, D.C. according to the percentage of
their bridges rated structurally deficient or functionally obsolete by the
Federal Highway Administration:
<p>
New York topped the list with 63% of its bridges needing extensive repair or
replacement.  Washington, D.C. is second with 60%, followed by Massachusetts,
58%; Hawaii, 53%; Rhode Island, 49%; West Virginia, 47%; New Jersey, 46%;
Missouri, 46%; Pennsylvania, 44%; Vermont, 42%, and Mississippi, 41%.
<p>
Speaking at the birthplace of the 40-year old interstate highway system,  AAA
President Robert L. Darbelnet said,  "We have reached this era of decaying
bridges, crumbling roadways and antiquated air traffic control because the
government is investing only a  fraction of what is needed for infrastructure
maintenance."
<p>
AAA recently launched a nationwide campaign called  "Crisis Ahead--America's
Aging Highways & Airways,"  to urge policy makers to take action to repair
240,000 miles of roads and bridges the Federal Highway Administration says
are in poor or mediocre condition.  AAA was instrumental in mobilizing public
and governmental support for the Federal Highway Act of 1956, which
authorized the Interstate Highway System.
<p>
"The Federal Highway Administration estimates it needs $53 billion a year
just to maintain current road and bridge conditions, and $72 billion a year
to make improvements," Darbelnet said. "Current annual spending is only $35
billion--a virtual guarantee that the system will get worse. More
inefficient. More dangerous."  
<p>
Darbelnet urged people to contact their congressmen and tell them four
things: 
<p>
1.  Take the transportation trust funds off budget and only spend the money
for roads, bridges and airways.
<p>
2.  Stop spending gasoline taxes for non-transportation purposes.
<p>
3.  Put in place long-term financing for the nation's airports and airways,
and
<p>
4.  Develop a long-term comprehensive plan to address the needs of the
country's highways and airways.
<p>
Note: The FHWA defines a structurally deficient bridge as closed or
restricted to light vehicles because of deteriorated structural components
but is not necessarily unsafe.
<p>
A functionally obsolete bridge cannot safely service the volume or type of
traffic using it.  Though not unsafe for all vehicles, it has older design
features that prevent it from accommodating current traffic volumes and
modern vehicle sizes and weights.
<p>
U.S. BRIDGE CONDITIONS Source:  Federal Highway Administration
<p>

