<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Urges Dole to Address Transportation Crisis</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="potholesaconstantsafetyand.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="aaalaunchesnationwidecampa.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Urges Dole to Address Transportation Crisis</h1></center>
<p>
Washington, D.C., July 19, 1996 -- The American Automobile Association is
urging Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole to support a greater
investment in the nation's transportation system.
<p>
"We are facing a potential crisis in transportation and Sen. Dole should
speak out on the issue between now and the November elections," said James L.
Kolstad, vice president for AAA Public and Government Relations.
<p>
Kolstad met yesterday with the Dole for President
Transportation/Infrastructure Policy Committee in Washington.
<p>
Kolstad told the Committee that one-third of America's highways are in fair
or poor condition; that 25 percent of the bridges in the U.S. are either
"structurally deficient" or "functionally obsolete," and that the U.S. is
seriously under investing in transportation.
<p>
Last month AAA launched "Crisis Ahead:  America's Aging Highways and
Airways," a nationwide campaign to urge policy makers to address these
problems.
<p>
AAA is urging Dole to put common sense and trust back into the transportation
financing.  AAA has made a similar presentation to the Democratic Platform
Committee.
<p>
"The next administration, whether it is headed by Senator Dole or President
Clinton, must establish transportation as a high priority," said Kolstad. "We
need a long-term strategic plan to deal with a crumbling transportation
system."
<p>



