<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AAA Cites 10 Major Traffic Choke Points Around The Nation</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="aaalaunchesnationwidecampa.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="financial.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>AAA Cites 10 Major Traffic Choke Points Around The Nation</h1></center>
ORLANDO, Fla., Oct. 31, 1996 -- AAA today cited 10 of the nation's worst major highway bottlenecks that are choking the flow of traffic and frustrating motorists across the country.<p>

"Motorists are battling the bottleneck blues," said James Kolstad, vice president of AAA Public and Government Relations.  "They are feeling the stress caused every day by slow moving traffic, and ever-longer commutes."<p>

AAA's notorious bottleneck list includes roads and bridges in Boston, Chicago, Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles, Milwaukee, Minneapolis, New Orleans, New York City, and Washington, D.C.  (see attached list for details).  The list includes areas where the number of lanes is quickly reduced, several major roads merge and where development has outpaced road capacity.<p>

The list is based on the number of motorists affected and the length of delays typically encountered.  Information for the selections is based on AAA's experience in preparing 9 million Triptik( travel routings each year and from AAA's road reporters, who travel hundreds of thousands of miles per year monitoring highway conditions.   A survey of AAA clubs also contributed to the list.<p>

"A highway system is only as efficient as its most congested point," Kolstad said.  "Road sections that have not been upgraded to handle current capacity can cause miles of vehicle backup and thousands of hours of lost productivity."  <p>

In addition to inconvenience, traffic bottlenecks create shipping delays and hinder the quick response of ambulances and other emergency vehicles, AAA said. <p>

The bottleneck list is another example of AAA's continuing effort to call attention to the deteriorating condition of the nation's transportation system and to urge federal and state policymakers to take corrective action.  As part of AAA's campaign, "Crisis Ahead: America's Aging Highways and Airways," federal government studies have been cited showing more than one-third of U.S. roads are in poor or mediocre condition and 25 percent of the bridges are structurally deficient or functionally obsolete.<p>


# # #<p>

Notorious Traffic Bottlenecks<p>


Boston, Mass.
Interstate 93 north and south<p>

Boston's central artery cuts an elevated pass through downtown.  It was built in the 1950s to carry 90,000 cars daily but now overflows with 190,000 cars each day.  There are now between 6-8 hours of stop and go traffic each day, but without improvements the traffic jams will stretch to 14-16 hours per day by 2010.<p>

Chicago, Ill.
Interstate 88/Eisenhower Expressway<p>

Traffic from the western suburbs comes to a halt as 34,000 vehicles per day from    I-88 merge with 43,000 vehicles per day from the Eisenhower Expressway (I-290).   The road goes down to a single lane for 1 1/2 blocks before opening up to multiple lanes.  What should be a 20-minute trip to the city can take 1 1/2 hours.<p>

Dallas, Texas
Interstate 35/Interstate 30<p>

Known as "The Mix Master" by local motorists, these two major highways merge and struggle to carry more than 200,000 vehicles per day from downtown through the steep inclines and declines of  "The Canyon."<p>

Houston, Texas
U.S. 59 at the 610 Loop<p>

Only one lane exits U.S. 59 to 610 Loop, causing significant delays in all directions at this intersection that handles more than 330,000 vehicles per day.  Stop-and-go conditions occur for 5-6 hours per day.<p>

Los Angeles, Calif.
Interstate 5 at the intersection with I-10, SR 60 and SR 101<p>

An estimated 566,000 vehicles per day travel through this intersection, overwhelming the capacity of this major commuter highway.  Motorists making lane transitions as they approach this intersection create a traffic bottleneck that extends for miles.<p>

Milwaukee, Wisc.
Interstate 94 (East-West Freeway, Milwaukee County)<p>

This is Wisconsin's oldest and busiest stretch of interstate highway.  It was designed in the 1950s and built in the 1960s to outmoded design standards.  Stretches of the road that were designed to handle 80,000 vehicles per day now are clogged with twice that volume.  The corridor is currently under consideration for an improvement project estimated to cost between $800 million and $1.8 billion.<p>


Minneapolis, Minn.
Northbound Interstate 35W at Minnehaha Creek (South Minneapolis)<p>

Only three lanes are available on this major route into downtown for a daily flow of 100,000 vehicles.<p>

New Orleans, La.
Interstate 10 and Interstate 610 in both directions<p>

Lanes are reduced from three to two.  Traffic backs up at this interchange, even when conditions are clear.  Visibility is restricted as drivers move from an elevated interchange to a surface level roadway.   This stretch of road handles approximately 174,000 vehicles per day<p>

New York, N.Y.
Gowanus Expressway (in Brooklyn)<p>

The Gowanus Expressway (Interstate 278) is a major route connecting Brooklyn, Manhattan, Queens and Long Island.  The primary congestion point is a 3.8 mile segment between the Brooklyn Battery Tunnel and the Belt Parkway that carries 175,000 vehicles per day.  Significant delays occur in this area for six or more hours per typical day.<p>

Washington, D.C.
Woodrow Wilson Bridge<p>

This six-lane bridge is fed by the 8-lane Capital Beltway (I-95) and has a 2-3 mile backup every rush hour.  172,000 vehicles per day cross the span, which was originally designed to carry only 70,000 per day.  Additionally, the bridge -- the only federally owned bridge in the nation -- is deteriorating and is in urgent need of replacement.  A new bridge will not be in place for at least eight years.

