<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Gas Prices Up 2.1 Cents - First Increase Since June</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="gaspricesupsharplyforeast.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="autumngaspricesrefusetofa.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Gas Prices Up 2.1 Cents - First Increase Since June</h1></center>
<p>
ORLANDO, Fla., Jan. 16, 1996 -- Ending a six-month trend of declining prices,
the price of self-serve regular unleaded gasoline rose 2.1 cents since
December, according to the American Automobile Association.
<p>
According to AAA's monthly Fuel Gauge Survey, the national average price for
self-serve unleaded is $1.139 per gallon.
<p>
The average price of self-serve mid-grade unleaded is $1.233 per gallon, 2.2
cents more than last month.  Self-serve premium increased 2 cents to $1.315.
<p>
Full-serve regular unleaded averages $1.403 per gallon, up 1.3 cents from
last month.  Full-serve mid-grade averages $1.502, up 1.2 cents.  Premium
rose 1.5 cents to $ 1.562.
<p>
Self-serve regular unleaded is most expensive in the West at $1.238 per
gallon, down 1.6 cents from last month.  It is least expensive in the
Southeast at $1.059, 2.7 cents higher than a month ago.
<p>
Other regional average prices are:  New England, $1.187 per gallon, up 2.4
cents in one month; Mid-Atlantic, $1.125, up 1.7 cents; Great Lakes, $1.141,
up 5.1 cents; Midwest, $1.107, up 2.9 cents; and Southwest, $1.116, up 1.8
cents.
<p>
Nearly 39 percent of the stations surveyed will be open 24 hours.
<p>
The survey was conducted by Computer Petroleum Corp. of St. Paul, Minn.,
which publishes the National Petroleum Price Index that monitors more than
90,000 daily wholesale and retail prices in the United States and Canada.
<p>

