<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Gasoline Inventories Tool Low, AAA Says</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="holidaygaspricescontinueto.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="news.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Gasoline Inventories Tool Low, AAA Says</h1></center>
<P>WASHINGTON, D.C., Jan. 3, 1997 -- Gasoline and crude oil stocks continue to drop as the nation enters the new year, with oil industry inventories falling millions of barrels below earlier years, according to AAA.  
<P>
&quot;Gasoline stocks at the refinery level are at 192 million barrels, down 4 million barrels from a year ago and nearly 25 million barrels below 1994 levels,&quot; said William Berman, AAA's director of energy and environment.  &quot;Refiners have dropped their crude oil stocks below 295 million barrels, hitting their lowest level since record keeping began in 1971, and nearly 45 million barrels below 1994 levels,&quot; Berman said.
<P>
AAA pointed out that these inventories are the lowest levels reached since the Arab oil embargo of 1973-74, and combined with a long and cold winter could cause even higher prices and potential supply disruptions.
<P>
AAA's most recent price report in December showed the average - price for self-serve regular was $1.29 per gallon -- 17 cents higher than a year ago and the highest level since 1990.  The average monthly pump price for 1996 was higher than any year since 1986.
<P>
&quot;We are not suggesting the oil industry has purposefully  manipulated prices but we are concerned that lower than normal inventories could put upward pressure on gasoline prices,&quot; Berman said.
<P>
AAA wrote to Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary last month, asking her to urge refiners to shore up their inventories to protect the nation from unexpected changes that could occur in the marketplace.  &quot;By keeping gasoline and oil inventories at such low levels, the traveling public is more  vulnerable to the vagaries of the global market,&quot; Berman said.
<P>
&quot;AAA opposes federal control of petroleum inventories but believes Secretary O'Leary could be helpful in efforts to restore reserves to 1994 levels,&quot; he added.

<center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="holidaygaspricescontinueto.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="news.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
