<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Budget Cutting Must Not Focus on Economic Growth, Safety</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="ahistoryofservice.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="telecommunicationslegislat.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Budget Cutting Must Not Focus on Economic Growth, Safety</h1></center>
<p>
Washington, D.C., March 20, 1996 -- "Budget cutting must not focus on
programs that contribute to economic growth and improved aviation safety,"
according to the 38-million member American Automobile Association ,  one of
the nation's largest sellers of air transportation, ticketing 3.5 million air
travelers in 1995.
<p>
Testifying before the House Aviation Subcommittee, James L. Kolstad, AAA's
vice president for public and government relations, said, "We speak for the
passengers who use the system--who pay the fares and pay the ticket taxes
which comprise the bulk of the Airport and Airway Trust Fund.  These
passengers have placed their trust in the federal government to keep its
promise that these expenditures will produce the safest, most efficient air
travel possible.
<p>
"AAA strongly urges Congress to reinstate the aviation taxes which comprise
the aviation trust fund," Kolstad said.  "And we will vigorously oppose
efforts to use those fees for other than the intended purpose--the aviation
infrastructure." The association said it supports the "Truth in
Budgeting Act" (H.R. 842), which removes transportation trust funds from the
unified budget, and is asking AAA clubs in the 50 states to communicate with
Congress urging them to support H.R. 842.
<p>
"While AAA recognizes the importance of balancing the federal budget, we
strongly believe that attaining budget targets by cutting transportation
investments is poor public policy," said Kolstad. "The ability to move people
and goods is fundamental to America's strength.  Failure to invest in
infrastructure that reaps immediate dividends and economic strength for our
children cannot be rationalized."
<p>
AAA also said it strongly opposed diversion of airport revenues to city or
state treasuries for general budget purposes, and supports more investment in
airports to address the worsening flight delays and growing demand for air
travel.
<p>
The association also proposed an aviation "needs report" similar to the DOT's
surface transportation report on the condition, performance and capital
investment requirements of the nation's highway system.  No such report
exists for aviation.  AAA said an aviation version would
be a valuable tool in planning for wise, careful investment to bring the
greatest return in terms of economic efficiency and increased safety.
<p>

<p>


