<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Telecommunications Legislation Being Debated in Washington</TITLE></HEAD><BODY LINK="#0000bf" VLINK="#ee0000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="aaatile.gif"><center><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><TR><TD><a href="budgetcuttingmustnotfocus.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="prev.gif" alt="PREV"></a></TD><TD><a href="welcome.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="home.gif" alt="HOME"></a></TD><TD><a href="index.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="navigate.gif" alt="Navigate"></a></TD><TD><a href="travel.html"><img align="middle" border=0 width=100 height=40 src="next.gif" alt="NEXT"></a></TD></TR>
</table><h1>Telecommunications Legislation Being Debated in Washington</h1></center>
<p>
We're told that telecommunications legislation being debated in Washington
affects all Americans. While that may be true, the only examples we hear
about are big business issues involving the battle of the telephone
companies; cable TV, and whether our rates will go up or down; and the V-chip
device that lets us shut out violent TV programs.
<p>
There are other important services to Americans that will be affected by this
legislation thataren't being debated, but ought to be.
<p>
One is the safety impact on the motoring public of auctioning radio
frequencies. Because of this little-known provision of the Senate's
telecommunications bill, frequencies now reserved exclusively for use by AAA
around the nation for emergency road service would be auctioned off
and opened up to other users. This will create a severe impact on safety.
<p>
Emergency vehicles that are radio-dispatched through AAA to assist stranded
motorists, local police, fire and other rescue operations could be delayed
because of competition for air time.
<p>
AAA would be hindered in immediately dispatching emergency vehicles to rescue
motorists with medical conditions, or with children locked in cars, or who
are stranded in high-crime areas or along a busy freeway.
<p>
This is not a small problem. Last year AAA responded to some 27 million
emergency road service calls nationally. That's almost a call a second.
<p>
Having immediate access to radio frequencies with clear communications
channels is imperative to AAA's ability to respond to emergency situations.
These involve not only the everyday problems of motorists, but also those
brought about by natural disasters such as earthquakes,
floods, hurricanes and severe snow storms--often involving life and death
situations.
<p>
If Congress must auction off radio frequencies to reduce the national
debt,fine. But don't include frequencies used for public safety service. The
revenue loss would be small, but the loss to millions of motorists in some
kind of trouble would be immense.
<p>

<p>



