</table><h1>AAA Selects Three Airlines to Launch Preferred Supplier Team</h1></center>
<p>
ORLANDO, Fla., Aug. 12, 1996 -- The American Automobile Association has
selected Continental Airlines, Delta Air Lines and United Airlines to form
its team of preferred airline suppliers for its 1997-1998 program. 
<p>
"Continental, Delta and United have committed significant resources  to the
AAA partnership," said Jack Mannix, managing director, AAA Travel Related
Services.  "By concentrating our business with these three carriers, everyone
wins -- our 39 million members, AAA's more than 5,000 travel agents and our
supplier partners."
<p>
The selection process formally began in January 1996 with the formation of
the Airline Strategy Liaison Team, composed of AAA club executives and AAA
national office staff, to develop a strategy and negotiate with carriers.
<p>
Each carrier received a "Request for Information" proposal covering 11
issues, including: agency and management training, service commitment, member
benefits, enhanced commission structure, sales and marketing support and
financial conditions.  Further negotiations took place based on the
information provided in the proposals.  
<p>
AAA's final selection of Continental, Delta and United was based on careful
analysis of each carrier's comprehensive portfolio and the ability to form a
long-term and beneficial partnership with the association.
<p>
The two-year agreements are effective Jan. 1, 1997.
<p>
The AAA Airline Strategy Liaison Team consisted of the following AAA club
executives: Bill Best (AAA Michigan); Skip Davenport (Auto Club of Southern
California); Al Erdelen (AAA Minnesota); Walter Groux (New Jersey Auto Club);
George Howell (AAA Washington); Jenny McMutrie (AAA Auto Club South); Crystal
Sicklesmith (AAA Columbiana County, Ohio); Louis Thiele (AAA Arizona); Jane
Welsh (AAA Iowa) and Tom Wright (AAA Central Penn Auto Club). 
<p>
"AAA's new lineup of preferred airline partners will continue the momentum
set by the success of our tour and cruise strategy that generated a 59
percent growth in sales in the first year of the program," said Mannix.
<p>


